<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DEFFEAT ISLANDERS, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few minutes before, during a Rangers power play,
Wayne Gretzky had taken a good shot from a good spot but got beat
by Islanders goalie Wade Flaherty. ``Darn,'' he said, or a word to
that effect, as he winced and made a sharp gesture of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Returned to his center position because of an injury to Petr
Nedved, Gretzky had been firing the puck better and more often than
in most games this season. His next chance came soon, with more
than two minutes remaining in the third period and the score tied
at 1-1 in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After an Islander turnover, Gretzky fired, and Flaherty blocked
the first shot while falling back. As if in a slow-motion dream
sequence from a film, the puck lay in the blue-painted ice of the
crease. Players for both teams struggled and fell atop the goalie.
Gretzky charged forward, stick extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely got to the puck,'' he said. ``I hate to say I kind of
panicked. I felt like I couldn't get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he got to it and pushed it over the red goal line to give
the Rangers a 2-1 lead that eventually became a 3-1 victory. The
Rangers won all five games against the Islanders this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, it put them 5 points behind the Boston Bruins
in the race for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference of the National Hockey League. The Rangers have eight
games left and the Bruins have 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, it was Gretzky's goal No. 1,072, regular
season and playoffs combined in both the NHL and the World Hockey
Association. It broke the total held by Gordie Howe, Gretzky's idol
when he was a boy and the man Gretzky calls the greatest player in
the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good goal,'' Gretzky said, ``and a goal that I'll
never forget. It's a pretty special moment. I feel very
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The record won't be official, because the NHL does not recognize
the WHA, a rival league of the 1970s. But these were real goals
scored by real stars in real games. Gretzky, who broke in as a
17-year-old with the Indianapolis Racers in 1978, played one season
in the WHA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a record I guess won't be in the books,'' Gretzky
said, adding that people will remember it and debate it anyway.
``Some of my records are going to be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Among active players, Mark Messier, Gretzky's former Edmonton
and Ranger teammate, is next in career goals with 611. Howe had 202
in the WHA and Gretzky 56.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has only nine goals this season, only one since Jan. 10.
Since then, he missed 12 games with a disk injury in his neck and
this was his fourth game back. Shortly before he announced his
injury, in late February, Gretzky said Howe called to tell him he
was on his way to China and to wish him luck. Gretzky said he had
told Howe he didn't know when he would get another chance to score
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   After he scored, Gretzky reacted with jubilation. So did his
teammates and the fans, who chanted ``Gretzky! Gretzky! Gretzky!''
He finished the game with seven shots on goal, most in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said Coach John Muckler's original plan was to use
Nedved at left wing with Gretzky at center, but that Gretzky
suggested his own move to the left side. It all became moot when
Nedved left early in the game with a rib injury. Muckler said he
hopes Nedved can return for the next game, Friday, against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Of Gretzky's goal, Muckler said: ``I know he was looking forward
to it. I know it meant a lot to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The first period on Monday night was scoreless and the teams
exchanged goals in the second period. The Rangers took a 1-0 lead
when Adam Graves scored his 36th goal of the season, most on the
team and tied for eighth in the NHL with Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr.
Leading the league is Teemu Selanne of Anaheim with 43. Graves
scored at 3 minutes 21 seconds by deflecting a Brian Leetch shot
with his back to the goalie, Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders tied it at 8:53 on a goal of a scrambled play
scored by Mariusz Czerkawski past a sprawling Mike Richter.
Technically, the goal was at even strength, although the Islanders
had an extra skater because the goalie had been pulled for an extra
attacker when a penalty was about to be called against Chris Tamer
of the Rangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
