<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ This is the way it so often seems to wind up
in the last days of March. The month that is supposed to go out
like a lamb gives one more lion's roar.
</P>
<P>
   Or in this case, a Husky's howl.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke Invitational became the Great Conn Job.
</P>
<P>
   You can't imagine it? UConn believe it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Blue Devils' night to make history. Instead they were
history.
</P>
<P>
   Just the latest chapter in the book on the NCAA Tournament
championship game that has more plot twists and surprise endings
than an Edgar Allan Poe story.
</P>
<P>
   When the last seconds finally ticked down and Trajan Langdon
practically dribbled himself into the ground trying desperately and
fruitlessly to make any kind of play, it was Connecticut 77, Duke
74, and Khalid El-Amin, the Huskies' husky little point guard,
sprinted to the courtside press table and shouted straight into the
CBS camera: ``We shocked the world!''
</P>
<P>
   Only if the world hasn't been paying attention to these
maddening Monday nights when incredible things happen, when teams
like North Carolina State, Villanova and now UConn prove that
anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   It was a magnificent basketball game, 40 minutes of youthful
exuberance and untamed energy. It was like sitting at a window
watching a crackling display of summer lightning.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that should go directly to ESPN's Classic Sports
channel, no matter that the sweat has barely dried on the uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   It should be framed and hung in the Louvre, protected behind
velvet ropes. Or maybe the video should be locked away with other
precious heirlooms in a vault, pulled out any time in the future
when anybody dares to say that one team is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night of gripping drama and sparkling entertainment
that made it worth switching the channel from back-to-back episodes
of Ally McBeal, because it was a game where the gap between the two
teams was skinnier than Calista Flockhart's waist. There were 14
ties and seven lead changes.
</P>
<P>
   It was an evening when Duke came for a coronation and wound up
getting crowned by a pack of Huskies who sank their teeth in early
and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   It was big, dough-faced Irishman Jim Calhoun finally making it
all the way to the top after years of regular-season excellence
followed by years of Tournament frustration. There were all those
previous years when the Huskies expected to be here and were not,
and then they showed up and won on their first try. He implemented
a defensive game plan that used varying double teams to stifle
Duke's Elton Brand, the national player of the year, and turned the
Huskies loose on offense with a confident, pedal-to-the-metal
attack that told the Blue Devils that they were not afraid.
</P>
<P>
   It was two-time Big East Player of the Year Richard Hamilton,
who is smoother than a set of silk sheets and cooler than the other
side of the pillow, firing in 27 points and never looking anything
but confident.
</P>
<P>
   It was the little marshmallow of a point guard, El-Amin _ 5-10
and 205 pounds _ who struggled with his offense for most of the
night and then stepped up to score UConn's last four points of the
game on a running eight-footer and then a pair of clutch free
throws. When it was over and the Huskies were wearing their
championship T-shirts and running all over the floor at Tropicana
Field, the unlikely looking El-Amin was hauled in by a security
guard who thought he was a fan who had joined the party.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ricky Moore, the Huskies' best defender, who did his
usual excellent job on the perimeter and also helped carry the
offensive load early with 11 of his 13 points in the first half.
With UConn protecting a 75-74 lead, it was Moore, the spider, who
lured Langdon into his web and forced a a turnover on a walking
violation.
</P>
<P>
   It was Strake Jesuit's Jake Voskuhl, who kept his composure and
battled Brand all night, and it was Kevin Freeman and all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   For Duke, it was a night of shattered hopes and broken
expectations, a game that was supposed to take the Blue Devils into
the pantheon of great champions such as Indiana and UCLA and
Kentucky but left them tied instead to other heavy favorites like
Georgetown and Houston that couldn't carry the burden.
</P>
<P>
   At 37-1, the Blue Devils were a steaming locomotive. At 37-2,
the legacy of this Duke team has been derailed. A year ago, in this
same building, Duke blew a 17-point second-half lead to lose to
Kentucky in the South Regional. Twelve months later, they tied 1985
Georgetown as the largest point-spread favorites (9{) to lose a
national title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what we wanted,'' Moore said. ``This is the
game that we wanted to play, and this is the team we wanted to do
it against.''
</P>
<P>
   Another mad moment in March. A night to howl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
