<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKC-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES FINALLY REACH FINAL FORE 
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-RYAN COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Close down I-95. Just shut it down from
Clark's Falls to Westchester. Shut it down and turn it into one big
block party. The University of Connecticut Huskies are No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   No tricks, either. There were no tricks and no gimmicks. Jim
Calhoun lined up his athletes against Mike Krzyzewski's Duke
athletes to play a nice game of 40-minute basketball, and guess
what? Calhoun's were better.
</P>
<P>
   This was no Villanova-Georgetown anything-can-happen-in-one-game
miracle. This was a heavyweight title fight from the opening tip,
and we didn't need no stinkin' judges. We only needed to record
what we saw, and what we saw was an untainted, no-frills,
100-percent, totally legitimate 77-74 UConn victory.
</P>
<P>
   UConn? UConn? Yup, UConn! I'll say it again. UCONN!! The Huskies
of Art Quimby and Toby Kimball and Tony Hanson and Joey Whelton and
all those other nice New England players whose names meant zilch
outside the state lines have now graduated to the ultra big-time.
The University of Connecticut Huskies are the 1999 NCAA champions.
</P>
<P>
   UConn.
</P>
<P>
   The names to toast are Khalid El-Amin, the chunky and utterly
fearless guard who always sees to gravitate to the spotlight when
the game matters most, no matter what he has or hasn't been doing
earlier in the contest; Ricky Moore, the erstwhile defensive
specialist who turned the clock back to his high school big-scoring
days with a where-did-that-come-from? 13-point first half; nasty
Kevin Freeman, the King of Dirty Work; and, most of all, feathery
Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton, the 6-foot-6-inch junior who scored 27
points in the biggest game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget Calhoun, the kid from Braintree who learned
his basketball from the late, great Fred Herget. Think about this.
Coach K got whomped by a Wamp.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun will never have to apologize for anything again. They
pooh-poohed his phenomenal record in the '90s _ ``We've been
criticized for mere excellence,'' is the way he puts it _ because
he couldn't get to the Final Four. Now what will it be?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know. He shoulda won by 10.
</P>
<P>
   He did not seize the opportunity to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we won the national championship,'' he said. ``I am
no better coach now than I was three weeks ago. I am no worse a
coach now than I was three weeks ago. I don't have to prove
anything. I just want to be true to these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Those kids gave him everything but the rights to their
first-born.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played their hearts out,'' saluted Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   It was, without a shred of exaggeration, a great game, truly
worthy of a 1-2 designation. The first half may have been the best
display of the product in an NCAA title game since the epic
Kansas-Oklahoma first half 11 years ago. These were clearly the two
most complete teams in the country, replete with textbook players
at every position (and plenty of them), and extraordinarily
well-coached.
</P>
<P>
   If Coach K is, as Calhoun himself maintains, the ``coach of our
generation,'' Calhoun is a member of the Inner Sanctum Board of
Trustees. For, who knows? This may not even be his most talented
team. Maybe it is and maybe it isn't. I know I'd pay cash money to
see the '95 team that lost a 102-96 game to eventual champion UCLA
play this bunch. Ray Allen vs. Richard Hamilton? Hoo, baby. Pass
the beer and fill up the bowl of chips. I'm there.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has put team after wonderful team on the floor during
this decade, starting with the '89-90 bunch that came within a
miracle Christian Laettner shot of going to that Final Four. But
whatever he's done has never been enough for the stringent markers
down there in the Nutmeg State. Let's hope they recognize an A-plus
performance when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   There had to be a point sometime in the first half when Duke
knew it was in trouble. Duke simply had to know it was playing the
best opponent of the year, because Duke wasn't getting into its
offense at all. UConn was quicker and more aggressive. UConn was
every bit as basketball-smart. And UConn was surely as determined.
But Duke is still Duke, and despite being outplayed in many
departments, the 3-point shooting of Trajan Langdon gave them a
39-37 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Duke even went up by 5 (48-43), but over the next four minutes
the Huskies went on a 14-5 run to let Duke know this game was about
to go from merely being good to being a borderline epic. And how
about this? UConn was deeper. Coach K was forced to shorten his
rotation. There was absolutely no place for Chris Burgess in this
game, and not much of a spot for Nate James, either. Coach Calhoun
was even getting a contribution from Souleymane Wane, the pride of
Dakar, Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that this was a battle of equals. If they played
again, well, who knows? Coach K didn't even come close to making an
excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept the pressure on,'' he said. ``You have to give them
an immense amount of credit. Everything in the game was clean. They
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems redundant to point out that when UConn
absolutely, positively needed a play, it turned to the
extraordinary El-Amin. With the Huskies leading by a 73-72 score,
El-Amin slinked down the lane and tossed in a one-on-one 10-foot
leaner. And it was his two big free throws with 5.2 seconds
remaining that put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   But big plays by El-Amin hardly qualify as news in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   And two clutch defensive plays by the amazing Moore on Langdon
aren't bulletins, either. This is who the Huskies are. This is why
they are the new champs.
</P>
<P>
   UConn. The Yankee Conference and all those first-round tourney
KOs in the '50s and '60s. UConn, and Duke 101, UConn 54 in '64.
UConn, and the old field house.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Jim Calhoun left Huntington Ave. for Storrs and
brought a national vision to a parochial program. UConn is No. 1.
This is hard to digest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
