r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-ECONOMY-LADN     03-30 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-ECONOMY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SLOWDOWN FORECAST FOR STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California's economy, currently riding a
4-year-old wave of prosperity, is probably headed for a slowdown
sometime in 2000, according to a widely watched survey that will be
released today.
</P>
<P>
   But economic diversification in several regions including
Southern California and in some industry sectors will mute the
deceleration's impact, concludes the quarterly forecast from the
Anderson School at the University of California, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there has to be a limit to this expansion and the
longer it goes on the more concern we have about its
sustainability,'' said Tom K. Lieser, the executive director and
author of the California report at the Anderson School.
</P>
<P>
   California's recovery began in 1994 and accelerated in the
following year. The state has just completed its fourth consecutive
year of solid economic performance despite turmoil in international
markets with key trading partners. And the expansion of
California's economy during the last half of 1998 is carrying over
into this year, the business graduate school's survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey predicted nonfarm employment will expand by
3.4percent this year, off slightly from 1998's 3.6percent rate.
Jobs will grow at an annual rate of 3.6percent in this year's first
quarter and 4.4percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters expect unemployment in California to average
5.5percent this year and 5.6percent in 2000, somewhat higher than
the national rate but impressive in light of the predicted strong
growth in the size of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in personal income won't be as robust as in the past.
Personal income in California grew 6.6percent in 1998 but UCLA
believes it will taper off to 6.4percent this year and slow to
5.3percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation will continue to remain in check.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California Department of
Finance, notes that the state's economy is coming off three
consecutive years of growing by at least 3percent. ``That's pretty
strong and it's reasonable to expect one way or another there is
going to be some slowdown in 2000 and 2001,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while a slowing of the economy is likely, it still will
remain relatively strong, Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty good breadth in the mix of industries so if
we lose a driver, such as exports to Asia, we have been able to
make that up. It's hard to come up with a shock such as the loss of
the defense business we experienced in the late 1980s and early
1990s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are some factors that could speed the slowdown,
including the highly leveraged status of stocks in some of the
state's high-tech companies, the survey noted. Silicon Valley has
typically drawn high-risk investment in new companies by venture
capitalists seeking profits, but they are usually well-capitalized
and prepared to absorb periodic losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it has more recently become a primary focus of
so-called day trading, high-risk investment in existing companies
by amateurs,'' Lieser said of the region.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that there was an upside to the state's export
sector suffering more than the nation's from the Asian economic
crisis. ``That weakness has given a breather to Silicon Valley
manufacturers who were running out of room to expand and couldn't
fill all of their high-tech job openings anyway,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
