<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKC-UCONN-DUKE-BOS &LR;      03-30 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN IS THE 1 
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-UCONN-DUKE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ So much for this ``one of the greatest
teams in history'' business.
</P>
<P>
   On a magical night when Ricky Moore, Khalid El-Amin, and Richard
Hamilton made classic plays in the most pressure-filled situations,
a gutsy Connecticut team hung on and hung in to win its first
national championship, beating Duke, 77-74, before 41,340 at
Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (34-2) became the first New England team since Holy
Cross in 1947 to win a national championship in men's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (37-2), which had been called by some one of the greatest
teams of all time going into this NCAA Tournament _ and was a
9-point favorite Monday night _ tried its best to win its third
title this decade, but in the end did not have enough answers for
what UConn threw at it.
</P>
<P>
   This tightly contested game, in which a 5-point lead looked
enormous, came down to one key defensive play, provided by Moore,
who showed the skills that have made him a standout for four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, which found itself trailing in a game for the first time
since November, when it sustained its only other loss (to
Cincinnati), faced its greatest crisis of the season when Hamilton
(27 points, tournament MVP) pumped in a 3-pointer from the corner
with 3:38 left to give the Huskies a 73-68 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Chris Carrawell followed that by making one of two free
throws to cut the deficit to 4, 73-69, with 3:1l left.
</P>
<P>
   The game then turned into a series of mini-dramas, with each
possession holding enormous importance.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Huskies felt they could breathe a little bit
easier, Trajan Langdon, playing his last game for Duke, fired in a
22-foot jump shot from the right to make it 73-72 with 1:43 left.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, UConn faced its most important possession of
the season. El-Amin responded with a driving jump shot with 1:05
left to increase the lead to 75-72.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's William Avery was fouled and made both shots, making it
75-74.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies ran the clock down to 34.3 seconds before calling a
20-second timeout. El-Amin then threw up an airball, and Duke had
its chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   With 5.4 seconds left, Langdon drove to the basket but was
called for traveling on his spin as he could not get free of Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies took the ball out under the Duke basket and El-Amin
was fouled by Avery with 5.2 seconds left. He made both, and when
Langdon couldn't go the length of the court for a game-tying shot,
UConn had its championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question thse guys pulled it out with the help from
the guys before them,'' said UConn coach Jim Calhoun, referring to
former Husky stars such as Cliff Robinson and Ray Allen, the latter
of whom was so intent on seeing the Huskies win that he chartered a
plane to make it to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment for Duke was immense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Moore in the first half was the difference,'' said
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   Moore scored all 13 of his points in that first half to keep
UConn within 2 of the Blue Devils at the break, 39-37. He also was
the difference in the end, foiling Langdon's efforts and causing
the turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a move,'' said Langdon, who scored a team-high 25
points. ``I might have traveled. I might not have. That's the call.
That's the way the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, the senior guard who has played in the shadow of Allen,
Hamilton, and even El-Amin at UConn, made a statement with his
first half. No one was surprised at his defense, but his offense
(which included 9 of UConn's first 15 points) was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out to prove myself tonight,'' said Moore, who went to
high school with Avery in Augusta, Ga., and wanted to reestablish
the student-mentor relationship they had when Moore was a senior
and Avery a sophomore. ``I wanted to show everybody that I have an
offensive game as well as a defensive game.''
</P>
<P>
   He had more than enough of both. But UConn, like Duke, is not a
one-player team on any night. Monday night was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils went to all of their weapons. After a first half
in which he was harassed by a defense that sagged and swarmed over
him every time he touched the ball, Duke center Elton Brand broke
loose as the second half started. He was part of the reason Duke
took a 5-point lead in the first three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn, whose only two losses came when it was depleted
(missing Hamilton and center Jake Voskuhl), responded.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case all season, different people stepped up and
filled roles.
</P>
<P>
   First it was Moore. Then it was Hamilton, throwing in key
baskets when the game turned into a scoring derby. And then it was
El-Amin, who after committing a turnover and shooting an airball
came back to make the two most critical foul shots of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there was Calhoun, who was remarkably calm all week,
savoring the highest moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leading the parade, saying how good Duke was,'' said
Calhoun, ``but we felt all along we had a reasonable chance to beat
a great, great Duke team.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Huskies had more than a reasonable chance.
On a night when Duke expected to be crowned, it was the Huskies who
played like champions.
</P>
<P>
   National champions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 0217EST &QL; 
