<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATERS URGED TO BAN ADVANCE SALES TO STOP `MENACE' SCALPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scalpers, beware of the Force.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest wrinkle surrounding ``Star Wars Episode 1: Phantom
Menace,'' George Lucas and 20th Century Fox have asked theater
owners to ban advance ticket sales for the prequel when it opens
May 19 and for two weeks after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest fear is that if we sell tickets in advance,
scalping will take place and you and your families would either not
be able to get tickets or would have to pay above face value,''
said Tom Sherak, chairman of Fox Domestic Film Group, in a message
on the official ``Star Wars'' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sherak conceded Monday that the issue remains unresolved since
Fox cannot force theaters to ban advance sales. But he added that
the studio hopes to sway exhibitors by staking out its position
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   What's uncertain, however, is how much clout Lucas and Fox will
have with theater owners wanting to cash in on a movie expected to
eclipse ``Titanic's'' box office records.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations Co., said
theater chains will probably go along with the request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think exhibitors will agree because they want to maintain
the best possible relationship with Lucas and Fox,'' he explained.
``I think holding off on advance sales is a good idea. People are
going to cry foul if they stand in line and can't get tickets
because people on the phone have gotten them all.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, services such as MovieFone have enabled
moviegoers with credit cards to buy tickets by phone up to a week
in advance. ETM Entertainment Network announced plans this month
for presales of movie tickets through its network of kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   Dergarabedian said he was not surprised at the move, citing the
previous decree by Lucas and Fox that ``Menace'' be shown only in
theaters with state-of-the art sound. The studio plans to book
3,800 to 4,000 screens in about 2,000 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox is being very careful about every element on
distribution,'' Dergarabedian said. ``This will be quite an event
with a lot of camaraderie among the people standing in line, which
will build the excitement even further.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 0220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
