<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-UCONN-REWRIT     03-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-UCONN-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN STUNS DUKE FOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The pursuit of history ended here Monday
night with a brilliant collision, leaving a state in ecstasy and
the nation's No. 1 team without the crown required to validate its
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   In a frantic, fabulous 40 minutes, Connecticut did what few
thought possible and no team had done in four months: It stopped
the Duke machine with an airtight game plan, swarming defense and a
little help from a guard named Rip.
</P>
<P>
   Behind 27 points from All-American Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton,
Connecticut captured its first NCAA title _ and authored the
greatest chapter in the Nutmeg State's sporting history _ with a
breathtaking 77-74 victory over Duke before 41,340 at Tropicana
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the greatest games I've ever been involved
with,'' Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun said. ``The kids were saying
they wanted Duke instead of Michigan State. I said maybe the wiser
head knows better. But the kids knew better.''
</P>
<P>
   The buzzer sounded with Duke senior guard Trajan Langdon (25
points) sprawled on the court _ his full-court charge had ended
with a turnover _ and Calhoun embracing his assistants. Together,
they designed a masterful game plan that accentuated Connecticut's
strengths (its speed and one-on-one ability) and smothered Duke
center Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   But this night was as much about the losers as the winners.
Calhoun composed himself quickly, then hugged Blue Devils coach
Mike Krzyzewski, who departs the decade with two NCAA titles and
three title-game defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for hip replacement surgery next week, Krzyzewski left
the court with a methodical stride and stern expression _ one he
had seen before. Eight years ago today, his Devils stunned
supposedly unbeatable Nevada-Las Vegas in an equally riveting Final
Four duel in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, a team that couldn't be beaten once again whiffed
on history's fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But to put Connecticut's victory in the upset file alongside
North Carolina State over Houston and Villanova over Georgetown is
to ignore the Huskies' talent and accomplishments. They won 34
games, they won the Big East title, they beat Michigan State, St.
John's, Stanford and Ohio State, and they lost just one game
(Miami) with Hamilton in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're shocked,'' Calhoun said. ``We're happy as
heck, we're proud, but I don't think anyone's shocked. We truly
felt we could beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have much company. The Blue Devils eliminated
Connecticut from the tournament in 1990 _ Christian Laettner's
last-second shot _ and 1991. They have the most talent, one of the
best coaches ever, and they dominated the regular season like no
team since ill-fated UNLV in '91. The tournament gives, and the
tournament takes away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were a 10-point underdog, and we felt that was
ridiculous and we felt that hurt our pride,'' Connecticut point
guard Khalid El-Amin said. ``We wanted to come out and prove
everyone wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Their quest started with strategy. Realizing it was no match for
Duke in a half-court game, Connecticut opened with full-court
pressure and pushed its fastbreak at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of backing down from the Durham bully, the Huskies
attacked. They spread Duke's man-to-man defense and used their
speed to slash into the lane and create scoring chances. Senior
guard Ricky Moore shed his reputation as a defensive specialist and
scored nine of Connecticut's first 15 points, but the main man was
Hamilton. He was too quick for Duke, and his jumper was right all
night.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hit 10 of 22 shots, then gave way to El-Amin, whose
short jumper from the left side with 1:05 left gave Connecticut a
75-72 lead and proved to be the winning shot. Duke's best chance
collapsed when Langdon, matched against Moore, traveled on his way
through the lane with five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, positively, I want Trajan to take that shot,''
Krzyzewski said. ``I'll win or lose with Trajan. I'll walk down any
road with Trajan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies edged to a 36-32 lead late in the half when Langdon
singlehandedly changed the momentum. He buried a 3-pointer from the
top of the key, then drained a 3-pointer from the left wing as
Moore fouled him. The rare four-point play gave Duke a narrow lead
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon kept his rhythm through intermission and scored five
quick points to open the second half. When William Avery found
Brand for a dunk and Chris Carrawell did the same to Shane Battier,
the Blue Devils had carved a 48-43 lead and seemed on the verge of
a game-breaking surge.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut reserve Albert Mouring slowed Duke's momentum
with a 12-footer from the lane, and Connecticut scored on its next
six possessions. Its margin expanded to 65-59 on Hamilton's jumper
from the left wing with nine minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Duke responded immediately. Brand blocked a Hamilton shot, then
raced downcourt to receive Avery's pass for a layup. Two
possessions later, Carrawell's mid-range jumper trimmed
Connecticut's lead to 65-63, and he tied it with 4:50 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The final minutes were riveting, beginning with Hamilton's
3-pointer from the left wing that gave Connecticut a 73-68 lead.
Two minutes later, Battier grabbed an improbable rebound and fed
Langdon for a 3-pointer _ right wing, 1:40 left _ that brought Duke
within one point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 0233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-GRIZZLIES-     03-30 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-GRIZZLIES-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT GRIZZLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ As if the Los Angeles Lakers haven't been
shaky enough lately, the schedule took its best shot.
</P>
<P>
   From playing the New York Knicks on national TV on Sunday, the
Lakers hosted the Vancouver Grizzlies on basic cable on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Lakers were rolling right now, which they are not,
that's a recipe for a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in that they were coming off a literally hard-fought
victory over the Knicks and playing their 17th game in March, and
it was clear this could be a long evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the Lakers took their time before knocking out
Vancouver 116-98 before 17,312 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there wasn't enough energy in certain situations,''
point guard Derek Harper said. ``We've played a lot of games of
late and you have to grind out a win in a game like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``After an emotional game like yesterday, it was (tough). But we
were able to put them away and that was encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The way things have been going, any win is appreciated, though
only slightly more than a day off.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers (21-11) have played more games than any team in the
league, and a matchup with the lowly Grizzlies wasn't going to be
enough to jumpstart their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a couple steps slow today,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``It
was one of those games.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had a career-low one rebound in 34 minutes. His previous
career low was three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had more than that,'' O'Neal said, after insulting the
statistician.
</P>
<P>
   How many? ``Three,'' O'Neal answered playfully.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain how Dennis Rodman had 17 rebounds and the
rest of the team had just 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played down to our opponent,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis
said. ``We did what we had to do and that's basically the end of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until Glen Rice hit a 3-pointer with less than five minutes
left to give the Lakers a 100-84 advantage did the fans feel
comfortable enough to head for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   It just wasn't any way to be playing the Grizzlies, who came to
the Forum with a 5-23 record, and without center Bryant Reeves, who
has been out more than a week with a knee injury. Not to mention
starting an all-rookie backcourt of Mike Bibby and Felipe Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Lakers have gone just 5-5 in their past 10 games,
perhaps it wasn't totally unexpected they struggled with Vancouver.
Maybe the Lakers were worn out from all the shoving and scuffling
the previous day with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we came out a little flat,'' Rice said. ``I know
that Vancouver defeated the Lakers before and we didn't want that
to happen again. In the fourth quarter we came up big and really
slammed the door on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers unimpressively held a 75-67 lead entering the fourth
quarter, but outscored the Grizzlies by 10 in the final period,
with Rice scoring 12 points and Rick Fox adding 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers got a terrific boost from their bench, with Fox
scoring 17 points and center Sean Rooks scoring a season-high 11
points with six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the ever-vigilant Rodman watch, the erratic forward
started again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play the guys that are going to get the job
done,'' Rodman said. ``For me, I have to start, I have to get my
motor running and at least get an idea of what I have to get done.
I'm accustomed to doing certain things and I hope this team
respects me for doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm going to come here and be the star of the
team. I came here to win, that's the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers may have been a little out of it after playing the
Knicks, but their defense was better than average. They had a
season-high 16 steals and Vancouver committed 25 turnovers, the
most for a Lakers opponent all season.
</P>
<P>
   They also had a season-high 31 assists.
</P>
<P>
   But they were happiest after the game about having today off, a
welcome occurrence with the lockout schedule forcing them to play
so many games in a short period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for the guys, they have (a day) off, to
mentally get away from the game, physically get themselves a little
bit of rest'' Rambis said. ``We're still in a transition period
with this ballclub so we have to come back to work to get geared up
for the next run of games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not escape the lowly Grizzlies without an injury.
Forward Robert Horry suffered a strained left hip flexor in the
first half and did not return. His status is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Horry will get at least three days to rest, however, since the
Lakers are off until Friday, when they play at Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
