<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CIENFUEGOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SHOULD SHOW CIENFUEGOS THE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rarely do people side with the athlete in a
contract dispute. But in Mauricio Cienfuegos' case, the Los Angeles
Galaxy should show him the money.
</P>
<P>
   He's underpaid, his team is owned by a billionaire and he's
worth as much to Major League Soccer as any player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what Cienfuegos did to win the hearts of his
countrymen in El Salvador, but the Salvadoran population in Los
Angeles clearly loves and supports him. There is, in fact, talk of
a Salvadoran boycott if he decides to leave the team Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jorge Campos left last year, there has been no bigger
attraction than the 5-foot-5 wizard. Ask anyone in the Galaxy's
front office and they will tell you Cienfuegos is a big reason Los
Angeles led the league in attendance in two of its first three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Paul Caligiuri talk about the three-time MLS
all-star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those players who makes everyone around him
better,'' Caligiuri said. ``If you compare him to basketball, you
think of Magic Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   But unless something dramatic happens in the next 48hours,
Cienfuegos will board a plane for El Salvador and likely never
return to the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   In the off-season, Cienfuegos hired sports agent Corey
Clemetson, the same man who represented Caligiuri in his successful
lawsuit against the MLS two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson told Cienfuegos his $106,000 contract is well under
the league maximum, which is said to be $230,000. Clemetson also
explained he believes players are earning figures in the
million-dollar range after signing incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming all this is true, a million for Cienfuegos isn't a bad
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Galaxy president Tim Leiweke claimed that spending
$30 to $40million to build a new stadium for the Galaxy was pocket
change for new owner Phillip F. Anschutz. So what does that makes
Cienfuegos' asking price? Pennies.
</P>
<P>
   It also is in the league's best interest to accommodate him. To
replace a foreign player of Cienfuegos' caliber on and off the
field would require a transfer fee of at least a million dollars,
and the league still would have to pay a hefty contract.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, lies with MLS' single-entity concept, in
which the league negotiates all the contracts, instead of
individual owners and general managers. But where is this league
headed if a billionaire owner can't help his financial stake in the
league by securing a valuable player?
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is that Cienfuegos isn't asking for a million
dollars. He is believed to be asking for roughly $500,000 (which
the league can make up with incentives). Cienfuegos has said
countless times that he is willing to meet the league halfway.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the league hadn't changed its stance. It offered
Cienfuegos a 15percent raise at one point -- a slap in the face if
Clemetson's figures are correct.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure how this will play out. Last week,
Cienfuegos ended his season-long holdout for 10 days so the two
sides could work toward an agreement. But nothing has changed
since.
</P>
<P>
   MLS and the Galaxy surely will pay the price if he leaves. In a
year in which attendance is vital to the league's growth,
Cienfuegos' absence figures to be a hefty blow to attendance.
</P>
<P>
   In an age in which some athletes earn a salary equal to the
worth of some sports franchises, Cienfuegos' asking price is hardly
unreasonable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
