<SLUG> BC-SOC-AZUSA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZUSA PACIFIC TO BE PRACTICE SITE FOR '99 WOMEN'S WORLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-NYT.AZUSA (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO 
San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AZUSA, Calif. _ Azusa Pacific University will serve as a
practice site for the 1999 Women's World Cup, officials announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, which will be televised to more than 60
countries worldwide, begins June 19 and ends July 10, with the
championship and third-place matches to be played at the Rose Bowl.
Teams from 16 countries will compete at seven venues throughout the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl also is the site of a first-round June 20
doubleheader, pitting Germany against Italy and Korea against
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Four days before the first-round match, Germany and Korea will
train at APU. In the week leading up to the championship game, the
WWC organizing committee will decide which of the final four
participating teams will use APU's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Finn, director of public relations for the WWC, said the
Galaxy's willingness to train at APU on occasions helped with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``With (the Galaxy) there, it showed there was something good
about that school,'' Finn said. ``We just didn't pluck this out of
nowhere. A German official was there last week and was satisfied
with the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, the overall quality of the field is
very good. They have put some care into that surface, and we feel
it best mirrors the conditions of the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   APU men's soccer coach Don Lawrence said the school is delighted
to be part of the event. With two of the teams staying at Arcadia
hotels, the short ride to APU and its well-maintained fields played
a big role in the WWC's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a solid field, as far as training,'' Lawrence said.
``Our surface is similar to the Rose Bowl, and this is a good
atmosphere for teams to come and train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, we have made sure we can take care of the privacy
part. We have security and locker rooms that are efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence also said it will be good for the neighboring
community, as well as APU's 1998 NAIA women's championship soccer
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a good opportunity for our women to sit in the
stands and watch the training sessions,'' he said. ``They will be
able to see first-hand what it is like on the next level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
