<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ABORTION RIGHT TIED TO 2000 ELECTION  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the nation's leading abortion advocates
warned Monday that if the next president elected is opposed to a
woman's right to end her pregnancy, that protection is likely to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, made her prediction after
addressing several hundred boisterous supporters gathered in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The event celebrating the 30th anniversary of NARAL resembled a
political pep rally with rhetorical speeches by California Gov.
Gray Davis and Michelman, underscoring the national effort to make
abortion a pivotal issue in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get an anti-choice president in the year 2000, we will
see the overthrow of Roe vs. Wade,'' said Michelman after the
luncheon, referring to the landmark 1973 U.S. Supreme Court
decision establishing a woman's constitutional right to an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that if two of the justices who form the majority
supporting abortion rights are replaced by abortion opponents, it
will mean the end of the constitutional right. For instance, she
said, it is possible that Justice John Paul Stevens, a liberal who
is 78, could leave the court in the next few years, as well as
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, a crucial swing vote. O'Connor, 69,
has had a history of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   In its last major decision on the issue, a divided Supreme Court
in 1992 reinforced the right to have an abortion but allowed states
to impose certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect that the freedom to choose will be a major
issue in the presidential campaign,'' said Michelman, whose group
is pouring millions of dollars into a campaign to keep the issue
near the top of the political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been running a series of television ads in Iowa
and New Hampshire that accuse two Republican presidential
candidates of trying to hide their anti-abortion positions.
Michelman said that their next step is to air the ads in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole has declined
to state where she stands on the divisive issue, and Texas Governor
George Bush Jr. has stated that he would allow abortions only in
the cases of rape, incest or where the mother's life is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But Michelman said that the two Republican front-runners are
trying to portray themselves as moderates as part of a campaign
strategy to maintain distance from the far right.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to obscure their views and say they're in the
middle. We can't let them get away with that,'' she said. ``It is
important for us to get in early and not let them establish
themselves based on erroneous information.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelman, who has been at the forefront of the abortion battle
for decades, admits that one of the biggest challenges will be
getting the attention of abortion supporters who think that the
fight has already been won.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest threats in the last six years has been the
complacency of pro-choice people,'' she said, citing in particular
the generation of young men and women who grew up after abortion
was an established constitutional right.
</P>
<P>
   Because of threats to doctors and numerous state laws
restricting abortion rights, Michelman said, ``it is harder today
in 1999 for women to exercise their right to choose than anytime
since Roe vs. Wade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 0332EST &QL; 
