<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SETTLEMENT TALKS TO START IN MICROSOFT ANTITRUST SUIT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Settlement talks are to begin Tuesday between the
Justice Department and Microsoft Corp., but the two sides remain
miles apart on the core issues of their antitrust battle.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders familiar with the case estimated the probability of a
settlement at zero to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, the 19 state attorneys general who joined the
federal government's suit against the software behemoth want
Microsoft to auction off the heart of the company _ the secret code
to the Windows operating system used on roughly 90 percent of the
world's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, Microsoft has offered to make relatively modest
changes to its business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of posturing going on,'' said Daniel
Wall, a San Francisco antitrust attorney who worked for the Justice
Department on the breakup of AT&AMP;T in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The government has charged Microsoft with wielding monopoly
power over personal computing software to stifle competition.
Microsoft denies both having a monopoly and doing anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The states' proposal to auction off the Windows source code ``is
ludicrous as an antitrust remedy,'' Wall said, ``so they can't be
serious if they think either that Microsoft would agree to it or
that they would go into court and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   But an industry player opposed to Microsoft argued that the
government is winning in court and has every reason to press hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have your opponent on the canvas and he says he's
ready to settle, it's not surprising that the guy who's hitting him
says, let's finish the bout,'' this source said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department refused to comment Monday on the talks,
which Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson had urged during a trial recess
that could continue through mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates emphasized Monday that although
his company remains open to settlement talks, any agreement must
protect both Windows' ``integrity'' and the company's right to
integrate new features into Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The last settlement talks collapsed nearly a year ago on the
brink of the government's filing of the lawsuit, and matters hardly
look more promising today, after months of court battle that has at
the very least bruised Microsoft's public image.
</P>
<P>
   Under the states' proposal, Microsoft would be forced to auction
its Windows intellectual property to two or three outside
companies, while keeping a copy for itself to develop. Microsoft
shareholders would get ``reasonable compensation'' under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the Windows source code, Microsoft's lifeblood, would
``actually break up and render impotent the Windows monopoly, which
is the source of Microsoft's power,'' the state plan said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made its own four-page settlement proposal last
Wednesday, offering to stop making exclusive contracts with other
companies to enhance sales of its products, and to allow computer
makers to alter the first screen that users see when they turn on
their computers.
</P>
<P>
   But the government dismissed the proposal as meaningless, saying
the company has already ceded that ground under pressure from the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has done no more than offer what they did before
trial started,'' said Kevin Arquit, an antitrust lawyer at Rogers &AMP;
Wells in New York and a former antitrust official at the Federal
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to Microsoft, giving up the Windows code would be tantamount
to total surrender. And some outside lawyers believe that the
appellate courts would never force the company to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both sides have reasons to settle. For the government,
the longer the case goes on, the greater the risk that changes in
the fast-paced technology industry will make its case obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision by Judge Jackson is almost sure to be appealed,
ensuring at least two more years in court.
</P>
<P>
   The government also risks losing the case, or winning on such
narrow grounds as to yield a hollow victory.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, meanwhile, also  &LR; faces the risk of losing or _ almost
as bad from its view _ being legally  &LR; declared a monopoly, which
could open the door to a crippling wave of private litigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
