<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKLUSTER MAVS FALL TO SUPERSONICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Somewhere out there in America, Jim Cleamons is
probably laughing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's because Cleamons is assured of having a better record
during his 98-game tenure as the Mavericks coach than the man who
fired him, Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton and Detlef Schrempf scored 20 points apiece as the
Seattle SuperSonics defeated Nelson's Mavericks, 109-101, Monday
night before an announced crowd of 13,311 at Reunion Arena. The
loss pushed Nelson's record to 26-71 since he took over for
Cleamons as the Mavericks' coach Dec. 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson gave Cleamons the ax and became the Mavericks' coach
after the 16th game of the 1997-98 season, Cleamons ended his
Mavericks' coaching tenure with a 28-70 record. More than a year
later, the landscape is basically the same at Reunion _ only the
leadership at the top has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was puzzled the Mavericks (10-21) put up no more than a
meager showing against a Seattle team that was ambushed, 104-87,
Sunday in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not a good effort by our team, and I'm a little
surprised by it,'' Nelson said. ``I really thought we'd be ready to
play tonight; this was what I considered a winnable game for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Sonics) approached it as a much-needed win for them. The
bottom line is we just had a hard time controlling Payton. He
played a terrific game, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's Mavericks have lost seven of their past nine games and
will play in Minneapolis tonight, where they battle the Minnesota
Timberwolves at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Only a 44-point performance by the Mavericks in the fourth
quarter prevented Monday night's game from being a complete
wash-out. It was the most points the Mavericks have scored in a
quarter since they racked up 46 in the fourth quarter Feb. 29, 1996
against the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were 4-of-20 from the field in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense isn't running as smooth as it has,'' Nelson said.
``I can't give you all the answers, but we couldn't run plays out
there in the third period.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trent, recovering from a stomach virus that has been
bothering him for 11 days, kept the Mavericks within striking
distance. Trent finished with 20 points and nine rebounds, and his
layup moved the Mavericks within 52-44 early in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But Billy Owens, Payton and Schrempf took control the rest of
the period, and the Sonics eventually built an 81-60 lead before
coasting down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they took us out of our rhythm,'' said Erick
Strickland, who logged a season-high 39 minutes in making his first
start of the year. ``Everybody's shots were there all night; they
just didn't fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland finished with 17 points, seven assists and four
steals, while reserve forward Samaki Walker pitched in with 10
points, 13 rebounds and three blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to come out with more energy,'' Walker said.
``Normally in the game we'll have some spurts, and tonight I didn't
see that. They had control from the beginning to the end.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
