<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LIKELY WON'T DEAL FOR A'S ROGERS THIS SPRING
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers continue to scout Oakland
Athletics pitcher Kenny Rogers, but general manager Doug Melvin
said a deal isn't likely during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll listen, but I don't think he's that available,''
Melvin said. ``Most clubs feel they want to start the season with
their best pitching staffs and wait until the season to make a
deal. They feel there's a better chance of a team panicking in
July. I think it will be hard to upgrade dramatically in spring
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said a number of clubs have asked about Esteban Loaiza,
who is in danger of losing his spot in the rotation to Mike Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to listen to anybody,'' Melvin said. GONZALEZ BACK
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Juan Gonzalez returned to the Rangers' lineup after
spending the weekend in Puerto Rico with his ailing mother. He
missed three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is all right,'' Gonzalez said. ``She's getting
better.'' RELIEF SHINES
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers received four scoreless innings from relievers Eric
Gunderson, Danny Patterson and Tim Crabtree, the trio of pitchers
who will have to serve as the closer committee should John
Wetteland not be ready for Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said the performances were encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get people out,'' Oates said. ``Gundy has been
good all spring, Patty has had some good outings and Crabby turned
it up a notch today.'' GAME RECAP DEVIL RAYS 8, RANGERS 1
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays scored seven runs in the third inning and
defeated the Rangers at Al Lang Field. Bobby Witt held his
ex-teammates to one run on four hits through five innings. The
Rangers have lost four of five.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate: Tom Goodwin went 2-for-3 with a run-scoring single
in the fifth off Tampa Bay starter Witt. It was his second run
batted in during 54 at-bats this spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound: After two strong starts, John Burkett was smacked
around by the Devil Rays, allowing eight runs in five innings. The
Devil Rays scored seven of those runs in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had one bad inning and four good ones,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett allowed eight hits, walked three and struck out two.
Opponents are hitting .275 off him this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In the field: Gonzalez misplayed Bubba Trammell's line drive for
a three-base error with no outs in the second inning. But Trammell
didn't score. Third baseman Scott Sheldon made two nice backhanded
stops on grounders, and left fielder Rusty Greer made a sliding
catch on Kevin Stocker's line drive to end the inning. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
