</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE JOKES, BUT HELLING CLOSEST TO ACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ For a good laugh from most of the
baseball world, just suggest this spring that Rick Helling will
repeat as a 20-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, such rampant disbelief signals Helling is gaining
in respect. What has become laughable this March was unthinkable a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, manager Johnny Oates selected Helling as the
Texas Rangers' Opening Day starter. This bit of non-news provided
final proof both Randy Johnson and Roger Clemens had officially
declined the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the scene with the wood-chopper machine in the movie
``Fargo?'' Having advanced from a career-high five victories in a
season to 20 in 1998, Fargo-native Helling finds his head stuck in
a baseball version of the same device. A majority opinion around
the game has Helling being reduced to shavings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as mentally tough as Helling is, and as much bulldog as
he's got in him, I kinda like him constantly hearing this spring
how he can't or won't,'' general manager Doug Melvin said Monday.
``Rick has the right kind of attitude to repeat last season, just
out of spite.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Melvin and the Rangers didn't intend for it to be
this way. Helling also didn't spend the winter trapped in a
snowbank in Fargo _ the Rangers pursuit of baseball's best
available No. 1s was interesting reading in North Dakota. But when
Johnson and Clemens declined, the responsibility came back to
Helling, who has had a decent spring _ easily the best of the
Rangers' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the ``Sports Illustrated'' staff of baseball writers
has any definitive answers, but this week the magazine rated the
Rangers the seventh-best team in the majors. Add Johnson or Clemens
to the rotation, and that ranking goes to third, or maybe second to
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a questionable rotation has been a 27-year tradition
in Arlington. The difference this time, however, is the Rangers
will be leaving Florida on Thursday with their best-ever collection
of everyday talent. Oh, for a true No. 1 pitcher. How good could
this club be?
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody else had the No. 1, we'd feel worse,'' Melvin
said. ``The truth is, very few teams have that ace because there
aren't many aces. You can pursue them in free agency. You can try
to trade for one. We've done both. We thought we were close, but
close doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do like is we've got a Helling, and he's a tough,
durable guy who had a breakthrough season in '98. I don't mind
giving the ball to Rick and asking him to lead the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, 28, spent most of his career scuffling to be noticed by
the Rangers after being drafted in the first round out of Stanford
in 1992. After being traded to Florida in '96, Melvin re-acquired
him a year later.
</P>
<P>
   For a career comparison, Melvin points to the Phillies' Curt
Schilling, although Helling is not that type of strikeout king.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Schilling is on everybody's list as a true No. 1
pitcher,'' said Melvin, ``and he's won 84 games in his career.
Schilling is 32, and his stock has jumped mainly in the last two
years. A lot of teams made a mistake on Schilling before he was 30
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Baltimore front-office assistant, Melvin recalled the great
deal the Orioles made _ trading veteran pitcher Mike Boddicker to
the Red Sox for a couple of youngsters named Schilling and Brady
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then (the Orioles) thought we just had to have a power
hitter, and made an awful trade,'' said Melvin of the trade that
sent Schilling, Steve Finley and Pete Harnisch to the Astros for
Glenn Davis.
</P>
<P>
   A year later (1992), the Astros also blundered. Schilling was
dealt to the Phillies for pitcher Jason Grimsley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three different clubs had a true No. 1 in Schilling and didn't
even know it,'' said Melvin. `` A lot of times it takes a while to
find out. Rick overcame much doubt and adversity to have his
breakthrough season. I'm just glad we got him back so he could do
it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin recalled a chance meeting with Helling last season in a
room off the visitors' clubhouse at Coors Field in Denver. ``I
walked in before the game, and Rick was in there alone. Two TVs
were on. One had ``The Jerry Springer Show.'' The other had a tape
of the Colorado hitters. Rick was ignoring Springer. Like always,
he was absorbed in his pitching homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Melvin added, ``Believe me, I've seen far too many
Springer fans in the clubhouse before a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The laughter has been heard this spring. Come Monday, Helling
begins his reply. The Rangers have a lot riding on that answer. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
