A9279 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UGA-COACH-COX     03-30 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia trims search for basketball coach to three finalists
 &HT;    (EDS: Must credit The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Newspapers.)
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley said
Monday that the interview process for a new basketball coach has
been completed and a new coach could be named as early as
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley and UGA president Michael Adams are expected to choose
from three finalists that emerged from interviews conducted in St.
Petersburg last weekend - Mike Brey of Delaware, Rhode Island's Jim
Harrick and Buzz Peterson of Appalachian State. In the last week,
Dooley has interviewed Brey, Harrick, Peterson, Jim Crews of
Evansville, Georgia assistant coach Jerry Waters and former St.
John's coach Fran Fraschilla, who has accepted the New Mexico job.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley is searching for a replacement for Ron Jirsa, who was
fired March 11 after only two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a few other names, but I don't think we'll
interview them,'' said Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   Brey, 39, first interviewed with Dooley March 21 in Atlanta and
had a second interview Saturday in St. Petersburg, Fla., while
attending the Final Four. But Brey, a former Duke assistant who has
led Delaware to the NCAA tournament the last two years, is also a
leading candidate for the vacant Notre Dame post along with
Xavier's Skip Prosser and reportedly is awaiting word from the
Fighting Irish before announcing his intentions. When contacted
Monday in Tampa, Brey declined to discuss the Georgia coaching
search.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not comment on that situation right now,'' said
Brey, who turned down the Auburn job five years ago. ``I would love
to comment on it eventually, but I just can't right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick, 60, won a national championship at UCLA in 1995 and has
led Rhode Island to two straight NCAA appearances. One sticking
point for Harrick could be Georgia's nepotism policy, which would
prevent him from hiring his son, Jim Harrick Jr., on his staff if
he came to Georgia, but said he would not rule out the possibility
if the job was offered to him.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, 35, is the former North Carolina player who has been
endorsed by former coach Dean Smith and former teammate Michael
Jordan. He was the first of the finalists to have a second
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
