r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN31-CO     03-30 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds look to solve pitching question
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ An American League scout sat behind the
screen at City of Palms Park Monday, casually asking questions
about the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many pitchers will they carry?'' the man asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten? Ten? How can they do that? Their bullpen arms will be
dangling like cooked spaghetti strands by May,'' he said. ``I mean,
check out their starters. Other than Brett Tomko, they don't have
guys who will go more than five innings.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an astute observer, a guy worth the price of his straw
hat and sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Avery pitched against his old teammates, the Boston Red
Sox Sunday, still unable to spin the numbers on the radar gun above
84 miles an hour, mostly hitting 81 to 82 during his 91-pitch day
</P>
<P>
   He owns one complete game since 1995 and is known these days as
a five-and-fly guy _ five innings and which way to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, though, he worked six innings, giving up three runs
on two hits, walking five and striking out five. The Reds won,
12-4, behind two home runs by outfielder Jeffrey Hammonds, who
leads the team with four, and a seven-run third inning that
included home runs by Brian Johnson, Dmitri Young and Aaron Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bere is just now regaining full strength in the surgically
repaired elbow that took nearly three years of intensive care and
recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Harnisch regressed last week when back spasms hit, forcing
him to skip a start and pushed him back in the stretching-out
process for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle won't be ready until mid-April, at the earliest,
and when he returns he won't be ready for long outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, we should be looking at 12 pitchers,'' manager Jack
McKeon said. ``Even 11 would help. We carried 11 most of last
season. With the make-up of this staff, this is the wrong year to
go with 10. . .but I understand the situation and we'll make it
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even general manager Jim Bowden agrees 12 is the number he'd
like, but 10 is the working figure. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Four reasons: Mark Lewis. Jeffrey Hammonds. Michael Tucker. Hal
Morris. All four are extra players with guaranteed contracts.
Unless Bowden makes another trade, he can do nothing with these
players but keep them, leaving no room for extra pitchers. And he
doesn't want to trade any of the four. . .if it were possible.
</P>
<P>
   Two of baseball's astute managers, Colorado's Jim Leyland and
St. Louis' Tony La Russa, are filling their roster with 12
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that the Reds will have only five bullpen
occupants and the workload will be burdensome, maybe strenuous, for
guys like Scott Williamson, John Hudek, Scott Sullivan, Danny
Graves and Gabe White.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of those five bullpenners, Sullivan, hasn't
pitched since last Wednesday when he left a game with a strained
left buttocks. The plan is an inning for Sullivan today against the
New York Yankees, or as pitching coach Don Gullett said, ``We
anticipate Sullivan being ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good with the bullpen, though. Sullivan's spring
earned run average is 0.82 (one run in 11 innings over eight
appearances), White has not allowed a run in his last nine
appearances, Williamson has not allowed a run in his last nine
appearances (10.2 innings) and his ERA over 12 appearances is 0.61.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sure getting a lot of work and it is going to take its
toll. . .and I don't see how we can go with only 10 pitchers,''
Hudek said.
</P>
<P>
   Gullett watched Harnisch throw for 12 minutes in the bullpen
Monday morning, after Harnisch begged off an attempt Sunday. He
threw 12 minutes Saturday, but felt tightness in his back Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used all his pitches again (Monday),'' Gullett said. ``He
is on schedule to pitch Wednesday (against Philadelphia). A game
situation, facing hitters, is a big test. We'd like to see 75 to 80
pitches, but it depends on how he is going, whether he is smooth
and throwing with no problems.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch gave up 12 runs and nine hits in 2 1/3 innings against
Detroit on March 16 and hasn't pitched since, leaving his Opening
Day assignment in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he is feeling, McKeon said, ``I'd feel a lot better if
our pitchers threw strikes and quit walking people. Avery was fine,
but five walks. . .that's gotta go down. Two of 'em scored.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
