<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ I take the issue of underage drinking
personally, very personally. Especially where it concerns adults _
parents _ throwing parties and making alcohol available to
youngsters. Not just their own. Other people's kids. My kids.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what goes through their minds as they watch the
teen-agers get in their cars and drive away after the party,
putting their young lives in danger, as well as other people's
lives, including mine and my kids'.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they think they are super cool parents because, well, kids
are going to drink anyway. And they drank when they were kids, and
survived. Oh, and giving ``supervised'' drinking parties allows
them to keep an eye on the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Don't do me any favors.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder about those who have been cited for their law-breaking
ways, providing alcohol to minors, and what went through their
minds as they saw their misguided efforts result in their child or
someone else's child
</P>
<P>
   becoming a criminal. In Texas, a citation to a minor in
possession of alcohol is no traffic ticket. It becomes part of an
individual's criminal record. But maybe those adults' twisted logic
holds that as another one of
</P>
<P>
   those rites of passage and that makes it OK.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Alcohol has passed over these lips. But I'm not
selfish or stupid enough to give it to my children, who are all
still underage, or to make it available to them. Neither am I such
a bonehead that I'd give it
</P>
<P>
   to your kids.
</P>
<P>
   It gets even more personal. I have watched a talented family
member waste his life away, a slave to alcohol. Some adult was
trying to be cool with him and saw no harm in introducing him to a
cold beer. Now in his late 50s, he still battles the demon. I've
watched him and his bottle destroy two marriages. I've watched his
parents suffer as he dies slowly before their eyes. I've watched
his son become an alcoholic. And I dread the day I get
</P>
<P>
   the telephone call telling me this person I love dearly is dead
or that he has gotten behind the wheel and killed someone.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he has been through countless programs and treatment
facilities but alcohol is still winning the game he started playing
long before he was 21.
</P>
<P>
   If it is ingrained in your family's culture to introduce alcohol
to minors, if you believe you must absolutely do so, then keep it
at your house. Do not be a distributor to other people's children,
especially mine. And do not
</P>
<P>
   serve alcohol to young people and then send them out in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Stupidity such as this has a way of coming back to bite you,
hard. It is commendable that the Texas Legislature is considering
laws against minors who are found in possession of alcohol, but we
need stricter laws and much
</P>
<P>
   higher fines for those adults who provide it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the possibility of sharing a criminal record with their
child would deter some of our free-wheeling adults. I've also heard
angry parents say they would seriously consider a lawsuit against
those who provide alcohol to their kids.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is it never needs to get that far _ if adults would
stop acting like children.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
