<HEADER>
A9386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN31-COX     03-30 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush has one way to get around First Amendment: the old end run
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush and John Cornyn may be on to
something asserting that a court-ordered ban on prayer at football
games violates Texans' freedom of religion.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe, as most Texans do, that football is religion,
the governor and our new attorney general are paydirt-bound in the
appeal they plan. On the other hand, if they assert that the
Constitution gives the majority power to make sports events
religious events, they have some selling to do.
</P>
<P>
   The latter being the apparent case, Bush, who claims to be an
education governor, is giving children a most damaging civics
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   In words and actions he is patronizing those who cling to an
absurdity: that majority-rule religion is a ``constitutional
right''; that if the majority can't impose religion on others, the
rights of those in the majority are denied.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable why Bush would take that position,
politically. After all, he needs the votes of those who live in the
Wobegon world where every kid is above average and Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is not so homogenous. But some genes have more political
capital. So those who support majority-imposed school prayer _
decided by the students if not by the principal or school board _
need not worry that Islam, Buddhism, Judaism, Taoism or Scientology
would come from the loudspeakers as students sharpened their
pencils or as gridiron warriors prepped their cleats.
</P>
<P>
   The too-common argument on behalf of school prayer is not what
you'd sell to a judge: ``We had it when I was in school. So what of
it?''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court that in 1963 ruled against organized school
prayer (the ``Lord's Prayer'' in that case) has been depicted as
Satan's servant, as some mortals cavalierly ``taking God out of the
classroom.'' None of those whose umbrage still overflows from that
moral affront seem to acknowledge that after the court in '63 did
what it did, courts subsequently affirmed it over and over and over
and over. The 5th Circuit Court did it again on the issue of
majority-rule prayer at football games.
</P>
<P>
   You see, courts aren't operating under the ``we had it when I
was a kid'' standard. They are examining the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Just once I want school-prayer backers to have the intellectual
honesty, instead of saying ``the courts took prayer out of
schools'' (they did not; students can pray to themselves any time
they wish), to say ``the Constitution doesn't appear to allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is implied in attempts to amend the Constitution to allow
organized school prayer. The Warren Court isn't Satan's servant,
ladies and gentlemen. The First Amendment is.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue Cornyn will challenge is the court's limiting
graduation ceremonies to ``nonsectarian'' or ``nonproselytizing''
prayer. The court ruled that graduation is a sufficiently solemn
event for an invocation not to be construed as an invasion of
religious rights, but said solemnity doesn't give the majority the
authority to impose sectarian prayer on a public-school audience.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-prayer? If anything, this decision bends over backwards to
rationalize state-established religion _ not a particular sect but
religion unto itself. We don't have to go so far as the ghost of
Madalyn Murray O'Hair to raise questions about that. We can call on
Baylor University religious liberty scholar James Wood, whose motto
is: ``There is no freedom of religion without freedom from
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we aren't there and we won't be, and we can live with
that. We also can live with prayer at football games. But the fact
is, a majority imposing its sectarianism on others at a school
event is exactly what what the establishment clause forbids.
</P>
<P>
   However, if we can convince the courts that football is a
religion unto itself, then prayer is just part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
