<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, March 30, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (San Francisco) _ Exasperated relief workers,
locked out of Yugoslavia as NATO continues its airstrikes against
Serbian military forces, are taking early steps to help Serbs and
Kosovars once the bombings end and Western relief workers are
allowed to return to the country. By ERIC DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   TUMOR-SURGERY (San Antonio) _ In the first operation of its
kind, surgeons here have used a heating technique similar to the
way a microwave oven cooks food to try to kill a malignant,
pancreatic tumor. Doctors say the procedure could lead to a change
in the way tumors are attacked. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ The Board of Supervisors here,
under threat of a national boycott and feeling the wrath of
Catholic Church leaders and parishioners, refused to back down from
plans to allow a group of drag queens dressed as nuns and called
the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence to hold a street party on
Easter Sunday. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ UCLA economists have predicted a
slowing of California's economy in 2000 but said the effect will be
muted by favorable economic diversification. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-WATER (San Francisco) _ Chevron Corp. says it plans to
eliminate MTBE, a gasoline additive that has turned up in drinking
water, from its California gasoline supply within two years of
receiving federal approval to do so. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-RIGHTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Seven Republican lawmakers who
switched their vote and came out in favor of a gay rights bill in
the New York State Assembly will have some explaining to do to the
state's Conservative Party, which reacted with disdain after
realizing that a bill banning discrimination based on sexual
preference had picked up support. By JOHN CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-READING (San Francisco) _ Gov. Gray Davis has signed a
bill aimed at ensuring that more California children learn to read.
The bill, one of four of the governor's education reform measures
passed swiftly by the Legislature. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   BIAS-SUIT (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco State University
lecturer has been awarded $2.75 million in a reverse discrimination
case in which a college dean allegedly said he would hire ``a white
guy over my dead body.'' A jury gave the award to a 51-year-old
white teacher who was denied tenure in S.F. State's College of
Business. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-RANCH (Mountain Home, Texas) _ A gray day in spring turns
a lot brighter when you get up close with a giraffe, feed a fallow
deer and make friends with an ornery ostrich. The scene is the Y.O.
Ranch in South Texas not far from Kerrville. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   SCHANGING-FACES (San Francisco) _ Sabella Rossellini was ``The
Face'' of Lancome until she had the bad manners to turn 42. Then
the French company replaced her with four different models,
including actress Juliette Binoche. Now one face seems to get more
``face time'' on the page than the other four _ Ines Sastre. With a
visage like a kitty-cat, Sastre is a young (25), Spanish-born
actress who photographs like a chameleon. By CYNTHIA ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-RATED (San Francisco) _ It's better to be an actuary than
an actor. It's better to be a statistician than a surgeon. It's
better to be a janitor than a professional basketball player. And
it's better to be a dishwasher than president of the United States.
Those are some of the conclusions reached in the ``Jobs Rated
Almanac,'' a new book by Illinois author Les Krantz. By DAVEMURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-KING (undated) _ ``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon''
is a gem from horror master Stephen King (Scribner, $16.95, 219
pages). In the press release, King says, ``it was my idea to write
a kind of fairy tale, `Hansel and Gretel,' without Hansel.'' King
has succeeded beyond his wildest expectation. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-OLD (undated) _ A Harvard University Medical School
study has revealed some pretty staggering facts about America's
``oldest old'': For example, there are more than 50,000
centenarians in the United States today, almost three times the
number recorded in 1980. The study is the subject of a new book,
``Living to 100: Lessons in Living to Your Maximum Potential at Any
Age.'' By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Although it is staple fare on
most TV news shows, the person-on-the-street interview has never
looked so silly as during this NATO bombing in Kosovo. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ I've received a number of phone
calls from readers curious or furious about a column I ran not long
ago concerning Hillary Clinton's possible bid for the U.S. Senate
from New York. In that column, I recounted a telephone conversation
in which she expressed surprise that Manhattan was an island.
Callers wanted to know if that conversation really took place. The
answer, of course, is no. That column was satire. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
