<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9440 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GREEDY-AZR &LR;      03-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GREEDY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDENING WORLD OF TAXES IS EXPLORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Duplication warning: Story also moved in the ``K'' (commentary)
category.  
 
THE GREEDY HAND: HOW TAXES DRIVE AMERICANS CRAZY AND WHAT TO DO
ABOUT IT 
Amity Shlaes (Random House, $22.95) 
 
 By BOB KAMMAN  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For readers who always wanted a book that makes sense out of the
federal, state and local tax system, Amity Shlaes' ``The Greedy
Hand'' brings an end to the search. It's not that the book provides
a logical explanation, but it makes clear that there are no good
reasons for the absurd tax rules that too often control our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Shlaes, an editorial writer for the ``Wall Street Journal,''
took her title from early American tax protester Thomas Paine, who
complained about ``the greedy hand of government, thrusting itself
into every corner and crevice of industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy the book to learn where to shop for clothes without paying
sales tax (anywhere in Minnesota will do, but the Mall of America
is best because its restaurants are also tax-free). Read it to find
out more than accountants know _ at least until after April 15,
when they have time to catch up on their reading _ about the causes
and effects of our bizarre tax system.
</P>
<P>
   In each of 10 well-researched, highly readable chapters, Shlaes
discusses an aspect of life touched by taxes in a way that it
probably shouldn't. ``Your Baby,'' ``Your Work,'' ``Your Success,''
``Your Retirement'' and ``Your Death'' all illustrate that history
and politics, more than logic and fairness, determine not just our
tax bill, but how we live.
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax, income tax, employment taxes and estate taxes, Shlaes
writes, are ``meddling, bossy, intrusive. Today, our tax code
doesn't stop at merely taking its share. It also wants to tell
people how to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone should read her chapter on ``Your Marriage.'' Only
taxpayers who are married, or thinking about it, would find it
educational and disturbing. She tells the story of Congressman Dave
McIntosh (R-Ind.), and a letter he received in early 1997 from two
constituents who were living together and wanted to marry but
couldn't afford the $2,800 tax increase. McIntosh undertook to
repeal the ``marriage penalty,'' and received encouragement from
then-Speaker Newt Gingrich, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman
Bill Archer, and the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, however, conservatives had discovered
that repeal of the marriage penalty, for couples with two incomes,
also meant repeal of the marriage (itals) bonus, (end itals) for
couples with just one income. ``The failing marriage penalty
legislation,'' Shlaes writes, ``came to symbolize the greater
failure of the Republican Party to unify on important issues, and
the failure of the Democrats to play a meaningful role in
addressing Americans' tax troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Shlaes, however, fails to deliver on her subtitle promise to
tell us ``what to do about it.'' Her recommendations are slogans:
``Taxes have to be simple,'' she writes. ``Taxes have to be lower .
. . we must lock in change.'' Helpful observations, but not a
comprehensive plan.
</P>
<P>
   She contributes to the discussion, though, by pointing out that
a national sales tax is no panacea. ``In Europe, where value-added
taxes have long reigned, they have done much to sour the political
culture. Heavy sales taxes have helped render Europe a continent of
scofflaws. . . . America is too good for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she endorses the ``alternative maximum tax,'' proposed
by Stephen Moore of the Cato Institute. It gives taxpayers a
choice: Pay the lower of what you owe under the old system, or pay
a flat rate of ``something like 25, 23 or 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, of course, there are already opportunities
to figure tax both ways. Itemize, or take the standard deduction?
Separate, or joint returns for married couples? Convert to a Roth
IRA now, or pay on IRA distributions later?
</P>
<P>
   Another way of figuring the tax, on top of the many choices that
already must be considered? If tax reform must wait until the
system collapses from its own weight, that idea might be the last
straw. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Bob Kamman is a Phoenix attorney and tax practitioner. He can be
reached at bobkamman(at)aol.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
