<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-IRS-AZR &LR;      03-30 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR PUSHES REFORM, BUT IRS CHANGES SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   Duplication warning: Story also moved in ``E'' (entertainment)
category.  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 By BOB KAMMAN  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If American taxpayers were to vote on which senator born in July
1921 accomplished the most in 1998, John Glenn might take second
place.
</P>
<P>
   The winner could be William V. Roth Jr. (R-Del), whose Senate
Finance Committee hearings set a fire under the Internal Revenue
Service and launched the IRS Restructuring and Reform Act with a
unanimous Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Roth's efforts, our federal tax system may never be
the same. Then again, the result may be much the same as Glenn's
space-shuttle mission, going around in circles while public
interest fades, then landing in the same place where it started.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiring such skepticism is Roth himself, who writes in a new
book:
</P>
<P>
   ``As Charles Rossotti, the agency's new commissioner, told me,
changing the culture of the IRS will require more than legislation.
It will take a decade of training and oversight, vigilance by
Congress, and zero tolerance for abuse and mismanagement within the
Service. . . . As we discovered in our investigation, many of the
abuses committed by Service personnel were in violation of laws
that were already on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, prevention of IRS abuse is much like cancer
research; there is great hope for the future, but no immediate cure
for many of today's victims.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's book, published by Atlantic Monthly Press and co-authored
with his senior staffer, William H. Nixon, is the right material
with the wrong title, ``The Power to Destroy,'' from Chief Justice
John Marshall's quote (in an opinion that had nothing to do with
federal tax collection) that ``the power to tax is the power to
destroy.'' A better title would be ``Making Sausage,'' from a maxim
by German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck: ``The less people know
about how sausages and laws are made, the better they'll sleep at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   One revealing insight into the legislative process is Roth's
admission that Congress for many years failed to watch IRS
operations closely because of ``intimidation, the concern that the
agency, as it had been known to do, might wreck the political
fortunes of the senator or congressman who probed too deeply into
its activities.'' He says his committee's senior Democrat, Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York, told him, ``What seemed to matter
most was that taxes were being collected . . . we have never paid
attention either to (IRS) or to the job we were giving it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Roth and Moynihan were members of Senate Finance when a
subcommittee chaired by their now-retired colleague David Pryor
(D-Ark.) conducted an earlier round of hearings on IRS abuse. After
I testified at those 1992 hearings, Pryor wrote me, ``Over the past
year, it has become obvious that we need additional safeguards to
protect taxpayers from the devastating effect of IRS mistakes and
misdeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth's conversion to the cause of taxpayer rights may have come
late in his Senate career, but (perhaps for that reason) it came
with considerable zeal. In fact, his book sets an example for
lawmakers who grapple with other major legislation.
</P>
<P>
   One way Congress deals with problems is to appoint a commission
to study them and make recommendations. A couple of years later,
when the subject is no longer in the headlines, the commission's
report is filed away and forgotten, or turned into legislative
proposals that are watered down in committee before final dilution
during floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   Roth stood the process on its head.
</P>
<P>
   The National Commission on Restructuring the IRS, an 18-member
bipartisan group set up by Congress in 1996, finished its work in
1997 with a report that identified many IRS problems and offered
solutions for them that were acceptable to its mix of public
officials and private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned that they didn't go far enough,'' Roth says of
the commission's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   He prevented a Senate vote on a bill the House had passed
quickly in 1997 with most of the commission's recommendations
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to see a small step taken by Congress when I
knew that events were coming together in such a way that we could
restructure and reform the agency from the ground up,'' he writes.
``Only a few times in history had conditions been so ripe for
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to real reform evaporated after the 1998 Senate
Finance Committee hearings, chaired by Roth. The resulting
legislation is not perfect, but it is significantly better than its
earlier drafts. Roth himself admits that ``much more needs to be
done,'' and he promises to carry on the good work.
</P>
<P>
   There are already signs, though, that the book on IRS reform is
not only written and published, but closed.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the law is an IRS Oversight Board, with six
members appointed from the private sector and an IRS employee
representative joining the commissioner of Internal Revenue and the
secretary of Treasury to monitor the IRS administration. As Roth's
book explains, ``The board will have the authority to influence the
appointment and removal of commissioners, as well as top-level
officers, and it will work to ensure that the organization and
operation of the agency is carried out as Congress intends.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law required that the president appoint the Oversight
Board's members by Jan. 22. That date came and went, with no action
from the White House and no expression of concern from Capitol
Hill. (Both, of course, were occupied with other matters.) A month
later, a White House spokesman said appointments were ``very
close.'' Two months after the deadline, it's possible that names
will be announced by April 15, because tax stories attract
attention around that date. But it's not possible that taxpayers
who delay filing their returns for the same amount of time will
escape IRS attention.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the average taxpayer should exercise even greater
caution to escape penalties for tardy compliance, according to
Roth's collection of supposedly helpful tax hints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always file your tax return by registered or certified mail,
or use another carrier like Federal Express, Airborne or UPS. But
it's not enough simply to send the return in this manner; you
should also prepare a written statement that you sign, stating what
was inside the envelope you sent. . . .On the day you mail the tax
return, you should prepare a declaration of mailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say; he doesn't have to stand in line at the
post office. (If you mail your return on time, trust the post
office to get it to the IRS. But if your check is not cashed
quickly, or your refund isn't issued within normal processing
times, follow up on the reason.)
</P>
<P>
   Buy the book _ even though the $23 price isn't deductible for
most people because of tax ``reform'' that Roth helped pass in 1986
_ but skip the chapter of banal tax advice.
</P>
<P>
   And if you expect everything that comes out of Washington these
days to touch on sex scandals, the book won't disappoint you. It
tells of the IRS district director who solicits sex from a female
employee. When she reports it to internal inspectors, they do
nothing, so she calls the local police. The district director is
transferred to Washington, where he gets a raise. Also, there is
the IRS collection supervisor whose career went downhill after he
objected to a stripper named Miss Goodbody appearing at a manager's
birthday party in an IRS office during business hours.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Roth's book is about taxpayers getting raped.
And there are hints that even Roth doesn't get much respect. He
asks for a copy of a report on an IRS employee attitude survey and
is told by current management that it doesn't exist. Employees in
district offices have it, though, and send it to him. Every
taxpayer should hope to find such decency at the bottom when there
is lack of concern at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Roth ends with a pledge ``to push for tax reform _ a tax code
that is fair, simple, and economically constructive.'' Along with
IRS reform, however, his legacy to American taxpayers is the Roth
IRA, which has convinced thousands of taxpayers to pay millions of
dollars in tax now to avoid paying more later. Yet if you believe
that the income tax will cease to be the major source of revenue
for the federal government, you have to feel sorry for anyone with
a Roth IRA, and for its senatorial namesake.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's book is subtitled ``How the IRS Became America's Most
Powerful Agency, How Congress Is Taking Control, and What You Can
Do to Protect Yourself Under the New Law.'' When was the last time
a lawmaker wrote a book about how Americans can protect themselves
under a newly enacted law he sponsored? &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Phoenix attorney and tax practitioner Bob Kamman is a former IRS
employee who has testified several times to Congress on reform
measures. He also writes for the National Taxpayers Union's ``Tax
Savings Report.'' He can be reached at bobkamman(at)aol.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-IRS-AZR &LR;      03-30 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$23) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 Senator pushes reform, but IRS changes slowly  
 Duplication warning: Story also moved in ``K'' (commentary)
category  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
THE POWER TO DESTROY: How the IRS Became America's Most Powerful
Agency, How Congress Is Taking Control, and What You Can Do to
Protect Yourself Under the Law 
by Sen. William V. Roth Jr. and William H. Nixon (Atlantic Monthly, By BOB KAMMAN  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
