<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      03-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE TIMES OF MY LIFE &QL; 
 &UR; Max Frankel (Random House, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Frankel and his mother came to America in 1940, after months of
terror in Nazi Germany. Life as a refugee had a peculiar effect on
young Max. ``In a sense,'' he says, ``I became a chronic fugitive,
forever looking to escape the mundane, to find new soil and
stimulation.'' He went to Columbia University (at that time for
less than $700 a year) because he wanted to write for its newspaper
_ as he says, he ``followed the ink'' _ and won a job as campus
stringer for the ``New York Times'' when another student in line
elected to go with the ``Herald Tribune.'' Over the next 50 years,
Frankel rose from stringer to rewrite man to foreign correspondent,
Washington bureau chief, editor of the editorial page and finally,
executive editor of the ``Times'' (he retired in 1994). Here he
offers his impressions of the Cold War, the Cuban missile crisis
and the Vietnam War, the Pentagon papers and Watergate, and leaders
such as Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon. There are also interesting
passages about the inner workings of the ``Times,'' including
Frankel's efforts to diversify its staff. He had his bungled
moments, as when he made a remark to a ``Washington Post'' reporter
equating the coverage of ``teas'' with the presence of more women
on the front page. The next day, every woman at the ``Times''
protested by wearing tea bags as earrings. This memoir is both an
account of survival in Hitler's Germany and an American success
story played out against some of the most interesting events of the
century. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ROCKS OF AGES &QL; 
 &UR; Stephen Jay Gould (Ballantine, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   The symbol of the scientific revolution that flourished during
the late 17th century is Isaac Newton, a man to whom Alexander Pope
paid tribute: ``Nature and nature's laws lay hid in night / God
said, `Let Newton be,' and all was light.'' Yet Gould points out
that Newton and many of his contemporaries were ardent theists _
``He spent far more time working on his exegeses of the prophecies
of Daniel and John, and on his attempt to integrate biblical
chronology with the histories of other ancient peoples, than he
ever devoted to physics.'' In this book, Gould argues that science
and religion are profoundly different but equally vital subjects.
While science tries to record and explain the factual character of
the natural world, religion looks to human meanings and values.
Gould proposes that we abandon the notion that the two are in
conflict and adopt instead a principle of ``respectful
non-interference, accompanied by intense dialogue between the
two.'' This is Gould's contribution to Ballantine's ``Library of
Contemporary Thought,'' a monthly series of books by authors on
topics of their choosing. Anna Quindlen wrote about her love for
reading. Carl Hiaasen trashed the Disney empire. John Feinstein
analyzed the talent of Tiger Woods. Needless to say, Gould's book
takes the series to a higher plane. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ELEMENTALS &QL; 
 &UR; A.S. Byatt (Random House, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Here's another of Byatt's ``little books'' (after ``The Matisse
Stories'' and ``The Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye''), which are
lovely to look at and have wonderful stories inside. There are six
here, subtitled ``Stories of Fire and Ice.'' In ``Cold,'' a
beautiful and adored princess flourishes only in the icy weather of
her homeland and risks everything when she falls in love with a
prince from a faraway desert country. In ``Crocodile Tears,'' a
woman reacts to the sudden death of her husband by running away,
taking train after train without knowing where she is going until
she arrives in Spain and meets a stranger who is escaping from
troubles of his own. In ``A Lamia in the Cevennes,'' an enchanted,
snakelike monster takes up residence at the bottom of a painter's
swimming pool. In Byatt's hands, these are odd, otherwordly stories
that have no boundaries, elegantly told fairy tales. Enjoy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FACTASTIC BOOK OF 1001 LISTS &QL; 
 &UR; Russell Ash (DK, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   We don't know how we came this far in life without knowing that
the longest coastline in the world belongs to Canada, with 151,485
miles (Monaco, with two miles, is the loser). Or that Lebanon _
yes, folks, Lebanon _ is the most moviegoing country, with the
United States eighth behind China, Georgia, India, Iceland,
Australia and New Zealand. Or that the Stephens Island frog,
evolved about 275 million years ago, is found only in New Zealand
and is thought to be the ancestor of all frogs. New &AMP; Notable has
never paid attention to Ash before, but our resistance has been
worn down by his dogged success with his annual ``Top Ten of
Everything'' volumes (they are so trivial that if you let them go
they might just float away). This book has headings such as
``Grisly Execution Methods'' and ``Famous Assassination Victims,''
``Unusual Things Sold at Auctions'' (how nice that the skull of
Swedish philosopher Emanuel Swedenborg sold in 1978 to the
Stockholm Royal Academy of Science, reuniting it with the rest of
his body), ``Famous Disabled Achievers'' and ``Odd Arty-Facts'' (In
1961, it was discovered that a Henri Matisse painting had been
hanging upside-down in the Museum of Modern Art for two months and
no one knew). Ash includes his e-mail address so you can send him
factastic ideas for future volumes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
