<SLUG> BC-INVESTOR-TAXES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARN TO MINIMIZE MUTUAL FUND TAX BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Members of Congress have a lot on their minds these
days _ the Kosovo unrest, Social Security reform, next year's
elections . . . and mutual fund taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a bill recently was introduced in Congress that would
direct the Securities and Exchange Commission to require fund
companies to disclose the after-tax impacts of their trading
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (have) suggested that shareholders need more information
on the effect of taxes on their investments,'' SEC Chairman Arthur
Levitt said last week during a stop in Palm Desert, Calif. ``I
share this concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The days when people could trade stocks, bonds, mutual funds and
other investments while remaining blissfully unaware of the tax
consequences are drawing to a close. The tax impact of investing
has become a hot topic thanks to the roaring stock market and new
saving incentives such as 401(k) retirement plans. As a result,
millions of Americans have amassed big paper profits and, sooner or
later, will have to face the tax bite. Investment companies, the
media and even Congress are paying more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest cost by far on unsheltered capital _ bigger than
management fees, custodial charges and commissions, and nearly
always enough of a bite to outweigh stock dividends or bond price
gains _ is taxes,'' reads a report from Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.,
a New York investment-research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonial Group, a mutual-fund family in Boston, estimates
that Americans shelled out $34 billion in taxes on their fund
capital gains in 1997, the most recent year for which information
is available. That's more than the annual cost of operating all
U.S. prisons and exceeds the yearly amount the government spends on
medical care for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   It also represents a quintupling from the estimated $7 billion
in taxes paid out in 1990, the first year of Colonial's study.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the best ways to minimize your tax bill while not
letting tax fears keep you on the investment sidelines? Here are
some guidelines as suggested by Sanford C. Bernstein and other
sources:
</P>
<P>
   - Avoid short-term gains. If possible, avoid selling an
investment and locking in a profit until your holding period has
crossed into the long-term range, after one year. You will pay no
more than 20 percent in taxes on a long-term capital gain. But
short-term profits, which are taxed as ordinary income, could face
a hit of up to 39.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of trading, even if it's profitable, creates a lot of
taxable gains,'' said Ernie Scarbrough, a managing director at
brokerage US Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   - Offset gains with losses. If you must sell a stock or other
investment at a short-term profit, consider getting rid of another
investment that's in the red. You can use losses to shelter gains,
dollar for dollar. Excess losses can be applied to reduce ordinary
taxable income, up to $3,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it's easier to put an offsetting strategy into play
during the fourth quarter, when you can estimate your gains and
losses for the year. Yet Scarbrough points out that by delaying,
you might face lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wait until the last quarter, you're competing with
other investors in the same situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   - Lean to index mutual funds. Regular mutual funds must pay
distributions to shareholders that reflect stock or bond positions
sold at a profit. These payouts are taxable in the year received,
even for investors who didn't do any trading of their own. Index
portfolios and other ``tax-efficient'' mutual funds trade
infrequently and thus don't often convert paper profits into
realized gains.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you need to realize that the tax bite on any such profits is
merely deferred, not eliminated. ``When you transfer into another
fund, or sell shares for any reason, the tax bill may shock you,''
the Sanford C. Bernstein report reads.
</P>
<P>
   - Consider individual stocks for tax efficiency. Unlike with
mutual funds, you control your tax destiny with stocks because you
decide whether _ and when _ to sell. In theory, you can permanently
avoid taxes because any liability gets lifted for your heirs when
you die. That said, most people don't hold stocks throughout their
lives, which means a tax bill will come home to roost eventually.
</P>
<P>
   One key advantage of hiring a private money manager rather than
using mutual funds is that the adviser can time his or her trades
to boost the tax efficiency of your account, notes Eric Nelson,
senior portfolio manager at Wells Fargo Investment Management in
Scottsdale. However, private managers might not accept you as a
client unless you have a portfolio of $250,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't avoid high-dividend stocks. According to conventional
wisdom, you should stay away from high-yielding stocks since
dividends are taxed more heavily than long-term gains. But the
pattern of historical returns suggests that such a strategy may be
counterproductive in the long run, the Bernstein report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-dividend stocks have returned so much more than
low-dividend stocks before taxes that the lesser taxability hasn't
made up for it,'' the report said. Between 1967 and 1997, on an
initial $1 million portfolio, the 167 highest-yielding stocks in
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index would have grown to $18.2 million
after taxes, compared with $9.6 million for the 167 lowest
yielders, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   - Use options to avoid risk. Hanging on to stocks for the long
haul makes sense from a tax standpoint but subjects you to the
danger of falling prices. One way to get around this is to retain
your shares and buy put options to minimize your downside exposure.
Put options become more valuable if the underlying stock drops in
price. They thus represent a form of insurance against market
setbacks, although their use should be rationed because of the
costs involved.
</P>
<P>
   - Lean to tax-deferred accounts. In addition to workplace 401(k)
plans for which you might be eligible, you also can open some type
of individual retirement account. With traditional IRAs, you can
deduct the amount you invest, provided you meet the income limits.
Your money in a traditional IRA grows tax-free until withdrawn _
presumably after age 59{ to avoid a 10 percent tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   With new Roth IRAs, you don't get a deduction but you do receive
completely tax-free growth assuming you hold the account at least
five years and past age 59{.
</P>
<P>
   - Consider tax-free bonds. Municipal bonds and bond mutual funds
pay interest that's tax-free, although any profits resulting from
bond-price movements would be subject to capital gains taxes. Muni
bonds do pay lower nominal yields than government and corporate
bonds, which means their tax advantage might not be compelling
unless you're at least in the 28 percent federal tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   One additional pointer involving taxes is that you need to
accept responsibility for your own decisions. If you're like many
people, you probably maintain investment accounts at various places
_ perhaps at both a full-service and a discount brokerage. As a
result, none of your advisers may understand your entire tax
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be hard for advisers to see how the various parts of
your portfolio fit together,'' Scarbrough said. ``Consequently,
they alone may not be able to help you become more tax
efficient.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at russ.wiles(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
