<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9472 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      03-30 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CULTURES, STORIES PRESENTED FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New books about other cultures and collections of stories from
around the world will expand the horizons of older children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; IN SEARCH OF THE SPIRIT: THE LIVING NATIONAL TREASURES OF JAPAN &QL; 
 &UR; Sheila Hamanaka and Ayano Ohmi (Morrow Junior Books, $16)
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese kimono is a work of art that takes eight weeks to
design and paint. Basket weaving is another painstaking craft,
particularly ``tabaneami,'' a technique in which a basket is made
from a single length of bamboo. ``Bunraku'' puppet masters train
from childhood to perfect their art; operating one puppet requires
three people.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of World War II, the Japanese decided to
preserve their cultural history through a program that awards
grants to special masters who train apprentices. This book, with
fascinating photographs and illustrations, features six of these
artists. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THUNDER BEAR AND KO: THE BUFFALO NATION AND NAMBE PUEBLO &QL; 
 &UR; Susan Hazen-Hammond (Dutton, $16.99)
</P>
<P>
   Thunder Bear Yates, an 8-year-old Pueblo Indian who lives in New
Mexico, helps his father care for the buffalo. His ancestors have
long depended on buffalo, both as a food source and as a spiritual
brother. Thunder Bear and his people take measures to ensure the
buffalo's survival from hunters who shoot for sport.
</P>
<P>
   This beautifully photographed book captures life on Nambe
Pueblo. Pictures contrast traditional costumes and dances with
modern images such as a 2,500-pound buffalo nuzzling the hood of a
bright red sports car. Hazen-Hammond lives in Sante Fe. The author
of seven adult books makes her debut as a children's writer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ASK THE BONES: SCARY STORIES FROM AROUND THE WORLD &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Arielle North Olson and Howard Schwartz; illustrated by
David Linn
 &UR; (Viking, $15.99)
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the family ever went near the attic.'' Thus begins
``The Bridal Gown,'' a tale from Germany about an upstairs demoness
who loved silken gowns. The collection of 22 ghost stories from 14
countries has something for everyone who loves to get scared.
Perfect for sleepovers! &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE OXFORD TREASURY OF WORLD STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Harrison and Christopher Stuart-Clark (Oxford University
Press, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This brightly illustrated anthology contains 23 tales from
around the globe. Anansi, a Caribbean spider, begins by spinning a
tale about bananas and tricking his friend. Other unusual plots
center on the barber's wife from India, Robin Hood, the frog
princess and a thief from Egypt. Folklore devotees will appreciate
rarely heard stories, as well as familiar plot lines with new
twists. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
