<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of March 29, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
March 30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., April 2.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE AT LEAST 2 COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM ROME: On a sunny morning, the distinctive dome of St.
Peter's Basilica casts a shadow that dominates the landscape below.
The shadowy shape adds symbolism to the scene. This modern city
_where motorscooterists regard red lights as suggestions, cellular
telephones ring continually and tourists line up outside Gucci and
Prada _ is defined by Catholicism. To celebrate Easter, the holiest
day of their year, tens of thousands of Christians are here to
gather outside St. Peter's, the home church of a billion Catholics.
With the year 2000 only months away, the festivities are a
foretaste of what will take place here as Christians hold a
yearlong birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VATICAN CITY: On the ancient gray-brown cobblestones of
St. Peter's square, with moss and trampled cigarette butts between
them, a Sunday-morning crowd gathers that seems to be a portrait of
the world. This is ground zero for the largest Christian
denomination in the world, the center of a separate ``country''
with its own government, newspaper, radio station and publishing
house, home to about 1,000 people. Decisions made here have changed
the course of Europe and the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., April 1) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE 4 COLOR PHOTOS AND 1 COLOR GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   RON HOWARD PROFILE: Ron Howard, one of Hollywood's hottest, most
versatile directors, doesn't fit anyone's mold. (Includes color
photo of Howard.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CARTOONS: The great television toon-in is gaining momentum
like an Acme safe dropped from the top of a building. The networks
are going animated like never before, loading their prime-time
schedules with cartoons. (Includes color photo from new cartoon,
``Futurama.'')
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN: A 2-column color graphic,
``Countdown to 'Star Wars,''' outlining the number of days
remaining until ``The Phantom Menace'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``The Rugrats Movie,'' ``Everest,'' ``Home
Fries'' and ``The Farm: Life Inside Angola Prison.'' (Includes
2-column color studio photograph from one of the reviewed films.)
WITH: CD REVIEWS: New discs from Jeff Beck, Richard Goode and
rock*a*teens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., April 1) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE AT LEAST TWO COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR GROWING PAINS: Its meteoric rise from the backwoods to
the big time has been staggering for NASCAR, now in its 51st
stock-car racing season. NASCAR's growth has been unprecedented in
sports, but for every plus there's a minus, and the sport faces
major issues and decisions that will shape its future.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GRASS-ROOTS LOYALTY: A big reason for NASCAR's popularity
has been the personality of its drivers and their accessibility to
the fans and media. NASCAR officials say they take pride in being
the only sport to offer fans an open locker room _ the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 1 COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FOR A BLUE MOON: March 31 _ Wednesday _ is the last chance
for a couple of years to do what seems to have been written in the
stars: Have a ``Once in a Blue Moon'' dinner party. On that day the
moon will rise full for the second time in the month, a celestial
event that occurs, as they say, only once in a blue moon. So
conjure up the heavenly possibilities for a dinner menu that
focuses on blue food. (Includes 3-column color illustration.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BLUE DRINKS: Go all out for a ``Once in a Blue Moon''
party with matching drinks.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Full Moon Pepper Soup, Steak with Blue Cheese
Sauce, Peas Extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: Only a few decades ago, a well-stocked pantry
meant having a good supply of flour, sugar, lard, some rice, beans
and maybe some canned tomatoes and other canned goods. Today, there
is an unprecedented variety of foods that have a long shelf life.
There is nothing second rate about a meal put together primarily
from the pantry shelf.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOOD NOTES: With the population explosion at the cheese
counter these days, a guide that fits into a pocketbook could come
in handy. ''The Cheese Companion'' is filled with tempting color
photographs and evocative descriptions of about 50 varieties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 3 COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ACURA INTEGRA: The Integra is the lowest-priced model imported
by Acura, the upscale Honda division, but it's possible to make an
argument that it comes with the most potential for enjoyable
driving. (Includes 4-column color photo of Integra exterior and a
2-column color photo of interior.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 1999 Acura Integra.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: Technology is an ongoing process, with one
innovation often leading to another. Nowhere is that more apparent
than in the automotive industry. First there were anti-lock braking
systems, followed by traction-control systems. Now the industry is
offering stability control systems. (Includes 1-column color mug
shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 5 COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALL IN THE PALM: The PalmPilot, a hand-held computer, has
sold nearly 3 million units, and its success has awakened the giant
in Redmond, Wash., known as Microsoft. Microsoft's entry into the
market has spawned scores of new hand-held computers, powered by a
light version of its Windows operating system. Today, there are
plenty of models, and they come in all sizes, colors and
configurations. But don't be fooled; there's less variety than
meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   (Includes two 2-column color photos of hand-held computers.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Hand-held computers at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON-LINE DIVERSITY: The Internet's ability to turn people
into voices without faces makes it hard to see that the Net is
becoming more diverse. According to a new study by Forrester
Research Inc., minorities are getting onto the Internet at an
enormously increasing rate.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ``STAR WARS'' REVIEW: ``Star Wars'' fans clamoring for
information about the highly anticipated ``The Phantom Menace'' can
find clues and answers only a mouse click away with ``Star Wars:
Behind the Magic,'' a two CD-ROM set for PCs from LucasArts.
(Includes 1-column color photo of ``Star Wars'' character Princess
Leia taken from the CD.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: General Motors, the granddaddy of the
automakers, has stepped onto the Internet retail sales floor. The
company has unveiled its on-line shopping site, GM BuyPower.
(Includes 2-column color photo of web site.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: As a kid, we tortured engines to get the most
out of them, even though we knew that shortened their life span.
The same thing happens with hopped-up computer chips: They live a
short but exciting life. (Includes 1-column color mug shot of
columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   ON-LINE AIR DEALS: Finding that rock-bottom airfare on-line is
easier said than done, but that doesn't mean it's impossible. Deal
seekers willing to do more work for the elusive cheap ticket can
visit dozens of Web sites. (Includes 4-column color illustration of
plane emerging from a computer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MILLENNIUM CRUISE: More than 60 people from Palm Beach
County, Fla., are going on a cruise to seven continents, 27
countries, 34 ports. They'll leave Athens, Greece, Nov. 20, 1999,
on the small Ocean Explorer I and return to Athens March 25, 2000.
Along the way, they'll celebrate the millennium in style.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: If you are planning a trip to France and
have a question about a historic site, an art exhibition, a music
festival, transportation or a place to eat or stay, there's a new
number to call.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 7 COLOR PHOTOS, 1 B&AMP;W PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ORTH ON SERIAL KILLER ANDREW CUNANAN: Maureen Orth, best-known
for her work in Vanity Fair, has written an exceptionally good
account of suspected serial killer Andrew Cunanan's spree in 1997.
(Includes 18 pica color photo of designer Gianni Versace, a
2-column B&AMP;W photo of Andrew Cunanan from his high school yearbook
and a half-column color photo of book cover.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Who is the real Bill Gates? Is it the author who
insists, in his new book, ``Business (AT) the Speed of Thought,''
that all interoffice communications should flow ``over e-mail so
workers can act on news with reflex-like speed'' or is it the
witness who testified in the government's antitrust case against
his company that he could not remember dozens of e-mail messages he
wrote or received in recent years. (Includes 2-column color photo
of Gates testifying at a Congressional hearing and a 6 pica color
photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Just how many lives did Janis Joplin lead? Joplin
has been variously cast as tragic bluesmama, lesbian lover, loving
sister, junkie maneater. Now here comes Alice Echols with Janis
Joplin, feminist icon. (Includes 6 pica color photo of book jacket)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: New readers from Random House and Grove Press
offer selected chapters, routines, short stories and passages from
the voluminous libraries of Gore Vidal and William S. Burroughs.
(Includes two 6-pica color photos of book jackets.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES TWO COLOR PHOTOS, 1 COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNEY OF THE BUTTERFLIES: It's a phenomenon of nature that's
older than modern humans. Yet within our lifetime, we may destroy
it. The miraculous journey of the Monarch butterflies from Canada,
through the United States and into Mexico and back is one of the
world's greatest natural events. (Includes a 3-column color photo
of butterflies on a tree, a 1-column color photo of a butterfly
being tagged and a 2-column color illustration of butterfly
migration)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ALIEN VISITS: Extraterrestrial aliens haven't visited here
and won't be coming here, says a noted physics professor. It's not
that there are no extraterrestrials out there. It's just that if
advanced civilizations exist elsewhere in the universe, they are
bound by the same laws of physics we are.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: A new, easy-to-use device that jump-starts
a stopped heart could save up to 100,000 lives a year, if it goes
into widespread use.
</P>
