<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WEREWOLVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT STORIES DELIVER HAIR-RAISING HORROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 
WEREWOLVES IN THEIR YOUTH: STORIES 
Michael Chabon (Random House, $22.95) 
 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Michael Chabon's ``Werewolves in Their Youth'' sounds like a
batch of horror stories, that's because it is.
</P>
<P>
   But not of the lycanthropic variety.
</P>
<P>
   No, these stories deal with human horror, the horror of everyday
people mired in often unfathomably dire circumstances. (One story
does deal with supernatural horror, but more on that in a minute.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Son of the Wolfman,'' the most ambitious and grueling of
the nine stories, a woman is impregnated by a serial rapist. Chabon
explores the changes the pregnancy and its circumstances have on
Cara, the woman, as well as her foundering marriage. Her decision
to keep the baby estranges her even further from her husband,
Richie _ they haven't been able to conceive despite years of
trying. Yet through the help of a colorful midwife, they arrive at
the beginning, maybe, of a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so lucky. In the title story, Timothy Stokes is a
troubled schoolboy who sometimes pretends to be a werewolf. That
wouldn't be so alarming if he hadn't pursued realism to the point
of biting a little girl on the neck. Another strike and he is bound
for ``the fabulous corridors of the Special School.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is told through the eyes of Paul Kovel, a neighbor
with troubles of his own. Paul's classmates describe him in a song:
``What's that smell-o? Paul Kovel-o / He's a big fat hippo Jell-O /
He's a snoop / He smells like poop / He smells like tomato beef /
Alphabet soup.''
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, his parents are divorcing. His attempts to salvage
his parents' marriage and his adventures with Timothy are told in
the straightforward, innocent voice of a clever child, often
hilarious, often heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Chabon switches voices and styles with ease. In ``That Was Me,''
he captures perfectly the desperation and pathetic air of an
off-season beach bar:
</P>
<P>
   ``The local drunks _ there must have been about sixty-five or
seventy of them, many related by blood or sexual history _ were a
close-knit population, involved in an ongoing collective
enterprise: the building, over several generations, of a basilica
of failure, on whose crowded friezes they figured in vivid
depictions of bankruptcy, drug rehabilitation, softball and arrest.
There was no role in this communal endeavor for the summer
islander, on leave, as it were, from work on the cathedral of his
or her own bad decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final story, ``In the Black Mill,'' Chabon adopts the
voice of an entirely different writer _ ``August Van Zorn,'' the
pseudonym of a tangential character in Chabon's excellent novel,
``Wonder Boys.'' In the previous book, Van Zorn was described as a
horror writer who wrote at night, ``a Hudson Bay blanket draped
across his lap and a bottle of bourbon on the table before him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a flat-out horror story, the tale of a mysterious
Pennsylvania town and the mill that seems to claim the life, or at
least limbs, of every male resident. An outsider pokes around too
much, suspicions are gruesomely proven true and . . . it's perfect.
Chabon expertly adopts the tone of a bourbon-soaked hack, yet still
manages to raise the hairs on the back of your neck with the story.
Just because you can see what's coming from a long way off doesn't
make it any less enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   And stay away from the locally brewed beer.
</P>
<P>
   Chabon is a comfortable writer, obviously at ease in any number
of settings. ````Werewolves in Their Yout''h'' allows him the
chance to show off that talent, without ever giving the impression
that he's trying to. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach Bill Goodykoontz at bgoodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
