<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a five-page package of stories
and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Washington) _ Kosovo developments from Washington. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ Kosovo developments from NATO
headquarters. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLANA (Brussels) _ Javier Solana, the NATO secretary
general, talks about the Yugoslav campaign, says the primary need
is to stop the killing in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Berlin) _ The Russian prime minister, Yevgeny
Primakov, goes to Bonn to talk to German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder after first meeting in Belgrade with Slobodan Milosevic,
the Serb leader. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Ethnic-Albanian refugees give
matching, credible accounts of systematic expulsions and brutality
in southern Kosovo. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The government of
Macedonia says it is swamped and has to send some refugees back
into Kosovo. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Feature on how people in the
Yugoslav capital get information on the war, and how they process
it. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BRITAIN (London) _ How Britain, with harsh, emotional
language about war crimes, is leading the campaign to win the
public's hearts and minds against Milosevic. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin, in
his annual state of the nation speech to Parliament, says NATO
violates international law in its Kosovo campaign, but he wants
``normal'' ties with U.S. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Benjamin Netanyahu, the Israeli
prime minister, under fire from critics for his government's tepid
response to the expulsion and killings of ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, on Tuesday condemned mass murder by all sides in the
conflict and said that Israel would send humanitarian aid to the
refugees. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GORE (Washington) _ Looking at the role of the vice
president in the Kosovo campaign. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEGAL (Washington) _ With the legal justifications for
the bombing ranging from flimsy to justifiably inventive, the U.S.
action in Kosovo may be effecting profound changes in the evolving
field of international law. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With a brief sidebar:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENOCIDE (Washington) _ Now that officials are freely
accusing the Serbs of genocide in Kosovo, what is the meaning of
that term. It is defined in the International Genocide Convention
of which the United States and Yugoslavia are signatories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IRELAND (Dublin) _ The NATO air attacks on Yugoslavia
have severely strained Ireland's traditional policy of military
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering stories on a Milosevic TV address,
remarks by President Clinton at a State Department ceremony and a
look at the activities of the international war crimes tribunal.
</P>
