<SLUG> BC-JOBS-RATED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER SURVEY PUTS DISHWASHER OVER THE PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's better to be an actuary than an actor. It's
better to be a statistician than a surgeon. It's better to be a
janitor than a professional basketball player. And it's better to
be a dishwasher than president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the conclusions reached in the ``Jobs Rated
Almanac,'' a new book by Les Krantz that illustrates how you can
use statistics to prove anything _ or absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The almanac takes 250 jobs and ranks them in each of six major
categories: environment, income, outlook, physical demands,
security and stress. A job's rankings in each of those categories
are then added up to see where it lands overall.
</P>
<P>
   Web site manager finishes in first place, followed, in order, by
actuary, computer systems analyst, software engineer and
mathematician. Finishing last is an oil field laborer.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz bases many of his ratings on numbers compiled by the U.S.
Bureau of Labor Statistics and private research organizations, and
the job-by-job profiles for the six categories give job seekers and
potential career changers a good flavor of each job.
</P>
<P>
   He also offers shorter lists of jobs that have particular
attributes, like tight deadlines, long hours or limited physical
activity.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall rankings are one instance when the whole is less
than the sum of its parts. Each of the six categories is given
equal weight, which explains why a cashier can be ranked 87th while
a National Basketball Association player ends up 205th _ even
though the typical NBA player earns more in a year than a cashier
would in a century.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Krantz explained that most of the jobs on the
list earn middle-class wages, so he felt there was no need to give
income more emphasis than the other five criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people won't look at all the aspects of the job,'' he
said, adding that job hunters almost always look at the potential
salary while they overlook other items. Besides, he said, a high
salary doesn't ensure financial security.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see an awful lot of people who were in professional
athletics who end up in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   What the list does emphasize are jobs with low unemployment that
are expected to be in demand through at least 2005 _ those factors
are counted in both the outlook and security criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing even more favor are jobs that involve limited physical
activity, a component in the environment, physical demands and
stress categories.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes it no wonder that the book, put out by the career
site of the Wall Street Journal's on-line edition, gives its
highest ranking to jobs involving technology or number crunching.
</P>
<P>
   Stress, physical demands and competition are seen as negatives,
even though many workers find them healthy in moderate doses.
</P>
<P>
   If you had a mythical job that paid minimum wage for staring at
a brick wall eight hours a day, for example, it would probably rank
better than at least half the 250 jobs in the almanac. It would
score extremely well in stress and physical demands, and at least
reasonably in environment and security.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes such useful information as typical hours
worked, potential for promotion and salary growth, degree of
competition, time pressure, travel and perks. The physical demands
section considers such things as long hours and potential hazards,
plus the time spent lifting, crawling, climbing and crouching.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether RSI was included in that section, Krantz said
he didn't know what RSI was. When told it was repetitive stress
injury (also known as repetitive strain injury), a frequent
disability among people who use computers for long hours, he said
it would fit in somewhere among the more than 20 components that
make up the stress rating in his book.
</P>
<P>
   Some other jobs and their rankings: statistician, considered to
have the best work environment, 32nd overall; musical instrument
repairer, 78th; surgeon, 135th; janitor, 154th; teacher, 164th;
mayor, 188th; dishwasher, 213th; actor, 218th; president of the
United States, 229th.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz said his figures do not directly consider the prestige of
a job, but in some cases jobs with higher salaries have more
prestige. But the salary of the presidency, for example, was more
than outweighed by the job's low scores in the five other
categories, including last place finishes in environment, outlook
and stress.
</P>
<P>
   He said his favorite part of the book is the one on workplace
environment, which lists about how many hours a person has to work
and offers about 200 words describing the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about what people do all day _ what they have to put up
with,'' Krantz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
