<HEADLINE>
WHEN POLITICAL SATIRE BITES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I've received a number of phone calls from
readers curious or furious about a column I ran not long ago
concerning Hillary Rodham Clinton's possible bid for the U.S.
Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In that column, I recounted a telephone conversation between
Mrs. Clinton and an unnamed, upstate New York Democratic Party boss
she'd supposedly called to explore her possible candidacy. In that
conversation, Mrs. Clinton expressed surprise that Manhattan was an
island and that not all the land west of the Hudson River was New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Callers wanted to know if that conversation really took place. A
few called to express to their outraged suspicions that I'd
concocted the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is that the conversation I described
never really happened. That column was satire. That's a literary
form described by the ``Random House Dictionary of the English
Language'' as ``caricature'' or ``parody'' involving the use of
``irony'' or ``sarcasm'' pointing up ``human folly'' or ``vice.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I made it up. The point was simply that Hillary
Clinton, whatever her other virtues, is not an expert on New York.
</P>
<P>
   Writing satire is always risky, I suppose. Most people will get
it; some most assuredly will not. Whenever I've used it, I've
unfailingly received a certain number of angry or mystified phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the Monica Lewinsky story broke 15 months ago,
my column the next day dealt with a 1963 visit by a teen-aged Bill
Clinton to the White House. Clinton actually did go there as a kid,
as part of a Boys State delegation. The kids got to meet President
John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The column dealt with a newly discovered _ and totally fictional
_ tape of a conversation in the Rose Garden between Kennedy and
Clinton. In it, I reported, Clinton confided his desire to become
president some day. Kennedy replied that it was a great way to meet
chicks. The phone just rang off the hook on that one.
</P>
<P>
   I did another one involving New York Gov. George Pataki's habit
of taking off from work. Every other day, the Associated Press
reports, ``Gov. George Pataki has no public schedule today.'' I
dealt with this by reporting a fictional conversation with my wife
in which she asked me my plans for the day, and I responded that I
had no public schedule.
</P>
<P>
   I'm really sorry if some people don't get it, but satire is a
time-honored journalistic form. Nobody does it better than Art
Buchwald. I vividly recall a Buchwald column of decades ago on
Bobby Kennedy's decision to run for the Senate from New York,
although Kennedy was really from Massachusetts. In that column,
Kennedy was wandering around Manhattan trying to find New York
Common.
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald's best satirical column ever was a piece on Richard
Nixon's failed effort to nominate a U.S. Supreme Court justice
whose primary qualification would be Southern roots. Nixon failed
in the Senate Judiciary Committee with two nominees _ one who was a
dope and the other who had ethical problems. But, Buchwald reported
one day, Nixon finally had found the perfect guy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert E. Lee Beauregard of
Mississippi, Buchwald wrote, was a legal genius and a man of
unchallenged, unimpeachable integrity. He had only one potential
problem with confirmation, Buchwald confided to his readers. Judge
Beauregard still owned slaves.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet that some people took it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
