<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-RANCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANCH OFFERS A TASTE OF THE EXOTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN HOME, Texas _ A gray day in spring turns a lot brighter
when you get up close with a giraffe, feed a fallow deer and make
friends with an ornery ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   There was a chill wind on an overcast Saturday morning in South
Texas during the 45-minute drive from Kerrville to Mountain Home,
home of the Y.O. Ranch. The kids were getting antsy in the back of
the van as we turned into the gates of the Y.O. off state Highway
41.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's keep our eyes peeled for animals,'' was barely out of my
mouth when we saw the first of many white-tailed deer.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, everyone sees deer in the Hill Country of Texas, but we
would be seeing some pretty exotic animals before the day was over
_ and getting a lot closer than the passenger seat of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   The Y.O. Ranch has been a working ranch since 1880, when Capt.
Charles Armand Schreiner, a former Texas Ranger and native of
Alsace-Lorraine, bought the Taylor-Clements Ranch. The story behind
the Y.O. brand is rather vague; some say that Schreiner had bought
up so many cattle branded with Y.O. that he kept the brand and the
name for the ranch, figuring it was a hard brand for rustlers to
tamper with.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiner introduced longhorns to the ranch, a breed that
continues today. This is home to Bevo, the mascot of the University
of Texas _ at least the retired one. The Y.O. breeds and lends a
longhorn to the university every few years, and that's not much of
a sacrifice since the Y.O. has about 2,600 longhorns and 2,000
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Schreiner family, headed by Charles III (Charlie 3, they
call him), still operates the ranch. Each son of 73-year-old
Charlie 3 has a role in the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Y.O. has had day tours every day (closed Christmas Day) for
about 20 years. All tours are by reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Schreiner introduced longhorns to the ranch. This is
Bevo's home, at least the retired one. The Y.O. breeds and lends a
longhorn to the University of Texas in Austin every few years. The
Y.O. has about 2,600 longhorns out of 4,600 head of cattle.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't cattle or even longhorns that we had come to see _
there was a kid in the backseat with a hankering to meet a giraffe.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Y.O. is known for the some 7,000 exotics,
representing 53 species, that can be found among the 40,000-acre
ranch. This is a breeding and hunting ranch. Animals are auctioned
to buyers, including zoos, while 20,000 acres are set aside for
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   At the chuckwagon _ really a cookhouse for ranch hands and
guests _ we met driver/guide Jim Hanks and six other visitors for
the morning tour.
</P>
<P>
   As the old school bus pulled out, Hanks filled us in on the
schedule. We would be driving around two pastures for about two
hours, and we could get out of the bus occasionally to take
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get too far away from the bus and if I ask you to load _
load damn fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the first stop Hanks discovered his nemesis, an ostrich who
stood guard at the gate. We all tumbled out of the bus for a closer
look and Hanks offered the critter some corn.
</P>
<P>
   We had to try another gate, but once inside the pasture it was
like a mini African safari. Over at the water hole were a couple of
Gray's Zebra (which Hanks told us sell for about $6,000 each), some
waterbuck, emu and wildebeest (watch out for the droppings).
</P>
<P>
   Emu were abundant, which made us wonder: Has the Y.O. taken in
any emu abandoned by Texas speculators trying to sell the meat of
the Australian birds? ``We have over 100 (emus) that the banks have
given us,'' Hanks said.
</P>
<P>
   But here came the ostrich again, so back in the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the hill stood a giraffe and we wanted a closer look.
Approaching a giraffe stealthily is the key. The adults go first,
balancing the corn on their heads while the kids hang back. Hanks
called this big fellow ``Papa'' and explained that the pregnant
female giraffe died in an accident in August.
</P>
<P>
   In the next pasture, we found an abundance of exotics: graceful
Dama gazelle that followed the bus; a rare Eld's deer from
Cambodia; a funny little addax, a type of antelope, from the
Sahara; an eland, the largest breed of antelope; and herds of
fallow deer.
</P>
<P>
   The fallow deer swarmed the children, one group eager for a feed
cube, the other for a chance to touch this gentle deer.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the bus doors swung open, the addax poked his head in
for a treat. Casey, 6, ran to the front of the bus to dish out some
corn. The addax had only one remaining horn and a top knot of hair
that looked like a bad toupee.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks warned the children to be careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not mean, he just found out if he knocks you down he gets
the whole can of corn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the chuckwagon, we lined up for a hearty lunch of
chicken-fried steak, gravy, potatoes, salad, pinto beans and peach
cobbler. Lunch is part of the tour package.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we moseyed over to the lodge, checked out the pool
and posed for pictures in the giant rocking chair left over from
the annual Y.O. Ranch party.
</P>
<P>
   What a day. We saw longhorns and buffalo, emu and eland. The
only cowboy around was behind the wheel, driving a Longhorn brand
bus full of camera-toting tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Yippee-i-o Y.O.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Y.O. Ranch is located at Mountain Home, bounded by
Interstate 10, U.S. 83 and Texas 41. The ranch is open for tours
daily _ except Christmas Day. Tour meal packages start at $25.95,
half-price for children younger than 12.
</P>
<P>
   Photo safaris, kids summer camp, overnight packages and
horseback riding are also available. Call 800-967-2624 or
830-640-3222 for reservations; on the Web at www.yoranch.com.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Y.O. Ranch Texas Longhorn Trail Drive is May 28-30.
Participants sleep under the stars, round up cattle, attend a
costume dance and ride the range.
</P>
</TEXT>
