<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-AGING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READ ALL ABOUT NEW WRINKLES IN AGING
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for BOOK-REVIEW-OLD.) 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England Centenarian Study conducted at Harvard
University Medical School revealed some pretty staggering facts
about America's ``oldest old'': For example, there are more than
50,000 centenarians in the United States today, almost three times
the number recorded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Geriatrician Thomas Perls, director of the study, has teamed up
with neuropsychologist Margery Hutter Silver and health journalist
John Lauerman to produce ``Living to 100: Lessons in Living to Your
Maximum Potential at Any Age'' (Basic Books/Perseus, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Profiles of centenarians (some with photos that demonstrate a
youthfulness inspiring to readers of any age), information blocks
and quizzes, including a Life Expectancy Calculator, will give you
an idea of your chances of being among the 75 million people alive
today who can anticipate ninth and tenth decades _ and good health
to boot.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd rather learn about healthy aging from a celebrity than
from a doctor, comedian Joan Rivers has lent her signature ``Can we
talk?'' style to ``Don't Count the Candles _ Just Keep the Fire
Lit! Staying Young at Any Age'' (HarperCollins, $25). As you'd
expect, Rivers sneers at those Pollyannas who insist we're not
getting older, we're getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' she asks. ``Is that a medical diagnosis? Then you
had better get a second opinion because I can't find my glasses to
read how good I've become.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers reminds us that we can fight aging every step of the way,
working on the things we can change and laughing about those we
can't. In the ``Good Things That Happened to You Today'' category,
she counts the day a success if you can say 1) you woke up; 2) you
woke up without pain; 3) you remembered you woke up without pain.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, of course, that Rivers has more resources at
her disposal than some of us: Her book is dedicated ``To all the
innovative plastic surgeons of tomorrow: Hurry!!''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the professionals: Preventive gerontologist Michael
Roizen believes that only 30 percent of aging is genetic; the rest
is determined by environmental factors and our own behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``RealAge: Are You as Young as You Can Be?''
(Cliff Street Books/HarperCollins, $25), he takes the reader
through 44 steps that he presents as scientifically sound and that
can make you look, feel and live ``up to 26 years younger'' (an odd
number, but few of us past the half-century mark would turn down
the chance to be a quarter of a century younger).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a ``RealAge Test,'' then advice and tips for
choosing the life-enhancing behaviors he reveals. The good doctor
considers health like money: ``It has an exchange value. Health
decisions and behavioral choices you make today are capital toward
living younger tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
