<SLUG> BC-TUMOR-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS USE RADIO WAVES TO ATTACK TUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In the first operation of its kind, surgeons here
have used a heating technique similar to the way a microwave oven
cooks food to try to kill a malignant, pancreatic tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors believe the procedure, performed Friday at the Wilford
Hall Medical Center at Lackland Air Force Base in San Antonio,
could lead to a change in the way tumors are attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kevin Watkins used radio frequencies to try to stop the
growth of cancerous cells in a 73-year-old patient's pancreas. The
patient, an Air Force retiree, was in serious but stable condition
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The process, called radio-frequency ablation, involves heating
diseased cells with a fine electrode. The high-frequency current
causes molecules to vibrate, heating the tissue from within just as
a microwave oven heats food.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure has been used before to fight tumors of the liver,
but Friday's operation was believed to be the first use on a
patient with pancreatic cancer, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent here was to give some chance of cure,'' he said.
``The problem has been that the tumors cannot be removed because of
their proximity to blood vessels. With radio-frequency ablation,
heat is used to destroy tumor cells.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be several weeks before doctors can judge the outcome of
the operation, Watkins said. Still, surgeons noted, no apparent
traces of tumor cells were left after the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   During the surgery, Watkins used ultrasound imaging to help
guide an electrode probe inserted in the tumor. Ten wires fanned
out at the tip of the probe, resembling an umbrella without the
cover, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   An alternating current flowed through the wires and into the
tumor, using heat to coagulate tissue by stopping blood flow to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Destroyed cells are later reabsorbed by the body over a period
of time.
</P>
<P>
   The tumor operated upon Friday was very large _ about 3 inches
by 3 inches, Watkins said. But it was ideal for radio-frequency
ablation because it was in the body of the pancreas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most pancreatic tumors are found near the small intestine,
making it more difficult to target without doing damage to the
walls of the small intestine.
</P>
<P>
   The patient also was an ideal candidate for the surgery because
his cancer, uncharacteristically, had not spread from the pancreas.
By the time of diagnosis, cancer of the pancreas often has spread,
usually first to nearby lymph nodes and then to the liver.
</P>
<P>
   The pancreas supplies the intestines with enzyme-rich juices
that help digest food. It also secretes insulin and other hormones
that control the amount of sugar in the blood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
