<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-FACES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LANCOME FACE RISES ABOVE THEM ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Isabella Rossellini was ``The Face'' of Lancome
until she had the bad manners to turn 42.
</P>
<P>
   Then the French company replaced her with four different models,
including actress Juliette Binoche, as the face of Poeme perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, one face seems to get more face time on the page than
the other four _ Ines Sastre.
</P>
<P>
   With a visage like a kitty-cat, Sastre is a young (25), Spanish-
born actress who photographs like a chameleon, depending upon what
look Lancome makeup artist Fred Ferrugia wants to give her.
</P>
<P>
   She was the butterfly woman for Les Chrysalides; the Kabuki
bunny for the Rouge collection; and now, with the cotton candy
spring collection, Candide, she is all innocence and trembling
lips.
</P>
<P>
   Sastre also has the third-most recognized mole in the beauty biz
_ behind Cindy Crawford and Madonna. ``They used to take it out,''
she laughed one day last week. Fresh off the plane from London,
Sastre was in San Francisco for a Lancome promotion and to open the
Macy's ``Colors of Provence'' Easter flower show. Her outfit was a
mixture of European ready-to-wear _ Chloe skirt, Mulligan camisole,
Voyage cardigan and Ungaro flats; her face, with her wide, dark
chocolate eyes, etched brows and generous mouth, was completely
free of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Valladolid in Castile and grew up in Madrid, but
left for France when she was 17. Being The Face is nothing new for
her. In 1992, she was the face of the Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A film actress since she was 13 (her first was ``El Dorado'' for
Carlos Saura), she flies to Argentina for three months to star in
``Un Amor de Borges.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way anyone would ever mistake Sastre's sultry looks
for Rossellini's, but comparisons are inevitable. ``One of the
reasons I wanted to represent Lancome was because I adored
Isabella,'' Sastre said diplomatically. ``I had a clear idea when I
was a teen-ager that she was my favorite. It's always difficult in
a sense _ you're not the other face. You still need a little bit of
time for people to get used to you.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they manage to recognize her in her many guises.
</P>
<P>
   To help you out: Watch for Ines's distinctive looks in ads for
Tresor, Vitabolic, Hydra Zen, the color campaigns and the sun
products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with last year's transformer line, Les Crysalides,
which Nordstrom had exclusively, Lancome started a growing trend in
cosmetic marketing _ confining specific products to specific
stores. The latest is the reissue of the 1967 fragrance, Climat, an
unusual blend of woody, floral-aldehyde with a musky, sandalwood
base in green juice. Find it only at Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
