   GM-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Folo on reports that General Motors'
president, G. Richard Wagoner Jr., may be backing away from an
ambitious plan to revolutionize the way the company makes small
cars and that he also told analysts that the company might not meet
some financial targets. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   OLSTEN-FINE (Undated) _ Olsten, a provider of home health-care
services, will pay $61 million, and a subsidiary will plead guilty
to criminal charges, to resolve federal investigations into the
company's billing practices. Olsten had said earlier that it was
the target of a Miami Federal grand-jury criminal investigation
regarding its relationship with Columbia/HCA. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIVITY (Washington) _ Some Labor Department studies
suggest that the department has been underestimating gains in
worker productivity. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-SUN (Undated) _ AOL and Sun discuss plans for an alliance.
By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The column: The airline industry is
in a public-relations tailspin. In just the last few months,
airlines have come under strong criticism from the White House and
Congress, have been faulted by travel agents and have been raked
over the coals by angry passengers. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-BT (Undated) _ The European Union clears AT&AMP;T and British
Telecommunications' planned joint venture after the companies agree
to some conditions. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The industrial average heads downward. At
midday, it was down 78 points, or 0.8 percent, at 9,930. The Nasdaq
index was up 0.1 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 1 percent in Tokyo
and rose 2.4 percent in Hong Kong. They fell half a percent in
Frankfurt, 0.1 percent in London, and 0.4 percent in Mexico. Stocks
in Brazil rose 1.2 percent. On the American debt market, the long
bond was up 8/32 point. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
