 Tuesday, March 30, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ Once again, the White House is
standing by as a top Russian envoy dramatically rushes into a war
zone to negotiate with a former Soviet-era ally. This time the
talks are between Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade. We look at the
similar role that Primakov played in Iraq during the Persian Gulf
War and again in Bosnia. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   STEALTH-FIGHTER (Washington) _ For days the Pentagon has refused
to reveal what caused the crash Saturday of a $45 million F-117A
stealth aircraft over Yugoslavia. But despite criticism, it may
never give the details. Officials say that if a missile hit the
fighter, they don't want to admit that a plane once believed to be
virtually invisible to radar is seriously vulnerable. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATIONS-Y2K (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission issues a report on whether the communications industry's
computers are prepared for Jan. 1. If they aren't, they may misread
2000 as 1900 and malfunction. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GUNS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that people
accused in multi-state crime sprees involving a gun can be charged
in any of those states with using the weapon even if they used it
in only one state. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Supreme Court dealt affirmative
action another blow Monday, continuing the trend of giving up on
efforts to remedy bias through racial and gender preferences. But
we are not yet a gender-or color-blind nation. Only last week the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology confessed that female
professors there suffer from pervasive discrimination. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
