<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9548 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-THINGS-REVIEW-LAD     03-30 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-THINGS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKESPEARE FOR TEENS _ SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1 1/2 STARS 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The teen film ``10 Things I Hate About You'' has a
great title and a terrific soundtrack, featuring a mix of new songs
and 1980s ``oldies.'' Unfortunately, the title and the music are
the two best things about this movie from Disney's Touchstone
Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The story is based loosely _ very loosely _ on Shakespeare's
``The Taming of the Shrew.'' High school senior Kat Stratford
(Shakespeare in-joke), played by Julia Stiles, is an angry young
woman with a sharp tongue and no apparent interest in boys. Her
younger sister, Bianca (Larisa Oleynik), by contrast, is sweet and
popular. Both attend the fictional Padua High School (ha-ha,
another Shakespeare reference).
</P>
<P>
   Since the two girls live in an idyllic Pacific Northwest coastal
town, are financially well-off and have perfect skin, what's the
problem? Here it is: Their overprotective physician father,
amusingly played by Larry Miller, tells Bianca that she can date
when her sister starts dating. He figures Kat will never date.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca desperately wants to go out with Joey Donner, a gorgeous
but heartless male model played by Andrew Keegan. Donner and
Cameron James, another would-be suitor of Bianca's played by ``3rd
Rock From the Sun'' actor Joseph Gordon-Levitt, both persuade a
bad-boy student named _ get it? _ Patrick Verona (played by Heath
Ledger) to ask Kat out on a date.
</P>
<P>
   Ledger starred in the recent TV miniseries ``Roar,'' and looks
like he walked off the cover of a romance novel. The equally
striking Kat, of course, resists his advances. The two finally hit
it off, until Kat discovers Patrick originally asked her out as
part of a bribe. ``You're  &UR; !ital! &LR; so &UR; !end! &LR;  not the person I
thought you were,'' storms Kat in an adolescent huff.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, both Kat and Bianca learn a lesson. Kat learns to
loosen up and love someone, while boy-crazy Bianca learns the
subtle art of kicking a boy in the groin.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's tamer than many of recent R-rated teen films, the
characters in ``10 Things'' live in a world filled with sex, drugs
and alcohol. The filmmakers may see as mitigating factors the facts
that Kat ends up stressing to her younger sister the importance of
waiting for ``the right guy,'' and that one of the male characters
keeps condoms on his shelf.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still difficult for those of us over this movie's
target age to see the humor in, for instance, Kat flashing her
breasts at a middle-age teacher to distract him. It's also a little
shocking to see well-known brand names such as Budweiser and
Heineken prominently displayed on the cans being stacked up at a
party by underage drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad all these pretty, appealing young actors weren't cast in
a smarter, funnier movie _ something like 1995's ``Clueless,''
which was based on Jane Austen's ``Emma.'' It's possible to do this
sort of film well, but ``10 Things'' misfires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
