<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEGADE REPUBLICANS BACK GAY RIGHTS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Seven Republican lawmakers who switched their
vote and came out in favor of a gay rights bill will have some
explaining to do to the state's Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party officials reacted with suspicion and disdain
Monday after realizing that a bill banning discrimination based on
sexual preference had picked up several supporters in the New York
Assembly _ including seven Republicans who had opposed the measure
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven are from Nassau County, where there may be
hell to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it cost them? That will be up to their county leader,''
said state Conservative Chairman Michael Long, adding that the
detractors could face a primary challenge if they seek re-election
next year.
</P>
<P>
   That could hinge on Jack O'Leary, the chairman of the Nassau
County Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack's a tough character and I'm sure he won't make life easy
for them,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he would ``have to have a talk with them...There'll
be a little bit of explaining to be done, let's put it that way
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For seven straight years, the Democratic-controlled Assembly has
passed a bill to prohibit discrimination based on sexual
orientation in the areas of employment, housing, public
accommodation and credit. Ten states, including most states in the
Northeast, have such a law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the measure was approved by the Assembly, although it
is doomed to again fail in the Republican-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the margin in the Assembly was far wider than
ever before _ 105 to 43 _ and the ranks of supporters included
seven Republicans who had previously voted against it: Frances T.
Sullivan, of Fulton, H. Robert Nortz, of Watertown, Harold C. Brown
Jr. of Onondaga County, and four Assembly representatives from
Nassau County _ Thomas Alfano, Maureen O'Connell, Kathleen Murray
and Donna Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cushing, chief of staff for Alfano, said the assemblyman's
decision to change his vote resulted from ``thoughtful
reflection...He felt, he really strongly felt, it was the right
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrara, who has opposed the homosexual rights bill six times in
the past, said the brutal murder last year of Matthew Shepard, a
gay college student in Wyoming, changed her mind once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really was the catalyst,'' Ferrara said. ``It clearly
showed that we have a class of people here who need extra
protections. That's why I changed my vote, which unfortunately is
opposed to the fundamental tenets of the Conservative Party. But I
thought it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrara said she was expecting political fallout from
Conservative forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they will not be pleased with this vote,'' Ferrara
said. ``Jack O'Leary is pretty politically savvy, and there will be
a little bit of explaining to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Foreman, executive director of Empire State Pride Agenda, a
gay rights group, said he was encouraged by the widespread support
the bill secured in the Assembly, and particularly from Republicans
who changed their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it took courage and strength of character on the part
of many Assembly Republicans who voted `no' in the past,'' Foreman
said. ``It is also a clear sign that they are listening to their
constituents. Every poll...has show New York residents want hate
crime legislation. It takes a really good legislator to change
their position in response to the real needs and interests of their
constituents. We hope it is a harbinger of fresh wind in Albany.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
