<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATRIX-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MATRIX' GREAT TO WATCH, HARD TO FOLLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 1/2 STARS 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The future, as seen in the brain-rattling and
ridiculous new sci-fi film ``The Matrix,'' is one scary place.
Life, unbeknownst to humans, has become a computer-generated
illusion. Machines no longer serve humanity; they rule it. And
Keanu Reeves is the Chosen One, the only hope the planet has to get
out of this pickle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's what we'd call a bleak tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The world is indeed a poorly lit place in ``The Matrix,'' a
dark, fast-paced, groundbreaking action film from brother
filmmaking team of Larry and Andy Wachowski. The movie will excite
the comic-book crowd with its stunning visuals and kinetic camera
work, which give it the look of a live-action Japanese anime film.
But a complete lack of story logic, coupled with the narrative's
propensity for meandering mumbo-jumbo, make this a movie best seen
and not heard.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves plays Thomas Anderson, a slacker computer hacker who has
always suspected that something wasn't quite right with the world.
His suspicions are confirmed when he meets a young, leather-clad
woman named Trinity (Carrie-Anne Moss) on the lam from a couple of
black-suited, law-enforcement types. Trinity leads Thomas to the
mysterious Morpheus (Laurence Fishburne), who tells him that life
is an illusion ``pulled over your eyes to blind you from the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point, things really get weird. The Wachowskis (whose
previous film, the lesbian heist picture ``Bound,'' certainly
didn't prepare us for this) have pioneered some remarkable
filmmaking techniques in this movie, giving the movie's action
sequences a distinct, fresh and fantastic look that audiences have
never before seen. These boys truly have redefined the action
genre.
</P>
<P>
   Example: The Wachowskis employ a technique called ``bullet-time
photography'' that allows them complete flexibility in controlling
the speed and movement of what's happening on the screen. Thus, in
a head-spinning martial-arts sequence between Reeves and Fishburne,
the fighters can accelerate to the apex of their leaps, hover in
midair, then kick _ rapidly and repeatedly _ and settle softly on
the ground. (Think kung-fu Fred Astaire and you'll get a glimmer of
what the scene looks like.)
</P>
<P>
   The results are eye-popping. But the Wachowskis, who wrote and
directed the film, seem unfamiliar with the maxim that a little
goes a long way. By the end of this overlong movie, the brothers
have staged a few too many loud, bullet-intensive showdowns.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse is that the world of ``The Matrix'' has no logic,
no rules. Even on the rare occasion when someone in the film
(usually Fishburne's Morpheus) says this is the way things are, you
can bet that 15 minutes later the ridiculous plot will dictate
otherwise. As for the theme of questioning reality and not letting
any system think for you, we think that's a good idea, too. We
certainly found ourselves questioning a few things here.
</P>
<P>
   The actors perform their stunts capably. Fishburne epitomizes
cool, while Reeves says ``Whoooa!'' with a conviction that no other
star in Hollywood can match.
</P>
<P>
   After watching about an hour or so of the movie's muddled
mayhem, you are completely inclined to wave the white flag, turn
off your brain and just go along for the ride. And it is a pretty
good head trip. If the Wachowskis had just devoted as much time and
energy to the logic of their universe as they did to its look,
``The Matrix'' would add up to something unequivocally worth the
price of the ticket. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
