<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LEGISLATURE SHOULD DRAW THE LINE ON THE SIDE OF PUBLIC
SAFETY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A minister I knew a long time ago in my youth used to
make a homespun analogy about personal freedom vs. public
responsibility that went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   You have the right to swing your fist, as long as it doesn't
encounter the tip of my nose.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that sounds corny _ and it probably does _ then you
likely have little stomach for legislative debate, an art form
often punctuated with misplaced cliches and stale corn pone.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Legislature's most difficult tasks is balancing the
rights of individuals with the welfare of society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Some issues, of course, are no-brainers. It was easy for
legislators to outlaw crimes like murder, theft, robbery and
assault. The only challenge there is deciding from one legislative
session to the next how tough the punishment should be, a task most
lawmakers readily welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Other forms of harmful, anti-social behavior are not as easy to
address, sometimes because influential interests have money at
stake, sometimes because sanctions strike too close to home, and
sometimes because people fear that government is getting too
intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   An issue that remains controversial is drunken driving, despite
successes in recent years by such groups as Mothers Against Drunk
Driving, or MADD, to toughen anti-DWI laws.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the focus now is on prevention, which is a key purpose
of a pending bill to lower the legal intoxication limit for drivers
from .10 percent to .08 percent blood alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
   That bill, which already has been approved by the Senate, is
likely to become law this session, partly because it is backed by
Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, partly because Texas
could gain millions of dollars in additional federal highway
funding if it is passed, and partly because many legislators
believe it is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The only organized opposition to surface so far has been from
the restaurant industry, whose members stand to lose money if the
proposed law, as expected, encourages responsible drivers to order
fewer drinks with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But I received a letter the other day from a reader who objects
to the bill and to a recent column I wrote endorsing it. He
believes government would be going too far in trying to regulate
personal behavior, just to please people like the ``righteous MADD
zealots.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point, the reader said he had a friend who has
driven more than 1.5 million miles, never had a fender bender nor a
traffic citation, but has had ``three DWIs'' and now faces the
prospect of going to prison, a penalty that can be imposed after a
third conviction for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   I assume he meant no traffic citations other than the three
DWIs, which are, of course, serious breaches of the law.
</P>
<P>
   I don't doubt that the reader's friend has never been involved
in an accident and has never harmed anyone. But I don't doubt
either that he and the people sharing the streets and highways with
him have been extremely lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The letter suggests that the driver's ``three DWIs'' have all
been convictions. If so, that same driver probably has been
intoxicated many other times while behind the wheel and just wasn't
caught.
</P>
<P>
   In that event, he is a tragedy waiting to happen if he continues
driving. He belongs in jail, an alcohol-treatment program or both.
</P>
<P>
   The letter writer goes on to suggest that it isn't fair to send
his drunken-driving friend to prison while not coming down hard on
another potential tragedy _ a sober but distracted driver on a
mobile phone who runs a red light, plows into another car and kills
several people.
</P>
<P>
   There is a bill pending in the Texas House that would prohibit
drivers from using their hands to operate mobile phones while their
cars are moving. That bill won't pass _ and it probably shouldn't
pass _ although some drivers misuse their mobile phones to the
point of recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   But there already are laws on the books that can send a
negligent or reckless driver who kills someone in an auto accident
to jail, even if no alcohol was involved in the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are we going to draw the line?'' the letter writer
asked.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that, when it comes to drunken driving, the Legislature
will draw the line on the side of public safety.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1440EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
