<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9568 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-30 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR TRAVELERS UNITE FOR FAIR TREATMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reacting to increased complaints from outraged travelers,
Congress has begun hearings on an Airline Passenger Fairness Act.
Not to be outmaneuvered, the Clinton administration has proposed an
Airline Passenger Fair Treatment Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath, but, because Republicans and Democrats
alike fly the ``friendly skies,'' a small chance exists that we may
see an eventual consensus on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   One consumer advocate urges all air travelers to join the
crusade. ``It's time for us to let our elected officials and the
airlines know that we're fed up and that we're not going to take it
anymore,'' says Tom Parsons, editor of Arlington-based
Bestfares.com magazine and the online site www.bestfares.com.
</P>
<P>
   Impetus for legislation grew after some Northwest Airlines
passengers were stranded on the tarmac for up to eight hours during
an early January snowstorm in Detroit. But issues of concern are
wide-ranging and include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Compensation for passenger inconveniences and full disclosure
on why flights are canceled or delayed;
</P>
<P>
   -- Lost luggage liability;
</P>
<P>
   -- Disclosure of frequent-flyer program mileage-redemption
allotments on each flight;
</P>
<P>
   -- Fare structures, with emphasis on providing passengers more
time to pay for a ticket, or to request a refund, after making a
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents has hailed legislation
introduced by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, and Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., a committee member,
and a separate bill proposed by Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman
of the House Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Airline officials argue that new laws are unnecessary and would
result in higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Travel agents and airlines in disagreement. Has that ever
happened before?
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, whose Web site attracts more than 1.5 million monthly
visitors, minced no words in expressing his position during a
recent visit to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   -- On frequent flyer redemption: ``There are more ways to earn
mileage today than ever before. But when we call an airline to book
reward seats on a flight, we are told nothing is available. Then
that plane departs with empty seats. Airlines operated at a 70
percent load factor last year. What percentage of those seats were
made available for mileage redemption? They won't tell us. They're
worried that if they say 5 percent or 10 percent, a competitor will
announce that it's making 20 percent or 30 percent of its seats
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loyal support of airlines through their frequent-flyer
programs has made them millions of dollars. They're paid by phone
companies and credit card companies and other businesses we support
as we earn frequent-flyer miles. In return, we have a right to know
how many seats are available to us.
</P>
<P>
   -- On lost luggage: ``Airlines are forcing us to check bags by
instituting stricter carry-on limitations. So if they lose those
bags, they should pay more for their negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On delays and cancellations: ``Airlines charge us $75 to redo
a ticket. So why shouldn't they have to compensate us when we're
inconvenienced? We didn't create these huge hub-and-spoke systems
that cause delays; they did. When they cancel a flight and there is
no bad weather, who is to blame? We don't make schedules that have
planes zig-zagging all over the country instead of going back and
forth on one route; they do. If there is one pimple in the sky, the
whole system goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're ever going to get cash from airlines (when
flights are canceled or delayed), but at the least, we should
receive vouchers for discounts on future travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons isn't relying on legislation to satisfy his No. 1
obsession: discovering air fare bargains. ``Some people collect
coins and stamps,'' he says. ``I collect deals.''
</P>
<P>
   That quest began innocently enough two decades ago when Parsons
took a sales job with Pier 1 Imports in Fort Worth, Texas. ``I was
the greenhorn of greenhorns,'' he says. ``They gave me a travel
card, and I said, `How and where do I book my tickets?' Then, as I
began traveling to 42 states and Canada, I realized that air fares
had no rhyme or reason. So I studied ways to cut corners
(irritating airlines with some of his ticketing gimmicks). I began
making fare charts. Next, I started a company newsletter that we
called Best Fares. The president gave me time to work on it because
it was saving the company so much money.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, an independent and greatly expanded Bestfares.com
magazine has 110,000 member-subscribers. Those who invest $59
annually learn about thousands of bargains _ some uncovered by a
staff that now totals more than 100; others negotiated exclusively
with airlines, cruise lines and hotels. (Call 800-880-1234 for
information.)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet site touts subscriber deals and serves as a
comprehensive free resource for other bargains, including each
airline's special weekend fares. Click on the ``News Desk'' icon to
learn about discounts for air travel, rental cars, hotels and
cruises; hundreds of items are added daily.
</P>
<P>
   What I like best about this Web site is that, even as he
recruits magazine subscribers, Parsons isn't reluctant to direct
browsers to rival companies or individual airline Web sites and
toll-free numbers. ``We're trying to serve as a clearinghouse for
travel bargains,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The savvy bargain-hunter, Parsons says, keeps an open mind,
studies fare trends and comparison-shops. Those slow to embrace the
Internet, he says, ``probably have an Uncle Leo in Cheyenne, Wyo.,
who can do the online research.'' He recommends purchasing tickets
from a travel agent but says, ``You can't expect the travel agent
to do all the work for you. Finding the best deals requires some
`smarts.'''
</P>
<P>
   After all, who wants to pay a fortune to wait on the tarmac for
eight hours?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
