<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF WORKERS READY TO RETURN TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC DRUDIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Exasperated relief workers, locked out of
Yugoslavia as NATO continues its air raids on the nation's military
forces, are taking early steps to help refugees from Kosovo when
calm is restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go back to Kosovo and help everyone trapped in
the region,'' said Angela Mason of the World Vision relief
organization. ``We intend to go back as soon as possible. This is a
huge humanitarian tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, relief workers have intensified efforts in
southeast Europe as refugees from Kosovo flood shelters in Albania
and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   World Vision, the largest privately funded children's agency in
the world, has had to suspend operations because of the NATO
bombings. Kevin Cook, director of the agency's work in Kosovo,
reported that violence had engulfed Kosovo's capital of Pristina
since the North Atlantic Treaty Organization launched air raids
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real needs are with at least 300,000 people inside Kosovo,
and there is no way for foreign aid to reach them now,'' said Cook,
who has been based in Macedonia since the bombing campaign began.
``Under current conditions, relief agencies can't deliver aid.
Without that assistance _ and a peaceful resolution to the crisis _
there will be tremendous loss of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO alliance launched the air raids on March 24 after
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia defied efforts to forge
a peace deal with the largely Albanian population of Kosovo. Kosovo
is a province of Serbia, the dominant state in Yugoslavia. Some 2
million people live in Kosovo, regarded by Milosevic as the cradle
of Serbian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Although few independent monitors remain in Kosovo, the ethnic
Albanians appear to be fleeing their homeland in the face of
intensifying attacks by Milosevic's police and paramilitary units.
But some evidently are escaping the NATO air attacks on Yugoslav
army installations and ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragedy,'' Mason said. ``We have been forced to
withdraw our supplies when we are most needed and we fully intend
to return as soon as it is over.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO asked all 30 relief organizations based in Kosovo to leave
in advance of the air raids, or they were expelled by Serbian
officials before the bombing started.
</P>
<P>
   CARE International has relocated its Kosovo relief operations to
Belgrade, the capital of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They evacuated (Kosovo) last week because the situation became
more difficult and the threats of bombing and violence became too
dangerous,'' CARE representative Claudia Chang said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE has intensified operations in Macedonia and expects to
establish a presence in Albania soon.
</P>
<P>
   OxFam America spokesman Seth Amgotg said his organization left
Kosovo once it was apparent relief workers were in ``imminent
danger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
