<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITY THE `POOR' EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today we take up the collection plate for a few poor souls who
are down on their luck. They're all good, hard-working men, honest
and God-fearing to a fault. They deserve every penny they earn.
But, of late, fortune has turned against them.
</P>
<P>
   Our hearts go out to them.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that just last year they were able to look their fellow
man in the eye and revel in the joy of arrogance. Now they shrink
at the thought of bumping into those whose lives have more richly
rewarded them in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the least we can do to take up the collection plate in a
selfless effort to restore the lifestyle to which they are so
accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop is the St. Johns Episcopal Church in Charleston,
W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   We'll circulate among the tables of the soup kitchen with our
palms out for donations from the bedraggled crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these kind spirits can part with a nickel or a dime
to help lift up a fellow man, even though, as Wanda Long, assistant
director of the soup kitchen, explained to The New York Times: ``We
usually give them a small can of food or a sandwich or a container
with leftovers. Otherwise, they wouldn't have any supper.''
</P>
<P>
   Our plate jingling with a few shiny coins, we'll make our way to
North Korea. In the barren rice fields of this sad country _ where
by some estimates famine has killed 2 million people since mid-1990
_ we'll step over the dead and dying, the emaciated and immobile
from hunger, until we find someone who can still lift an arm to
drop a coin into our plate.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'll race home to present our donations to our downcast
souls.
</P>
<P>
   First is Eckhard Pfeiffer, the chief executive of Compaq
Computer Corp. Mr. Pfeiffer's grin is a little frayed these days
because, instead of receiving $46.3 million, as he did in 1997, he
had his salary slashed to a poverty-stricken $23.3 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's $23.3 million for running a company whose operating
profit plunged 71 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Our soup kitchen diners and starving North Koreans did God's
work in lending him a hand.
</P>
<P>
   Any man who makes $23 million less in one year than he did the
previous year certainly needs a handout. There are many reasons,
not necessarily clear to us all, why a single individual needs more
money than a small country.
</P>
<P>
   Next are David Komansky, chairman and chief executive of Merrill
Lynch, and Hugh McColl Jr., chairman and chief executive of
BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   We wish were able to fully restore Mr. Komansky's pay of $11.1
million in 1997, but we were only able to add a little stack of
coins to his $9.9 million of last year. If we were able to ease his
suffering at all, we're pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McColl, painfully, had his bonus cut 29 percent last year to
$2.5 million. A bonus of just $2.5 million for leading his company
to a 21 percent decline in profit.
</P>
<P>
   What pains these panhandlers most of all is seeing their
friends' compensation tumble but still exceed their own by envious
amounts.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to overlook Sanford Weill, co-chairman of
Citigroup. His total pay slumped 24 percent last year _ but he
still trotted home with $166.9 million. Now there's something to
burst a few blood vessels in any down-at-the heels executive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at levingston(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
