<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9611 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRALIZATION VS. PLURALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I confess that I have always liked and admired George Bush. He
occupied the White House at an extraordinary time. The Cold War was
ending. The Soviet Union was coming apart. China flirted with
democracy. Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait in a bold attempt to seize
the ``the oil weapon'' _ and Bush firmly repudiated him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was defeated for reelection by the right wing of the
Republican Party because he trimmed the deficit on the eve of the
Gulf War. Even in defeat, therefore, he had laid the early
groundwork for the current 10-year boom. I believe his
administration was the most undervalued since Gerald Ford took over
from Richard Nixon in 1974 and restored the nation's trust in
central government.
</P>
<P>
   So when the bombs started falling on Belgrade last week, I took
a look back to see what the Bush administration had thought and
done about Yugoslavia. I took down my copy of ``A World
Transformed,'' the graceful colloquy with Brent Scowcroft that Bush
and his national security adviser published last year. I turned to
the index.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia, 43, 514, 516, 541.''
</P>
<P>
   The first entry in the 590-page book is a description of a
meeting in the Oval Office in March 1989, not long after Bush took
office. Present were Vice President Dan Quayle; Secretary of State
James Baker; Defense Secretary Dick Cheney; Scowcroft and his
deputy, Lawrence Eagleburger; CIA director Robert Gates; and chief
of staff John Sununu. The topic: a speculative memo on Gorbachev by
Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scowcroft, Rice had raised an intriguing
possibility: ``that we might have leverage over Moscow because of
its need for Western economic resources and know-how.'' The
Russians were looking for ideas to rebuild their failing system at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion in the meeting also noted: ``Although in Western
Europe the notion of nationalist conflict was passe, it was too
soon to tell whether political evolution in Eastern Europe had
moved at an equal pace in places like Yugoslavia, Hungary, or
Roumania, where there were long-standing ethnic tensions and
separatist pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in March 1989, Slobodan Milosevic stripped Kosovo of its
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Three eventful years passed. The entries on pages 514 and 516
come as Bush and Scowcroft report the chilly reception to a speech
in August 1991. Bush was about to visit Babi Yar, where 33,000
Ukrainians, Jews, and others had been shot to death by Nazis in 36
hours during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans will not support those who seek independence in
order to replace a far-off tyranny with a local despotism. They
will not aid those who promote a suicidal nationalism based upon
ethnic hatred,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Critics dubbed the remarks Bush's ``chicken Kiev'' speech,
charging that it was a plea to keep the Soviet Union together. Two
weeks later, a coup in Moscow attempted Gorbachev's dismissal. Its
failure eroded the authority of the Communist party, and
accelerated the rise of the republics.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later occurs the last reference to Yugoslavia in ``A
World Transformed.'' During an Oval Office meeting, Baker says:
``The peaceful breakup of the Soviet Union. We don't want another
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   That summer of 1991, the Yugoslav navy was shelling the coastal
resort of Dubrovnik, as Milosevic began his war on the Croats. A
European Community delegation, led by Lord Carrington, failed to
make him stop. The horrors of ``ethic cleansing'' were yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Origins of a Catastrophe'' by Warren Zimmerman,
Bush's last ambassador to the federal republic, the administration
did little to prevent the breakup of Yugoslavia. Baker, for
example, spent exactly one night in Belgrade trying to prevent the
secession of Slovenia and Croatia. Laura Silber argued in the
Financial Times the other day that a simple show of force by NATO
in 1991 could have deterred Milosevic. But then there are those
four passing entries in ``A World Transformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it's just possible that Bush bet wrong _ not only
on Yugoslavia but on Russia and Gorbachev. After all, he was as
greatly constrained by his right wing in foreign affairs as in
domestic matters. Dismantling governments was all the rage in those
days.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight? Of course. What better way is there to learn?
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
