<HEADLINE>
BIG WINNERS AS DOW TOPS 10,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What to make of Dow 10,000? Think of it as a monument
to the stock market's fabulous gains in what will be remembered as
one of America's most prosperous decades.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, some of them have been achieved close to home.
Dozens of Massachusetts companies have created enormous wealth for
their shareholders during the Nifty Nineties. The repeated lesson
contained on that local list of winners: innovation and execution.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp. of Hopkinton was a runaway winner in a Boston Capital
survey of local stocks that were publicly traded at the start of
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the data storage company gained an amazing 47,692
percent during that period. Adjusted for splits, EMC stock that was
worth 129 5/8 Monday began the 1990s trading at 27 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Staples Inc., the office supply retailer based in Westborough,
was second on the Massachusetts list with a gain of 3,022 percent
through the decade to date. Parametric Technology Corp. of Waltham
was third, advancing 2,235 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one way to put those very best stock gains in proportion:
the Dow advanced during the same period from 2753 to Monday's
closing value of 10,006.78. That's an admirable gain of about 263
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The top 20 performing stocks in Massachusetts of the 1990s make
up a list that's heavy on technology, with a sprinkling of retail,
banking and money management. All but one of them, each with a
value of at least $250 million, beat the performance of the Dow
itself.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat to our list: companies that first went public in the
1990s are not included. One notable absentee, Internet investing
comany CMGI Inc. of Andover, has risen from a split-adjusted price
of about 63 cents per share in 1994 to 186 9/16 Monday, a 296-fold
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The advance of EMC shares turned an obscure technology company
into the second most valuable public company in Massachusetts. EMC,
now worth more than $65 billion, trails only Gillette Co.'s market
valuation of $70.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EMC began to show up on computer screens at big money management
firms like Putnam Investments because it consistently outpaced
expectations and showed consistent promise for the future. Putnam
continued to buy EMC stock and owned 16.5 million shares by the end
of 1998, making it one of the company's largest institutional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``EMC has run up against the likes of IBM and Storage
Technology, some pretty substantial companies with a lot of
resources and brainpower,'' said David Santos, a Putnam portfolio
manager who works with the firm's group that buys and sells large
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've succeeded because they were so focused on their market
and developed unique advantgage in that niche. The niche turned out
to be a pretty substantial part of the technology market,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is what transformed data storage from a small
corner of the technology world into an important specialty. The
Internet required hardware to store large amounts of information
and EMC cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, institutional investors that did not want to buy the
latest Internet stock rocket bought companies like EMC, Lucent
Technologies and others that were building the Internet's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   There was no comparable chain of innovations in paper clips this
decade. But Staples survived and prospered on execution, outlasting
all but two of what was once a field 28 companies that tried to
make a buck the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't always flawless,'' said John Ballen, president of
MFS Investment Management, which has been a large investor in
office superstore chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock was flat at times, often for a period of a year or
two. But they perservered, mostly through internal growth, and
dominate the marketplace. It's a matter of execution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The value of execution can be found elsewhere on our top 20
list, from fellow retailer TJX Cos., to other companies like State
Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But few companies on our list can match Gillette when it comes
to turning consistent business performance into huge stock market
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, one of the few top 20 stocks that started the 1990s as
a big company, has appreciated by 936 percent through the decade so
far. Only BankBoston Corp. (ranked 19th) would have been considered
one of the state's largest companies in 1990 and its gains are
helped by depressed bank stock values at the start of the decade
and the modest acquisition premium of its intended acquisition by
Fleet Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
