<HEADLINE>
MEN, WOMEN, AND VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPNTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men and women definitely are not the same. We noticed that years
ago, but the latest proof comes in a survey of Caribbean activities
from Aruba Sonesta Reports. Here are the results:
</P>
<P>
   -- Men spend 20 percent (14 hours) of their time on the island
beach, while women spend 25 percent (18 hours).
</P>
<P>
   -- Although the Caribbean's waters are warm and inviting,
surprisingly little time is spent in them. Men spend only an
average of 3 percent of their vacation time submerged, while women
spend 6 percent. The water time for women is believed to be higher
because they tend to be watching the youngsters, who, the survey
says, spend an amazing 84 percent of their waking hours in the
ocean or a pool.
</P>
<P>
   -- Men snooze slightly more than women _ 10 percent of their
time (seven hours) vs. 8 percent (5.5 hours). (Instead of snoozing,
they should be helping their wives watch the kids in the water!)
</P>
<P>
   -- When it comes to shopping time, women lead with 8 percent
compared with 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The resort report is based on a six-night vacation with two days
of travel time and five vacation days and assumes one full day of
sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   Travel trivia: On which island is the Bahamas capital of Nassua
located? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   In a name: Jamaica was originally called ``Xaymaca'' (the ``Land
of Wood and Water'') when founded by the Arawak Indians. And never
mind that Columbus took all credit when he set foot on the island
in 1494.
</P>
<P>
   Cool: When the 300-room Hyatt Regency St. Lucia opens this fall,
features will include swim-up verandas, allowing guests to enter
their rooms directly from the pool. The resort will also have its
own helicopter pad.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``Welcome to Jamaica, where the left side is the right
side, and the right side is the suicide side.'' _ billboard in
Montego Bay that reminds visitors that driving is on the left in
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Martinique's French accent: The romance of France extends to its
sunny Caribbean ``Departement'' of Martinique. An ocean may
separate this island from its mother country, but nonetheless
you'll find gendarmes directing traffic on streets with names like
rue Victor Hugo and rue de la Liberte. Martinique, in fact, is
enjoying a tourist vogue, with its 86 hotels; its French-Creole
cooking where seafood is king; its pleasant and popular ``Empress
Josephine'' golf course; its shopping, which can include savings on
perfume, spice, and everything nice; and its walking, hiking,
cycling, and nature areas, including the Valley of the Butterflies.
For more information, call the Martinique Promotion Bureau at
800-391-4909, fax 212-838-7855, visit www.martinique.org, or write
to 444 Madison Ave., New York, NY 10022.
</P>
<P>
   Bond . . . James Bond: You, too, can stay at Goldeneye Estate in
Jamaica where Ian Fleming wrote his James Bond thrillers. But it
will cost you: $5,000 a night for up to six people. Meals are
included, however. For more information, call 800-OUTPOST.
</P>
<P>
   Mail bag: Basil of Boston and Homer J. Rajotte of Northbridge
dispute a recent mention about how much fuel the Queen Elizabeth II
burns and what kind of fuel it is. According to Basil, at 28 knots
the QE II burns one gallon of bunker fuel for every 6 feet of
forward motion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? Nassau is on New Providence Island in the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
