<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVRON SEEKS TO REDUCE GASOLINE ADDITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Chevron Corp. plans to eliminate MTBE, a
gasoline additive that has turned up in drinking water, from its
California gas supply within two years of receiving federal
approval to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron has heard the concerns Californians have voiced about
MTBE in gasoline,'' Chevron Chairman Ken Derr said in announcing
the move Monday. ``While we believe that MTBE poses no significant
health risk, we also believe that it does pose an environmental
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron's announcement came four days after Gov. Gray Davis
ordered the removal of MTBE from the state's gasoline supply by
2003 _ contingent on a change or waiver in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., has sponsored a bill that would
amend the Clean Air Act to do away with the requirement to add MTBE
to the nation's gas supply. There is no estimate on how long it
will take for the federal policy on MTBE to change.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fracisco-based oil and gas company said that
immediately upon gaining federal approval, it could cut by at least
half the amount of methyl tertiary butyl ether, or MTBE, it puts
into its gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE had been hailed as the star ingredient for cleaner-burning
gasoline. In 1996, the federal government required MTBE to be added
to gasoline sold in the nation's smoggiest urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   However, the chemical proved menacing when it found its way into
groundwater, lakes and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron spokesman Fred Gorrell said the company cannot
immediately eliminate all MTBE because the additive boosts octane,
which allows cars to run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its plan, Chevron also recommended that all refiners
in the state cut by half the amount of MTBE they add to their
gasoline supply in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Gorrell said this recommendation should be easy to implement
since the federal Clean Air Act requires only one city in Northern
California _ Sacramento _ to sell MTBE-laced, or oxygenated, fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron also suggested that all refiners produce gasoline that
is MTBE-free within two years after the law is modified.
</P>
<P>
   Derr said the cost to eliminate MTBE would be modest, increasing
the price of a gallon of gas by perhaps 1 or 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been at odds with Chevron in the past were in
accord with the company's plans to eliminate MTBE from its
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best of all possible scenarios,'' said Krista
Clark, a spokeswoman for the Association of California Water
Agencies, a Sacramento group that represents nearly all of the
water agencies in the state. ``We can come up with a process that
meets federal (rules) and prevent backsliding on air quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over MTBE has become particularly acute in
recreational areas where there are large numbers of personal
watercraft such as Jet Skis and small boats, many of which are
powered by two-stroke engines.
</P>
<P>
   According to scientists, up to 30 percent of the fuel in the Jet
Skis' two-stroke engines is released unburned into the water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
