<HEADLINE>
THE CARIBBEAN HEATS UP, OFF SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Caribbean used to be thought of as a winter destination. No
more.
</P>
<P>
   More and more travelers are discovering the Caribbean in summer,
with resorts costing anywhere from 20 percent to 50 percent less
than winter, or high season, rates. There is also another reason:
weather.
</P>
<P>
   On many islands, summer means a rain-free vacation. And the
weather is almost consistent, with temperatures in the 80s. Compare
that with many places where rain can wipe out a week's vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``off-season'' deals:
</P>
<P>
   At Chenay Bay Beach Resort in St. Croix, one night is free when
five nights are booked. A free car rental for three days is
included on bookings made for April 15-July 15. For information,
call 800-548-4457.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott's new Aruba Ocean Club is featuring rooms beginning at
$160 a night, April 24 through Dec.18. For information, call
800-845-5279.
</P>
<P>
   The West Indies Management Co. in Newport, R.I., is offering
low-season rates at 18 luxury properties throughout the Caribbean.
Packages are for three to seven nights and include accommodations,
airport transfers, car rentals, breakfasts, and more. For
information, call 800-932-3222.
</P>
<P>
   First-time guests will receive a $69-a-night, double occupancy
rate (a savings of more than 50 percent) at the Tamarind Reef Hotel
on St. Croix, June 1-Dec. 1. For information, call 800-619-0014.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-room upscale Spice Island Beach Resort in Grenada is
offering savings of $600-$1,300 on an eight-day, seven-night stay.
For information, call 800-223-9815.
</P>
<P>
   Families will also find activities for children. At the Westin
Resort on St. John in the US Virgin Islands, a Summer Jammers Camp
is available June 14-Aug. 13 with activities for the young set.
Children 12 and under eat free during their stay, and those under
18 stay free with their parents. The camp is an extra cost. For
information, call 800-808-5020.
</P>
<P>
   A handy guide to those planning a Caribbean vacation is the
fifth edition of the Caribbean Vacation Planner. The free 168-page
guide covers 27 destinations, has island maps, facts, figures, Web
site addresses, and general information. For a copy, call
800-356-9999, ext. 799. The guide can also be requested on the Web
at www.caribtourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   While off season offers good travel value, keep in mind that
some properties use this time for renovations. So, before you book,
make sure the facilities you desire are working or available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WORD UP!
</P>
<P>
   Where are all the writers heading? They're off to Club Med in
Cancun, Mexico. Twenty of America's top literary authors, along
with journalists from major magazines and newspapers, will join
with vacationers in exploring a series of provocative questions
from different perspectives. Among authors participating will be
Pulitzer Prize winner Richard Ford and National Book Award finalist
Jamaica Kincaid. The ``Word Up! The American Mosaic'' program will
be held April 10-17.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in Word Up! is included in the village stay. The
seven-night, all-inclusive package is $959 a person. A combination
air and land package is also available. Previous Club Med forums
have covered cinema, art, and photography. The next forum will be
in May on book publishing and will be held in Turkey; a '60s forum
is set for September in France; and the final forum for '99 will be
dedicated to magic and magicians and held in the French Alps. For
information, call Club Med at 800-CLUBMED or a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   SKI SEASON
</P>
<P>
   There's still good skiing in New England. Vermont reports more
than 90 percent of its slopes are operating, and many will continue
to operate into May. (For Vermont ski conditions, call
800-VERMONT). Among spring events are the Reggae Fest and Pond
Skimming Weekend, April 10-11, at Sugarbush (call 800-53-SUGAR), a
mogul competition at Jay Peak on April 3, featuring moguls the size
of a Volkswagen (for information, call 802-988-2611).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FLOWER STORE
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest store, Macy's in Herald Square in New York
City, is celebrating its 25th anniversary flower show through April
7. Every window of the famed store offers a scene from another
place, with floral arrangements that exemplify a foreign land.
Inside, flowers will be found just about everywhere in the store.
Visitors will also find seminars on garden topics and a free
20-minute guided tour. For information, call the flower show hot
line at 212-494-4495. For tour reservations, call 212-494-3827.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAYMAN FESTIVALS
</P>
<P>
   One of the best destinations is the Cayman Islands. Not only is
it a great destination for diving and snorkeling _ especially
Stingray City _ but it's also a festival isle. Upcoming is the
second annual fishing tournament, April 24-May 2, with $450,000 in
cash prizes, and Cayfest, a monthlong program celebrating Caymanian
culture, begins April 5; Batabano Carnival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
