<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      03-30 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, March 31:
</P>
<P>
   FISH-NY (New York) _ New Yorkers may take it for granted. But
browsing the menu at Tropika is a rare opportunity. There are conch
from Mexico, John Dory from Australia and pompano from South
America. A walk though a good fish market is no less extraordinary.
The fish _ a stunning display of glistening specimens _ come from
all over the world. There may be red snapper from New Zealand, so
bright they look as if they are illuminated, and with eyes so
alive, you think the fish may jump if you touch it. Or sardines
from Portugal stacked like silver rods. And you will almost always
find sushi-quality tuna from the Gulf of Mexico, as red as a rose
petal, shrouded in flakes of white ice. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   FISH-STRANGE (New York) _ It was a fine day for fish, a bad day
for humans _ cold, wet and windy. After squeaking into a parking
place near Grand Central Terminal, Patricio Osses jumped out of his
white van and flashed a triumphant smile at Julian Alonzo, the
executive chef at Cafe Centro. ``Man, I have got some ugly fish,''
he said, throwing open the back doors of the truck. He wasn't
kidding. Deep within the refrigerated gloom, his eyes made out the
horrid forms of fish that dare not speak their names, strange
creatures that haunt Chilean waters but are now, thanks to Osses,
creeping onto restaurant tables in New York. In a city full of the
remarkable and various fish of the world, the very strangest
creatures of the deep come from one purveyor. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With 1 recipe.
</P>
<P>
   BRING-YOUR-OWN-WINE (New York) _ The right, even the necessity,
to tote your own wine to dinner is a time-honored practice among
many smaller restaurants that are not licensed to sell wine and
beer. But the practice also occurs at fancier, more ambitious
restaurants that have invested considerable amounts of money in
building their wine lists. Restaurants do not encourage the
practice, but most allow it, especially, as I found out by
experimenting at several restaurants, if you adhere to a certain
protocol. This essentially consists of politely asking a
restaurant's permission to bring wine, and having a good reason for
wanting to do so. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
