<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MARCH
30, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO -- MOOD-KOSOVO. With the United States engaged in its
most perilous military operation since the Gulf War -- airstrikes
against Yugoslavia that threaten to fray ties with old Cold War
enemies -- the reaction in the Capitol of the Free World has been a
collective yawn. Unlike various other ``crises'' this decade --
such as the Gulf War or President Clinton's impeachment trial --
NATO's intervention in Yugoslavia has sparked only a muted public
reaction. The few protests that have been staged were scattered and
poorly attended, security precautions have been tightened only
slightly and people seem, for the most part, to have things other
than the Balkans on their minds. Colorado congressional aides
recall former crises in Washington. (800 words). By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- DRUG-ALLEN. Almost everybody in Washington agrees that
now is the time to fix Medicare. The government's health care plan
for the elderly has become medically outdated, and, without a huge
cash infusion from the federal government, it will go broke in less
than a decade. Everybody says the situation is dire, but nobody can
agree on a plan to solve it. Even the much-ballyhooed ``National
Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare,'' created to find
a solution both the GOP-controlled Congress and the White House
could accept, broke up two weeks ago without making any formal
recommendations. Enter Tom Allen. The second-term Democratic
congressman from Portland says he has devised a plan to help the
elderly poor afford prescription drugs and, at the same time, save
the government a fortune. (800 words). By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS--ISTEA--MONEY. The federal government released
more than $2.4 million to the Worcester Regional Transit Authority
to be used for the Worcester Intermodal facility. (200 Words) By
Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS--KOSOVO-TROOPS. Bay State lawmakers chip in with
their opinions about sending ground troops into Kosovo. (300 words)
By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- WATER. States vary in their restrictions for
bottled water, with many, including Pennsylvania, stricter than the
Food and Drug Administration's regulations. Bottled water may not
be any better for you than tap water, an organization said in a
study released today. The Natural Resources Defense Council says
bottled water is not as regulated as tap water, and sometimes has
misleading labeling about the source of the product. (700 words.)
By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
