<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVITT31-COX     03-30 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVITT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC WIDENS CAMPAIGN AGAINST 'PAY TO PLAY' PRACTICE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Securities and Exchange Commission this spring
will propose rules aimed at stopping money managers from making
political contributions to officials who could steer public pension
fund business their way.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which had been expected, was announced Tuesday by SEC
Chairman Arthur Levitt at the spring meeting of the Council of
Institutional Investors, a pension fund organization.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said the trading of political contributions for
investment business, known as ``pay to play,'' is an ``insidious''
practice that ''has tainted the management of public funds.'' He
said the SEC had heard allegations that political contributions
have affected the selection of money managers for public pension
plans in 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   All told, public pension funds have more than $2 trillion(cq) in
assets, Levitt noted.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would extend the SEC's campaign against ``pay to
play.'' Earlier, the agency attacked the practice in the municipal
bond business.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues:
</P>
<P>
   Levitt repeated his position that education, not rule-making, is
the best way to protect investors caught up in online investing and
day trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the kind of phenomenon that invariably arises
at times of high market activity, you may even say market
overexuberance. Because of that, the best remedy for it will be a
market remedy,'' he said. ``You cannot protect people against their
own foolishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said the SEC is ``looking very closely'' at the how day
trading is promoted, and is checking online trading firms to see if
they are following regulations on margin rules and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman said progress has been made on efforts to keep
companies from managing earnings _ reporting profits in a way that
they meet Wall Street expectations _ but added that ``we still have
a way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1551EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
