<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SEDER-ARTIFACT-BO     03-30 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SEDER-ARTIFACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIFACT RECALLS FIRST SEDER AFTER GERMANY'S FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three years ago, when Saul Touster was deep in the task
of cleaning the attic of his summer home in Plymouth, Mass.,
sorting through the accumulation of four generations of family
history before selling the house, a flimsy, yellowing pamphlet fell
from his father's papers to the dusty floor.
</P>
<P>
   In that serendipitous moment, Touster discovered a copy of a
1946 Haggadah, a Passover prayer book put together by Jewish
survivors of the Holocaust, published by the US Army and used at a
Seder in Munich on the first Passover after the fall of Nazi
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The American-born son of American-born parents, Touster vowed to
learn the book's story and to preserve it. On Wednesday, when the
retired college professor sits down to his Seder meal, he will use
a newly published limited edition of the survivors' Haggadah,
complete with commentary that he researched and wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Haggadah replete with Zionist yearnings and haunting
parallels between the survivors' own suffering and liberation and
the suffering and liberation of the enslaved Jews of ancient Egypt.
On its cover is the insignia of the US Third Army, the American
army of occupation. Interspersed through its pages are seven
harrowing woodcut prints depicting the life, and death, of Jews in
Hitler's Europe. In it is the lament, ``The sorrow is great and so
is the pain, such that the survivors swear . . . to go to the Holy
Land at any cost, for it is hard for them to remain in lands that
are soaked with their blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis University historian Jonathan Sarna calls the
survivors' Haggadah ``a remarkable document in terms of spiritual
history.'' David Stern, professor of Jewish literature at the
University of Pennsylvania, calls it ``an incredible testament to
Jewish creativity and Jewish persistence'' and says that ``there's
nothing quite like it in terms of a Haggadah that was produced by
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   For Saul Touster of Boston, 73, professor emeritus of law and
social policy at Brandeis University and a World War II veteran who
served in the South Pacific, the labor of these past three years
has been ``a tremendous fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, he surmises, received the Haggadah in appreciation
of his work as president of the Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society in the
early 1950s. ``I felt that he valued this especially,'' Touster
says, ``and kept it separate from the institutional archives (of
HIAS) and somehow fate had delivered it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of very deep strains in my life,''
Touster says after a long pause. ``The strong Jewish feelings. The
family's commitment to service for the refugees. I wanted to honor
those who survived. And what I put into it was a special feeling of
doing honor to my father.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Historical Society has printed 500 copies
selling for $360 apiece, and the Jewish Publication Society plans a
less expensive bookstore version in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   What Touster has preserved is a Haggadah composed in Hebrew and
Yiddish by Yosef Dov Sheinson, a Lithuanian Jewish teacher and
writer in modern Hebrew who survived Dachau. It is illustrated with
Sheinson's drawings and the woodcuts of Miklos Adler, a Hungarian
Jewish artist whose transport to Auschwitz was unexpectedly
diverted to Vienna. When Jewish leaders in postwar Munich showed a
copy of the Haggadah to US Army chaplain Abraham Klausner, the
rabbi arranged its publication.
</P>
<P>
   The Seders Rabbi Klausner held at the Deutsches Theatre
Restaurant on April 15-16, 1946, were ostensibly for Jews in the US
military, but most of the 200 to 300 who came to each Seder were
Holocaust survivors living in Munich. Different ones came each
night, because Klausner, who'd brokered a Passover meal of fish and
chicken, wanted to feed as many people as possible. Although
Sheinson labeled his work a supplement to the Haggadah, for these
Seders it was the only text used.
</P>
<P>
   Where the traditional Haggadah opens the Passover story with the
sentence ``We were slaves to Pharoah in Egypt,'' Sheinson uses
those words as the caption to a woodcut of Jews digging ditches in
a slave labor camp, and Rabbi Klausner, in his English
introduction, offers, ``We were slaves to Hitler in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the traditional Haggadah features four sons who ask their
father the meaning of the Passover story, the four sons in the Army
Haggadah ask about a Jewish homeland in Palestine. ``What is this
land and state that you long for?'' the wise son of 1946 asks. When
the wicked son admonishes, ``Use your strength to rebuild a
devastated Europe,'' Sheinson's narrator lashes back, ``You should
set his teeth on edge and tell him: We have already given our best
to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the traditional Haggadah features the song ``Dayenu'' _
``it would have been enough'' _ that praises God for redeeming the
Jews, Sheinson's version is a litany of Jewish affliction. ``Had
God brought us out of Egypt and not divided the sea for us, it
would have been enough,'' the traditional song begins. Sheinson's
charts a darker course. ``Had He scattered us among the nations,
but not given us the First Crusade,'' it starts, ``we would have
been content.'' Later comes this: ``Had He given us gas chambers
and crematoria, but our wives and children had not been tortured,
we would have been content.''
</P>
<P>
   That spring day in the attic the week before Passover in 1996,
all Touster knew about the pamphlet was what he read in Klausner's
English title page and introduction and the handwritten inscription
to his parents from a man named Joe Levine. Though he understands
little Hebrew and no Yiddish, he recognized the power of the
woodcuts and the pages illustrated with border drawings featuring
the smokestacks of the crematoria.
</P>
<P>
   His first instinct was to hand the project to a scholar in
Jewish studies, but friends persuaded him to undertake the pursuit
himself. Thus, he embarked on a mission he likens to detective work
in which ``my main witnesses were in Munich, Israel, Austria,
England, as well as other parts of the United States and Canada and
in which four languages are involved.'' By then too, many of
Touster's ``main witnesses'' were dead _ Sheinson, Adler, and
Levine, who worked for the American Jewish Joint Distribution
Committee in postwar Germany and whose precise connection to his
father Touster never determined.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted colleagues to translate the Hebrew and Yiddish in
the Army Haggadah. For the Yiddish he turned to Robert Szulkin, a
professor of Russian literature at Brandeis who spent part of the
war in a Soviet labor camp. He celebrated Passover 1946 in the
former Nazi barracks of a displaced persons camp near Munich, near
the restaurant where the Army Haggadah was used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shot me backwards in time,'' says Szulkin, 65. ``It was
probably the most emotional Seder that I recollect. It was at once
sad because of the horrors that preceded it. At the same time the
need to go on and rebuild lives was the theme set.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Touster's first questions was to his brother Irwin, an
artist in New York. ``Listen, do you have anything about Dad?'' He
did. After their father, Ben, died in 1979, Irwin received _ but
never looked at _ his scrapbook from HIAS. In that scrapbook, Saul
uncovered a hidden side of his father. ``That,'' he says, ``touched
me deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found was a 1952 report Ben Touster had written about
HIAS's post-war achievements after he toured displaced-persons
camps in Europe and after HIAS helped 167,490 Jews emigrate to
Israel, the US, and elsewhere. Touster included his father's words
in his commentary in the survivors' Haggadah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistics are cold things, and one must look for the human
story behind each figure,'' Ben Touster wrote. ``Each figure stands
for the transplantation of a human soul, a Jewish soul, from
wretchedness and terror to a good land and a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered in that quotation,'' the son says, ``a kind of
sensitivity and reflectiveness that was not apparent. My father's
character was that of a very efficient, businesslike man,
practical, almost cold in manner. Here I discovered the inner
life.''
</P>
<P>
   He made other discoveries, too. The woodcuts in the Haggadah
bear the Hebrew name ``Ben Benyamin.'' A hunch by a researcher at
Yad Vashem, Israel's Holocaust memorial museum, led Touster to a
British art dealer who recognized the prints as Adler's work.
Touster traveled to England, where he saw Adler's series of 16
prints and met his sister. He met a survivor, John Najmann of
London, who'd attended Rabbi Klausner's Seder in 1946. A week after
giving Touster an unpublished translation of the Army Haggadah,
Najmann suffered a fatal heart attack while visiting Yad Vashem.
</P>
<P>
   Touster found one other survivor who'd attended Klausner's
Seder. Solly Ganor, now a 70-year-old writer living in Israel,
survived Dachau and the ``death march'' from the camp as Allied
forces approached in the spring of 1945. He'd learned English in
the Kovno ghetto from the British wife of a Lithuanian Jew, and in
1946, at 17, he was working as an interpreter for the US Army. He
remembers how driven Sheinson had been to complete his Haggadah.
Ganor and his father and stepmother were planning to go to Canada,
but, at this Seder in Munich, Ganor decided to go instead to
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each Jew has to consider himself as if he left Egypt himself,
and I was thinking about our death march. I was thinking how much
more terrible was our exodus than the one from Egypt,'' Ganor says.
``What I read in the Haggadah crystallized it for me. Unless we
have our own country we can't defend ourselves. We would always be
the same kind of flotsam.''
</P>
<P>
   Touster's quest also led him to Sheinson's widow, in Montreal,
and to Rabbi Klausner, who held the pulpit in Boston's Temple
Israel from 1949 to 1953 and now lives in New Mexico. In telephone
calls and letters, the 83-year-old retired clergyman re-created the
scene at that first Passover after liberation, when holding a Seder
``was just another thing on my agenda,'' along with publishing a
Yiddish newspaper and printing lists of survivors to help people
find lost loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was crowded. Every corner was filled,'' Klausner
recalls. ``We had a little pulpit, so to speak, in the center of
the room, and we just conducted a Seder. We had no sound system. It
was kind of a celebration, over and above being a Passover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haggadahs,'' he says, ``disappeared in the sense that
everyone clung to them in remembrance of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Touster's curiosity and diligence, the survivors'
Haggadah is getting new life. Touster likes to write poetry, but
since he began this project he has penned no verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if this is my poetry,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
