<HEADER>
A9679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET US NOW PRAISE A FAMOUS USAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year-end note from the editor suggested that 1998 had
produced a especially bounteous crop of ``famouslys,'' not only in
our pages but in other newspapers and magazines as well. Was there
a trend underfoot, he wondered? On that very New Years Eve, a story
in the works spoke of ``Red Sox management, a group famously bad at
the business of doing business,'' and other examples could not be
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   His observation was on the money: After ambling quietly along
with the herd during the 60s and 70s, famously has charged ahead
like the bull market in the 90s. In this newspaper alone, there
were 147 citations last year, nearly six times the number logged a
decade earlier. In fact, the famously boom has already attracted
some criticism: E.J. Dionne of the Washington Post, though a
confessed user of the word, recanted in 1997, saying famously was
often a way of implying you're hip when you're merely highlighting
the obvious, a bit of rhetorical posturing. If someone or something
is already so well known for being a certain way, do we really have
to be reminded of it? he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a more charitable view of famously. Anyone
addressing a heterogeneous audience _ including print and broadcast
journalists - has to allow for enormous variation in the public's
knowledge. Can we mention Cincinnati or Caracas, newspapers ask
themselves, without identifying the state or country? Will a
reference to MIT or the ICA drive newcomers nuts?
</P>
<P>
   No writer wants to be impenetrable. On the other hand, assuming
total ignorance among the readers is hardly practical, especially
in a 600-word rock review.
</P>
<P>
   Famously can help solve that problem. If you already know, for
instance, that the late Yehudi Menuhin was famously photographed in
short pants, the word signals that the writer, like you, is aware
that this is not news. But if Menuhins name means little to you,
famously tells you that for the music crowd, an image of young
Yehudi's shins is part of the violinist's legend. For many music
reviewers, trademark and patented are shortcuts to the same goal:
Scholz moved over to play his trademark manic organ riffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say famously isn't a bit overexposed these days.
When pretty much everyone knows something, the famously is
superfluous: Clinton (famously) said he smoked marijuana but didn't
inhale. On the other hand, using famously of something obscure
seems ridiculous, if not insulting: When a daily newspaper reports
that the Holy Roman Emperor Sigismund I famously told the Council
of Constance in 1414, I am king of the Romans and above grammar, I
can't help wondering about that famously. Among whom, and since
when?
</P>
<P>
   These are all judgment calls, though. And they're no easier
today than in the more restrained era when the performed the work
now assigned to famously, as in the violinist Yehudi Menuhin. That
the is meant to tip you off that this isn't just any old violinist;
in fact, the late usagemeister Theodore Bernstein said Motherwell,
the painter was simply an elliptical form of Motherwell, the famous
painter. In a page devoted to the in Miss Thistlebottoms
Hobgoblins, Bernstein concluded that journalists had to figure out
on a case-by-case basis whether people ranked among the famous, the
near-famous, or the slightly known.
</P>
<P>
   Making those decisions, he said, is not the simplest job in the
world, but it is not the most difficult either.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as his own examples show, fame is a fleeting thing. In
1971, when the book was published, Bernstein's top-tier guys were
Beethoven, Shakespeare, and Newton, no first names necessary; three
decades later, they're still secure. But Bernstein's semi-famous
folks _ those who rated a the _ were Glinka, the composer; Uris,
the novelist; Watson, the biochemist.
</P>
<P>
   Below them, on the rung just above obscurity, were composer Burt
Bacharach, poet John Ciardi, and physicist Hideki Yukawa. Sic
transit gloria mundi, as Thomas a Kempis famously said. Perhaps we
should be scattering those famouslys a bit more sparingly, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   60 Minutes recently revealed _ all too publicly _ that its grasp
of slang is not ready for prime time. The promo spots for a story
broadcast last Sunday intoned, ``Even though the child welfare
agency said she was guilty of murder, the jury said she wasn't.
What's that all about?'' I didn't stick around to find out, but if
the segment was about a childs death _ murder or not _ the
Seinfeldesque skepticism of ``What's that all about?'' was truly
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Has CBS got a tin ear, or what?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
