<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-30 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED SOX DISCOVER GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is spring, exactly when a young man's fancy is
supposed to turn to love. So the timing is right for our eternally
young boys of baseball, the Boston Red Sox, to discover girls.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox recently announced the hiring of Micho Spring and
her firm, BSMG Worldwide, to develop a communications strategy as
plans to build a new Fenway Park move forward. The day-to-day
spokeswoman for the project will be Kathryn Murray St. John, a
former Republican activist, marketing specialist, and principal in
BSMG's Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their political and professional resumes, Spring and St.
John bring something else to the table: their gender.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, they are competent. But it is no accident that they
are also female.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting to update assorted business people, Red Sox
master consultant John Sasso actually said that the key to the
club's success in advancing a new ballpark proposal ``could be
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Be still, my heart!
</P>
<P>
   Here's the theory: Women like baseball more than other sports.
Its slow pace soothes us. It's lack of bone-crunching violence
appeals to our gentle souls.
</P>
<P>
   Like historian Doris Kearns Goodwin, we hear the roar of the
crowd and think of the sound coming out of the radio on Sunday
afternoons many summers ago, when our fathers would stop mowing the
lawn long enough to catch the score. We also revel in more recent
memories of our pint-sized children stepping up to take a whack at
a grapefruit-sized baseball, propelling it 2 feet forward and
almost certainly scoring a run _ because no one on the other team
can field it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women make up key constituencies,'' explains St. John, who
replaces Dick Bresciani as the voice of the Red Sox, at least when
it comes to ballpark development. ``They are fans, neighbors,
political leaders. They are moms taking their kids to games.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that women almost always prefer clean bathrooms
and comfortable seats to the current Fenway experience. Because of
that, the Sox presume female fans will look favorably upon the
improved amenities offered by a new ballpark, such as better
restrooms, family seating areas, and children's play sections.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, that was a marketing strategy overlooked by Robert
Kraft when he was trying to promote a new stadium for the New
England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   That discussion was framed by men, for men, and for one even
more specific male subgroup, sports talk-radio devotees. Women were
not viewed as a constituency worth courting, even women in elected
office. Former state senator Lois Pines mentioned recently how she
believed Massachusetts should try to keep the Patriots here. Asked
why she never said so during the debate to support Kraft, a
constituent, she replied: ``Because no one ever asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond hiring female consultants, it remains to be seen how far
outside the old boy network the Red Sox plan to reach.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, this is one woman who likes baseball, has warm
baseball memories as a daughter and a mother, and still believes
the Sox have plenty of questions to answer about their ownership,
direction, and long-term financial status before they win political
support for a new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   For what seems like endless innings, the Sox have been slowly
winding up their pitch to replace 87-year-old Fenway Park. They
still face significant resistance from neighbors and from those who
would like to derail the project and perhaps push current Sox
ownership into selling the team sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   The ballclub must find a way to deal with those special-interest
agendas _ and to satisfy the broad public interest.
</P>
<P>
   The team is owned by the Yawkey Trust and run by John
Harrington. As chief executive officer, Harrington recently
released carefully selected information on the trust that controls
the ball club and the two charitable foundations set up by the late
Tom and Jean Yawkey.
</P>
<P>
   He denied any improper use of the Red Sox trust, specifically
rebutting a report in the Boston Herald that charged he ``has
personally reaped millions of dollars from Jean Yawkey's estate and
the charitable foundations of her and her husband Tom.'' Harrington
also put out word via friendly media contacts that his salary is
only in the ``$1 million range.''
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of ballpark estimates will not fly if the Sox plan
for a new Fenway requires any public investment. The business of
baseball demands specific numbers, whether a man or a woman is
looking at the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
