A9685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-KING-HNS &LR;      03-30 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-KING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STEPHEN KING BOOK IS A GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The world had teeth and it could bite you with them anytime it
wanted. Trisha McFarland discovered this when she was nine years
old. At ten o'clock on a morning in early June she was sitting in
the back seat of her mother's Dodge Caravan, wearing her blue Red
Sox batting practice jersey (the one with 36 GORDON on the back)
and playing with Mona, her doll. At ten thirty she was lost in the
woods. By eleven she was trying not to be terrified, trying not to
let herself think, ``This is very serious, this is very serious.''
Trying not to think that sometimes when people get lost in the
woods they get seriously hurt. Sometimes they died.``
</P>
<P>
   So begins ``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon,'' a gem from horror
master Stephen King (Scribner, $16.95, 219 pages). In the press
release, King says, ``It was my idea to write a kind of fairy tale,
`Hansel and Gretel,' without Hansel.'' King has succeeded beyond
his wildest expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Before her parents divorce, Trisha and her family lived in
Massachusetts. Now Trisha and her older brother Pete live in Maine
with their mother, who every Saturday takes them on some kind of
trip. This Saturday, she decides they will take a six-mile hike on
the Maine-New Hampshire branch of the Appalachian Trail. As usual,
Pete and her mom begin bickering before they even get to the
trailhead and once the hike begins, the arguments get more heated.
The bickering is driving Trisha nuts, so she decides to escape by
going off the trail. She goes down a mild slope so no one can see
her. Then ``Trisha turned back to the slope, and then turned around
as the worst idea of her life came to her. This idea was to go
forward instead of backtracking to the Kezar Notch trail.''
</P>
<P>
   She begins walking, faster and faster, trying to quell her fears
as the bugs hover and bite her everywhere. She begins calling for
help. Eventually, she takes a break and checks out what's in her
backpack _ her Gameboy, her Walkman, suntan lotion, a bottle of
water, a bottle of Surge, her blue plastic poncho, and her lunch
(hardboiled egg, tuna fish sandwich, Twinkees, celery sticks and
potato chips). After putting on some suntan lotion, she repacks her
backpack and begins walking again and calling out for help as the
tears roll. She starts picking checkerberries and eating them. In
droves, the bugs encircle her and land on her eyelids. Then the
rains come and panic sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she stops to eat the egg. Having no idea what time it
is, she turns on the Walkman and finds out it is 3:30 in the
afternoon. Then, she gets her next bad idea _ find a stream and
follow it to civilization. Eventually, she hears running water and
heads for it, then she trips and falls hard down a rock slope and
into a wasp nest.
</P>
<P>
   Now hurting and in total panic, she runs through the woods until
she finds the stream. She checks her body to see how many times she
has been bitten. Fearing the Walkman is broken, she turns it on and
hears a broadcaster say that a search has begun for Trisha. Knowing
she must conserve her batteries, she turns the Walkman off and
begins to walk again, this time following the stream.
</P>
<P>
   Near dusk, she stops and decides to listen to the Red Sox game.
In the bottom of the eighth, the Red Sox go up 5 to 4 over the
Yankees and Tricia's hero, reliever Tom Gordon, comes in to pitch
the ninth inning. Trisha tells herself, ``If we win, if Tom gets
the save, I'll be saved.'' Tom closes and Trisha goes to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   She will be alone for more than nine days _ hurt, scared, and
sure someone or something is watching her. Resourceful, she finds
nuts and berries and even water. She imagines that Tom Gordon is
with her to protect her, keep her company and ultimately teach her
how to close a game.
</P>
<P>
   King does a wonderful job of making Trisha real, her thoughts
and words those of a bright, but still 9-year-old girl. The terror
is in her mind and you feel it growing on every page. The only
glitches in this superb story are a couple of flashbacks to her
parents' reaction _ but you don't care about them, only about
Trisha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedford Square.'' By Anne Perry. Ballantine Books. $24.95. 330
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's 21st mystery featuring Bow Street Superintendent Thomas
Pitt and his wife, Charlotte, is a fascinating look at the social
structure of Victorian England.
</P>
<P>
   Early one morning, Pitt is awakened by a patrol officer who has
found a shabbily dressed body on the steps of a house in Bedford
Square, one of London's most fashionable sections. The owner,
retired Gen. Brandon Balantyne, denies any knowledge of the victim.
Pitt doesn't believe him because a snuffbox belonging to the
general has been found in the victim's pocket. Pitt has Sgt.
Tellman begin a search to learn the identity of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Charlotte visits Balantyne and learns that he is
being blackmailed, but so far the only thing the blackmailer has
asked for is the snuffbox. Soon, Pitt discovers that other men of
influence and social standing are being blackmailed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitt mysteries are always genteel reads. ``Bedford Square''
shows how important name, honor and social standing were to the
Victorians. Just one hint of scandal and a man and his family would
be shunned or driven to leave the country. This time around, it's
the down-to-earth common sense of the Pitt's maid, Gracie, that
enables Pitt to find the blackmailer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
