<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDITIONS HAMPER PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their fighter jets might soar through enemy air
space faster than the speed of sound. But this week, NATO air units
seem to have found one of their most daunting obstacles: the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is not only rain and sleet but also clouds that are
threatening to hamper NATO pilots in the coming days, as inclement
weather settles over most of Yugoslavia. Already, some foreign
warplanes have returned without dumping their full payloads,
according to Pentagon and NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weather is bad right now, and it's bad for the next couple of
days,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Monday night.
``That doesn't necessarily cancel all of the sorties, but it can
cause entire packages of planes to be canceled. Or it can prevent
planes that do take off from dropping some or all of their
ordnance.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, officials say, is that many ``smart bombs'' are
guided by lasers _ requiring light to refract off a target, which
cannot happen under cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   To counter such a common occurrence, the US Air Force frequently
relies on missiles. Recently, however, the military has also has
developed what is considered a superior weather-resistant weapon.
Known as the ``JDAM,'' the Joint Direct Attack Munition, it is
essentially a normal warhead directed by a global positioning
system rather than a laser.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb is directed in the following way: A target is located
on the ground by a network of satellites. Its coordinates are sent
to a receiving system on the warhead. An internal computer on the
warhead then directs it to the target site, all without relying on
outside stimuli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't care about rain or sleet, or any other kind of
weather,'' said John Pike, defense analyst for the Federation of
American Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first batch of JDAMs was produced in May 1998, the
current operation in Yugoslavia marks the first time the US
military has used the bombs in significant amounts. Dropped
exclusively from B-2 bombers, they have played a major role in
Operation Allied Force, and as many as several dozen have already
been used, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has sent an array of other equipment to help
combat the weather obstacle, including the Predator, an unmanned
plane that flies at slow speeds to snap aerial photos of the ground
below, and ``JSTARS,'' the Joint Surveillance Target Attack Radar
System, a plane filled with sensors to detect movement from objects
on the ground such as tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is expected to work quite as efficiently in cloudy
conditions as the JDAM system. According to military analysts, the
satellite-guided bombs are so new that they were not expected to be
in wide use until sometime later this year, and many of those that
have been deployed already are believed to have been test bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bacon said: ``They seem to be performing very
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
