<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WARNING-BOS &LR;      03-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEGRAPHING OF ACTIONS IS CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In the first week of the NATO air war against
Yugoslavia, US and European officials have told Belgrade via the
media when, where and how the bombs will fall. President Clinton,
meanwhile, signaled the limits of the American campaign, pledging
that no US ground forces would be used to fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that telegraphing NATO military
strategy in Kosovo is designed to coerce the Serbs into halting
their military offensive in Kosovo and accepting a peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But some defense analysts argued that the United States and its
NATO allies have been giving too much away to the Serbs, imperiling
allied pilots and potentially undermining NATO's diplomatic and
military goals in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given away the element of tactical surprise, and we
have taken a lot of options off the table'' said Lieutenant General
Terry Scott, a fellow at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
``From a military perspective, Milosevic shouldn't know what phase
we're in; he shouldn't even know we have phases.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the air attacks, US officials privately alerted
reporters that bombs would start falling during the night.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign got underway, American and European generals
began giving televised briefings describing how they would target
Yugoslavia's formidable air defense system and command and control
centers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, NATO Secretary General Javier Solano announced that
the alliance was shifting its strategy into Phase Two, targeting
Serbian troops, police, artillery and tanks posted south of the
44th parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Western media have also helped provide Milosevic with valuable
battle intelligence. American and European news agencies routinely
report on the number and type of American and European aircraft
headed into battle in Yugoslavia. For instance, Reuters news agency
reported Monday that ``32 fully-armed F-16s, F-15s and F-18s soared
into the sky'' from Aviano air base towards the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon voiced concern Monday that
Milosevic's forces are monitoring American television to glean
military intelligence about NATO tactics.
</P>
<P>
   And he expressed frustration that details of a top secret rescue
of an F-117A stealth fighter pilot on Saturday, including the make
of the helicopters and aircraft used in the operation, had been
leaked to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs monitor the TV very closely,'' Bacon said at the
daily Pentagon press conference Monday. ``They are very aware when
planes take off. They use that to make military calculations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Serbs know what kind of aircraft we use for these
rescue missions it would be operationally significant
information,'' added Carnes Lord, a national security adviser to
former vice president Dan Quayle and currently a professor at Tuft
University's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy. ``In the Gulf
War, we were extremely sensitive about releasing details about
special forces operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts said that the Pentagon has become increasingly
transparent in telegraphing its military intentions since the
Vietnam war. Under the Clinton administration, the practice has
become an integral component of its efforts to use the threat of
force to achieve political objectives from Iraq to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Zalmay Khalilzad, a US undersecretary of defense for policy
under the Bush administration, said that the military often
publicized strategic goals during the Gulf War, while keeping the
tactical operations under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating humanitarian crisis has ratcheted up the pressure
on the White House, the Pentagon and the NATO allies to strike
directly at Yugoslav forces responsible for driving tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanians out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics are understandable, but this has the effect of
exposing our pilots to greater risk,'' he said. ``We are doing
things sooner than we would have done otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts counter that the Pentagon's strategy can lull its
rivals into thinking, incorrectly, that it knows exactly what's
coming. Khalilzad said the Bush administration successfully
employed such a strategy to confuse Iraqi military planners seeking
to anticipate US troop movements.
</P>
<P>
   Khalilzad and Scott said that the Clinton administration has
gone too far in the past week, assuring the Serbs that if they
weathered the NATO air strikes, they needn't be concerned about
facing ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the effect of making them stay the course,'' said
Khalilzad, ``If they believe air attacks may not be protracted or
sustained they can afford to remain defiant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONTAINMENT-BO     03-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONTAINMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS GIVE RISE TO FEARS OF SPREADING CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until just last month, Bulgaria refused to recognize the
Macedonian language, making it impossible for the two bordering
countries to sign treaties. For years, Greece tried to block its
northern neighbor from using the name Macedonia, saying the real
Macedonia lies on Greek soil.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic tensions run long and deep in the Balkans. And these
conflicts over language and identity help explain why US officials
fear that the fighting in Kosovo, if left unchecked, could spread
into Macedonia, Bulgaria, Greece and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conflict with no natural national boundaries,''
President Clinton said last week in outlining the rationale for
NATO military strikes in Kosovo. The area is inherently unstable,
Clinton said, with ethnic Albanians living in Greece and ethnic
Albanians and Turks living in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let a fire burn here in this area, and the flames will
spread,'' the president warned.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts say Clinton has overstated the fears of an
expanded war, many say that the long-held tensions make a broader
conflict a real possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, for example, might suffer as ethnic Albanian refugees
flood over the border from Kosovo. As a ``miserably poor country,''
Albania might not be able to supply food and other resources to
everyone within its borders, leading to riots and other problems,
said Andrew Winner of the Institute for Foreign Policy Analysis, a
Cambridge think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, those Albanian refugees might include armed members of
the Kosovar separtist movement, which is trying to break away from
Yugoslavia, led by President Slobodan Milosevic. The Albanian
government, already weak, might have to contend with Kosovar rebels
waging war from within its borders, or with Milosevic's forces
chasing its enemy onto Albanian soil, Winner said.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Albania might enter the Kosovo conflict to protect
its own borders. And that is only one strand in the knot of tangled
political interests in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia could face problems similar to Albania's. About
one-third of its people are ethnic Albanians, and Albanian refugees
have been streaming in from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's forces could use that as an excuse to move into
Macedonia, or they could lay claim to Macedonian territory under
the excuse that Macedonia was once a republic within Yugoslavia. It
broke away in the early 1990s and is an independent parliamentary
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Political instability in Macedonia could prompt Bulgaria or
Greece to send troops into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a symbolic gesture when Bulgaria, starting in
the early 1990s, refused to sign treaties in the Macedonian
language, saying it was merely a dialect of Bulgarian. By refusing
to recognize the Macedonian language, the Bulgarians were refusing
to recognize the legitimacy of the Macedonian government.
</P>
<P>
   The Greeks also have a long-running fight with Macedonia, though
it has been muted since a successful round of diplomacy in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Greeks fear that Macedonia has designs on a northern Greek
province that is also called Macedonia. Greeks say the name
Macedonia, as well as the country's flag and a provision of its
constitution, reveal its ambitions in Greece. Because of Greek
sensitivities, the young country has been known officialy as the
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   As they play out the ramifications of the war in Kosovo, some
analysts said there is a chance that Greece would attack a
destabilized Macedonia to prevent Macedonia from acting on its own
alleged ambitions in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   That could raise a truly nightmarish scenario: Turkey could
enter the conflict under the guise of assisting Macedonia's Turkish
and Albanian minorities. Like the Turks, the Albanians are Muslim.
A fight between Greece and Turkey, two heavily armed NATO members,
would be the most destabilizing outcome of the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who watch the region closely, however, said there is
little chance the war will spread beyond Kosovo. ``The Albanians
have no army to speak of and will do whatever the West wants them
to do, because they need aid,'' said Stacy Sullivan, a freelance
journalist who has covered the Balkans, and who is now a consultant
to the Human Rights Initiative at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School
of Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulgarians are impoverished, and the last thing they need
is to get involved,'' Sullivan said. ``They believe Macedonia is
theirs, but they're not going to go after it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kurt Bassuener of the Balkan Action Council, a Washington
educational group, said there is danger in a weak government, like
that of Albania, becoming weaker still as rebels and refugees cross
its borders. If one government collapses, other nations might feel
the need to step in to prevent the instability from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to have trans-border army movements to have
destabilization,'' Bassuener said. ``You can have an implosion that
brings in outside forces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
