<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov meets with the leader of Yugoslavia amid the stepped-up
NATO air campaign. We look at the diplomatic effort and other
developments in the conflict. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIMAKOV (Washington) _ The White House is once again
standing by as a top Russian envoy dramatically rushes into a war
zone to negotiate with a Soviet-era ally. This time the talks are
between Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade. We look at the similar
role that Primakov played in Iraq during the Persian Gulf War and
again in Bosnia. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   STEALTH-FIGHTER (Washington) _ For days the Pentagon has refused
to reveal what caused the crash last Saturday of a $45 million
F-117A stealth aircraft over Yugoslavia. But despite criticism, it
may never give the details. Officials say they don't want to admit
that a plane once believed to be virtually invisible to radar is
seriously vulnerable. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-ECONOMY (Washington) _ In a report that could give
Congress an excuse to put off overhauling the federal health
insurance and retirement benefits programs, the Treasury Department
says the robust economy and already enacted changes will extend the
solvency of Medicare by seven years and Social Security by two
years. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   REHNQUIST-CENSUS (Washington) _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist
asks Congress to leave the nation's courts out of the
appropriations fight over the 2000 Census. His complaint stems from
a spending bill that not only includes the Census Bureau, but also
the judicial branch. ``The judicial branch should not, and does
not, have any role in this debate,'' Rehnquist tells the Senate
Judiciary Committee in a letter. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATIONS-Y2K (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission, in a report on the year 2000 computer glitch, is
assuring Americans that they will be able to make telephone calls
and watch television on Jan. 1, 2000, without a hitch. That's
because most of the telecommunications industry's computers have
been upgraded to avoid any problem in reading the new year. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GUNS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that people
accused in multistate crime sprees involving a gun can be charged
in any of those states with using the weapon even if they used it
in only one state. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOUND-INTERNET (Houston) _ A mother who pretended to deliver a
singing telegram as a distraction when she abducted her three
children from their school in San Diego has been found in Liberty
County, Texas, the authorities say, snared by someone who spotted
her picture on the Internet. The father has custody of the
children. By CINDY HORSWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-MOON (San Antonio) _ Like the countless number of
earthlings who will mistakenly celebrate the dawn of a new
millennium on Jan. 1, 2000, many people will think Wednesday's full
moon will be a ``Blue Moon.'' Technically, it is not, but the
mistaken definition for the second full moon of the month is
embedded in popular culture. By ROGER CROTEAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
