<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL ROUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benziger Merlot 1996, Sonoma County, Calif. About $16.
</P>
<P>
   Many laymen, confronted with several glasses of wine and asked
to separate the merlots from the cabernet sauvignons, will have
trouble doing it. So will many wine professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers routinely add cabernet to merlot to give it
structure, and they routinely add merlot to cabernet to give it
roundness, which means softening it up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   This delicious Benziger wine is less than 80 percent merlot. It
includes 10.5 percent cabernet sauvingon, plus cabernet franc,
petite sirah and petit verdot. The result is a velvety wine with
some nice cabernet tannin.
</P>
<P>
   It was aged for 15 months in French oak barrels. Thanks to the
cabernet component, it will improve in the bottle for another five
years, if you can wait that long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
