<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA REPORT SAYS CALIFORNIA'S BURGEONING ECONOMY WILL TAPER OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Economists predicted Tuesday that the California
economy would slow down next year but said the effect would be
muted by economic diversification.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern is already established. While Silicon Valley's
fortunes have dipped somewhat, the economy in Southern California
has been expanding, and the Central Valley, although plagued by
persistent double-digit unemployment, grew faster than Los Angeles
County did last year, according to the Andersen Forecast from the
University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched quarterly report by economists at the John
E. Anderson Graduate School of Management also projected that the
U.S. economy would slow from a 3.5 percent pace in 1999 to 2.1
percent in 2000. It estimated an unemployment rate increase from
4.4 percent to 4.8 percent in 2000 and predicted there would be yet
another ``soft landing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a cost to obtaining economic diversification in
California,'' said Tom Lieser, executive director and author of the
California report. ``It did not just happen. But now that we have
it _ and we are no longer so dependent on aerospace, for example _
I think we are in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there were factors that could cause the state's economy
to slow down more abruptly than the Anderson Forecast imagines.
</P>
<P>
   One potential vulnerability is the highly leveraged status of
stocks in some of California's high-tech companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state, and particularly the Silicon Valley area, has long
been a world focus of venture capital. However, it has more
recently become a primary focus of so-called day trading _
high-risk investment in existing companies by amateurs,'' Lieser
said Monday, before the report was released.
</P>
<P>
   He said he feared these investors ``could lose their cool and
more tangible assets in a bear market, and to the extent that
untested amateur traders have built highly leveraged portfolios,
those stocks may be much more vulnerable than broad market issues
to a major sell-off in the equity market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anderson Forecast also noted that exports from the state
were up modestly despite continued economic troubles in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``California will remain a hub for trade with Asia when that
region strengthens again, probably in the next year,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, California exports to the rest of the world
were down 4.2 percent in 1998. For the fourth quarter, state
exports were 6.6 percent below the year-ago totals. Shipments to
Mexico and Canada were up a combined 10.7 percent last year but
were only 2.9 percent higher, year-over-year, during the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments to Western Europe were up nearly 10 percent last year
and 4.1 percent in the fourth quarter compared with the year-ago
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   California's exports to Latin America, excluding Mexico, rose
15.9 percent in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   There will continue to be growth in certain sectors such as
residential construction, the Anderson Forecast said. UCLA predicts
that 1999 will be the best year since 1990 for home building, with
more than 150,000 new residential units. Housing output is
predicted to rise to more than 200,000 units in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there will likely be too few new homes to satisfy demand
given current price levels, and prices and rents will continue to
rise, the UCLA study said.
</P>
<P>
   In job growth, both Southern California (greater Los Angeles
area plus San Diego) and Northern California (the San Francisco Bay
area and Sacramento) grew at virtually the same 2.3 percent rate
during 1998, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
