<SLUG> BC-LAMB-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND THE ROAST: A LAMB FOR ALL SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Easter and Passover upon us, and the first tender leaves
emerging on the trees, the thoughts of many American cooks are
turning to lamb. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   After making its annual appearance at springtime dinners, lamb
will all but disappear from the table in most households. Americans
consumed, on average, just over 1 pound of lamb per person in 1998,
compared with almost 53 pounds of pork and some 68 pounds of beef.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's lack of popularity in the United States is a bit
puzzling, given its prominence in the Mediterranean cuisines we so
admire. From Spain to the Middle East, this savory meat is a
luxurious staple; in North Africa, it is so dominant that when you
say ``meat'' it is understood to mean lamb.
</P>
<P>
   But there are historical reasons for this phenomenon. Unlike in
Mediterranean countries, where farms were small and pasture lands
scarce, in land-rich America it was both easier and more profitable
to raise cattle than sheep. Even in colonial times there was a
widespread feeling that lamb was somehow ``un-American,'' the food
of people from less-fortunate lands.
</P>
<P>
   The range wars between sheepherders and cattle ranchers that
flared in the West during the late 1800s helped to solidify this
negative attitude. Cattle ranchers successfully characterized
sheep, which will eat grass right down to the roots, as little
better than four-legged locusts.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not only history that is to blame for lamb's relative
obscurity. The meat also has a reputation for being gamy, with too
strong a flavor for many diners. This preconception seems to have
originated with mutton, which is the meat of sheep that are more
than a year old. Mutton does have quite a strong flavor, but that
has little relevance today, since it is virtually unavailable
commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb is actually rather delicate in flavor, almost aromatic,
with a slight undercurrent of sweetness. But it also has a
distinctive, rich earthiness that makes it ideal for use with
strongly flavored seasonings, like garlic, citrus and mint, and
spices like coriander and chili peppers.
</P>
<P>
   To take full advantage of lamb's virtues, it helps to put aside
two supposed truisms. The first is that you should always buy
``spring lamb''; the second is that the best use of a leg of lamb
is as a large roast.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier days, the term ``spring lamb'' did indeed connote
high quality, as it referred to lambs born in the spring and
slaughtered in the fall. Their meat was particularly tender and
therefore highly prized.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the term has meaning only as a marketing tool. Lambs may
be born at any time throughout the year, but most are slaughtered
at between five and seven months. So almost any lamb you buy today
will be tender.
</P>
<P>
   There is another important difference between the cuts of lamb
available today and those that our parents bought. Today's cuts are
considerably larger. Since the 1940s, the average weight of a sheep
at slaughter has increased by about 60 percent, to about 130
pounds. Kreg Leymaster, a research geneticist with the U.S. Meat
and Animal Research Center in Clay Center, Neb., said this has been
achieved by increasing the proportion of meat to bone, without
sacrificing tenderness or increasing the ratio of fat to lean meat.
</P>
<P>
   The larger size provides many opportunities for the savvy cook.
This is particularly true of the leg. Well known as an excellent
roast, it can also be used in a much more dynamic way. Spend a few
minutes talking to your butcher, and you can walk away from the
meat counter with luscious chops, meaty steaks and cubes for
kebabs.
</P>
<P>
   The first option for dividing a leg is to have the butcher cut
four or five thick chops from the sirloin, or butt, end. These
chops have the advantage of being cheaper than chops from the rib,
and they are far more tender than those from the shoulder. As a
point of comparison, they are identical in bone and muscle
structure to the steaks from the sirloin of the cow. Some butchers
actually call them steaks, to distinguish them from chops from
other parts of the lamb.
</P>
<P>
   A tip: Check the first chop taken from the end, as it sometimes
has a large knot of white fat in it. If so, ask the butcher to make
that meat into shish kebab cubes.
</P>
<P>
   With the chops removed, what remains is a four-to-five-pound
roast. This is the perfect size for many cooks, who find a whole
leg not only too large for most meals but too large for their
roasting pans, as well. This smaller roast is also of a more
uniform thickness, which translates to more even cooking.
</P>
<P>
   A second option for dividing the leg is to cut about a half
dozen thick steaks from the center. These substantial but meltingly
tender center-cut steaks, which somewhat resemble ham steaks, can
be cooked in the same way as leg chops.
</P>
<P>
   Once the steaks are cut from the center, the remaining two
portions of the leg can be cut into cubes for shish kebab. While
kebabs from shoulder meat can be gristly, leg kebabs are rich and
meaty, almost silky in their tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   When selecting a leg of lamb, look for meat that is pinkish-red,
since the darker the color, the older the lamb. The meat should
also look moist and bright, rather than sticky, and the fat should
look waxy white rather than yellowish.
</P>
<P>
   Like beef, lamb is graded prime, choice, good and utility, but
almost all lamb sold commercially is choice.
</P>
<P>
   So, by all means cook that paschal lamb. But remember that,
unlike tulips and daffodils, this meat does not need to disappear
with the passing of spring.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BROILED LAMB LEG CHOPS ON EGGPLANT PLANKS WITH MINT-YOGURT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons freshly cracked coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 10-ounce lamb leg chops, }-inch to 1-inch thick (or substitute
center-cut lamb leg steaks), trimmed of exterior fat
</P>
<P>
   1 small eggplant
</P>
<P>
   \ cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler. In a small bowl, combine yogurt, honey and
mint. Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine coriander, and 1 tablespoon each salt and pepper, and
mix well. Rub mixture all over the lamb chops. Place chops on a
broiler pan, broil until they are well seared on one side, then
turn and cook to desired doneness, about 8 to 10 minutes total
cooking time for medium rare, depending on thickness of chops. To
check for doneness, cut into one of the chops; when the center is
slightly less done than you like it, remove lamb from heat. Place
chops on a platter, cover with foil, and allow to rest while
eggplant cooks.
</P>
<P>
   3. Trim the top and bottom half-inch off eggplant, then cut
lengthwise into 4 planks about }-inch thick. Brush eggplant with
olive oil, sprinkle with salt and pepper to taste, and press garlic
onto both sides. Place planks on broiler pan and broil until well
browned, very soft and moist all the way through, about 4 minutes a
side.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place an eggplant plank on each plate, top with a lamb chop,
spoon a couple of tablespoons of yogurt sauce over the top, and
serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   OREGANO-CRUSTED ROAST LEG OF LAMB WITH LEMON, POTATOES AND
ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   } cup roughly chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 4- to 5-pound bone-in leg of lamb
</P>
<P>
   6 medium potatoes, peeled and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 red onions, peeled and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lemon, sliced very thin
</P>
<P>
   \ cup olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500. In a small bowl, combine garlic,
oregano, olive oil, 2 tablespoons salt and 1 tablespoon pepper; mix
well. With the point of a paring knife, cut 8 or 10 slits about 2
inches deep into the roast. Push some of the oregano mixture into
these slits and into any gaps between bone and meat on ends of
roast, then rub the rest all over outside of roast.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large roasting pan, combine potatoes, onions and lemon.
Drizzle with olive oil, sprinkle generously with salt and pepper,
and toss to coat.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place lamb in roasting pan with potato mixture, place in oven
and roast until well seared, about 30 minutes. Stir potato-onion
mixture, reduce oven temperature to 300 and continue to cook until
lamb reaches an internal temperature of 120 for rare or 125 for
medium rare, about 30 to 45 minutes more. Begin checking for
doneness after 50 minutes total cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove roast to a cutting board, cover with foil and allow to
rest for 10 to 15 minutes. Carve into thin slices, and serve,
accompanied by potatoes and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
