<HEADLINE>
DAVIS SIGNS EDUCATION BILL AIMED AT IMPROVED READING SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Gov. Gray Davis has signed a bill
into law aimed at ensuring that more California children learn to
read.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, one of the four education measures sought by Davis and
passed swiftly by the Legislature, creates reading instruction
programs and professional development academies to train teachers
on reading instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was elected to restore the promise of education in
California,'' Davis, a Democrat, said Monday during a signing
ceremony at a San Francisco elementary school known for its
successful literacy program. ``This is a very important bill that
sets up a number of reading programs.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, the governor signed a bill that requires high
school students to pass a graduation exam. Davis is scheduled to
sign two other education bills next week, one establishing a peer
review system for evaluating teachers and another to begin
measuring the performance of schools and sanctioning those that
don't improve.
</P>
<P>
   The reading bill, a Davis campaign pledge, provides $75 million
for grades K-4 to provide intensive reading instruction.
</P>
<P>
   It also allocates $12 million for summer programs to train
beginning teachers to teach reading and $1 million to establish
leadership training institutes for principals and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, co-authored by Assembly members Kerry Mazzoni,
D-Novato, and Jim Cunneen, R-San Jose, who accompanied the governor
Monday to San Francisco's Gordon J. Lau Elementary School, would
provide another $2 million for schools that improve reading scores
by 5 percent or more next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you learn to read,'' the governor said. ``Then, you read
to learn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
