<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES A CHOWDER?  
 TRUFFLE OIL  
 SOFTENING BROWN SUGAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What makes a chowder? Clam chowder, Manhattan chowder, New
England chowder _ I'm confused.
</P>
<P>
   A. Generally speaking, a chowder is a hearty milk-based soup
made from onions, cubed potatoes and either seafood or vegetables
like corn. Salt pork or bacon is often used for flavor. The
earliest New England recipes for chowders always included seafood,
since chowders were primarily fishermen's soups, made from whatever
was reeled in that day. Today, as long as a soup is thick and
chunky with a creamy broth, it can arguably be called a chowder.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception is Manhattan clam chowder, made with tomatoes.
James Beard described it as resembling ``a vegetable soup that
accidentally had some clams dumped into it.'' Culinary historians
disagree on how tomatoes came to wind up in a chowder, and how the
Manhattan chowder got its name.
</P>
<P>
   The word chowder itself might come from chaudiere, the French
word for boiler or cauldron. In the French-speaking areas of
Newfoundland, these pots likely held fish soup, and it is easy to
imagine how, as the dish moved down the New England coast, the pot
came to signify its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I received a bottle of truffle oil for Christmas. Except for
drizzling a bit on my green salads, how can I use it?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Truffle oil is usually extra-virgin olive oil infused with
fragrant white truffle. You can try it over anything that won't
overpower its earthy but subtle flavor: potatoes, pasta, risotto,
polenta, simple pizzas, omelets and slices of good bread and
focaccia. It's also fine addition to soups or mushroom ragout.
</P>
<P>
   White truffles are extremely rare, even more so than black
truffles, and the oil is expensive. The Baker's Catalog
(800-827-6836) sells a 1.8-ounce bottle for $17.75. (It can also be
bought in any good market in New York.) It's best stored in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I stored brown sugar in an airtight container in the
refrigerator, and now it's hard as a rock. How can I soften it?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Either heat it in the microwave on high power for 30 to 45
seconds (watch to make sure it doesn't melt), or put it on a pie
plate, and heat it in a 250-degree oven for about five minutes. Use
the softened sugar immediately, or it may firm up again.
</P>
<P>
   To store brown sugar so it stays moist, tightly seal the plastic
bag it comes in (I use a rubber band), then place it in a
heavy-duty resealable plastic bag or an airtight tin. Keep it at a
cool room temperature. If the sugar shows signs of hardening, you
can add an apple wedge to the bag, seal it and let it stand for a
day or two before removing the apple.
</P>
<P>
   When buying brown sugar, give the box or bag a squeeze. If it
feels rock hard, choose another package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
