<SLUG> BC-NYLITE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Brooke Hayward, and I were en route to see ``Death of a
Salesman.'' The curb in front of the O'Neill Theater was jammed
with cars disgorging passengers, so our cab pulled up to the
opposite curb. Walking across, we paused to allow an elderly
hot-dog vendor, who was pushing one cart and pulling another, to
get by. The vendor looked at the theater, then looked at us and
said, ``Hey, I hear that's a pretty good show.''
</P>
<P>
   We picked up our tickets and stopped next door to have a
pretheater drink. There was the playwright, Arthur Miller. We told
him about the comment made by that other kind of salesman, the
hot-dog vendor. ``That's the greatest review,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER DUCHIN
</P>
<P>
   I was sitting near the front of a bus, listening to a rather
loud conversation somewhere behind me. The woman was talking about
her day, the man about his.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that I was witness to a typical interchange in the
life of a ``Me Generation'' couple, I heard her tell how hard it
had been to find just the right fabric for the curtains she needed
to order. He, on the other hand, without seeming to hear a word she
said, went on and on about a real-estate deal he had tried to close
that day.
</P>
<P>
   I did not realize how wrong my assumption was until I saw the
woman pass me on her way off the bus, holding her cell phone at her
ear, still talking about her fabric. The man, still seated
somewhere behind me, was obviously on his cell phone, still talking
about his real-estate deal. I guess ``Cell Phone Age'' has replaced
the ``Me Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ISOLDE SOMMER BLUM
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Finnell was waiting for a friend in the East '60s when
he heard a driver honking his horn, obviously agitated because he
was hemmed in by another vehicle, double parked.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle displayed a large cross inside the windshield, so
Finnell suggested that the driver ask the doormen nearby whether a
member of the clergy was visiting their building, perhaps on an
errand of mercy. The driver did so, with no success. He was
becoming increasingly frustrated and explained that he had an
important interview.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a priest turned the corner and headed toward the two
men. The driver rushed toward him, angrily criticizing his lack of
consideration, especially given his profession. The priest
patiently heard him out and then quietly said: ``Son, I know
exactly how you feel, as would I, but this isn't my automobile.
Would you, however, allow me to assume that motorist's blame?''
</P>
<P>
   Finnell couldn't wait around to find out what happened when the
real culprit appeared to claim his car.
</P>
<P>
   I live in Chicago, but travel to New York frequently on business
and have established many routines. For several years, I've had the
same man cut my hair, and we often joke about how tourists in New
York are easily identified by their ``anything goes'' approach to
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, I took an early flight to accommodate my
boxing workout session and haircut before lunch. I arrived during a
downpour, had the taxi wait as I dropped my bags at my hotel and
raced downtown for my gym session. Then I took the subway uptown to
my hair appointment. Completely drenched, I arrived at the salon
wearing my workout clothes and carrying my gym bag and boxing
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   My stylist looked at me and smiled. ``The quality of tourist in
New York has really gone downhill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY WISHMEIER
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Irwin Trinkoff took his 6-year-old grandson fishing
one day. The little boy's line became tangled and he asked his
grandfather for help. After a few minutes of struggle, the
grandfather straightened the line and the boy said, ``You're the
smartest grandfather in the whole world _ how did you get to be so
smart?''
</P>
<P>
   The grandfather, knowing the boy's dislike of a certain
vegetable, replied, ``When I was your age, I ate a lot of
broccoli.'' The little boy paused only a moment: ``It ain't worth
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How Times Have Changed Department: The future bride was
unwrapping the gifts at her shower amid a chorus of oohs and aahs.
Lacy and brightly colored lingerie items followed one after the
other, and Dovie Wingard began to squirm as her offering was
unwrapped.
</P>
<P>
   There was a puzzled silence as a vertical roaster emerged. ``At
that moment,'' Ms. Wingard confessed, ``I felt the irretrievability
of the 10 years I'd lived before most of the women in the room were
born.''
</P>
<P>
   The Easter season reminded Patricia Honea of one some 30 years
ago. It was a beautiful Sunday and she stood outside the Fifth
Avenue Presbyterian Church watching the Easter parade.
</P>
<P>
   A bicycle approached carrying an older woman in a gray sweat
suit. On her head was a straw hat, complete with a big red rose. A
bed roll was strapped to her bicycle seat. As she pedaled past,
Mrs. Honea read the sign hanging off the bed roll. It said: HATTIE
SMITH IS BACK FROM CINCINNATI!''
</P>
<P>
   Good Samaritan? Harvey Garner and his wife had left their
doctor's office at 33rd Street and First Avenue and asked several
passers-by for the name of a restaurant where they might have
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   After several negative responses, a man who overheard the query
named what he called a ``delightful'' place but said that they
would need a taxi to get there. A cab was hailed and the man got in
with the couple. When they arrived at the restaurant, they thanked
him for going out of his way to help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saved me a big walk,'' he responded. ``My train station is
on the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAVID LETTERMAN LATE SHOW TOP TEN &LR;
</P>
