<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER PARTY BY GAY `NUNS' TURNS BITTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Board of Supervisors, under threat of a
national boycott and feeling the wrath of Catholic Church leaders
and parishioners, refused to revoke the permit for an Easter street
party by gays who dress as nuns.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has jumped from one hot-button topic to another:
the separation of church and state, Christian values, religious
freedom, gay rights and personal persecution.
</P>
<P>
   It has been tinged with ugly infighting among the city's elected
leaders and deep divisions among two of San Francisco's most
powerful constituencies _ Catholics and gays.
</P>
<P>
   The board, in a 9-2 vote Monday, blocked a plan by Supervisors
Alicia Becerril and Amos Brown to pull a city permit granted to the
Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence to close a stretch of Castro Street
for the group's 20th anniversary celebration on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Becerril and Brown wanted the party delayed one week after the
Archdiocese of San Francisco and Catholic organizations said that
such an event should not be allowed on the holiest of Christian
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, the campy street theater
group whose members dress as nuns, refused to back down from their
plans to hold a street celebration on Easter. The celebration,
which the Catholics consider irreverent, includes a ``hunky Jesus''
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic leaders say the Sisters, who have a long history of
charitable work in the city's gay community, mock church ritual.
They are threatening a boycott of San Francisco for upcoming
conventions and vow to exact revenge on elected officials who
defied them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third rail for us,'' said Wade Johnson of
Catholics for Truth and Justice, a conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   The other side was just as fervent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Sisters want to shut down the street, we will shut it
down,'' said Criss Romero, president of the Harvey Milk Lesbian,
Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Democratic Club.
</P>
<P>
   The chasm sent political tremors through City Hall that haven't
been felt for years.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors have fielded hundreds of phone calls, faxes, e-
mails and letters on both sides of the issue since the board gave
unanimous consent two weeks ago for the street closure in what
started out as little more than a debate over rerouting traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The rift boiled over Monday night in a packed gymnasium when the
measure by Becerril and Brown was up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five public speakers weighed in with their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of others were prevented from testifying because of a
board- imposed time limit. There was hooting and hollering, hissing
and clapping, tambourines and sign-waving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics have a right to celebrate in peace. They don't need
to be ridiculed and laughed at,'' said Roger Grimes, a parishioner
at St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Clementina Garcia, who held a crucifix up when she testified,
said: ``I want to tell the homosexual community that there's a time
for everything. ... If you want to be respected, respect us.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union said the board
would be treading on dangerous legal ground if the Sisters' permit
were yanked. And it was that argument, more than any other, that
swayed the board majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence may be offensive and
objectionable,'' said Supervisor Mabel Teng, ``but we, the
government, cannot violate their First Amendment rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
