<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LISTERIA-EATING-WELL-     03-30 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LISTERIA-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTIC WRAPS, LISTERIA: TO WORRY OR NOT?  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Eating Well column of Jan. 13, about the
potential health hazards of some plastic wraps, raised many
questions among readers about plastics in general. The column
looked only at data from Consumers Union, which suggested that a
component in some forms of wrap is an endocrine disrupter.
Endocrine disrupters can mimic or interfere with hormones in the
body and may cause breast cancer, birth defects, low sperm count,
and mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   The component, called a plasticizer, is di-(2-ethylhexyl)adipate
or DEHA. It is used to make some soft, clingy wraps called
polyvinyl chloride (PVC), which are primarily for commercial use,
and Consumers Union found that it could leach into some cheeses
wrapped in it by supermarkets. (Of seven consumer brands of plastic
wrap tested by Consumers Union, only Reynolds Plastic Wrap
contained DEHA.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chemical Manufacturers Association says that DEHA has never
been shown to be an endocrine disrupter, and the Society of the
Plastics Industry, an industry group, says that the Food and Drug
Administration and the Environmental Protection Agency have given
the plasticizer a clean bill of health. Even Consumers Union
emphasizes that the risks are small. But Dr. Edward Groth, an
environmental scientist and food safety specialist with Consumers
Union, said that the size of the risk ``should not dissuade people
from taking reasonable steps for avoidable exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that plasticizers leach into food on contact,
especially food with a high fat content. The simplest solution is
to rewrap food like cheese or cold cuts at home, after slicing off
a thin layer where the wrap touched the food.
</P>
<P>
   Readers were also concerned about plastic containers marked
microwave-safe, storage bags, the wrap used on frozen foods, and
the wrap found on processed cheese slices. Consumers Union found no
DEHA when it tested the plastic on cheese slices and in two brands
of microwave-safe containers, Tupperware and Rubbermaid.
</P>
<P>
   Groth said that the few hard plastic trays for frozen entrees
that Consumers Union tested contained no DEHA. The same was true of
the plastic wrap used on frozen dinners, he said. The plastic wrap
on frozen foods probably does not contain plasticizers, he said,
because it is brittle. And any plastic wrap or plastic bag that
says polyethylene on the label does not contain DEHA.
</P>
<P>
   For the safest recyclable plastics among bowls and containers,
Consumers Union recommends those with a recycling code of 1, 2, or
5 (referring to different kinds of plastic). Those are good for
storage but not for reheating in a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic containers used for microwaving should be marked
microwave-safe. That rules out containers like margarine tubs. And
even the plastics industry agrees that no type of plastic wrap
should touch food while it is to being microwaved.
</P>
<P>
   LISTERIA
</P>
<P>
   Listeria, a food-borne bacteria, also worried a number of
readers. The bacteria, which is only a minor concern for most
healthy people, poses a more serious threat for the elderly, those
with a compromised immune system, pregnant women and newborns.
Listeria had not been a problem in recent years, but led to one
serious outbreak and eight recalls of cold cuts and hot dogs from
December to February.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers wondered whether the potentially hazardous
ready-to-eat meats include the precooked poultry found in
delicatessen cases. Turkey breast and chicken are often displayed
in these cases without any indication that they were prepared at
some distant plant, wrapped in plastic and shipped to the store.
They look as if they might have been cooked on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   But listeria was found in just such meats in an outbreak in
December, which was traced to Bil Mar Foods, a subsidiary of Sara
Lee, in which almost 100 people became ill and 20 died. For those
at risk, all ready-to-eat meats could be hazardous unless they are
precooked to 165 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Soft, ripened cheeses should also be avoided by those most at
risk. Brie, Camembert and all blue-veined cheeses are in this
category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
