<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0331-CO     03-30 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM SARAJEVO: A RAVAGED LAND PLEADS DON'T LET IT HAPPEN
AGAIN
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ This predominately Muslim city
felt the brutality of civil war, besieged by Bosnian Serb forces
for more than 40 months until late 1995 with artillery and mortar
fire from the misty peaks around Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   It became the Beirut of the Balkans. Now for many, the pain and
fear are back as they watch the ongoing Yugoslav Serbian offensive
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of mass killings and scorched-earth bombardments by
Serb forces in Kosovo, the television pictures of frightened
refugees on the run -- all cause 72-year-old Emina Juncer-Erich to
shudder with fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing to the Kosovo people is the same as they
did to us,'' she said. ``I feel it all again. I'm sorry for those
babies and those young people suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Assisted by the United States late in their war against the
Serbs and still protected by 32,000 U.S. and NATO peacekeeping
troops, the Bosnian Muslims and minority Croats look to America as
a liberator, and the only force in the world powerful enough to
stop the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   A poster plastered around the city by a Bosnian political party
declares: ``Long Live America! Long Live NATO!''
</P>
<P>
   A pensioner, Juncer-Erich sells linens from a outdoor market in
Sarajevo's city center that was ground-zero in one of the deadliest
attacks of the Bosnian war from 1992-95. A red blot of paint marks
the grim spot where an artillery shell fell on the crowded market
in February 1994 and killed 68 people.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the Sarajevo market jolted the United States and
its allies into action to intervene. NATO escalated an air campaign
against the Serbs that eventually brought the combatants -- the
Bosnian Muslims, the Croats and the Bosnian Serbs -- to the
negotiating table in Dayton, Ohio, and resulted in an enforced
peace that has endured for three years.
</P>
<P>
   In Sarajevo, they are pleading for America to do it again,
before more fellow Muslims, this time the ethnic Albanians
remaining in Kosovo, are dead.
</P>
<P>
   And before the war expands, perhaps returning to this
still-recovering city, where blast marks and bullet holes still mar
hundreds of buildings, including the Olympic stadium which hosted
the 1984 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Some 800,000 people in Bosnia, a quarter of the population,
remain displaced by the war. Muslims, Bosnians and Croats live
largely in separate enclaves carved out at the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic tensions are growing with the developments in the past
week in Kosovo, say international aid workers. Furthermore, some
5,500 refugees have entered Bosnia from Yugoslavia, most of them
Muslims fearful of Serb aggression related to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us here are afraid of the war spreading,'' said Jamila
Bajraktarevic, 48, whose table laden with vegetables for sale rests
next to the bomb-crater from the deadly Serb assault. ``No one is
safe. Even if the peacekeepers are here, the Serbs could attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are doubts that American and NATO planes alone will be
able to bomb Serb forces and their leader, Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, into submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way planes can do the job without troops on the
ground,'' said Chamil Chatic, 36, a Bosnian Muslim selling bananas
and tomatoes from his market stall. His pregnant wife lost her baby
during the war when she was knocked over by the concussion of a
nearby artillery strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbian soldiers are doing the same thing there that they
did here, the killing, the ethnic cleansing. It will only continue
unless the U.S. sends in the army to protect the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton and administration officials
declared even before the air strikes began last week that U.S.
ground troops were not being considered in the operation against
Serbs in Yugoslavia. It is a vow they have repeated, including
Tuesday at the daily Pentagon press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But as tens of thousands of refugees continue to flee Kosovo,
pressure is growing within NATO to intervene with ground troops to
protect the refugees and prevent Serb forces from overtaking the
province.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims in Sarajevo have faith that America, like its fabled
Cavalry, will come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise God for President Clinton,'' said the linen-seller,
Juncer-Erich.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331-     03-30 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAST OUT, KOSOVO REFUGEES RECOUNT TALES OF SERB BRUTALITY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ As Dashurie Gashi searched for the words
Tuesday to describe the past few days, she was overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Her face reddened, and the tears fell in line down her cheeks.
She placed her hands over her mouth and spoke. ``I saw 50 people
dead, just like that,'' she said, whipping her hands at the ground
for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Serb soldiers gathered up the people in her village,
Suvareka, and took the men away, she said. She thinks her husband
may have fled before being taken but she wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   The women and children were ordered to line up and were warned
to be silent. ``The soldier says, 'Don't cry or don't say anything,
or else we will kill you,''' she said through a fresh flow of
tears.
</P>
<P>
   The women and children were allowed to leave, but as they moved
out of the village they discovered the bodies near the road, she
said. ``Men and women shot, just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is no way to independently verify her story, Gashi
offered herself as another witness to what is happening inside the
southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombings continued to pound away at Serb military targets
all across Yugoslavia Tuesday, including Serb troops and
paramilitary gangs in the Kosovo province, in an effort to force
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace agreement
signed by Kosovar rebel leaders. In apparent reaction to the
punishing air strikes, Serb forces have begun a ``scorched earth''
policy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of dozens of refugees paint a disturbing picture of
Serb police, soldiers and militia ordering people from their homes,
stealing their valuables, taking their passports and sending the
refugees to Albania. Homes are being torched and leveled, and many
refugees reported seeing dozens of dead civilians along their march
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw 30 people dead,'' said Husnia Shala, a grandmotherly
woman with a scarf wrapped around her head. ``The dogs and the
birds were eating from their bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the two daughters of her neighbor were found dead
with their throats cut.
</P>
<P>
   Such accounts are common among the tens of thousands of refugees
who have fled to neighboring countries since the air strikes began
a week ago. Since Saturday, 73,000 refugees from Kosovo have
crossed the border near here to seek refuge in this starkly poor
mountain community of 50,000, said Zakareik Kawi, an official with
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-million Kosovars -- nearly one fourth of the
population of 2.2 million -- have been uprooted by the crisis, the
biggest population shift in Europe since 1945, NATO said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100,000 were expected here Tuesday, but Serb
authorities closed the border allowing only 6,000 to 8,000 to
cross, Kawi said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believed the refugees are still coming, however, and
now say they expect as many as 250,000 in the next few days.
``Albania is very poor, and the sudden influx of 70,000 is a real
catastrophe,'' Kawi said.
</P>
<P>
   Kukes sits in a valley ringed by rugged mountains, many topped
by snow. It is isolated with its only road a little more than a
glorified goat path connecting it to Tirana, the Albanian capital.
There are no phones in the city capable of making international
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The one winding road, which often shrinks to only lane, was
filled Tuesday with scores of trucks, buses and minivans carrying
refugees to other Albanian towns and villages. Many refugees road
in the back of flatbed trucks exposed to the sun and cold mountain
air.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 refugees remained in Kukes, said Feriz Ameti, the
community's vice chairman. Most stay in private homes, moving in
with families. ``I saw 30 persons in one one-bedroom flat,'' Ameti
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 90 percent of the community's residents have volunteered
to assist in housing the refugees. ``It's an emergency situation
and our reserves are small,'' he said. ``Without the quick
intervention of international aid groups we would not make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Four elderly refugees have died from exposure, and two have died
from gunshot wounds received in Kosovo, Ameti said. There were
unconfirmed reports that two were injured after stepping on
landmines near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Near the town's center Tuesday afternoon, refugees crowded
around a shack where the Red Cross was distributing loaves of bread
and goat cheese. They waited patiently as the food was distributed.
</P>
<P>
   As Gashi arrived with her small daughter, the door to the shack
had been closed. She received no bread. She began to sob as she
recounted her story to a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   A woman nearby interrupted. ``You can come to my house,'' said
Lumitori Tucila, who stood next to her husband. ``We will give you
a place to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucila said her family doesn't have much but will share what it
has. ``We shall divide by half our bread, and we shall stay
together,'' she told Gashi. ``We are family, we are all
Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331-     03-30 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAST OUT, KOSOVO REFUGEES RECOUNT TALES OF SERB BRUTALITY
