Muslims fearful of Serb aggression related to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us here are afraid of the war spreading,'' said Jamila
Bajraktarevic, 48, whose table laden with vegetables for sale rests
next to the bomb-crater from the deadly Serb assault. ``No one is
safe. Even if the peacekeepers are here, the Serbs could attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are doubts that American and NATO planes alone will be
able to bomb Serb forces and their leader, Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, into submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way planes can do the job without troops on the
ground,'' said Chamil Chatic, 36, a Bosnian Muslim selling bananas
and tomatoes from his market stall. His pregnant wife lost her baby
during the war when she was knocked over by the concussion of a
nearby artillery strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbian soldiers are doing the same thing there that they
did here, the killing, the ethnic cleansing. It will only continue
unless the U.S. sends in the army to protect the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton and administration officials
declared even before the air strikes began last week that U.S.
ground troops were not being considered in the operation against
Serbs in Yugoslavia. It is a vow they have repeated, including
Tuesday at the daily Pentagon press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But as tens of thousands of refugees continue to flee Kosovo,
pressure is growing within NATO to intervene with ground troops to
protect the refugees and prevent Serb forces from overtaking the
province.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims in Sarajevo have faith that America, like its fabled
Cavalry, will come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise God for President Clinton,'' said the linen-seller,
Juncer-Erich.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
