<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRING-YOUR-OWN-WINE-2     03-30 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRING-YOUR-OWN-WINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD YOU LIKE THE WINE LIST? NO, JUST A CORKSCREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I was nervous as I approached Patroon, the clubby
restaurant known for its fine American food and excellent but
expensive wine list. In my bag I had a special bottle of my own, a
cabernet sauvignon from Dunn Vineyards that had been aging for a
decade. On this night, I hoped, I would drink it with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That's what made me nervous. Would the sommelier roll his eyes
at the rube with his own bottle? Would the hostess sneer at my
audacity? Would they tell me to get lost?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing of the sort. As the hostess showed us to our table, I
showed her my bottle and whispered my request. ``Of course,'' she
murmured. A minute later a waiter appeared. ``May I take your
bottle?'' he asked. A sommelier returned with the bottle and
decanted it, as was appropriate for this wine. ``Where did you ever
find this?'' he asked appreciatively. Success _ and I didn't have
to be embarrassed, or even whisper.
</P>
<P>
   The right, even the necessity, to tote your own wine to dinner
is a time-honored practice among many smaller restaurants that are
not licensed to sell wine and beer. But the practice also occurs at
fancier, more ambitious restaurants that have invested considerable
amounts of money in building their wine lists. Restaurants do not
encourage the practice, but most allow it, especially, as I found
out by experimenting at several restaurants, if you adhere to a
certain protocol. This essentially consists of asking permission to
bring wine when you make the reservation. And if you encounter
resistance, it helps if you can offer a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants go along with it mostly to accommodate regular
customers and special occasions. They don't advertise the fact
because they aren't particularly happy about it under any
circumstance. Alcohol, after all, provides them with some of their
best profits _ the price is generally twice what you would expect
to pay at a retail store, sometimes more. And in many instances, a
restaurant's wine service allows it to show off an expertise beyond
the expected culinary wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not thrilling when somebody brings in a bottle of wine,
because it's one less bottle you're going to sell,'' said Danny
Meyer, whose restaurants include Union Square Cafe, Gramercy
Tavern, Eleven Madison Park and Tabla. ``We've got a huge amount of
money tied up in our wine cellar.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, most restaurants charge a fee to uncork a bottle
of wine brought in by a customer. Depending on the wine you've
chosen to bring, the corkage fee may still permit a considerable
savings or obliterate any advantage at all. These fees can vary
tremendously. At Patroon, the fee was $30. Orinoco, a Venezuelan
restaurant on the Upper East Side, charges $10. At Meyer's
restaurants, the charge is $15. At La Caravelle and Windows on the
World, it's $20. At Montrachet, it's $35. At the Post House, it's
free.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing your own wine is desirable, especially in New York,
where so many people do all their entertaining in restaurants. Some
people want to drink a special wine on a birthday or anniversary.
Others, who have amassed a stock of old and rare bottles, want to
bring in wines from their collections that are hard to find in
restaurants. And some restaurants have small or limited wine lists
to begin with _ Thai and Indian restaurants, for example, rarely
offer rieslings or cabernet francs, the kinds of wine that go so
well with the food. The bottom line, though, is economic.
</P>
<P>
   Even when a wine list is not inflated beyond reason, the costs
can be staggering. Those who think nothing of paying a restaurant
$30 for a wine they can buy in a store for $15 may pause at paying
$200 for a wine they can buy for $100 less.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have collected wine over the years, to pay the prices
in restaurants is amazing,'' said Bill Plotch, a bond trader and
wine enthusiast, who has brought his own bottles to restaurants for
special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Erika Moore, a communications consultant, and her husband,
Terence, belong to a wine-tasting society that occasionally scouts
around for restaurants with modest wine lists that charge minimal
corkage fees. ``It's always been very pleasant,'' she said. ``A lot
of our members have incredible cellars. They've bought stuff at
auction or 10 or 15 years ago where they spent $80 a case and now
it costs much, much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant attitudes toward those bringing in wine vary, ranging
from a polite acceptance to outright hostility. As a practical
matter, restaurants are free to set their own corkage policies.
``No laws regulate or prohibit corkage fees,'' said Alan Gardner,
whose law firm, Verini &AMP; Gardner, represents a number of
restaurants that do business with the New York State Liquor
Authority. ``It's strictly up to the individual restaurateur
whether to permit you to bring alcohol or what to charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even restaurants that strongly discourage the practice find
themselves accommodating it occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy is fairly firm against people bringing their own
wine,'' Daniel Johnnes, the wine director for Montrachet, said.
``However, like all things in life, there's room for maneuver. If
somebody's celebrating a 50th anniversary, and they bring in a
bottle they've been saving, you can be sure we're not going to
charge corkage, and we'll serve it with pleasure. However, that's
very different from somebody bringing in a case of wine for a
tasting and trying to get away from paying for wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnnes recalled six businessmen who walked in once with a case
of expensive wine, expecting to be accommodated. ``They handed us
the box, told us which order to serve them in and said, `We'd like
Riedel glasses,''' he said. ``Of course we refused. You have to
have some courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Etiquette is crucial when bringing your own wine. It begins with
a phone call, simply to smooth the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walk into a restaurant cold with a bottle of wine in
your hand and say, `Pour this,' somebody's going to get a little
uptight,'' said Alan Stillman, the chief executive of the New York
Restaurant Group, which includes the Post House, Smith &AMP; Wollensky,
Cite and Park Avenue Cafe. He does not charge a corkage fee at his
restaurants, he says, because the only people who bring their own
wines are regular customers who do so only on special occasions.
``When it happens, we say there must be a reason for it,'' he said.
``I wouldn't be happy if somebody came in with wine once every
three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers understand that politeness counts. Plotch, the
bond trader, says that he rarely brings wines to restaurants, and
only to those where he's developed a relationship with the owner.
``I wouldn't feel comfortable unless over the years I'd spent a lot
of money in a restaurant,'' he said. ``I think it's rude
otherwise.'' He also recognizes the value of sharing the wealth.
``If I do bring in a really great bottle, I'll always offer the
owner or the one who's taking care of me a glass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A quick phone call might have saved embarrassment one recent
evening when I tried to bring in a bottle of Jean-Louis Chave
Hermitage 1994 to Peter Luger Steak House, where the
hamburger-class wine list does not do justice to the restaurant's
legendary steaks. I was politely but firmly rebuffed by the maitre
d'hotel, and no amount of diplomacy could change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do that,'' the maitre d'hotel said. ``I've even
turned down Henry Kissinger.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Luger's treasurer, Amy Rubenstein, said the policy makes
things simpler for the restaurant. ``It's just easier for us,'' she
said. ``We don't charge excessively, we don't have large markups,
but we're in business to sell wine, and that's what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you've received permission from a restaurant to bring
that special wine, the hand that pours the bottle for you will
still be outstretched. ``The waiter's salary has to do with what we
make on wine,'' Meyer said, ``so generally people are more generous
with the gratuity.'' As a rule, Johnnes of Montrachet recommends
tipping as if you had bought the wine at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   While restaurateurs dread the BYO bordeaux crowd, the actual
number of people bringing in their wines is small. ``Our restaurant
has been open about six months, and I can count on my fingers the
number of people who have brought bottles,'' Steven Eckler, the
general manager at Eleven Madison Park, said.
</P>
<P>
   Eckler, the former general manager of Postrio in San Francisco,
says this small number is in direct contrast to his experience
there. ``On the West Coast, I would see two to three times as many
people,'' he said. ``It's a different restaurant culture. People
don't feel the same hesitancy. They weren't embarrassed about
bringing it in. As a restaurant, you got used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Stone, the wine director and a co-owner of Rubicon in San
Francisco, says the different attitude stems from the area's
proximity to wine country. ``Winery owners entertain a lot and have
to bring their own wines, and that became the basis for it,'' he
said. ``Seattle, too, is fairly tolerant, but Southern California
is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone says that the practice was so common that many area
restaurants have not only abandoned hope of resistance but have
completely capitulated, instead accepting the profits they make on
corkage fees, which Stone said range from $8 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of restaurants don't want to stock wines because people
bring their own anyway,'' Stone said. ``They've just given up on
creating a wine list. You just don't see anything older. You don't
find the kind of collections that you might on the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that when Rubicon opened in 1994, 20 to 25 percent
of the customers on some nights paid corkage fees. The restaurant
managed to reduce the figure to 3 percent by emphasizing rare wines
at reasonable prices, he said. But that victory comes at a cost of
smaller profits on wine, a greater dedication to training the staff
about wine and an effort at ferreting out unusual bottles. And
still, the restaurant lives in fear of customers bearing bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four people bringing in 10 different bottles of wine,'' Stone
envisioned, practically shuddering. ``That's the nightmare part of
this. That's 40 glasses. It takes up a lot of time for the server,
they have to be washed and scrubbed, and they don't tip!'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
