<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGG-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLIDAY EGGS': A CELEBRATION WITH RECIPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In gentle pastels, ``Holiday Eggs'' by Georgeanne Brennan
(Smithmark, $14.95), celebrates the egg as a symbol of springtime
and renewal. Eggs are showcased not only in recipes, but also in
clever seasonal crafts, including stunning Ukrainian Easter eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Without getting too deep into the subject, Ms. Brennan
introduces eggs with descriptions of ancient legends, superstitions
and traditions from English, Greek and Roman cultures. She mentions
the custom of eating eggs with salted water at Passover and how
eggs represent the resurrection of Jesus at Easter.
</P>
<P>
   What may come as news to some is that white eggs are favored in
America and brown in Europe. And that hens with white feathers and
white ear lobes lay white eggs, while brown eggs come from birds
with red or reddish-brown feathers and ear lobes. Who knew chickens
had ear lobes?
</P>
<P>
   The general cooking information is given the same kind of
cursory once-over as the history and folklore. It's useful as far
as it goes, but neglects some basic, perennial questions about
cooking with eggs like:
</P>
<P>
   Why are some so easy to peel after cooking and some not? And how
do you avoid a black ring around the yolk when hard boiling?
</P>
<P>
   The collection of familiar, classic recipes, accompanied by
lovely, soft-tone photographs, is divided according to the way the
eggs are used: whole, beaten, whites only and so forth. Highlights
in the repertory include a salad of frisee aux lardons with an egg
on top, softly scrambled eggs with truffles, huevos rancheros,
seafood quiche and oeufs a la neige.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brennan does include nice little touches. A simple open-face
egg salad sandwich is beautified with edible flowers; French toast
is made from stale croissants, and eggs Benedict is dressed for
spring with asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Simple iced lemon-butter cookies cut into ovals can hang from
budding branches on silken cords as Easter decorations. But the
recipe for eggs pickled with tea and star anise omits an
instruction to crack the shells, though it does describe how
marbleizing occurs at the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonedible creations, using eggs and eggshells, include napkin
rings, votive candles, centerpieces and elegant little containers
for flowers. Egg decorating instructions are given not only for the
complicated Ukrainian eggs, or pysanky, but also for techniques
that children can handle, like tie-dyeing. Children also get
instructions for fashioning the baskets to hold those eggs.
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY SABAYON
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Holiday Eggs'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry Marsala or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine egg yolks, Marsala or sherry and 3 tablespoons sugar
in the top of a double boiler. Place the mixture over simmering
water, and whisk constantly until thick and custardy. It should
leave a path if you draw a spoon through it. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Dissolve gelatin in 2 tablespoons warm water, stir into
custard and refrigerate custard.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mash all but 1/3 cup raspberries in a bowl with remaining
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   4. Beat egg whites until stiff. Fold into cooled custard, then
fold in mashed raspberries. Transfer to a serving bowl or
individual goblets, and refrigerate at least 2 hours before
serving. Garnish with remaining raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
