<SLUG> BC-BIAS-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PROF WINS DISCRIMINATION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco State University lecturer has
been awarded $2.75 million in a discrimination case in which a
college dean allegedly said he would hire ``a white guy over my
dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   A jury awarded Howard E. McNier, a white teacher who was denied
tenure at the university's College of Business, $2.75 million in
damages Friday for discrimination and another $2.2 million for
retaliation, but a pretrial agreement limits the total award to the
higher of the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll (university officials) probably appeal it, but the
critical thing at this point is vindication,'' McNier, 51, said
after resolving his three-year legal battle. ``If this kind of
discrimination is ever going to stop, individuals will have to face
the music.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials declined to comment on the details of the
case, but were stunned by the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shocked, dumbfounded, deeply, deeply disappointed, and
we are actively considering all of our options at this point,''
said Ligeia Polidora, a university spokeswoman. ``The university
believes and continues to believe that there is no merit to these
claims.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Trials Digest Publishing Inc., McNier's award is
the highest employment verdict against any California institution
since the Oakland-based company began tracking statewide trial
results in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask if this is a reverse discrimination,'' said Robert
Jaret, McNier's lawyer. ``There's no such thing as reverse
discrimination. If you discriminate against someone and prejudge
them _ whether it's sex, race, religion _ it's discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jaret and court documents, McNier was a full-time
lecturer on hospitality and hotel management for five years when a
full-time tenure track position became available in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, McNier said he was told by the chairwoman of the
hospitality management department not to apply for the position.
McNier applied for the job anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's evidence there was a mandate in the College of
Business to hire recognized minorities over Caucasians,'' Jaret
said. ``Howard was precluded from the list of candidates solely
because they wanted to hire a recognized minority.''
</P>
<P>
   McNier said the job required a doctorate in hospitality, a
qualification he said was deliberately added to exclude him.
</P>
<P>
   McNier has a law degree and master's in business administration,
but no doctorate in hospitality. In April 1996, the department
hired a Chinese citizen from Hong Kong who had a doctorate in the
field but less practical experience, according to Jaret.
</P>
<P>
   A tenured business professor testified at McNier's trial that
the former dean of the College of Business, Arthur Wallace, who is
black, made comments over time about refusing to consider white
males for staff openings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the comments reported in the lawsuit, the dean allegedly
said, ``I will hire a white guy over my dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was dean from 1993 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, after McNier filed a complaint with the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, Jaret said his client was no
longer given hospitality and accounting courses to teach.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to continue teaching some management classes at San
Francisco State because of his friendship with the chairman of that
department, Jaret said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five years of teaching (hospitality) management and
accounting, he was completely eliminated,'' Jaret said, adding that
McNier's salary also was cut. ``It was clearly direct
retaliation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
