<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY31-COX     03-30 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY FUNDS WILL LIVE LONGER, TRUSTEES SAY
 &HT;    490&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The potential bankruptcy of the Medicare and Social
Security trust funds have been postponed for years thanks to
economic prosperity and policy changes, the programs' trustees
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that seven more years of life for Medicare and two more
for Social Security might relieve pressure for reforms, President
Clinton and the chairmen of key Senate committees pledged to work
hard on the popular programs' long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare trust fund that pays hospital benefits for 38
million Americans will last until 2015, the trustees said in their
annual report. That is seven years later than last year's
projection, and 14 years later than the previous year's prediction
of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees said the Social Security trust funds that finance
pensions and disability payments for 44 million Americans will last
until 2034. That is two years later than they projected last year,
and five years later than their prediction of 2029 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The growing economy helped both programs by raising wages and
the number of workers paying payroll taxes, the trustees said. That
means the bankruptcy dates could again shift earlier if the economy
nosedives.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security trust funds will also stretch further
because the newly revised consumer price index doesn't rise as fast
as the old one, the trustees said. That means that beneficiaries
get a smaller inflation adjustment each January when payments are
raised to match increases in the index.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare trust fund also got a lift from the phasing in of a
1997 law that removed the lid on wages taxed for Medicare and
squeezed payments to hospitals and related care-givers, the
trustees said.
</P>
<P>
   Crackdowns on waste, fraud and abuse also helped, said Health
and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, one of the four Clinton
administration officials on the six-person board.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and officials disagreed on what the good news _ which
the trustees acknowledged were only experts' ``guesses'' _ means
for current efforts to extend the life of both programs for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The odds that this Congress would ``seriously consider
long-range Medicare reform'' have dropped from ``very little'' to
``no chance,'' said Robert Reischauer, a scholar at the
Washington-based Brookings Institution who once headed the
nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House Rose Garden ceremony, Clinton disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might say this good news means we can simply delay
reforms. Nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said. ``If
we wait, we will be condemning ourselves to future changes that
will be much more costly and wrenching and much less satisfying in
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Chairman William Roth, R-Del., whose support
would be needed for progress in the Senate this year, indicated
within hours that he was ready to move on Medicare, and may push
for action on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let this good news make us complacent in our efforts
to improve the ability of Medicare to meet the needs of seniors,''
said Roth.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He announced that he would start a series of Medicare hearings
in mid-April. ``Based on these hearings, I intend to mark up
legislation and bring it through the committee later this spring,''
Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing Social Security, he said, ``I remain hopeful that at
the very least, we can get a personal retirement account program
under way in this Congress,'' which will end in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing, Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate
Special Committee on Aging, said, ``Today's news doesn't let anyone
off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the two outside trustees _ Democratic economist Marilyn
Moon and Republican actuary Stephen G. Kellison _ said the new
bankruptcy dates show that both programs should be saved through
small, step-by-step changes rather than sweeping and controversial
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substantial Medicare reforms'' could be put off until as late
as 2007, Moon and Kellison said in their portion of the report. For
the time being, they suggested, the government could adopt
``measured changes to make Medicare a more streamlined and
effective program.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Social Security, they said, ``The long-term financing
problem facing Social Security is significant, but could be solved
by small gradual changes, if those changes are enacted soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
