<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATIONS-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONES, TV SETS WILL WORK JAN. 1, NEW REPORT SAYS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Don't worry. On Jan. 1 you will be able to call
friends and relatives and settle in for hours of college football
games on television without a computer glitch, according to a
Federal Communications Commission report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Such typical New Year's Day activities should take place
normally because most of the telecommunications industry's
computers have been upgraded to read the date Jan. 1, 2000,
correctly, the report said. Thus, they will avoid any malfunction
due to the so-called Y2K or Year 2000 problem in which some older
computers may misread 2000 as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC, which regulates the nation's telephone, television,
radio and wireless communications industries, did warn that the
response time in 911 emergency systems could be longer as a result
of the date change.
</P>
<P>
   In many 911 systems, the report explained, operators see
callers' addresses on computer screens, and if those computers
fail, the operators would have spend more time getting information
from callers in order to dispatch ambulances, fire trucks or police
cars.
</P>
<P>
   But, overall, the FCC report said the telephone industry is best
prepared of all communications industries for the Y2K date change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of telephone consumers can expect few, if
any, Y2K disruptions,'' said Michael Powell, an FCC commissioner
who heads the agency Y2K task force. He spoke at a news conference
at which the report was released.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said the nation's seven largest local telephone providers
and the large long-distance carriers such as AT&AMP;T _ which provide
telephone services to 90 percent of Americans _ have fixed almost
all of their computers so they can read 2000 correctly.
</P>
<P>
   He said the FCC is concerned that some 1,200 small- and
medium-sized local telephone providers won't have their systems
upgraded by Jan. 1, which could disrupt phone service for the
remaining 10 percent of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   On TV reception, the FCC said it expects that people will
continue to have access to broadcast television signals and to
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said all Americans will be able to receive at least one
over-the-air television station even if a Y2K problem temporarily
halts operations at some stations.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said individual cable channels could be disrupted
because cable providers receive the channels from a variety of
sources that could be affected by a computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, the chairman of President Clinton's council on
Year 2000 conversion, who also spoke at the news conference, said
he expects that the nation's electricity systems to continue
working on Jan. 1, assuring that television and cable service will
also operate.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said he fears some of the largest Y2K-related problems
will come from people's overreactions, such as hoarding food and
withdrawing their money from banks.
</P>
<P>
   He and Powell did suggest, however, that people refrain from
making phone calls at 12:01 a.m. on Jan. 1 just to see if their
phones work.
</P>
<P>
   Powell noted that the nation's phone system isn't designed for a
majority of Americans to use their phones at the same time. He
noted that on Mother's Day, which is the busiest phone day of the
year, some people get busy signals or are unable to complete their
calls on the first try because of the larger-than-normal volume of
calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
