<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAIRY' ROSE IN CEMETERY POT MAY DETER THIEVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  NOTE: italic indicators in text 
 
By KATHY HUBER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My wife died in 1996, and I have been going to the cemetery
every day. In the beginning I took cut flowers, but after a while I
started taking flowers in pots, replacing them as needed. I bought
a hibiscus, which greeted me every day with its beautiful flowers.
Then came some sad experiences. Somebody stole it. This, of course,
limits my possibilities. I cannot put anything expensive on the
grave because the thieves have expensive tastes.
</P>
<P>
   What can you recommend that would last a little longer than a
few days, bloom nicely, be theft-proof and not require much
watering?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are many plants that would give you flowers for days,
weeks, even months, but the theft problem is the hitch here. Is it
possible to place a marble or concrete urn or other large, heavy
container at the grave site? If so, you could then plant a rose
called `The Fairy,' which produces sprays of double rose-pink
blooms. Such a thorny plant and a heavy container seemingly would
discourage a thief. The container would be an initial expense, but
I would hope it would be a permanent solution. Make sure the
container has a drainage hole in the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The rose would bring you months of beautiful blooms. Rainfall
would determine how much supplemental watering you would have to
do. During the hot, dry summer months, you may have to water two or
three times a week, depending on the size of the container and how
quickly the soil dries. Check soil moisture with your fingers. If
it's dry several inches down, give the plant a drink.
</P>
<P>
   You also could plant another hibiscus in a large, heavy
container. Or fill it with purple coneflowers and purple fountain
grass for late spring-fall color. These plants, like roses and
hibiscus, like sun but require little care _ just water to get them
off to a good start. Again, during the hottest months, you will
want to check the moisture. These plants are fairly
drought-tolerant, once established, but during extended hot, dry
periods, some watering will be needed. The coneflowers produce
rose-purple blooms that are attractive with graceful purple foliage
and purple-buff plumes of the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I brought seeds from my orchid tree in Arizona to Texas and
now have a small tree growing. How do I care for my tree in Texas?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most commonly seen orchid tree here is our native
Anacacho orchid tree ITAL (Bauhinia congesta), END ITAL the lovely
small tree that produces white flowers off and on from spring until
winter. The fruits, beanlike pods, appear in late summer. But I
like the foliage, too. The leaves are divided at the base into two
leaflets, but these appear as one wide, deeply cleft leaf that
resembles a hoof.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose this is similar to what you have. The orchid tree
grows at a moderate-to-fast rate up to 15 feet. I use it as an
understory tree on the south side of our home, where it receives
some protection from cold winds. Some years it suffers some top
damage after a hard freeze, but the tree is root-hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Mulch the roots well. Plant in an organically enriched,
well-draining, acidic soil in sun or partial shade. The pink orchid
tree, ITAL B. macranthera, END ITAL has beautiful pale
pink/lavender blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband has been contributing to the National Arbor Day
Foundation for years. Each year in early spring, he receives six or
more saplings. After starting the redbuds, he transplanted the
1-1/2-inch-diameter trees in several locations. Five years later
the trunks are up to 2-1/2 inches in diameter, and one tree is
1-1/2 stories tall. These trees have never bloomed. They just leaf
out in spring. Is there a reason?
</P>
<P>
   We have received cypress trees. Where can one person use eight
to 10 cypress trees?
</P>
<P>
   A: Redbuds and other flowering trees must pass through
adolescence before they bloom. Your trees should come around with
maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Cypresses are great in a Houston-area landscape, but they do
become large, and most gardens accommodate only one to three. You
could plant a grove in an area of your garden or use the trees
along a fence line. These trees are handsome, whatever the season.
I would pass any extras along to friends.
</P>
<P>
   The bald cypress ITAL (Taxodium distichum) END ITAL is a tall,
deciduous conifer, conical in shape with finely textured leaves
that are lime green in spring and deep rust in fall. Birds like the
seeds of this native.
</P>
<P>
   This large tree tolerates wet sites and will live in heavy clay.
It does not demand especially wet conditions and, in fact, is
drought-tolerant. Long-lived, the cypress can eventually reach 80
feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The thick, emerald foliage of my new blue hydrangea has been
turning brown around the edges for about a week, and this morning I
noticed something is eating it. The hydrangea is planted near my
lavender azalea. Should I move the hydrangea?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's possible your hydrangea is suffering from a little
stress. Too little or too much water will cause leaf margins to
brown. The recent heavy rains could have been partially
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas like bright shade or partial sun, and they like
adequate moisture, just as azaleas do. So if your azalea is
healthy, I would just leave the hydrangea where it is. Once it has
recuperated from being transplanted, and you maintain consistent
soil moisture, it will be fine. Mulch the root zone.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rains also helped the snail and slug populations in
our garden. Perhaps these pests have found their way into your
shrub, especially if thick, lush growth at the base offers an
invitation. There are slug and snail baits available at garden
centers, or you could use diatomaceous earth, also found at
nurseries, or even ground eggshells to discourage the pests.
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
