<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISH-NY-ART-2TAKES-NY     03-30 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-NY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM AUCKLAND TO ATHENS, A WORLD TOUR FRESH ON THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Yorkers may take it for everyday. But the menu at
a restaurant like Tropica is a global snapshot. There are conch
from Mexico, John Dory from Australia and pompano from South
America. A walk though a good fish market is no less extraordinary
_ like an art exhibition with works collected from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The fish, a stunning display of glistening specimens, do come
from all over the world. There may be red snapper from New Zealand,
with eyes so alive that you think the fish may jump if you touch
it. Or sardines from Portugal stacked like silver rods. And you
will almost always find sushi-quality tuna from the Gulf of Mexico,
as red as a rose petal, shrouded in white ice.
</P>
<P>
   These fish are in such pristine condition that it is hard to
believe that many of them were caught in a far-off sea and
transported across the world, making their way to a restaurant or
fish market in no more time than it takes to get from a hotel in
Auckland to an apartment in Manhattan. No longer does a diner have
to fly to the Mediterranean to savor rouget or branzino. The fish
comes to us. And home cooks have benefited as much as
restaurantgoers as the exotic becomes the everyday in good markets.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, this simply was not possible. Fish from Italy
or New Zealand may have made it to New York. But you might not have
wanted to eat them by the time they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, though, the stars in the world of fish
realigned: Transportation became much more sophisticated, importers
got savvy, and chefs seemed to acquire an almost ecstatic
enthusiasm for new varieties. Today, on restaurant menus, hamachi
from New Zealand, opah from Hawaii, rouget from the Mediterranean
and branzino from Greece have become as familiar as cod or striped
bass from New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to get all the exciting fish, we need to get it from
outside the country,'' said Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin.
``It's an excitement,'' he said, when he finds a fish he hasn't
worked with before. ``I feel like a little kid at Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Diners experience the same kind of excitement when they discover
that cockles from New Zealand are tender and sweet, maybe even
tastier than New England clams; that dourade from the Mediterranean
is delicate, much like porgy. Discovering new tastes is why we go
to restaurants in the first place, and why we follow the chefs'
lead at home. But the real surprise is that although a fish comes
from distant waters, it is hardly more expensive than high-quality
halibut or tuna. It is, after all, fish, not caviar.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers weren't always so interested in what lay beyond the
Eastern Seaboard. Chefs, in particular, were spoiled by an ocean
brimming with fish and constrained by a culinary tradition that
settled for the ordinary or the frozen.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Flying Foods, an importer in New York,
initiated a change in the industry by shipping then-exotic fresh
fish like Dover sole into the United States. Others began to see
the lucrative possibilities of a world fresh-fish trade.
Restaurants like Le Bernardin took risks by serving unfamiliar fish
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the demand for fish was steadily increasing.
People were traveling around the world, tasting fish and shellfish
and coming back asking for them at restaurants and fish markets.
</P>
<P>
   But delivering on those requests wasn't so simple. In some
cases, chefs got in touch with fishermen across the world that they
had met on their travels and persuaded them to send them fish. In
others, chefs encouraged dealers at the Fulton Fish Market to
search for varieties for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a progressive kind of improvement over the last
five years,'' said Costas Spiliadis, the owner of Estiatorio Milos,
a restaurant specializing in fish in midtown. More affordable cargo
flights from all parts of the world, with more efficient ground
transportation from ports to airports, have transformed the
business. The introduction of refrigerated trucks in places like
Tunisia and Greece in the last few years, Spiliadis said, has
altered their markets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in some cases, it is even quicker and hardly more expensive
to import fish from abroad than to buy domestic products. Red
snapper trucked from Florida, said David Samuels, the owner of Blue
Ribbon Fish Co., a fish seller at the Fulton Fish Market, takes 18
hours and costs 20 cents a pound. Red snapper flown all the way
from Rio de Janeiro takes half the time and costs 50 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   But time is not the whole story. ``Then it's the whole issue of
communication,'' Spiliadis said. ``I can directly communicate by
phone with the captain in the boat while he's fishing in the Greek
islands, and he's telling me, `I'm getting a big catch of
langoustines,' or `I'm getting a big catch of dourade.' So I know
what he's sending me. All these things were just unheard of five
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also emerging as a source, with Web sites
linking commercial fisheries and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen have realized they can get more money for their fish
if it is in good condition. Many are getting away from catching
fish by net and converting to line fishing, which batters the fish
less. They are investing in boats with refrigerated hulls, so that
the fish is kept cold from the moment it comes out of the water,
and they are no longer going out for days before getting their
catch to shore and on the way to market.
</P>
<P>
   For fishmongers and chefs, securing fish from all over the world
these days is actually the easy part. What's difficult is obtaining
superior quality. While the fish business has become a more global
enterprise, it also remains astonishingly small _ and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always 10 more restaurants or merchants looking for
the fish than they are able to supply,'' Spiliadis said of
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unless the fisherman catching hamachi in New Zealand thinks his
product is going to be treated with respect by a purveyor or chef,
no price can be placed on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the good fish is highly allocated,'' said Rocco Dispirito,
the chef at Union Pacific. He buys some from Louis Rozzo, an owner
of F. Rozzo &AMP; Sons, a 100-year-old company at the Fulton Fish
Market that buys from 150 suppliers. ``He just wants to know that
we know he goes the extra mile, and that we validate that,''
Dispirito added
</P>
<P>
   With great fish, that usually means cooking it simply so that
the essential flavor remains the most powerful element of the dish.
With many of these fish, particularly the European varieties that
can be cooked whole, the easiest cooking method is the best: Season
the fish, sprinkle it with a little oil and either grill it or
roast it in a 450-degree oven. Fillets can simply be seared.
</P>
<P>
   It is senseless to do anything more. These fish have their own
flavors. Branzino, for instance, is like wild striped bass but with
a much more delicate flesh. Hamachi is tuna on a higher plane, with
a texture that feels like butter in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   For chefs with well-tuned palates, getting fish with such varied
flavors is worth any effort.
</P>
<P>
   The relationships they must develop with suppliers take years to
cultivate. Twenty years ago, when Spiliadis opened his first
restaurant in Montreal, he said he was unable to buy great fish in
Canada. Frustrated, he borrowed a waiter's Impala and drove to New
York. For a week straight he went to the Fulton market trying to
persuade Samuels to sell to him. ``I begged him night and night and
night to begin working with him,'' said Spiliadis.
</P>
<P>
   The begging paid off. For months Spiliadis drove the Impala
twice a week to the market to pick up his fish. Eventually, he had
to buy the Impala from the waiter, but he no longer needs to go to
such lengths. He now buys enough fish to have it shipped and
delivered to his restaurants in Montreal and Manhattan. Along the
way, Spiliadis has sought out sources for Samuels, for
Mediterranean fish and shellfish like pagrus, a fish similar to red
snapper but meatier, octopus, dourade royale and loup de mer. And
in return Samuels has made sure Spiliadis gets the best quality
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most fish sellers and chefs _ at small bistros and
four-star restaurants alike _ know to nurture these kinds of
relationships, but few rely on just one supplier. Finding fish is a
continuously evolving project. Chefs may have a friend in Montauk,
N.Y., who sends local fish directly during the summer or a single
source for Hawaiian fish and a supplier like Samuels or Rozzo for
the bulk of their fish. Ripert, for instance, has a dozen
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a new product, Dispirito said, ``creates excitement in
the kitchen, it creates excitement on the floor, it creates
excitement with guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why chefs are always on the lookout for something new.
Dispirito is on a mission to import Norwegian skrei, a fish similar
to cod but with a slightly oilier flesh. Ripert is trying to get
Pacific fish from a top Asian supplier, no mean feat.
</P>
<P>
   Both, of course, are sure they will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   So are their teams of suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of 10,'' Rozzo said, ``if it's swimming in the
ocean and people are catching it and selling it, we'll be able to
find it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Top Markets
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, fish stores are like jewelry stores, with
colorful, sparkling displays of the world's rarest and most
precious catches. Here are some of the best shops:
</P>
<P>
   CITARELLA, 2135 Broadway (75th Street), (212) 874-0383, and 1313
Third Ave. (75th Street), (212) 874-0383. A good selection of
European imports like branzino, turbot and sardines, as well as New
Zealand specialties like green-lipped mussels and cockles. The
choice is best on weekends. Special orders are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   PISACANE MIDTOWN, 940 First Ave. (52nd Street), (212) 752-7560.
A vast variety, from John Dory and rouget from Europe to sea bass
and red snapper from South America.
</P>
<P>
   ROSEDALE FISH MARKET, 1129 Lexington Ave. (79th Street), (212)
288-5013. Called the Tiffany of fish markets, Rosedale carries a
huge selection from around the world. More than 20 varieties of
whole fish _ from carp to branzino _plus shellfish, fish salads and
even poached large fish.
</P>
<P>
   WILD EDIBLES, 255 Elizabeth St. (Houston Street), (212)
625-9971. In the world of fish, this store is the last word. You
may find elephant fish from Chile one day and dourade royal from
Israel the next. The store has the largest selection of fresh
oysters in the city. And if you don't know what to do with the
picorocos, there is always a chef on hand for consultation.
</P>
<P>
   SEARED HAMACHI WITH SAUTEED SPINACH AND GINGER
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Scott Bryan, chef at Veritas
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mirin
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 orange, peel and pith removed, cut into sections
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spinach, stemmed and washed
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   4 4-ounce hamachi steaks
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In small nonreactive pan, combine ginger, coriander, soy
sauce, mirin, lime and lemon juice. Boil over high heat to reduce
by one quarter. Off heat, add orange sections.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large saute pan, heat olive oil over medium high heat.
Add garlic, and saute until golden brown. Add spinach, and cook
until wilted. Remove from heat, and season to taste with salt and
pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place large, heavy stainless-steel or cast-iron skillet over
high heat. Add canola oil. Season hamachi. When oil is very hot,
add hamachi. Sear 1 to 2 minutes on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide hamachi and spinach on four plates. Ring
each piece of fish with orange sections, and spoon citrus reduction
over all. Garnish with cilantro. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
