<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYCARE-WEB-CAMERAS-N     03-30 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYCARE-WEB-CAMERAS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING THE INTERNET TO WATCH THE KIDS WHILE YOU ARE AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By AMY SCHLEIN   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Like many parents, Sheeda Ferguson misses
her 2-year-old son Blake while she's at work.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the pangs of separation, she keeps a bulletin board with
photos of him at her desk at the law firm where she is a legal
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But even better, Ferguson can look in on Blake any time she
wants during the day. On-site day care? No _ Web-site day care.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Beginnings, the private, in-home day care Blake attends,
has four Web cameras monitoring play areas. Every 15 seconds,
throughout the day, a Web camera captures images of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can dial up the password-protected Web site and peek in
on their children as often as they want. They can leave a small
window up on their computer screen while they work, seeing a
constantly updated image. And they can send e-mails to the day care
to let them know they're watching, and the children can wave back.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Web camera that drew Ferguson to Bright Beginnings,
but it wasn't the only reason she chose the day care. She liked Liz
Pivnarick, the care provider, and it was convenient to her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the factors that put her on top, though,'' she
said. ``It gives me a great peace of mind to be able to check on
him, and look in on him during the day. And it absolutely makes me
more trusting of Liz. She can't hide anything, the camera is always
on her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said she looks in three to four times a day.
</P>
<P>
   There are four camera views at the day care. Two are in the
backyard, two in the playroom. So the children are visible at all
times: eating, napping, painting, story time and playtime.
</P>
<P>
   Web cameras have been around for several years, with various
uses, such as weather cams showing surf and ski conditions and
sites with cameras focused on popular tourist attractions.
High-tech offices use them for video conferencing, and their widest
use of all is probably in the adult entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Digital day care centers are multiplying in places like Silicon
Valley, and larger cities. The trend is expected to grow as the
country becomes more tapped into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the trend grows so, too, do concerns over privacy _ both that
of the providers and the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you would live differently with a camera watching,''
said Carrie Anabo of the Community Child Care Council of Sonoma
County, a referral and resource center.
</P>
<P>
   Pivnarick said she has heard a lot of negative reactions about
Web cameras in day care settings, all from other providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all felt like it was an invasion of their privacy,'' she
said. ``But for us, it wasn't a matter of security or a way to keep
an eye on us, it was just a neat thing, to let the parents be in
touch with their kid's day.''
</P>
<P>
   She said while it felt a little strange to be on camera all the
time at first, she's gotten used to it.
</P>
<P>
   As for the children's privacy, Pivnarick said she doesn't
consider that an issue. ``These are 2-year-olds,'' she said. ``If
they're aware of it at all, they're saying `Hi' to mommy, and they
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said she doesn't feel surveillance has a negative
impact on Blake, making him feel he's constantly watched. Rather,
she said, it makes him feel as though she's with him throughout the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it's neat that Mommy watches him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pivnarick said there is one situation where she doesn't allow
the cameras. She cares for an 11-year-old handicapped child, and
makes sure she is out of camera range when she changes the child's
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to privacy issues, there may be other downsides. Win
Cary, a child care provider and officer with the Childcare
Association of Sonoma County said one concern with Web-patrolled
day care is cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Childcare providers are notoriously low-paid, with long hours
and no benefits,'' she said. ``Their ability to invest in this is a
real issue. ... It's certainly not going to be possible for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pivnaricks system required an investment of about $4,000 and
includes an IBM Pentium-II server, an ISDN modem, an ISDN line, an
ISDN dial-up account, four Web cameras, 100-base T-network hub and
cards and the domain registration for their site.
</P>
<P>
   The system could be cheaper. A Web camera can be set up with any
personal computer running an operating systems that has FTP
capability (file transfer protocol, the standard way of uploading
files). Also needed is Internet access and the hardware: the camera
_ which could be a regular video camera, some digital cameras or
any number of Web cameras _ and a video capture card for the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Web cameras often come with software applications that
allow users to set up an automatic FTP, or software is easily found
on the Internet. The computer expertise to be able to set this up,
though, is probably the most important element _ and the hardest to
come by.
</P>
<P>
   Parents looking into day care facilities with Web cameras will
want the most efficient browser to see the site with, and should
make sure the site is password protected.
</P>
<P>
   The Pivnaricks think the money they put into their system was
well spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line costs a couple of hundred dollars a month,''
Pivnarick said. ``But it's a good investment. I'm always full, and
I get three, four calls a day, looking for day care.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no extra fee for the day care's Web service. Parents
pay about $125 a week. And Pivnarick's day care is thriving with 17
children, although not all at the same time. Most are between 1{-
to 5-years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents tell me that when they interviewed with other
providers, they'll decide to go with us because of the Web
camera,'' Pivnarick said. ``They know we don't have anything to
hide. Even parents without Internet access, who can't use the Web
site, feel like their child is safe here.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
