<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Adds: MEXICO-DRUGS, CHOICES-CONFERENCE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, March 31,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _WASHINGTON _ Against a backdrop of punishing air
strikes and a seemingly endless stream of ethnic Albanian refugees
leaving Kosovo, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov meets with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in a desperate effort to
bring the defiant Serb leader back to the negotiating table on a
peace agreement and bring a halt to Europe's biggest humanitarian
crisis since world War II. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY _ WASHINGTON _ As NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia enter their second week on Wednesday, the mission is
shifting dramatically from a surgical campaign targeting equipment
and buildings to a harrowing assault on flesh and bone. With the
introduction of the supersonic B-1 and its cargo of armor-piercing
cluster bombs, ground-buzzing A-10 tank busters and possibly even
Apache attack helicopters, NATO is taking its punches directly to
the battlefield. After a week in which Serb troops and thugs have
had a free hand to rampage across the towns and villages of Kosovo,
the landscape is about to change. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ They've seen it
all before. The punishing NATO air strikes. The ethnic cleansing at
the hands of the Serbs. The build-up toward ground troops finally
giving way to NATO peacekeepers occupying their homeland. As
Bosnia's Muslim community watches these events unfold next door
they worry that events could widen and spillover to their area.
Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ It is a river of human
misery. Women carrying crying children, and in some cases, all of
their worldy possessions. Tractors pulling trailers of people who
can no longer walk after dozens of miles. Trucks carting old men
used to being the rock of their families, in tears after being
forced from homes they built with their bare hands. At the rate of
4,000 per hour, and swelling, they cross the borders of this tiny
country too poor care for them. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   LEVITT _ WASHINGTON _ SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt, as expected,
announces the agency will propose a prohibition on investment
advisors contributing to politicians who can direct business to
those advisors. Levitt also repeats his position that education,
not rulemaking is the best way to protect overly exuberant online
investors. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The healthy economy has pushed
the expected bankruptcy date of Social Security back by two years,
to 2034, and that of Medicare by seven years, to 2015. The new
estimates by the programs' trustees sparked worries that the
reformers would see the task of reforming the programs as less
urgent. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexican federal authorities are
reportedly working round the clock to assemble drug-and-corruption
charges against the governor of Quintana Roo state, who leaves
office April 5. This is the first time a Mexican governor has been
pursued so vigorously on corruption charges while still in office.
Analysts say the Mexicans aim to make a point -- high-ranking
policitians involved in drug trafficking can no longer count on
impunity. The governor, Mario Villanueva, says he's the victim of
political vendetta. He is testifying behind closed doors in Mexico
today. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHOICES-CONFERENCE _ AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has spent
a fair amount of bully-pulpit time blaming the Sixties for the
nation's moral ills, assembles a team of experts and lecturers for
Wednesday's Right Choices for Youth Conference. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-SENATE _ MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ A scene piece from the
chaotic Alabama Senate, which Tuesday night recessed three times,
adjourned at 10:45 p.m. and returned to session at 12:01 a.m. They
stayed until 3:55 a.m. local time but finally agreed on rules that
will govern them when they return to regular session April 6.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
