<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-30 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION SUFFERS ANOTHER BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court dealt affirmative action another
blow on Monday, continuing the national trend of giving up on
efforts to remedy discrimination through racial and gender
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The justices refused to review a lower court decision that held
unconstitutional an 11-year-old Dallas plan permitting black,
Hispanic and female members of the Fire Department to be promoted
over others even if they earned lower scores on written tests. The
5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans concluded that
achieving diversity through preferential treatment violated the
constitutional equal protection rights of firefighters who are
white and American Indian men.
</P>
<P>
   Although the justices did not explain their decision, it fit a
pattern of the past few years in which they have been backing away
from aggressive programs to achieve diversity in education and the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs have fallen from favor all over the country, as
white males have successfully claimed that reverse bias
artificially and unfairly blocks their own prospects of
advancement.
</P>
<P>
   But we still need safeguards against reverting to the bad old
days when white males promoted other white males and women and
racial minorities were bypassed. We are not yet a gender neutral or
colorblind society.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, for instance, the prestigious Massachusetts
Institute of Technology confessed that female professors there
suffer from pervasive discrimination in hiring, awards, promotions,
inclusion on important committees and allocation of research
resources. MIT wasn't simply being politically correct; it was
acknowledging the results of a five-year study of women in its
school of science.
</P>
<P>
   The gender discrimination at MIT is real and well-documented,
but it is the result of subtle cultural patterns rather than an
overt campaign to downgrade women. This is harder to fight than the
brutal racial segregation of old that forbade blacks access to
public facilities or the legally endorsed inferior status of women
that kept them out of professions and denied them economic
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, affirmative action plans that confronted
discrimination by applying easier job or educational qualifications
to minorities seemed like the only way to correct bias. The
reasoning was that blacks and women who had been denied equal
exposure to the workplace and equal opportunities to learn could
not be expected to compete intellectually at the same level as
white males.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and employers in search of diversity often applied
separate criteria for test scores and other measures of ability,
admitting, hiring and promoting minorities ahead of whites who
tested better and had stronger credentials. Individual merit became
almost irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Dallas Fire Department did. The court is
technically correct; unfair favoritism is unfair favoritism, no
matter how noble the social goal. Guaranteeing the equal right to
buy or rent a nice house does not mean those once discriminated
against should get it at half-price.
</P>
<P>
   But to abandon the concept of affirmative action altogether
would be a terrible mistake. Deceitfully, some conservatives
contend that individuals given unfair preference for which they are
unqualified are harmed psychologically and lulled into becoming
lazy.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney. This is an elitist assumption that disadvantaged people
prefer to remain in their disadvantaged condition.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Hispanic enrollment plummeted when the University of
California and the University of Texas ended admission preferences.
This is tragic. We cannot maintain a tolerant society if only young
whites are well-educated and grow accustomed to dealing only with
people who look like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do? The Supreme Court is clearly not prepared to help
us out of this cultural puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that minorities and women will just have to work harder
and get smarter is not the answer. It trivializes the heavy burden
imposed on individuals by a pattern of social discrimination they
alone cannot break.
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment programs that reach out to nontraditional candidates
in unfamiliar neighborhoods and situations do help, if in only a
limited way.
</P>
<P>
   To survive legally, affirmative action should apply only when
there are candidates of roughly similar qualifications. Race or
gender to add diversity can be a legitimate factor if there are,
say, four jobs and 14 candidates with competitive credentials.
</P>
<P>
   That's when it is desirable _ no, essential, actually, for
national unity and stability _ to look for that extra element to
make the school or the workplace more inclusive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
