<HEADER>
A9842 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV06-     03-30 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: SEPARATING THE MAN FROM HIS ACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, April 6)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably long after we forget who won which Academy Awards this
year, we'll remember who stood and who didn't for Elia Kazan. This
year there was more to talk about than bum jokes and collagen lips
while we watched Hollywood honor itself.
</P>
<P>
   We got into something real here _ a man who gave his friends up
during the McCarthy hearings.
</P>
<P>
   How desperate or scared would you have to be to snitch on a
friend? Could you do it knowing that friend would definitely lose
his or her job? And never work again? And maybe feel so despondent
he'd kill himself? How could you stand yourself?
</P>
<P>
   But what if in saving yourself you went on to do important,
beautiful things that contributed to human enlightenment and
compassion?
</P>
<P>
   OK, but wouldn't you have to say, at some time, ``I'm sorry''?
</P>
<P>
   Even ordinary people tend to have their disappointing traits as
well as their lovable ones, but famous people fall with such a
splat.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who watch and shake our heads in disapproval,
their screwing up provides some balance to their exceptional
talent. We'll never match them in creativity and brilliance, but at
least we would never rat on a friend. Or be a mommy dearest. Or
have an affair with an intern and lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Kazan question _ how to enjoy the work of a person but still
not want the person over for dinner _ is something we encounter all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Woody Allen. Many of us adored the man and his movies
until he took off with his step-daughter. We still had ``Annie
Hall'' and ``Hannah and Her Sisters,'' but the man was dead to us.
Well, at least we didn't think he was funny anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But then some of us began to miss his neurotic, zany discussions
and sneaked out and rented ``Everyone Says I Love You'' and it had
its moments. Lately, we can allow that as time has passed, he and
the young woman appear to have a healthy relationship. So, maybe we
go back to appreciating him, in part. But he's still a schmuck.
</P>
<P>
   Same with Bill Clinton. Strong president, weak man. Stunningly
disappointing. Does having an affair get in the way of being
president? Probably not, although if it distracts the president and
the country for a year or more, it makes it difficult to separate
the two. And it would be nice if our president was an all-around
good guy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Elia Kazan's offense is more Linda Tripp-like than
Clinton-like, which makes it even more interesting because it's
about the betrayal of a friend, an act that people find more
loathsome than, say, lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of balancing the good with the bad, Kazan had ``On the
Waterfront,'' ``Splendor in the Grass,'' ``A Streetcar Named
Desire'' to his credit. Linda Tripp has yet to reveal her
flattering side.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there isn't sufficient enough to overcome. A professor
once put down the notion that there's something commendable in
everyone, using the ludicrous: ``They say Hitler was a good
dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking it from that extreme, what if something beneficial to
humanity had come out of Hitler's madness? What if one of the
monsters in his experimental hospitals had developed a cure for
cancer?
</P>
<P>
   What if a killer in Kosovo ends up writing incredible poetry?
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Ware is a college instructor in Santa Rosa, Calif.,
whose father was a communist organizer in New York City, which she
writes about in the anthology ``Red Diapers: Growing Up in the
Communist Left.'' She remembers how people were hounded and
constantly feared arrest, how family members were tailed by FBI
agents while she was being assigned in school to write reports on
the menace of American communism.
</P>
<P>
   Her father believed that communism would end racism and classism
in America. When black families were kicked out of their apartments
he'd help move them back in.
</P>
<P>
   Had she been at the Oscars she would not have stood to applaud
Kazan when he got his Lifetime Achievement Award, but neither would
she have sat silent with her arms folded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that easy,'' she said. ``Nothing is that pat or
simple. We are so flawed as human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Government employees, including teachers, have to sign loyalty
oaths today. What would happen if some extremist type whipped up
enough hysteria about national security that a first-grade teacher
was pressured to snitch on the second-grade teacher?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they should have given Kazan the Lifetime Artistic Award
instead of Lifetime Achievement Award. It wasn't his life that
people want to celebrate as much as his art, which was enormous.
</P>
<P>
   He could have said, ``I'm sorry for whatever pain I caused.
Those were lousy times and you're lucky you didn't have to live
them. You need to make sure it never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who tried to squelch debate over Kazan said that we have
to separate the artist from his politics. There are also those who
say we have to separate the politician from his or her private
life. Same for separating the superior athlete from the way he
treats women.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that a character flaw should not erase a body of
work. But neither should a body of work erase a person's character.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the package. We all learn from it.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
