<P>
   COXNET-WHEELS 0326 _ The Integra is the lowest-priced model
imported by Acura, the upscale Honda division, but it's possible to
make an argument that it comes with the most potential for
enjoyable driving. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Includes
4 column color photograph of Integra exterior and a 2-column color
photo of interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 1999 Acura Integra.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ Technology is an ongoing process, with one
innovation often leading to another. Nowhere is that more apparent
than in the automotive industry. First there were anti-lock braking
systems, followed by traction control systems. Now the industry is
offering stability control systems. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist Linda Sharp
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWINDUSTRY _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes will give
Georgia Tech the resources it needs to double its computer science
graduates by 2001. The action was prompted by ISS, Nortel Networks
and Checkfree, who told the governor they want to expand in Atlanta
but are desperate to find software engineers. The three companies
will send executives to Georgia Tech to teach part time and have
agreed to hire at least 40 percent of the new graduates in computer
science. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ A day after Coca-Cola announced disappointing
beverage volume numbers for the first quarter, its stock was down 4
percent (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NEWHOUSES _ Atlanta led the nation in permits for new houses in
1998, breaking its own 1997 record in the process, and logged in
nearly four times more permits than Indianapolis, which ranked 6th.
(Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-INTERNET _ BellSouth offers cheaper Internet access in
Florida and other southeastern states to customers who sign up for
a complete local-telephone package of services. BellSouth.net
costs$12.95 a month _ compared with the standard $19.95 _ for
customers who also sign up for the Complete Choice package, which
includes up to 20 features such as caller ID and call-waiting. The
package averages about $30 a month (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NETBANK-DIRECTO _ The CEO who created NetBank and made it into a
thriving all-Internet bank is moving over to a new company called
Directo, owned and run by the same folks as NetBank (Including
former secretary of state Lewis Massey). He will run sales for the
company that is in the business of computer generated debit cards
that experts believe will be the next wave of credit/debit cards.
These are different from existing cards in that you can stick them
into a slot on any Internet enabled machine and use them to pay for
and authorize access to your e-mail, bank account, etc. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NET-RATINGS _ Nielsen Net-Ratings enters Web measurement field,
putting them head to head with Media Metrix/Relevant Knowledge
(based in Atlanta and New York) How Nielsen stacks up to Media
Metrix and if MM sees Nielsen as a threat or healthy competition.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CELLDEVICES-ATLANTA _ Atlanta, with the highest penetration of
cellular devices of any city in the country, has hundreds, perhaps
thousands of cell towers, but nobody knows where they all are.
These towers are in the news now because many of them have been
sold to a company which will lease them back to their original
owners and others for big bucks. The sales brought in nearly $1
billion for the sellers and will bring in more than that in revenue
to the buyer. How valuable are these towers, how do they work, and
why don't we know where they are? (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-FRAUD _ Peter Tosto, aka Lybrand, lately of Madison, Ga.,
has been caught selling fraudulent stocks more than once in the
past. In fact, he's pleaded guilty to same and been fined by the
Justice Department and the SEC. Why has that fine not been
collected? What kind of relationship does he have with the SEC that
keeps the agency at bay? Or what kind of enforcement power does the
SEC have in cases like this and is it adequate to protect
stockholders from fraudulent companies? (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: How much do I
need to put away if I want a long, comfortable retirement? (Ezell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-DRIVE _ The best way to approach BMW's new M Coupe is with
your eyes shut and your bank account open. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ There is probably more diversity in the methods
used to accomplish stability control than in the previous two
technological steps that preceded it: anti-lock brakes and traction
control. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ Questions and answers about auto electrical
systems. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
