<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UConn's win not magical, just methodical
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Late Monday night, some were looking for
a magical reason why Connecticut was able to knock off top-ranked
Duke, 77-74, and capture the first NCAA men's basketball
championship in school history. They looked for something,
anything, to explain how the Huskies, a decided underdog, were able
to beat the apparently-unbeatable Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   How about this one? UConn was a better team with a better plan
that simply outplayed what was supposed to be a team for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing magical about what UConn did to Duke, which
had its 32-game winning streak snapped. The Huskies, coach Jim
Calhoun admitted afterwards, started working on their game plan for
Duke back in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my free time, I watch a lot of games and take a lot of
notes,'' said Calhoun, who won his first national title after 27
years as a head coach. ``I started watching Duke and writing down
things a long time ago just in case we ever got a chance to play
them down the road. And frankly, our kids hoped that we would.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time UConn (34-2) got to St. Petersburg, Calhoun's Duke
file was pretty full. This players executed the plan to perfection
and dominated the Blue Devils in every phase of the game:
</P>
<P>
   _ On defense they held the Blue Devils to a season-low 41.1
percent shooting. Calhoun's defensive scheme on All-America center
Elton Brand was brilliant because it allowed the Huskies to
double-team Brand inside without giving up easy shots on the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   _ On offense, UConn shot 52.5 percent (32 of 61) from the floor.
The only other team to shoot over 50 percent against Duke all
season was Cincinnati, which shot 57 percent in Duke's only other
loss on Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Huskies out-rebounded Duke by 10, 41-31, and turned 12
turnovers into 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ UConn got 17 points and eight rebounds from its bench. Duke
got only eight points from its reserves, all from freshman Corey
Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broke our defense down. And really, a team hasn't broken
our defense down all year,'' said junior forward Chris Carrawell.
``They are a great, great team.''
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, UConn won the game because of something it
didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   So many times this season, Duke would literally force teams to
retreat with their constant pressure and talent. During the course
of the game with Duke, UConn had a number of chances to wilt. It
never did.
</P>
<P>
   With UConn clinging to a 75-74 lead, Augusta's Ricky Moore went
toe-to-toe against Duke's Trajan Langdon and forced him into a
walking violation with 5.4 seconds left. The play will define this
game for all time and take a permanent place on the highlight reel
of historic Final Four moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not back down from Duke,'' said Moore. ``We knew that
everybody was ready to put them on the all-time team list. In a
game like this, you don't back down. You stand up to the opponent.
That's exactly what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have a good chance to returning to the Final Four,
which will be held in Indianapolis in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   UConn loses Moore and probably junior Richard Hamilton, the
Final Four's most outstanding player with 27 points, who will
surely jump to the NBA. Point guard Khalid El-Amin, for all his
clutch plays down the stretch of the game, should stay. The Huskies
have a strong recruiting class coming in, led by 6-3 yard Tony
Robertson, who is compared to former UConn All-American Ray Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Duke played five sophomores, a junior, and a freshman in Monday
night's championship game and has the nation's best recruiting
class coming in. Langdon is the only senior who got minutes in the
game. Brand, the national player of the year, will decide in the
coming days if he will return to Duke. If he does, Duke will likely
begin the 1999-2000 season ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta's William Avery, a sophomore guard who has dropped hints
about jumping to the NBA, had his weaknesses exposed in the Final
Four. In two games, Avery hit only nine of 26 shots with five
assists. If he returns, he'll probably move to the shooting guard
position to make way for highly-regarded freshman Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both teams played hard, but Connecticut played
harder,'' said Avery. ``Hopefully, there will be better days
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
