<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTEXAS-DUNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QB Dunn among three to leave Longhorns
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Adam Dunn, enticed by the guarantee that he'll
be holding a bat on a major-league diamond in September instead of
wearing headsets on the Royal-Memorial Stadium sideline, left the
Longhorns on Monday to play full-time for the Cincinnati Reds
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They guaranteed me a September callup,'' said Dunn, who also
got his original signing bonus of $772,000 (over five years)
sweetened significantly. ``That was the key factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn _ projected as the backup for starting quarterback Major
Applewhite _ wasn't the only Longhorn to announce his departure on
Monday. Backup fullback Josh Spoerl and reserve halfback Eric Tasby
also were granted scholarship releases and intend to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Tasby, a sophomore from Corpus Christi Carroll, was beaten out
by Hodges Mitchell and Victor Ike. Spoerl, a junior from North
Mesquite, was running behind Ricky Brown and Chris Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dunn will likely report to extended spring training in
two weeks and be assigned to either of the Reds' Class A farm clubs
in Burlington, Iowa, or Charleston, W. Va., Cincinnati General
Manager Jim Bowden promised the 6-foot-5-inch, 240-pound
power-hitting outfielder a spot on the major-league roster when it
expands to 40 players on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made him an offer he couldn't refuse,'' said Dunn's
mother, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been substantial. Austin Kearns, whom the Reds
selected with the seventh pick in the first round _ the spot where
they would have likely taken Dunn had he opted for baseball only
and not already been selected by another team_ received a $1.95
million deal. Though a second-round pick, Dunn received a signing
bonus commensurate with selection late in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was so sweet that Dunn said he might have left even if
he had been starting for the Longhorns. ``It would have been a lot
harder to take it,'' he said. ``Still, I would have had to consider
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Selfishly, I am disappointed to lose as quality of a football
player and person as Adam,'' Coach Mack Brown said. ``The
Cincinnati Reds have offered him a terrific opportunity and one
that if he was my son I would have to advise him to take advantage
of.''
</P>
<P>
   With the transfer of sophomore Greg Cicero after last season,
Dunn entered the spring as the backup and the only player other
than Applewhite on the Horns' roster who was recruited as a
quarterback (two others, incoming freshmen Chris Simms and Adam
Hall, will join the team in the fall). Brown told Dunn he would
have a chance to win the starting job only if Applewhite got hurt
or struggled, which did not happen. Dunn visited the Reds' spring
training headquarters in Sarasota, Fla., during UT's spring break
before returning for the last week of spring football, in which he
received a trial at tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said the move to tight end was not a factor in his choice _
his mother said ``it helped in the decision'' _ though he had told
Bowden when he signed with the Reds in June 1998 that he would play
baseball full-time if the Texas coaches tried to switch him to
tight end, which was where many recruiting experts figured he would
play.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked the sixth-best prospect in the Reds' organization, Dunn
hit .288 with 13 RBIs and four home runs in an abbreviated season
for the Reds' Billings, Mont., rookie-league team last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realized that by doing both sports, he could delay
the inevitable, and that is being a big-time power guy in the big
leagues,'' agent Brian Peters of Houston told the Cincinnati
Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dunn was not on scholarship _ the Reds were paying his
way at UT and will continue to do so, should he choose to finish
his education _ the departure of Spoerl and Tasby puts the Horns
one scholarship under the limit of 85.
</P>
<P>
   Spoerl, recruited as a middle linebacker, saw limited time as a
backup his first two seasons before being switched to fullback
midway through the spring. He said he will transfer to a NCAA
Division I-AA school so he will be eligible immediately, and said
joining his younger brother, Jacob, at Texas A&AMP;M-Commerce is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart has always been at linebacker,'' Spoerl said. ``For
me to play linebacker, I had to transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tasby redshirted his freshman season and worked with the scout
teams last fall. He quickly fell behind Mitchell and Ike and, with
the addition of several highly touted halfback recruits in the
fall, didn't figure to get any playing time. Tasby said he hadn't
decided where he would transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
