<SLUG> BC-TEX-INVESTMENT-MGMT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT's money manager to disclose investments
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Responding to critics, the board that manages
$12.5 billion in public university money agreed Monday to be less
secretive about its higher-risk investments.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas Investment Management Co., a private
corporation the Legislature created in 1995, told lawmakers Monday
that when making future investments with riskier private firms, it
would name all principals, or individual managers, and would
disclose the annual rates of return.
</P>
<P>
   UTIMCO also is asking all of the private firms to which it has
already committed more than $1.6 billion to allow it to release
that information. Permission is needed because of signed
confidentiality agreements, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes a long way toward addressing my concerns,'' said
state Rep. Sylvester Turner, a Houston Democrat who criticized
UTIMCO's policies last week. ``This will provide some comfort as to
how public funds are being managed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a member of the House Appropriations Committee, was
responding to a recent article in the Houston Chronicle that cited
alleged conflicts of interest involving UTIMCO Chairman Tom Hicks.
The article said Hicks, a Dallas investor who recently completed a
six-year term as a UT System regent, had directed $252 million to
private funds run by business associates and friends. Another $205
million went to funds run by major Republican donors, the article
said.
</P>
<P>
   The private investments are mainly limited partnerships that
invest in such things as venture capital firms and buyouts. Such
investments have complex business structures, are not publicly
traded and are considered to be a higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   UT System Chancellor William Cunningham, one of UTIMCO's nine
board members, defended Hicks and said he was confident no
conflicts occurred. Hicks was very supportive of the disclosure
changes, which the board approved in a special meeting Friday,
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who testified before the Appropriations Committee on
Monday, provided written testimony outlining the disclosure changes
but they were not discussed at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A state auditor's report in 1996 warned that UTIMCO needed to
strengthen controls to avoid conflicts of interest with private
investments.
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up audit will be done this year ``to see how these
funds are being managed and to see if they followed any of our
recommendations,'' audit manager Carol Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   UTIMCO hopes to increase its private investments to as much as
25 percent of the total funds it manages in five years, said Tom
Ricks, president and chief executive officer of UTIMCO.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks added that his organization will not sign any new
confidentiality agreements that prohibit the disclosure of
individual names and annual return rates.
</P>
<P>
   Certain other information, such as a firm's investment strategy,
will remain private because it could put the firm at a competitive
disadvantage, Ricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
