u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0331-COX     03-30 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DRUG TRAFFICKING INVESTIGATION INTO MEXICAN GOVERNOR HEATS UP
 &HT;    450&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican federal authorities are reportedly working
around the clock to prove that the governor of Quintana Roo state
-- home of the resort city Cancun -- has assisted some of this
country's biggest cocaine traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   To deliver a strong message that no politician is immune, the
Attorney General's office here would like to indict Gov. Mario
Villanueva before his term in office expires on April 5, sources
close to the investigation of the governor say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems very important that governors in Mexico now know that
impunity here is no longer absolute,'' added Guillermo Velasco,
president of Mexico United Against Delinquency, an anti-crime
organization in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a spectacular case,'' Velasco said. ``It seems impossible
to me that they would have brought this case this far without good
proof.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Villanueva represents the first time that
federal authorities in Mexico have so vigorously pursued a governor
on corruption charges while he is still in office.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say to make a point, the investigation will continue
even if Villanueva is not indicted by April 5, but authorities
would like to charge him on corruption counts before he steps out
of office.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's justice system requires very strong proof and a judge's
consent to even indict a suspect, so the Attorney General's office
faces a difficult task in its case against Villanueva, Velasco
said.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva, a member of Mexico's ruling Revolutionary
Institutional Party, known as the PRI, has strongly denied
allegations that he has consorted with traffickers who use the
Caribbean state of Quintana Roo and Mexico's premiere resort city,
Cancun, as a base of operations. Villanueva is suspected of
allowing traffickers from a Juarez-based cartel to use the
governor's airport hanger in his state to unload and load cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   He is also believed to have offered protection to traffickers in
exchange for gifts, including a car and boats, which Villanueva
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Villanueva defied the Attorney General's
office by refusing to travel to Mexico City to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   After Villanueva challenged authorities to interview him in
Quintana Roo, they agreed to meet on the governor's home turf for
an interview that lasted more than 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Villanueva met again for another round of questioning
behind closed doors, this time in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva reportedly could face 28 allegations of consorting
with the trafficker Ramon Alcides Magana, known as ``El Metro,''
and other leaders of a cocaine cartel based in Juarez, a city on
Mexico's Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the Juarez cartel has moved much of its
operation to Cancun and Quintana Roo, which has become a virtual
``narco-state,'' according to sources following the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The state's long Caribbean coastline has become a prime
trans-shipment region for smuggling cocaine from South America into
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel development in the area, too, has proved a reliable way
for traffickers to launder drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying widespread police protection in Quintana Roo,
traffickers are smuggling as much as 15 tons of cocaine a month
into the United States, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   This month, pro-Villanueva protesters gathered outside the
governor's office in the capital city of Chetumal in Quintana Roo
to show support for the embattled governor.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva has claimed he is the victim of a political vendetta
because he belongs to a wing of the PRI that is in conflict with
Mexico's current president, Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
