<HEADER>
A9860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISHWRITER31-COX     03-30 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHWRITER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A.S. Byatt possesses secret of literary success
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a crystalline spring day at Lullwater, the Emory
(University) president's mansion in Atlanta. Enormous, black-purple
irises have announced themselves in the back garden with the
intensity of a bowl of plums. In front, there's a fountain of
goldfish _ streaks of orange swimming through curtains of olive
murk. A black sedan screeches to a halt in the driveway, and a
wholly ordinary-looking woman steps out and pauses to smile at the
fish and sniff the air.
</P>
<P>
   She is A.S. Byatt, the Booker Prize-winning English novelist who
has become something of a rara avis on the literary landscape.
</P>
<P>
   A deeply intellectual author with a magical gift for
storytelling, Byatt crafts gorgeously written books that become
best sellers. In town this week to deliver Emory University's
prestigious Richard Ellmann Lectures in Modern Literature, which
culminate tonight with a public reading, Byatt reluctantly agrees
to spend a day with a reporter. Gradually, she relaxes into herself
to unfurl the complex canvas of a mind bursting with poetry, art,
philosophy and opinion. Good gossip, too.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is a woman who went to school with
Oscar-winning actress Judi Dench, lunched regularly with Iris
Murdoch and once saw novelist E.M. Forster fall asleep at a dinner
party. This is also a woman who has had two marriages and four
children. Who almost died by electrocution in 1961, when she
touched an ungrounded refrigerator while trying to shoo a bird out
of her house. Who lost her 11-year-old son when he was struck by a
drunken driver, in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at 62, after steeping for years in a highly publicized
rivalry with her younger sibling, the novelist Margaret Drabble,
Byatt has discovered that writing well is the best revenge. Having
amassed an imaginative body of work that includes 10 books of
fiction and four of criticism, she is at the peak of her powers.
She says she has at least a dozen short stories and three more
novels in her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be Danielle Steel to make a very good
living,'' says Byatt, whose mood can switch from dark to light like
flickering shadows. Told that some Atlanta bookstores stock all her
titles, she is thrilled. ``That's rather like winning the lottery.
You can be very good and have that not happen. That's like living
in a fairy tale, because these are not mass-market books.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Antonia Susan Byatt seems to have spent her entire life
in a higher realm of thought. ``Right from the beginning, I sort of
lived in an imaginary world populated by all sorts of creatures and
people.'' Born into a stern Quaker family, Byatt took her
bachelor's degree at Cambridge. She is perhaps the only fiction
writer today who could embroider a resonant image of a bowl of
plums and lemons by weaving together references to T.S. Eliot, van
Gogh, Gauguin, Magritte, Vermeer, Velasquez, Rembrandt, Manet,
Balzac, Dickens, Flaubert, Sartre, Proust and the British food
writer Elizabeth David. (See the novel ``Still Life.'')
</P>
<P>
   She is equally at home writing masterpieces about modern
academics finding love in the ruins of Victorian poetry
(``Possession'') or precisely sculpted fairy tales (``The Djinn in
the Nightingale's Eye''). Embellishing her narratives with the
arcana of the natural sciences, she draws from a well of Western
literature that is deep and wide _ George Eliot, Willa Cather,
Jorge Luis Borges. ``The real English genius is twisting and
unexpected,'' she once wrote. She could have been describing
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, she plans to read from her new book of stories,
``Elementals'' (Random House, $22.95). With other stops scheduled
only for Washington and New York, her Emory visit is likely to be
Atlanta's literary event of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So what's on her mind on this dazzling Sunday afternoon in town?
Roast pig, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   Prestigious lecture series
</P>
<P>
   Since its inauguration by Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney in 1988,
the Ellmann lectures, named after the late professor and venerable
biographer of Joyce and Wilde, have become legendary in academic
circles. Though British novelist Anthony Burgess died before he
could fulfill his commitment (1992), other participants have
included critics Henry Louis Gates Jr. (1996) and Helen Vendler
(1994). They lectured, respectively, on Nobel laureate Wole Soyinka
and Pulitzer Prize winner Jorie Graham, who in turn came to give
readings (Soyinka is now on the Emory faculty). As a distinguished
critic and writer, Byatt fits both categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.S. Byatt is one of the most formidably intellectual and
erudite writers of our time,'' Emory English professor Ron
Schuchard said, introducing her at her first lecture, a Sunday
afternoon gathering that drew scholars from Oxford University,
Chapel Hill and Dublin. ``She is a novelist who tells a good story,
a critic who shares with us the passion and power of her personal
engagement with language and reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Her three academic lectures, which ended Tuesday, were titled
``Fathers, Forefathers, Ancestors: The Surprising Renaissance of
the British Historical Novel.'' They are scheduled for publication
by Harvard University Press in the fall of 2000. ``This has become
a very prestigious lectureship, because they have chosen people who
can speak to a broad audience as well as the academic world,'' says
Margaretta Fulton, the Harvard editor handling the book.
</P>
<P>
   All this made Schuchard's pig pull, a private affair Sunday at
Lullwater, a hot ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great mockery of the redneck professor having a pig
roast for the visiting dignitary,'' says Schuchard, adding more
coals and hickory wood to the pit. His bit of academic self-parody
included an invitation inscribed with a Latin homage to the pig:
Sues pacis in mundum solvite ut bona opera factum eant! (``Let
loose the hogs of peace upon the world to go and do their good
works!'') Pig Latin?
</P>
<P>
   The guest of honor loved it.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a crisp, upper-crust accent, Byatt _ whose round
face and square fashion are a mixture of British novelist Anita
Brookner and ``Hazel'' actress Shirley Booth _ can be stiff. But
give her a chance, and the asperity turns to chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Tell us about fellow classmate Dench. Turns out that Byatt
played Antonio to Dench's Ariel in their boarding school production
of ``The Tempest.'' ``She was terribly good, too,'' Byatt says
dryly.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing that really gets Byatt's goat is the fresh rumor
that Dench will play Iris Murdoch in a Hollywood adaptation of John
Bayley's ``Elegy for Iris.'' The memoir, by Murdoch's husband,
describes the brilliant novelist as she deteriorates from
Alzheimer's disease. Murdoch died in February. ``The odd thing is
that Judi could do Iris' voice perfectly, but that would make it
worse, not better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Murdoch, Byatt found a model for what a female novelist of
her generation might be, and she hasn't taken well to Bayley's
sentimental depiction of the genius. ``He was married to her for a
long time, and she loved him deeply, but he presented her as
slightly dotty and very unworldly.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was Murdoch really like?
</P>
<P>
   ``She was rather frightening, even at her best. . . . It was a
bit like talking to Socrates. She would grill you. She would ask
you a question about your life and you had to answer truthfully.
You felt that this person was staring at you, requiring you to be
absolutely accurate in your response. Then she would ask you a more
complicated, worse question. I never minded. But I would have felt
it was presumptuous to ask her any question. It was all rather one
way.''
</P>
<P>
   For a writer of such ambition, Byatt is a generous advocate of
other people's novels. So who's the greatest living novelist in
English?
</P>
<P>
   Saul Bellow, she says. Then there's Salman Rushdie, a close
friend. ``Toni Morrison is another writer I'd put there. I think
`Beloved' is one of the great masterpieces of our time.'' She's
also big on Canadian short story writer Alice Munro and British
novelist Penelope Fitzgerald, whose ``The Blue Flower'' won last
year's National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   What advice has she for aspiring writers?
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not be original if you haven't read everything and
seen what it is that you can do that nobody else is doing. That's
the key to it all. But once you've read something, you've got to
read everything, because otherwise you are influenced by the
`something.' You can't just decide to read Graham Greene and become
a novelist, because you'll end up like Graham Greene! You've got to
read everything that isn't like Graham Greene.''
</P>
<P>
   An interviewer points to a line in the final story of her new
book. ``The world is full of light and life, and the true crime is
not to be interested in it.'' Is this her credo of life?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sort of gulf between whether people are curious
about the world and whether they complain, really. . . . `They
ought to have made things better.' `They ought to have arranged it
so that my bones don't crack.' Whereas, I like people who are
interested in reasons why your bones are cracking. It makes life
better. They'll crack anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   THE A.S. BYATT FILE
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Born in Sheffield, England, in 1936. Married and
divorced Ian Byatt. Adopted T.S. Eliot's style of using initials.
Now married to Peter Duffy. Three daughters, three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Books: Fiction: ``The Shadow of a Sun'' (1964); ``The Game''
(1968); ``The Virgin in the Garden'' (1979); ``Still Life'' (1985);
``Sugar and Other Stories'' (1987); ``Possession: A Romance''
(1990); ``Angels &AMP; Insects'' (1992); ``The Matisse Stories''
(1994); ``The Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye'' (1995); ``Babel
Tower'' (1996). Criticism: ``Degrees of Freedom: The Novels of Iris
Murdoch'' (1965); ``Unruly Times: Wordsworth and Coleridge''
(1970); ``Passions of the Mind: Selected Writings'' (1991);
``Imagining Characters,'' with Ignes Sodre (1997).
</P>
<P>
   Movie: ``Angels &AMP; Insects'' adapted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Honors: 1990 Booker Prize; Commander, Order of the British
Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
