<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-APPRECIATION31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bluesman Williams bloomed late _ but great
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Joe Williams got the blues, audiences knew they
were in for a good time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cordele native, born Joseph Goreed, rose to fame in the
mid-1950s as a featured vocalist in Count Basie's band and three
decades later enjoyed a recurring role on ``The Cosby Show.'' He
was the rare entertainer who kept entertaining almost to the end of
his very long life.
</P>
<P>
   Williams died Tuesday in Las Vegas after collapsing on the
street a few blocks from his home. He was 80. The singer had been
reported missing from a local hospital several miles away, where he
had been treated for a respiratory ailment, said his wife, Jillean.
She survives him, as does a son, Joe, and a daughter, Anne.
</P>
<P>
   Though born Dec. 12, 1918, in Cordele in Middle Georgia,
Williams came of age in Chicago, influenced by spirituals (his
mother played organ in a Methodist church) and leading a gospel
vocal group called the Jubilee Boys. It took years, and stints with
such bandleaders as Jimmy Noone, Andy Kirk, Albert Ammons/Pete
Johnson, Count Basie, Red Saunders and Lionel Hampton before
Williams got a slice of the limelight: a minor 1951 hit, with King
Kolax, called ``Everyday I Have the Blues.'' Four years later, he
hooked up with Basie again, and his silky yet spirited version of
the song helped carry Williams, and the Basie band, to
international prominence.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Jazz Singers,'' critic Will Friedwald puts
Williams in perspective, comparing him with the much-loved Basie
vocalist Jimmy Rushing, who had preceded Williams in the band:
``Unlike Rushing, who seemed to spring fully grown out of the head
of Zeus, Williams was a late bloomer no one outside Chicago had
heard of until he was pushing 40 (most band vocalists became quick
celebs in their teens) and didn't become a truly great singer until
years later.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Williams' achievements was that as the big band era
faded, he was able to continue as a solo artist, refining his voice
while rarely, if ever, seeming to miss an opportunity to revive the
brass, sass and sizzle of the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Even on ``Cosby,'' on which he played the comedian's
father-in-law, Williams was a sagacious presence, spinning yarns
from his Chicago youth. Onscreen as onstage, he projected a vigor
without which the blues could not be half as blue.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
