</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-SENATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama Senate can now concentrate on other issues after
rancorous events
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ His doctor told him to get out of the sun. So
Jim Bates took a job as a part-time security guard at the Alabama
State House. But as Monday night dragged into Tuesday's dawn, it
wasn't the heat that was killing Bates. It was the boredom
following the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is beginning to get monotonous,'' Bates complained
Tuesday as the Alabama state Senate finally ended its quarrel over
how to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The acrimonious special session was ordered Friday because the
majority-Democrat Senate had wasted 11 days of its regular session
doing nothing but bickering with its Republican leader and his
allies over how to conduct business.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 House measures have piled up, including a
constitutional amendment to create a state lottery and a bill that
would allow video poker at Alabama's four dog tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives the Senate a framework for debate when the
regular session resumes April 6.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Republican Lt. Gov. Steve Windom feared someone from
Gov. Don Siegelman's Democratic majority might usurp his role as
presiding officer if he left to go to the bathroom. So, Windom
relieved himself into a jug under his podium _ this in the same
legislative chamber that requires men to wear coat and tie while on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' said Bates, 67. ``When people ask me
where I'm from, I tell them Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   After bursting a few of its seams, Senate decorum slowly eased
back into shape. Windom left the podium Monday. He returned to
applause as he wiped his hands on a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, senators were swapping compliments like
they were exchanging gifts at an office Christmas party. Members
who in previous days had shouted loud enough at each other to scare
small children now spread cordiality like a cold. Two senators said
they were ready to have Windom over for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The climactic session began at noon Monday. Senators recessed
three times _ including one break that coincided with the end of
the UConn-Duke national basketball championship game _ before
adjourning at 10:45 p.m. They met 86 minutes later at 12:01 a.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've learned how to do one thing _ recess,'' said George
Vest, the other security guard stationed on the ground floor of the
state house.
</P>
<P>
   When the hands of the dark, wood-trimmed clock behind the Senate
podium reached 3:50 a.m., the 35 senators finally had agreed on how
they would debate bills, appoint committees and record votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very tiring process,'' said Senate President
Pro Tem Lowell Barron, Windom's chief Democratic rival in the
Senate. ``But it's been a very worthwhile process because it's been
hammered on the anvil of equality.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, senators cloistered in small groups and
talked about the 45-page rules document. They inserted. They
deleted. Then they did it all again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep beating a dead horse, we might beat some life into
it,'' said Edward McClain, a Democratic Senator aligned with
Siegelman.
</P>
<P>
   The yawn replaced the handshake as the greeting of choice. Staff
members passed around ice cream sandwiches to keep everyone going.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows how hard it is to discuss one word for two
hours,'' Barron said.
</P>
<P>
   With its navy-blue carpet, three oversized TV displays and
modular desks with built-in cupholders, the Alabama Senate chamber
feels more like a modern hotel lobby than a legislative hall. But
there's one thing forever ingrained: raw politics.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Siegelman took a final act as lieutenant governor
before moving to the governor's mansion. He organized the
Democratic-held Senate to give him the best odds of passing a
lottery bill he had advocated throughout his fall campaign. The
rules relegated Windom to little more than a Senate administrator.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of five Democrats and all 12 Republican
senators, Windom reclaimed power March 2. A friendly Democrat
offered a motion giving Windom authority to assign committees and
chairmen. On a voice vote, Windom ruled the changes passed
unanimously, as Siegelman Democrats screamed for a roll call vote.
They were never acknowledged, and almost immediately sued Windom
and boycotted subsequent sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Less combative Tuesday, Windom said, ``We're birthing a
two-party system in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Republican lieutenant governor this century, Windom
has less power than Democrats who came before him. He must consult
with Barron on which committee will hear a bill _ a powerful
lawmaking tool. But on the Senate's two budget committees,
Siegelman must gain support from Windom allies to pass financial
proposals
</P>
<P>
   Just 19 days remain in the Senate session.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more than enough time to take care of the budgets and
the lottery,'' Windom said. ``It won't take long to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
