<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably warm air will cover much of the eastern half of the
nation Wednesday, especially where sunshine is plentiful, from the
central Plains across the southern Great Lakes to the Northeast
Coast. Meanwhile, a pool of high-level chill will drift southeast
over the interior West, resulting in cool and unsettled weather in
much of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Very warm conditions will surge from the eastern Ohio Valley
into the Middle Atlantic states and southern new England as breezes
from the southwest increase. The leading edge of the warm air will
be marked by a band of clouds and a few sprinkles or wet snowflakes
over northernmost New England.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will spread steadily toward north through the
Tennessee and southern Ohio River Valley. A few strong
thunderstorms will erupt in the humid air near the Florida
panhandle. Periods of rain will become steadier and heavier during
the day near the southern Appalachians where moist winds from the
southeast ascend the sloping terrain. The clouds and showers will
reach the Ohio Valley and Middle Atlantic States overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Intermittent mountain snow and valley rain showers will be
common over the interior West in the wake of a cold front. Periods
of snow will also develop from northern Montana to the northwestern
Dakotas as cold air seeps south from central Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Coast states, drier air will arrive over Washington
and northern Oregon on breezes from the northeast. Meanwhile, the
deserts of the Southwest will be mainly dry but cooler air and
gusty winds will arrive Wednesday afternoon and night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Chernobyl Concern
</P>
<P>
   Rapid run-off from melting snow has increased concern that the
rising Pripyat River, which flows by the nuclear power plant at
Chernobyl, Ukraine, might pick up radioactive particles left in the
aftermath of the 1986 accident there. The severe winter in eastern
Europe began in November, when outbreaks of Arctic air and heavy
snows started to mount. For much of the winter, low pressure
systems in the upper atmosphere recurrently stalled over Europe,
touching off widespread wintry weather, which included a barrage of
heavy snows that led to deadly avalanches in the Alps. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
