<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON KOSOVO BOMBING, BRITAIN STAKES OUT THE MORAL HIGH GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE,
KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-IRELAND) 
 (HLW)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair spoke on Tuesday of
``unimaginable suffering and barbarism'' in Kosovo. Defense
Minister George Robertson told of Balkan ``killing fields'' created
by Serbian atrocities. Foreign Secretary Robin Cook referred to
``appalling brutality'' and ``genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   The three separate briefings on the war, the resort to highly
emotive words, and the invocation of war-crimes-tribunal terms were
characteristic of the comprehensive and robust way that Britain has
been framing the rationale for bombing Yugoslavia in moral terms.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other European leader, Blair has stressed a sense
of his country's regional responsibility and yoked it to crusading
summonses to press ahead even more resolutely. ``This is happening
on our doorstep, and we simply cannot stand by and let it happen,''
Blair said in Belfast where he is overseeing talks between warring
Protestant and Catholic communities in a tribal conflict even
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Where some other European leaders are expressing doubts about
the correctness of the mission for NATO, Blair responds with
certainty that the Western military alliance should now be an agent
of retribution against Serbia for its campaign against the Kosovar
Albanians. ``The answer to what is happening is to intensify air
strikes,'' he said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The British public has responded with support for the strikes
and, by a lesser margin, for the entry of ground troops if
necessary. A Gallup poll published in Tuesday's The Daily Telegraph
showed that 58 percent backed the intervention and 52 percent would
support sending in ground troops. These are higher levels of
support than similar polls have recorded in France and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly for Blair and his effort to mobilize public
opinion, more than two-thirds of those surveyed agreed with the
view that ``recent actions in Kosovo constitute a humanitarian
outrage and should not be tolerated by the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   British networks have been giving graphic coverage to the
refugee crisis in Kosovo, and executives reported that audiences
for prime time news shows were considerably higher than they had
been during the bombing of Iraq in which Britain also participated.
``We are showing places being bombed close to where they have been
on their holidays and that tends to keep the concentration span
going,'' a BBC senior officer told The Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   The British press has been largely supportive, from the
characteristically jingoistic tabloid Sun (``Clobba Slobba'') to
papers on the center left like The Guardian and The Independent,
both of which have championed the intervention and urged Blair to
reconsider his refusal to send in the infantry. Blair has argued
that combat troops are not an option because of the numbers needed
and the time it would take to assemble them.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's aggressive commitment to the air strikes in Yugoslavia
and the passion with which Blair has justified the intervention are
a marked departure from the government of his Conservative
predecessor John Major when confronted with Serbian repression and
violence in Bosnia in the early 1990s. The British then were
reluctant to get immersed in a civil war they were not convinced
affected them and dubious about American involvement there.
</P>
<P>
   On becoming prime minister, Blair established a more assertive
British foreign policy, saying that his purpose was more to follow
a broad international ethic rather than strict national interest.
Britain's continuing arms sales to developing nations and its
involvement in some West African political crises have called that
pledge into question, but in the Balkans the new objective has been
reinforced with military force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been a strong tradition in the Labor Party
that you should only fight wars for strongly moral reasons,'' said
Vernon Bognador, professor of government at Oxford. ``People do
feel revolted when they see ethnic cleansing, it reminds people too
much of the Nazis, and the traditional Labor Party view is that
Britain has a moral obligation to act.''
</P>
<P>
   In power terms, the size and skill of Britain's military and its
willingness to use force has given it more impact abroad than other
European countries. Britain is trying to assert itself in Europe at
an awkward moment since it is not participating in the continent's
grand new venture, the euro as the common currency.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has been in the forefront of nations calling for the
arrest and trial of war criminals responsible for atrocities in
Bosnia. On Monday, Cook named key figures in the Yugoslav military
and security hierarchy, including President Slobodan Milosevic,
who, he said, would be hunted down and brought before the
International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague for their current
activities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   London's closeness to Washington under Blair has made Britain
suspect in many European capitals, though Blair argues that his
warm relationship with President Clinton should be viewed by other
Europeans as enhancing his influence. Typically, Blair said on
Tuesday that he had spoken on Monday night and again on Tuesday
morning to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, asked about the American-British alliance
in Washington last month, said it was the strongest it's been since
World War II. Blair's assertiveness came in for particular praise.
``Blair himself has a real grasp of foreign affairs, and we've been
able to get around all those lawyers in the Foreign Office,'' one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   By way of illustrating the intimacy the two governments enjoy,
the aide said that among the instant access buttons on the phone of
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger was one connected directly
to Sir John Holmes, his counterpart in 10 Downing Street. ``And
it's used every day,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
