<HEADLINE>
COURT REINSTATES GUN CONVICTION OF ACCUSED KIDNAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People accused in multi-state crime sprees
involving a gun may legally be charged with using the weapon in any
of those states even if they used it in only one state, the Supreme
Court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 ruling, the high court reinstated the gun conviction of
a man also found guilty of kidnapping and conspiracy in crimes
stemming from a 1994 drug deal gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling cleared up a nagging confusion among lower courts
over a federal statute that adds five years to a sentence when
someone uses a gun in the course of drug trafficking or committing
a crime of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some courts had ruled that if the initial violent crime or drug
trafficking offense occurred in one state and the use of a gun in
that crime in another, then the defendant should be tried for each
crime separately in the two states. In addition, these courts ruled
that the extra criminal sentence should not be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court's ruling Tuesday said that the two crimes
could be tried in one state and that the enhanced sentence should
apply.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, Jacinto Rodriguez-Moreno, a New York
drug dealer, and several others kidnapped Ephrain Avendano of
Houston, the middleman in a cocaine deal, after one of Avendano's
associates took off with 30 kilograms of cocaine without paying
Rodriguez-Moreno for them.
</P>
<P>
   After an unsuccessful search for the thieves, Rodriguez-Moreno
and his associates took Avendano from Houston to Middlesex, New
Jersey, where he had an apartment and where his wife and children
lived. They held the entire Avendano family captive there.
</P>
<P>
   Later they took Avendano to White Plains, New York, and then to
Wheaton, Maryland, where prosecutors said Rodriguez-Moreno grabbed
a gun, put it to Avendano's neck and said he was ready to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Avendano managed to escape through the back door to a neighbor's
house. The neighbor called the police, who later entered the house
where Avendano was held captive and found a .357 magnum gun with
Rodriguez-Moreno's fingerprint on it, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Moreno and five other defendants were prosecuted in
New Jersey. He was sentenced to seven years and three months in
prison on the kidnapping charges, plus an extra five years on the
gun charge, to be served after completing the other sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals threw out his conviction on the
gun charge, saying Rodriguez-Morneno could not be charged with that
crime in New Jersey because he used the gun in Maryland.
Rodriguez-Moreno could have been tried on all of the charges in
Maryland, the appeals court noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution gives criminal defendants the right to be tried
in the state and judicial district where their alleged crimes were
committed, although courts are authorized to switch trial sites to
guarantee that defendants will get a fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court reversed the appeals court
decision. Writing for the high court, Justice Clarence Thomas said
the fact that Rodriguez-Moreno used the gun only in Maryland ``did
not matter ... because the underlying crime of kidnapping had
occurred in four states.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas added, ``A kidnapping, once begun, does not end until the
victim is free. It does not make sense then, to speak of it in
discrete geographic fragments.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices Antonin Scalia and John Paul Stevens dissented.
</P>
<P>
   ``This defendant ... has been prosecuted for using a gun during
a kidnaping in a state and district where all agree he did not use
a gun during a kidnapping,'' Scalia wrote for the two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
