<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: GETTING TOUGH IS TOUGH ON PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, April 8)  
(mk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last weekend, my husband and I decided to ``get tough'' on our
8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   He's a good kid with a soft heart, but he has some bad habits.
Like leaving his metal scooter and his Star Wars laser guns outside
in the rain. Or staying up late to do his homework and then not
turning it in the next day. Or taking the cover off his tennis
racket and leaving it courtside. Or never filling the dog's water
dish, his one and only evening household chore.
</P>
<P>
   And we were tired of repeating requests, only to be ignored in
favor of the TV.
</P>
<P>
   So last weekend, we were consistent. He was grounded for not
turning in his homework. That included TV, computer and friends. He
also lost any toy he didn't put away. And if he didn't do as we
asked the first time, he was sent to his room. If he acted up, he
lost privileges.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we haven't used all those techniques before, in
moderation. But never with this little slack and this much
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   The grounding worked great. Adam remembered all the next week to
turn in homework, with minimal reminders on our part.
</P>
<P>
   But for a forgetful second-grader to have two hovering parents
waiting for a misstep was exhausting for all of us. By Sunday, the
whole family was cranky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the feeling this isn't working,'' I told Jim that night,
after the kids were finally in bed. ``If nothing else, I can't keep
up this level of concentration. And even I am getting confused over
what was taken away and for how long. There's got to be a better
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just tried to do too much, too fast. We've got to
concentrate on one change at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Adam turned 8 last month, we had suddenly decided that he
had passed a watershed of maturity. We expected more from him now.
But he was really just one month older, and not much wiser. Part of
the plan was going to have to be teaching him what the new
expectations were.
</P>
<P>
   Some of our habits would have to change as well.
</P>
<P>
   How long did we run his bath water before we trusted that he was
old enough to operate the spigots without scalding himself? How
long had I opened his cereal, poured his milk, and sliced his
banana before realizing that preparing breakfast was well within
his range of abilities?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who can maneuver Mario through a maze of seeping lava,
build a three-dimensional home for his Sim City ants and spend
hours running around the house with weapons drawn fighting
invisible armies, surely has the intelligence, strength and
fortitude to master a garbage run straight up the driveway or to
put a jacket onto a hanger and back in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as I wrapped a warm towel around him after his bath and
went downstairs to fix a snack of grapes and cheese, I thought that
8-year-olds still need a little coddling.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe their moms just like to think that they do.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a features writer for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers. She has master's and specialist degrees in
marriage and family counseling. The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
