<SLUG> BC-NEWHOUSES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta leads nation in new building permits
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta logged more building permits for new
single-family houses last year than any other metropolitan area in
the country. In doing so, the area beat its own 1997 record.
Nationwide, building permits also set a record _ barely.
</P>
<P>
   The 45,835 building permits resulted in about $8 billion worth
of construction last year, according to Dick Hearin, vice president
of builder/developer services at Northside Realty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's assuming our average sales price of $174,700 in the
11-county core metro area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Atlanta, came Phoenix-Mesa, with 36,641 permits. Third was
Las Vegas, with 21,791. Charlotte and Raleigh-Durham ranked fourth
and fifth, respectively, with 15,759 and 13,939 permits.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia ranked first among the states, with 69,425 permits.
North Carolina (63,167) and Arizona (50,178) followed.
</P>
<P>
   The report, compiled from preliminary census data by U.S.
Housing Markets, a Michigan-based research journal, noted that
nationally, builders filed for a record 1.18 million permits in
1998, surpassing a 20-year record by 1,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   While demand threatened to outpace supply last year, several
factors kept that from happening. One, said Brian Bragg, editor of
U.S. Housing Markets, was a widespread labor shortage in the
building trades.
</P>
<P>
   Others, Hearin added, included increased costs for lumber and
wallboard, concrete and insulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things affect the business,'' Hearin explained,
``along with the increased cost of land and finished lots, to say
nothing of the impact fees (builders) have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
