<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth discounts internet access
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. will now discount Internet access to
customers of its most popular calling plan for local service.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can have all-you-can-surf Net access from BellSouth
for $12.95 _ discounted from the regular $19.95-a-month tab _ so
long as they also choose the suite of phone services known as
``Complete Choice.'' Customers who sign up for the two services can
indefinitely keep the $12.95 rate for Net access.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, industry analysts and executives have touted
the coming of ``one-stop shopping,'' promising a key market
advantage to companies that can ``bundle'' numerous services
together.
</P>
<P>
   From a company's perspective, the notion of packaging is seen as
a way to win as well as retain customers. It is also meant to
convince customers of one service _ like Net access _ to sign up
for another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this packaging will attract many more customers,''
said Sue McLaughlin, president of BellSouth Consumer Services.
``Our customers have been telling us that simplicity and ease are
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 percent of households that use more than one kind of
communications technology would use one company for all
communication needs if given the choice, according to research
conducted by The Yankee Group. And more than 80 percent of all
households do buy some kind of communications besides local and
long-distance telephone service, according to Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   But one-stop shopping has been slow to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Complete Choice, which costs $34 a month in Georgia, includes 22
features, including the most popular, like caller ID, call waiting
and three-way calling. About 4 million residential customers _ 22
percent of the company's total _ have the plan, said Terry
Yarbrough, vice president of marketing for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has about 450,000 Internet subscribers, about
one-third of them customers for Complete Choice.
</P>
<P>
   With the market advantages of bundling in mind, BellSouth has
often complained that denial of its right to enter long-distance
markets allows rivals to offer packages that it cannot match.
However, BellSouth has thus far not even created a single billing
package that includes every service it does provide. For instance,
a customer cannot get BellSouth's wireless cable television service
and local phone service on the same bill.
</P>
<P>
   But McLaughlin said that the company is aiming to wrap many more
services together. ``Stay tuned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
