<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 4,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPACEY-ICEMAN-THEATER (New York) _ Kevin Spacey, resplendent in
black, from T-shirt to running shoes, is sitting amid the empty
seats of the Brooks Atkinson Theater, watching the international
scrum of lugs, louts and losers who frequent Harry Hope's bar in
``The Iceman Cometh'' by Eugene O'Neill. A respected and
prize-winning stage actor, he is probably best known for, and at
times hard to differentiate from, the dark, somewhat mysterious
characters _ all chilly control and sheen on the surface, all
menace and surprise underneath _ that he has played in films. These
include ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' ``Swimming With Sharks,'' ``L.A.
Confidential,'' ``Hurlyburly,'' and ``The Usual Suspects,'' which
won him an Oscar for best supporting actor in 1995. Spacey spent
much of the last year in London playing Hickey in the critically
acclaimed Almeida Theater production of ``The Iceman Cometh'' on
which the current American revival _ opening on Thursday on
Broadway _ is based. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-THEATER (Undated) _ Picture a Mount Rushmore in honor
of the monumental characters of American drama. What faces do you
see there, carved in stone? Willy Loman, Blanche DuBois, Theodore
(Hickey) Hickman and Mary Cavan Tyrone. But has our country yet
produced drama worthy to set beside the Greek tragedians,
Shakespeare, Calderon, Schiller, Ibsen, Chekhov? I think not. By
Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COOKIE'S-FORTUNE-FILM (Undated) _ A proper Southern lady knows
what to do when she finds a relative upstairs in bed with a bullet
through her brain and the pistol still dangling from her right
hand. When this happens to Camille Dixon (Glenn Close, dressed like
a blend of Blanche DuBois, Isadora Duncan and a Talbot's catalogue
cover), she simply rearranges things to make it look like murder. A
lot of things about Holly Springs, the setting of Robert Altman's
new movie, ``Cookie's Fortune,'' seem familiar. But then I grew up
in Vincent, Ala., population 1,200 or so, where ``y'all's'' is an
accepted plural possessive and people still refer to ``passing
away.'' Altman, whose hometown is the very metropolitan Kansas
City, Mo., got a lot of things about small Southern towns right,
but then his screenwriter, Anne Rapp, once lived in Mississippi. By
Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   GO-FILM (Undated) _ When the actor Jay Mohr showed up for the
first day of filming the new movie, ``Go,'' a dark, offbeat comedy
about a group of Los Angeles slackers whose lives collide after a
botched drug deal, he had his doubts about the director. Mohr had
never seen Doug Liman's breakthrough film, the 1996 cult hit
``Swingers,'' and when he first met the 32-year-old director, he
thought he looked and acted ``just like Einstein. Doug's IQ is
about 170 but I don't think he even knows how old he is,'' Mohr
said. He wondered if Liman was the right choice to direct a movie
about cynical, disaffected Generation X-ers. ``Go,'' which opens
Friday, takes place during 24 hours in the lives of three groups of
young people and involves everything from a bizarre Christmas Eve
dinner to Las Vegas lap dancing, tantric sex and couple-swapping.
By Dana Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-PSYCHO-FILM (Toronto) _ The humor being aimed for in
``American Psycho'' _ a swipe at the blind narcissism of the
youthful privileged class during the Reagan 80s _ is crucial to the
success of the movie, which may have more prerelease bias to
overcome than any film in recent memory. The 1991 novel by the same
name, on which it is based, depicts scenes of sadistic violence
narrated by Patrick Bateman in a seemingly indifferent manner that
by some literal readings was perceived as amoral. So much so that
many people who failed to recognize (or consider) the satiric
intent of the author, Bret Easton Ellis, thought the disturbing
work should not have even been published, much less made into a
movie. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GYPSY-DANCE (New York) _ The Gypsy Caravan, a sextuple bill,
produced by the World Music Institute, comes to City Center on
Friday and Saturday. The Gypsy music and dance heritage stretches
all the way from India to Andalusia. It's a musical diaspora that
has survived poverty and persecution while transforming, and being
transformed by every culture it has touched. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LE-CID-THEATER (Paris) _ The production of ``Le Cid'' was the
high point of last year's Avignon Festival, almost unanimously
praised by French critics as an intelligent and disturbing fresh
look at a dusty classic. Since then, it has been seen in many
French provincial cities as well as in London in February and most
recently at the Theatredes Bouffes du Nord, the Paris home of Peter
Brook's experimental theater company. Now it is ending its touring
life at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, with seven performances _
accompanied by English-language surtitles _ at the Majestic Theater
from Tuesday through next Sunday. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTERTENORS (New York) _ Time to strike the male alto from the
rare-species list. To appreciate how well established this once
marginal vocal category has become, consider the case of David
Daniels, who makes his Metropolitan Opera debut on Saturday evening
in a revival of Handel's ``Giulio Cesare,'' with an encore
scheduled for April 27 in the form of a recital at Alice Tully
Hall. It was with the premiere of this Met production in 1988 that
Jeffrey Gall and Daniel Dash struck for their brothers the blow
that in 1955 Marian Anderson struck for blacks, opening the doors
of the nation's most visible opera house to a class of artists
formerly excluded. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   VENGEROV-MUSIC (Undated) _ The young Siberian Maxim Vengerov
continues to stake out his ground among the most gifted and
engaging violinists of, let's say, the last 25 years. Let's say
that, because ``half-century'' or, indeed, ``modern times'' has an
inescapable ring of hyperbole. Yet Vengerov's magnificent new
recording of Brahms' Violin Concerto, with Daniel Barenboim and the
Chicago Symphony (Teldec 0630-17144-2; CD), immediately brings to
mind classic performances available on compact disk. By Lawrence B.
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FERNEYHOUGH-MUSIC (Undated) _ Brian Ferneyhough, an English-born
composer who has been teaching at the University of California, San
Diego, for the last 12 years, is a modernist by any definition,
except in his choice of media. He uses conventional instruments and
even has a penchant for traditional groupings, notably the string
quartet, and for historical models. A recent CD of solo works by
Ferneyhough (Etcetera KTC 1206), is played by the extraordinary
musicians of the Australian group Elision. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POP-SONGS-HERITAGE (New York) _ The noble parade of dead
songwriters in Lincoln Center's American Songbook series has begun,
starting with Harold Arlen in February and Richard Rodgers in March
and continuing in the fall with Jimmy Van Heusen and Jerome Kern.
The mission is nothing less than the preservation of our popular
song heritage. But is preservation enough? Clearly, the music of
that melodious roster of songwriting legends from the 1920s to the
1950s, like Cole Porter, George Gershwin, Irving Berlin and their
peers, will remain with us for the foreseeable future. Long-term,
though, their songs, written for a mass market that no longer
exists, employing standards of craft and sophistication that no
longer apply, seem destined for extinction. By Barry Singer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PILGRIM'S-PROGRESS-ART (Undated) _ Few art panoramas have
survived, and the ``Pilgrim's Progress'' versions were assumed to
have vanished, worn out from use or discarded once their vogue had
passed. Then in 1995, the traveling edition was discovered at the
York Institute Museum in Saco, Maine, where it had been hidden away
in storage for almost century. The painting was sent to the
Williamstown Art Conservation Center in Massachusetts for
restoration. And about a third of its 1,200-foot length is now on
view through May 2 at the Montclair Art Museum in New Jersey, in an
exhibition organized by Gail Stavitsky and Diane P. Fischer of the
museum, Tom Hardiman of the York Institute and Kevin Avery of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   ST.-FRANCIS-BASILICA-ART _ (Assisi, Italy) _ The recent tragedy
at the 13th-century basilica of St. Francis, where the entryway and
the altar collapsed 18 months ago during an earthquake, has been
entirely rebuilt and reinforced. The quake shattered ceiling
paintings attributed to Cimabue and Giotto. By Ken Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-AWFUL-TRUTH (Undated) _ In the debut episode of ``The Awful
Truth,'' the new series created by the guerrilla-style documentary
filmmaker Michael Moore, viewers meet Christopher Donahue, a
Florida man with a life-threatening pancreatic illness. Donahue
desperately needs a transplant but his health care provider,
Humana, refuses to pay for the operation. Those familiar with
Moore's work, particularly his breakthrough documentary film in
198, ``Roger and Me,'' and his Emmy-winning series ```TV Nation,''
will recognize that the basic ingredients remain the same in ```The
Awful Truth,'' which has its premiere next Sunday at 9 p.m. on
Bravo. By Warren Berger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   READING-ROOM-ANTIQUES (New York) _ The gloomy winter and the
bright spring have provided the proof. The glorious fullness of
light that the architects John M. Carrere and Thomas Hastings
envisioned 90 years ago for the New York Public Library's main
reading room has returned the Beaux Arts space to its former
splendor. The rescue was realized under Paul LeClerc, the president
of the library, through the largesse of Sandra Priest Rose, a
library trustee, and her husband, Frederick Phineas Rose, a real
estate developer, who gave $15 million to restore the space. By
Rita Reif.
</P>
