<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ SINGER JOE WILLIAMS DIES AT 80 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB BLUMENTHAL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Williams, the master of blues and ballad singing whose
vocals were crucial to the success of the ``New Testament'' Count
Basie band, and whose subsequent work on his own made him a
reigning jazz star for four decades, died in Las Vegas on Monday
night. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Admitted to a hospital last week for a respiratory ailment, Mr.
Williams ( scheduled to play the Regattabar in August) had
apparently left without informing hospital staff, and was
attempting to walk to his nearby home when he collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe and Tony Bennett are the last of what I call the graceful
genre, the folks who wear tuxes and take the time to say hello and
sign autographs,'' young vocalist Kevin Mahogany noted recently.
``They set a standard, especially for singers, and they have
managed to remain graceful after 40 or 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fortunate enough to have encountered Mr. Williams knew
that this grace was not feigned. He was one of the music's true
aristocrats, and he had worked in obscurity for years before Basie
gave him his crucial break.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Williams was born Joseph Goreed on Dec. 12, 1918, in
Cordele, Ga., and moved to Chicago at an early age. He broke into
nightclubs with clarinetist Jimmie Noone, and through the 1940s
enjoyed brief affiliations with Coleman Hawkins, Andy Kirk, and Hot
Lips Page, among others. It was his 1955 recordings of ``Every Day
I Have the Blues'' and ``All Right, OK, You Win'' with Count Basie
that finally brought him national attention, and in turn ensured
the success of Basie's recently reorganized orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 interview, Mr. Williams credited the Basie musicians
with helping him perfect his urbane style. ``I've been surprised
and pleased at how closely they listen to singers,'' he said.
``Benny Powell, one of Basie's trombonists, pointed out to me that,
no matter how softly I wanted to sing, I had to push in on the
diaphragm. It's basically an awareness of what you want from your
voice and what point you're trying to make.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was an all-around singer who also excelled with popular
ballads, Mr. Williams was most influential with his sophisticated
approach to blues material. ``Joe definitely dressed the blues
up,'' Mahogany explained. ``He made it okay to listen to the blues
for those who misperceived what they were all about. He pointed the
blues in another direction from just sitting out in a field and
moaning about your life. His diction was very proper, without a lot
of slang and idioms, and that made a big difference. And as he
aged, he learned finesse, how to be powerful when necessary without
being strong all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basie identification stuck with Mr. Williams, although the
singer had launched a solo career by 1961. Touring with a rhythm
section that has featured pianist Norman Simmons as musical
director for the past two decades, Mr. Williams was a regular at
clubs, festivals, and jazz cruises, where his conviviality brought
many fans back year after year. His Las Vegas home base and
friendship with Johnny Carson also landed Mr. Williams numerous
guest shots on ``The Tonight Show'' that together with a recurring
role as Bill Cosby's father-in-law on ``The Cosby Show,'' made him
perhaps the most widely exposed artist in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The consistent quality of Mr. Williams's performances in the
past decade, which are documented on several Verve and Telarc CDs,
set him apart from many of his aging contemporaries. ``They did a
lot of things that I didn't do and probably had a better time,'' he
joked when asked about his superior staying power in 1994, but it
was the intelligent application of his rare talents that made Mr.
Williams seem to get better with age. ``Here's to Life'' was his
last anthem, and it testifies to the spirit that illuminated his
art to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best of his available recordings are ``Every Day: The
Best of the Verve Years'' and ``Ballad and Blues Master,'' both on
Verve. His appearance on Marian McPartland's ``Piano Jazz'' has
also been released on a Jazz Alliance CD.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Mr. Williams leaves his son, Joe; and
his daughter, Anne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
