<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-DIRECTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President of internet bank to step down
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Donald Shapleigh, Net.Bank president and chief
operating officer, will resign from the nation's largest
Internet-only bank at the end of April, according to a Securities
and Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing, Shapleigh, 50, will become director of
sales at Directo, a debit card marketing and management company.
Former Secretary of State Lewis Massey is Directo's chief
executive. Shapleigh will remain on Alpharetta, Ga.-based
Net.Bank's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   D. R. Grimes, Net.Bank's vice chairman and chief executive, says
Shapleigh, like many successful Internet executives thrives best in
the start-up environment of emerging companies. Grimes said
Shapleigh will continue to be available for advice on credit and
lending and banking issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a really great blend of banking and technology
backgrounds. We think it takes both to be successful. I think what
Don really enjoyed was the start-up aspect of Net.Bank. Sometimes
you can look around at even 20 or 30 people and you think, 'gee I
liked it better when it was three or four.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been true as companies grew, they went through
transitions, but in Internet companies it happens really quickly,
but there's nothing between the lines and no falling out,'' Grimes
said. ``There are no problems between us.''
</P>
<P>
   No replacement was named for Shapleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Net.Bank has attracted about 23,000 customers and
over $300 million in deposits over the Internet in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Shapleigh had been president of Net.Bank since January 1996.
Before that, he held various positions over 23 years in the banking
industry, including stints at BankSouth Corp. and SouthTrust Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bankshares have risen 162 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
