<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG COURT RULES AGAIN MIGRANTS FROM MAINLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a decision reflecting fears about a flood of
immigrants from mainland China, a Hong Kong court on Tuesday ruled
against 17 mainland residents who had claimed the right to live
here.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 are among more than 1,000 mainland Chinese who entered
Hong Kong on temporary visas but now assert they have the right to
stay under a recent court ruling that relaxed immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   But in Tuesday's ruling, the high court said mainland residents
must return home first and apply to Chinese authorities to move to
the territory. Otherwise, it predicted a chaotic rush of people
across the border, with potentially millions of Chinese staking a
claim to residency in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unverifiable, unplanned, and unregulated large influx of
new immigrants to Hong Kong will be an unbearable burden,'' said
Judge Wally Yeung, citing a Chinese proverb about sinking ships.
``It may sink Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government welcomed the ruling, and warned it
would deport anyone who is here illegally. That could mean breaking
up families that have members on both sides of the border. By late
Tuesday, it had already detained 133 people, according to lawyers
for a group of mainland residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``While remaining in Hong Kong illegally, they have actually
broken our laws,'' said Regina Ip, the secretary for security. ``So
we really appeal to these overstayers to return to the mainland
voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement of people between Hong Kong and mainland China has
become a flashpoint between the former British colony and its new
sovereign. In January, Hong Kong's highest court ruled that
children born in the mainland who have at least one parent living
in Hong Kong have the right to residency in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The decision angered Chinese officials, which viewed it as an
attempt to usurp the authority of China's National People's
Congress. China has sought to keep a tight grip on the number of
people it allows to move to Hong Kong, which still has a higher
standard of living and is a freer society than the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Under intense pressure from the Hong Kong government, the court
later clarified its judgment to reassure Beijing it was not
challenging China. That averted a constitutional crisis, but still
left Hong Kong with a logistical problem of potentially vast
dimensions: how to deal with the immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong officials say they believe that at least 1 million
people could claim residency. If even a portion of those people
chose to move to Hong Kong, these officials said, it would place a
huge burden on a city of 6.8 million that is already among the
world's most densely populated.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments about social engineering mean little to the people who
are fighting to stay in Hong Kong. They say its immigration laws
are outmoded and tear apart families. As their lawyers prepared to
appeal Tuesday's ruling, these people reacted with fear, anger, and
a defiant refusal to return to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to go back, it would be very hard for me to apply to
come again,'' said Kong Kwok-fai, a 25-year-old from neighboring
Guangdong province whose mother is from mainland China and whose
father is from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Kong, who was left behind with relatives in the mainland when
his mother migrated to Hong Kong 10 years ago, said the Chinese
authorities would throw up endless hurdles to his effort to rejoin
his parents. ``If we lose this case, I will feel very helpless and
hopeless about having to go back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
