<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEALTH-FIGHTER-HNS &LR;      03-30 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-FIGHTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON MAY NEVER REVEAL WHAT DOWNED THE STEALTH JET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four days after a $45 million F-117A stealth
aircraft crashed in Yugoslavia, the Pentagon Tuesday again dodged
questions about what caused the radar-evading jet to plummet from
the skies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a news briefing if he had any further word about what
brought down the jet during a night of NATO air raids against
Yugoslav military targets, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said,
``it's still down.''
</P>
<P>
   The military may never release the details.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that if a surface-to-air missile hit the fighter,
as is suspected, they don't want to admit that a plane once
believed to be virtually invisible to radar is seriously
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the big hole in the wing, it looked very much to me like
a missile hit it,'' said a former NATO commander, referring to the
Yugoslav television footage showing pieces of a U.S. aircraft,
purportedly the F-117A. The official spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon couches the reluctance to discuss the incident in
national security terms.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon called questions surrounding the downed aircraft ``very
operationally sensitive.'' The Pentagon is conducting a crash
investigation, he said, adding, ``There's a chance that when we
complete this, we won't talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of the plane, who was rescued by Air Force commandos,
has declined to discuss the crash publicly and the Pentagon has not
released his name.
</P>
<P>
   Some military experts assert that the Pentagon should explain
what is behind the crash of a jet that cost taxpayers billions of
dollars to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't need to know the specific operational
details of the crash, but it has a right to know whether it was an
accident or the result of war,'' said Lawrence Korb, a former
assistant secretary of defense who is now with the Council on
Foreign Relations, a New York think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goure, deputy director for political-military studies at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington,
believes the public has the right to know if the aircraft crashed
because of a mechanical problem that renders the jets unsafe for
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Goure said, revealing information about the
jet's vulnerabilities could help the Yugoslav military and future
adversaries target other F-117A jets. ``The problem is that the
public's right to know may come at the expense at the safety of the
pilots,'' Goure said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Krepinevich, executive director of the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, a non-partisan think tank in
Washington, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   `The question here is when does the public's right to know
outweigh the benefits derived for the public's national security,''
Krepinevich said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Carroll, the deputy director of the independent Center
for Defense Information, said the military is doing the right thing
by not discussing the loss off the warplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, I can't fault the reticence of the Pentagon,''
Carroll said. ``We don't want to tell people how this plane got
shot down because we don't want to tell the Yugoslavs something
that will enable them to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be several reasons why the stealth fighter went
down: mechanical failure, pilot error, or _ the most worrisome
possibility for commanders _ the jet may have been tracked on radar
and struck by Yugoslav missiles or anti-aircraft gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army has sophisticated air defense missiles and
radar that it acquired from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Because the jet can evade radar systems, military planners
turned to the F-117A in the Persian Gulf War and now in ongoing
operations in Yugoslavia to conduct dangerous bombing missions over
heavily defended targets.
</P>
<P>
   The unique design of the triangle-shaped black plane renders it
significantly less visible to enemy radar than other jets, but it
is not invisible to radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was hit by a missile, it would not come as a terribly
great surprise because there is no military system that is entirely
invulnerable,'' Krepinevich said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two F-117As crashed while the jet was a top-secret
project in the 1980s, but what caused the crashes remains
classified. And another crashed during an air show in the suburbs
of Baltimore in 1997. Mechanical failure was blamed for that crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
