<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     03-30 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: COURT RIGHT TO UPHOLD INDIAN HUNTING AND FISHING RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper, Wyo., Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(mk) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, American Indians finally won one at the U.S. Supreme
Court _ unfortunately, a rare event. It was a significant but
narrow 5-4 victory that upheld an 1837 treaty between Mille Lacs
Band of Chippewa Indians and the United States. Had the Chippewa
lost this case, hunting and fishing rights of all other tribes off
their reservations would have been jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling should have been unanimous. The issues were that
clear. The Chippewa had filed a lawsuit against the state of
Minnesota seeking an injunction to keep the state from enforcing
hunting and fishing restrictions against band members. The Chippewa
won at the federal district level and again at the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1837 treaty, 12 bands of Chippewa Indians ceded land to
the United States, which later became the states of Minnesota and
Wisconsin, in exchange for money, goods and grain. Article V of the
treaty guaranteed ``the privilege of hunting, fishing, and
gathering the wild rice, upon the lands, the rivers and lakes
included in the territory ceded ... during the pleasure of the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the pivotal issues in the case, of course, was the phrase
``during the pleasure of the president.'' In February 1850,
President Zachary Taylor issued an executive order revoking the
tribe's hunting and fishing rights and ordering the Chippewas to be
removed from the ceded lands.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court notes, in agreement with the court of appeals,
that the ``president's power, if any, to issue the order must stem
either from an act of Congress or the Constitution itself.''No such
authority was granted by Congress. No such authority is granted by
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor writes for the majority of the
court: ``Because the parties have pointed to no colorable source of
authority for the president's removal order, we agree with the
Court of Appeals' conclusion that the 1850 removal order was
unauthorized.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's attorneys argued that even if the removal order in
the executive order was unauthorized, the revocation of fishing and
hunting rights in the president's order was, nevertheless, valid.
That is, the fishing and hunting revocation clause could be
separated from the illegal portion of the executive order and stand
as good law. Wrong, says the high court: ``We think it is clear
that President Taylor intended the 1850 order to stand and fall as
a whole. The 1850 order embodied a single, coherent policy ... The
order tells the Indians to `go,' and also tells them not to return
to the ceded lands to hunt and fish.'' The removal order was
invalid, and thereby any part of that order is also invalid, the
high court states.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota also argued that a later treaty with the Chippewa,
entered into in 1855, relinquishes the tribe's hunting and fishing
privileges on the lands ceded to the United States in 1837. Not so,
says the court: ``The 1855 Treaty was designed primarily to
transfer Chippewa land to the United States not to terminate
Chippewa ... rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys representing Minnesota made a third and final
argument. They claimed that when Minnesota was admitted to the
Union in 1858, the Chippewas' hunting and fishing rights were
thereby extinguished. The Supreme Court makes it clear that it
disagrees: ``Congress may abrogate Indian treaty rights, but it
must clearly express its intent to do so ... There is no such
'clear evidence' of congressional intent to abrogate the Chippewa
Treaty rights here.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional act that admitted Minnesota into the Union
makes no mention of treaty rights at all. Therefore, states the
high court, Minnesota's admission to the Union has no impact on the
1837 treaty rights to hunt and fish on the ceded land.
</P>
<P>
   This decision is significant, not only for itself, but for the
fact that it overrules a portion of an earlier ruling, Ward vs.
Race Horse, wherein certain treaty rights granted to tribes were
terminated when Wyoming became a state. The logic of that 1896
ruling relied on the notion that a state when admitted to the Union
had the same sovereignty over natural resources as the 13 original
states.
</P>
<P>
   The 1896 Supreme Court saw a conflict between a state's
sovereignty over natural resources and treaties which granted
tribes the right to hunt, fish and gather on state land. This court
sees no conflict: ``Rather, Indian treaty rights can coexist with
state management of natural resources. Although states have
important interests in regulating wildlife and natural resources
within their borders, this authority is shared with the federal
government when the federal government exercises one of its
enumerated constitutional powers, such as treaty making.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justices
Antonin Scalia, Anthony Kennedy and Clarence Thomas dissented. They
argue that President Taylor's executive order regarding the
termination of hunting and fishing rights had the authority of law
_ even if the removal order was invalid. Fortunately, they were in
the minority. And American Indian tribes finally got an even break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
