<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN31-COX     03-30 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bring on the Y2K headaches _ as long as there's butter
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Have you figured it out yet? Where you're
going to be when Y2K strikes? Me either, but right now I'm leaning
toward staying at home with the cats and waiting for the lights to
go out.
</P>
<P>
   At crucial times like these, it's a challenge not to reflect on
a more innocent age when, according to the predictions of
Nostradamus and various talk show hosts, all we had to fear from
the year 2000 was Armageddon _ the final battle between good and
evil. For a variety of reasons, not the least being I never met
this Nostradamus guy and for all I knew he was some goofball
smoking funny stuff and taking notes, I haven't been too concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the visitor to the American Consulate in Jerusalem who
claimed to be Jesus and left behind his cell-phone number so they
could get in touch with him when things started coming unglued, I
have not begun to panic. Nor have I rented a cave in West Virginia
and begun stocking it with Spam and automatic weapons. Talk about
an exercise in futility. Who'd want to shoot anybody over a few
tins of reconditioned ham?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the other day I started a list of things to do before
Y2K _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Item 1 was food supply, and that's as far as I got. The last
time I looked, my pantry was as bare as Old Mother Hubbard's
cupboard, except for a year's supply of cat food. The shelves are
lined with little more than shelf paper and even that needs
replacing.
</P>
<P>
   The refrigerator isn't much better. There's an open box of
baking soda on the bottom rack. Period.
</P>
<P>
   But the freezer is another story. It's filled with butter. I
know that sounds odd, under the circumstances, but it really isn't.
You see, mine was a butter-deprived childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Life was normal around our house until World War II came along
and brought shortages in its wake. I didn't miss coffee because I
was too young to drink it, and a lack of bananas at Mr. Swain's
corner store went unnoticed. But the day I watched my mother unwrap
a one-pound brick of white stuff that looked like a cross between
Crisco and paraffin, and heard her explain that I would be smearing
it on my morning toast, I realized that life as I had known it was
out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Oleomargarine, she called it. ``Tastes just like butter,'' she
insisted as she burst the deep orange ``color button'' that had
come with the pallid mass. I watched in horrified fascination as
she mixed up that first batch. In kid fashion, I reacted.
``Ble-eck! I'm not gonna eat that stuff.'' My mother questioned my
patriotism and explained that some sacrifices were necessary if we
were going to win the war.
</P>
<P>
   Because she suffered from a low boredom threshold, Mother quit
mixing before the color button had done its job. That evening at
dinner when Daddy asked for the butter, she passed him a bowl of
the variegated gunk. His reaction was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris,'' I remember him saying, ``I am a patriotic man. I work
16 hours a day to ensure that our troops are moved on comfortable
trains with good food and a cooling system that functions. I don't
mind driving on smooth tires, and I buy bonds every month. I even
tried to re-enlist but the Navy told me I was too old _ that I'd
already fought my war. No sacrifice is too great for my country,
but I will not eat striped butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother's answer was that oleomargarine was better for us than
butter. My father suggested in that case, it should all be shipped
to the front to save lives and grease axles. The discussion ended,
mother prevailed, and we never again saw real butter on the table,
which explains my freezer stash.
</P>
<P>
   So bring on the big GLITCH! If I survived those years of
Mother's sludge in a tub, Y2K's going to be a piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   With butter.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
Mail to 320 W. Madison, Gibsonburg, OH or email
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
