<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-STOCK-COX     03-30 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke stock takes dive after quarterly announcement
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. has seen better days on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Atlanta-based beverage company said it expects
worldwide case sales to fall in the first quarter because of weak
economies overseas, its stock dropped 2.4 percent in heavy trading
Tuesday. At one point, the stock had been down more than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, several analysts cut their earnings estimates or
downgraded their opinion of the stock, following Coca-Cola's
announcement after the market closed Monday that case volume will
decline 1 percent to 2 percent in the quarter. That compares with a
gain of 14 percent in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the magnitude of the malaise was greater than
expected,'' said Morgan Stanley analyst Andrew Conway.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be another choppy quarter in challenging
markets,'' Conway predicted.
</P>
<P>
   A First Call survey of analysts Tuesday showed a new consensus
earnings prediction at 28 cents per share for the quarter. That is
down from the previous forecast of 31 cents a share. The company,
which earned 34 cents a share in last year's first quarter, is
scheduled to release its quarterly earnings in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts also cut their 1999 earnings per share estimate to
$1.42 from $1.47, and their 2000 estimate to $1.64 from $1.69.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Cohen of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. downgraded the stock from his
``recommend list'' to ``market perform,'' while analyst Jennifer
Soloman of Salomon Smith Barney downgraded the stock to ``neutral''
from ``buy''.
</P>
<P>
   First Call said there was one ``strong buy'' in its survey, five
``buys'' and five ``holds.'' Those amount to ``meaningfully below
average'' ratings from stock analysts, said Chuck Hill, director of
research for First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola declined to comment on the analysts' actions. Conway
thinks investors should exercise ''near-term caution,'' but he
stands by his year-end price prediction of $75 a share. The stock
closed Tuesday at $63.25.
</P>
<P>
   Conway expects the company to start pulling out of the doldrums
by growing moderately in the third quarter, followed by a stronger
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, Coca-Cola will be reallocating some of
its marketing dollars away from television and other media
advertising, and toward locally-tailored promotions and events, or
those with special themes for niche audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts expect the company to try to drive up sales
overseas by turning to cheaper returnable bottles and smaller-size
containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this environment, it's whatever sells the product
immediately,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company is launching a new promotion for Coca-Cola
Classic this week, targeting 45 million teenagers and young adults
across this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get them to stop and take notice of this brand,''
said company spokeswoman Diana Garza. ``It is about driving
volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after a similar promotion last spring and summer, the
company will be distributing 45 million ``Coke Cards'' that qualify
users for money-saving offers at participating retailers. The
teenagers also get access to a special Coke voicemail system where
they can leave private messages for their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teens want to do stuff that's under the radar screen and
independent. They want to feel grown-up,'' Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the cardholder uses the system, the special access
number will expire. So another purchase of Coca-Cola Classic is
required to get another access number and continue on the voicemail
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to help generate volume,'' analyst Conway said of
the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States and Canada were the only regions where
volume is expectewd to grow in the first quarter, it is below what
analysts had predicted. Coca-Cola said case sales will rise about 2
percent in North America, but analysts had been expecting growth of
4 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said the declines in other regions of the world will
range from 1 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
