<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON-NYT     03-30 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPEECH, MRS. CLINTON SAYS NATO BOMBING IS NECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE,
KOSOVO-GENOCIDE) 
(ac) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARRAKESH, Morocco _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said tonight that
the NATO bombing in Yugoslavia was necessary to block a planned
``campaign of massive and systematic destruction'' against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton used a speech here on tolerance to add her voice to
the NATO position that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
bears responsibility for the bombing. She accused him of having
prepared to kill or expel ethnic Albanians from Kosovo even as
peace talks were under way earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why my husband and our NATO allies could not stand and
look the other way,'' she said. ``They could not permit this to go
on with impunity until most of the Albanian population was either
dead or displaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is also why my husband and our NATO allies are determined
to persevere until Milosevic has embraced peace or NATO has
significantly limited his ability to make war.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is 10 days into a 12-day trip through North Africa
to promote education, health care and human rights. On Tuesday she
attended a roundtable with Moroccan women, stopped at an orphanage
and visited a housing development that gets helps from the American
government.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke before more than a thousand people _ most of them
Muslims _ who gathered at sunset in the ruins of El Badi Palace, a
16th-century compound fragrant with orange trees and surrounded by
towering adobe walls. Although she had previously expressed her
support for American service personnel, her remarks this evening on
the fighting were her most extensive.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton accused Milosevic of having tried for 10 years to
fan ethnic and religious hatred in Yugoslavia. ``He did it for his
own personal political advantage,'' she said. ``Tolerance, he
thought, would not give him any advantage. But exploiting the
consequences of division, waging war on his neighbors and his
people, is what he thought was in his own personal interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mrs. Clinton said, President Milosevic is pursuing the same
sort of policy that he carried out in Bosnia, pointedly noting that
most of the Albanians in Kosovo are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, she said, had found waging war easier than building a
modern state. ``It is difficult, very difficult in today's world to
make some of the hard decisions that must be made in peace,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also attacked the treatment of women by the
Taliban, the fundamentalist Muslim group that controls most of
Afghanistan, and recalled the killings of hundreds of thousands of
people in Rwanda in 1994. At the same time, she congratulated
Morocco on a ``tradition of tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   On her stops in Egypt, Tunisia and Morocco, Mrs. Clinton, who is
traveling with her daughter, Chelsea, has visited several mosques
and repeatedly stressed American support for Islam, even as she has
condemned its fundamentalist strain.
</P>
<P>
   She has also stopped in several churches and synagogues, and she
visited a 440-year-old Jewish cemetery here on Monday evening. ``We
are all children of God,'' she said Tuesday evening. ``We are all
children of Abraham.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
