<HEADER>
A9927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SPIKES-COX     03-30 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SPIKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth Classic: It's gotta be the shoes
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heavy metal just doesn't quite cut it in golf these
days, and who would have believed it? When non-metal spikes first
appeared in 1993 as plastic swirls questioned by traditionalists,
few figured that by now many of the players on the PGA and Senior
tours would be using cleats that don't click on the cartpaths.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Darrell Survey Co., which provides statistics
for golf equipment manufacturers, 48.1 percent of PGA Tour players
and 68 percent of Senior Tour players are wearing non-metal spikes
this season.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the converted masses are no longer just players
being forced to adapt to local club rules, such as those for
members of the TPC at Sugarloaf in Duluth, Ga., which prohibits
metal spikes 51 other weeks of the year. Many of the best players
in the world are trading in their beloved nails for plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're going to see any steel spikes at all in
five years, and maybe less than that,'' said Marietta's Larry
Nelson, who plays on the Senior Tour. ``All the young kids are
growing up on them. They don't know anything about metal spikes.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? Non-metal spikes were introduced during one of
golf's biggest booms as a way to prevent damage to the greens and,
in turn, improve putting. Greenskeepers raved over the new product,
leading many of the nation's courses, including most PGA Tour
venues, including Sugarloaf, Muirfield Village in Ohio, Castle
Pines in Colorado and Augusta National, to mandate non-metal
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're a professional golfer making the tour
stop. The PGA Tour has no rules against metal spikes, and when the
Tour comes to town, its players have the option.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the debate begins on whether non-metal spikes
are a fad or whether they have improved the greens and, in turn,
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you lose is spike marks,'' said former
BellSouth Classic winner Paul Stankowski, a proponent of non-metal
spikes. ``I can't tell any difference. I think once every golf
course in America is banning metal spikes, I think metal spikes are
going to be put out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not everyone feels comfortable using the non-metal
spikes, most golfers say that if Mark Calcavecchia, whose feet
regularly slide at impact, can use them, anyone can.
</P>
<P>
   But Calcavecchia wears metal. He says he only wears non-metal
during rounds at his home course in Scottsdale, where it's
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia isn't convinced that non-metal spikes improve the
greens, except perhaps in summer when bentgrass is pulled up during
periods of high humidity. He said the crescent impressions that
artificial spikes make in soft greens are just as bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think they're any more comfortable,''
Calcavecchia said. ``I don't like hitting fairway bunker shots in
them. I don't even really like hitting greenside bunker shots in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia draws a sharp distinction between a tour pro
playing in non-metal spikes and a country club making them
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably better for most clubs, because the greens
will stay smoother,'' he said. ``Those old (people) can't walk in
spikes anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golf Club of Georgia, which hosts the Senior PGA Tour
Nationwide Championship next month, estimates that non-metal spikes
can save as much as $100,000 a year just through decreased damage
to greens, indoor carpets, asphalt areas, steps, wooden trim and
golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Country Club assistant superintendent Mark Douglas said
the non-metal policy the club adopted two years ago means, ``that
at the end of the day you've still got a smooth surface to putt
on.'' But he said members sometimes are duped into believing
non-metal spikes won't scrape the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives members a false sense of, `Hey, I can shimmy-shake if
I miss a putt now,' and they get a little sloppy,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   One ACC member is allowed to wear metal spikes for medical
reasons. ``And you can tell by the greens when that member plays,''
Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Many tour players, including Nelson, started wearing non-metal
spikes because their home courses demanded it, and now they wear
them all the time, for comfort and convenience. Now, hardly anyone
on the Senior Tour wears metal. Lee Trevino, in fact, once
suggested that players wearing non-metal spikes be allowed to tap
down spike marks, thereby rewarding them for not adding to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I kind of saw what they did for the greens, it was
really just a matter of finding the right ones,'' said Nelson, who
wears the ``spider'' spikes with cleats that flare to add traction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first ones they came out with were probably more dangerous
than they were helpful,'' Nelson said, ``but the ones they make now
probably give you better footing than steel spikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are players who make particularly large swing
turns, including Tiger Woods, who usually stick with the
traditional metal spikes to remain planted. Atlanta's Stewart Cink,
for example, only uses non-metal when practicing at home at either
East Lake or Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried pretty much all of them, and I slip,'' Cink said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, who practices in non-metal spikes because of
requirements at courses near his Phoenix home, wears metal spikes
on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slip quite a few times, especially when I really go after
(the ball),'' Mickelson said. ``I think that they're a real
positive for the game, but I don't want to risk a shot or a
tournament or even dollar amounts on that possibility. I would just
rather go with something that I have more confidence in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think that tour players don't typically have a problem
with spike marks, in that we tend to walk a little more conducive
to not creating spike marks. We don't drag our feet. I'm not saying
a lot of people do, but a lot of first-time players forget that
they actually have spikes on and get a little sloppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Non-metal spikes have improved greens, ``under all conditions
except soft greens,'' Mickelson said. ``And then I think they're
every bit as bad or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, who started wearing non-metal last year, said his
non-metal shoes feel so comfortable ``that I could go dancing in
these things.'' He plans to take metal and non-metal to Augusta,
``because that grass is cut really tight.''
</P>
<P>
   While the pros have that choice, amateur golfers have been left
out in the cold. Non-metal policies have been adopted at an
estimated 3,000 courses.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson has a short answer when asked if the PGA Tour will
ever mandate a change to non-metal spikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Why would we make a rule that guys can't wear
metal spikes? It's our tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
