<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-COD-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-COD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe 
 for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success.  
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Hawthorne Lane Cod Dresses Up for Dinner  
   
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  At Hawthorne Lane, David and Anne Gingrass combine
Eastern and Western flavors on the same menu. You can get a
Gorgonzola pizza with toasted walnuts and balsamic onions in the
bar, for example, or a crispy duck spring roll in the main dining
room.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signature dishes include Chinese-style roast duck with green
onion buns, house-smoked salmon and an impressive seafood platter
of spot prawns, lobster, crab, mussels, cockles and clams.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the few Western restaurants to feature a fish
tank for live prawns, which are used in many dishes, including
steamed with curried noodle salad in a chile soy broth.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite dish, however, is the rich, velvety-textured
Miso-Glazed Black Cod. The fish marinates overnight, which imparts
a distinctive flavor. Then it's simply broiled, emerging from the
oven with a caramelized top and just a hint of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   It can be served on its own or with the accompanying sesame
spinach rolls, flavored with lime-soy vinaigrette. It's an
innovative dish you won't find anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingrasses met when they were students at the Culinary
Institute of America in upstate New York. In the early 1980s, they
moved to California and both wound up at Spago, where Anne was the
chef and David was kitchen manager.
</P>
<P>
   They married in 1985 and were tapped by Wolfgang Puck to open
Postrio, his first restaurant outside Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The duo quickly shot to the top rank of San Francisco chefs and,
after working at Postrio more than five years, left to open their
own restaurant, Hawthorne Lane, in 1995. It's one of the most
popular and impressive restaurants in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The loftlike building features an expansive interior with
refined finishing elements, including a polished elliptical bar,
beautiful table settings and splashy modern artwork on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Hawthorne Lane, 22 Hawthorne St. (off Howard Street, between &LR; 
 &LR; Second and Third streets), San Francisco; (415) 777-9779. Open &LR; 
 &LR; for lunch weekdays, dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE SECRET
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Keep the fish moist.  &LR; Black cod is a rich, silky-textured fish that
can lose much of its charm when overcooked. The trick is to get a
deep mahogany color without drying out the fish.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingrasses solved the problem by using a bit of sugar in the
sauce. It's the same technique that is used to give Chinese-style
duck its rich color. The delicate fish browns, yet the fish remains
moist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HAWTHORNE LANE'S MISO GLAZED BLACK COD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons warm water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup yellow miso paste (2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mirin (sweet rice wine)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sake
</P>
<P>
   4 black cod fillets (about 3 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the marinade:  &LR; Combine the water and sugar in a small
pan and bring to a boil. Remove from heat and let cool to room
temperature. Stir in the miso paste, mirin and sake.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cod fillets in a small glass container that will hold
them comfortably. Pour the marinade over the fish and turn the
fillets to coat both sides with the marinade. Cover and refrigerate
for at least 4 hours and up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Place the marinated cod on a baking sheet or pan and broil (high
heat) for 5 to 7 minutes, turning once so both sides are lightly
brown and the fish is just cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 70 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 1 g fat (0 g saturated), 37 mg cholesterol, 46 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SESAME SPINACH ROLLS WITH SOY-LIME VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; At Hawthorne Lane, these are served with the Glazed Black
Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 large savoy cabbage leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 cups loosely packed spinach leaves, washed and spun dry
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons + plus 1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame seeds, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Vinaigrette &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice (about 2 limes)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 small garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the spinach rolls:  &LR; Blanch the cabbage leaves in
boiling salted water until limp. Drain. Spread each leaf
ribbed-side up on a cutting board and, using a sharp knife, trim
the thickest part of the center rib flat with the leaf. Blot the
leaves dry and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Select 20 of the best looking spinach leaves (they should be
about the same size) and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the oil in a large saucepan over
medium-high heat. When the oil is hot, add the garlic and shallots;
cook just long enough to release the aroma. Add the remaining
spinach and stir quickly to coat the leaves. Cook until the spinach
becomes completely limp. Season with salt and pepper. Remove
spinach and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Press all the liquid from the spinach; divide in half and roll
each half into a 1-inch-diameter cylinder. Wrap tightly in the
blanched cabbage leaves. Rub the leaves lightly with the remaining
1 teaspoon oil, then roll in sesame seeds to coat.
</P>
<P>
   If made ahead, wrap the rolls in plastic wrap until ready to
serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the vinaigrette:  &LR; Combine the soy sauce, lime juice,
vinegar, shallot and garlic in a small bowl; season with salt and
pepper. Stir to mix. Slowly add the sesame and peanut oils,
whisking to form an emulsion. Taste and adjust salt and pepper as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Toss the reserved spinach leaves in a small
amount of vinaigrette and arrange 5 leaves along the rim of each
serving plate. Cut each spinach roll into 6 slices; arrange 3
pieces on each plate. If serving with the Black Cod, place a fillet
in the center of each place. Serve with the remaining dressing,
either in a small pitcher or in individual dipping bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; stats  &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 8 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 28 g fat (4 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 576 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
