A9931 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICK-HAM-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICK-HAM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with 
 enough leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.  
   
   
 QUICK COOK: Pork Takes the Cure to Become Ham  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Have you ever wondered why it's so hard to find a
fresh leg of pork at the meat counter? That's because most of them
are tagged for curing, to produce hams.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's Quick Cook is built on a fully cooked, smoked ham. A
meat that is popular at Easter, ham is easy to make, easy to store
and easy to incorporate into numerous dishes throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Hams fall into two broad categories: Wet-cured, in which the
meat is soaked in or injected with brine; and dry-cured, in which a
salt-spice mixture is rubbed onto the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Country hams, including the renowned Smithfield ham from
Smithfield County, Va., are examples of a dry-cured ham. Country
hams need soaking before they are ready to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Other dry-cured hams include Italy's prosciutto and Spain's
glorious jamon serrano.
</P>
<P>
   Corn cob-smoked hams, ``spiral-cut'' hams and Polish hams are
examples of wet-cured hams. They often are smoked, and are sold
fully cooked. Home cooks can add additional flavor to these hams _
for instance, with a brown-sugar glaze, with pineapple and clove or
with an apricot glaze _ but the meat really requires only
reheating.
</P>
<P>
   A fully cooked, smoked ham is almost effortless to prepare even
though it takes a few hours in the oven because of its size. As in
today's Master Recipe, low heat works best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MASTER RECIPE: SMOKED HAM WITH BOURBON GLAZE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The ham is already cooked, so bake it only until it is heated
through.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 smoked, fully cooked ham, 10 to 12 pounds
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup bourbon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the rind from the fat side of the ham by creating a slit
at one corner with a knife and pulling the rind off with your
fingers. Score the fat with the knife to create a cross-hatch
pattern. Place the ham and any gelee from the wrapping in a
roasting pan. Bake for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whisk together the bourbon, sugar and allspice in a
bowl until the sugar is melted.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes of roasting, brush the ham with the bourbon
glaze. Continue roasting the ham for 21/2 to 3 hours, brushing with
glaze every 30 minutes or so, until an instant-read thermometer
inserted in several spots (away from the bone) registers 140
degrees. If you run out of glaze, you may brush the ham with the
pan juices. If the pan juices threaten to burn, stir in about 1/2
cup water.
</P>
<P>
   When the ham is heated, transfer it to a carving board. Place
the roasting pan over two burners on high heat. Heat the pan
juices, adding 1/2 cup water and scraping up all the bits that
cling to the bottom of the pan. Strain the juices, degrease and
serve with the ham. There should be about 3/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thinly carve 24 to 32 slices of ham; serve with the pan juices.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, cover and refrigerate the remaining ham for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 225 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 7 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 6 g fat (2 g saturated), 62 mg cholesterol, 1,508 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: LINGUINE IN CREAM SAUCE WITH HAM &AMP; PEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, halved and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups finely diced ham (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups frozen baby peas, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large saute pan over high heat. Add the onion
and saute, stirring frequently, for 3 minutes. Add the ham; reduce
heat to medium-high and saute, stirring frequently, until the onion
and ham are lightly caramelized, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken broth and boil for 1 minute. Add the cream and
boil for 2 minutes. Add the peas, season generously with pepper,
toss thoroughly and boil for another minute.
</P>
<P>
   Boil the linguine in a large pot of liberally salted water until
the pasta is al dente; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over the pasta, toss well and serve with
Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 725 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 76 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 33 g fat (18 g saturated), 129 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 774
mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: LENTIL SOUP WITH HAM &AMP; SQUASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon good quality curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 medium-small yellow squash, cut into 3/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced ham (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cans (19 ounces each) lentil soup (I used Progresso)
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the yogurt, curry powder and salt. Refrigerate
until ready to serve the soup.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a medium-size heavy saucepan over medium-high
heat. Add the squash, ham and onion and saute, stirring frequently,
until the squash is soft, 10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the lentil soup. Bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce
heat to medium and simmer, covered, for 3 minutes. Season with
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serve topped with a dollop of the yogurt mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 405 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 44 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (3 g saturated), 46 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 2,217
mg sodium, 11 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MORE IDEAS FOR LEFTOVERS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A 10- to 12-pound baked ham will yield plenty of leftovers for
use throughout the week. Here are only a few ideas:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ham and Collards: &LR;  Saute enough chopped onion and diced ham for
4 people in a little oil until the ham and onions are caramelized.
Deglaze the pan with a cup of water and boil for 2 minutes. Add a
10-ounce package of frozen, defrosted collard greens. Simmer for 5
minutes. Season with salt, if necessary, and hot sauce to taste.
Mixture should be soupy. Serve over rice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ham Steaks with Stewed Fruits: &LR;  Chop some dried apricots,
pears, dates and pineapple. Combine them in a small pan with water
to barely cover, a 2-inch piece of split vanilla bean, a small
piece of cinnamon stick and sugar to taste. Simmer until the liquid
is reduced by half. Add a little bourbon and simmer until the
alcohol burns off. Let stand, covered, until mixture is lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   Cut steaks from the leftover baked ham _ make them about
3/4-inch thick. Saute in a large pan, turning once, until they are
heated through. Serve topped with a spoonful of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ham and Bliss Frittata: &LR;  Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Boil red
Bliss potatoes in liberally salted water until they are tender.
Slice about 1/4-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Dice some baked ham, onions and a little green pepper. Saute
with the potatoes in olive oil until the vegetables are limp and
the potatoes begin to brown. Season well with salt and pepper.
Spread the mixture evenly in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly beat together 10 eggs, 1/4 cup water and a pinch of
salt. Pour the eggs over the vegetables. Cook over medium heat,
lifting the sides of the frittata periodically to allow the
uncooked egg to run underneath, until the eggs are almost set.
Sprinkle 1/2 cup coarsely grated Swiss cheese over the top. Finish
the frittata in the oven until the eggs are set and the cheese is
melted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ham Bone Soups: &LR;  When most of the meat has been taken from the
ham bone, simmer the bone and whatever ham bits remain in water to
cover for an hour. Add diced carrots, onions and a little diced
celery. Continue to simmer until the broth has a rich ham flavor.
Strain the broth.
</P>
<P>
   Ham is a good match with almost any bean or legume, so use the
broth as the basis for ham and black bean soup; ham and white bean
soup with sage; split pea soup; lentil, sauteed cabbage and ham
soup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ham and Cheese Bread Pudding: &LR;  Dice some baked ham and onions;
saute until the onion is wilted. Cool and combine with a generous
amount of coarsely grated provolone cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Cube some day-old French or Italian bread; combine the bread
with the ham mixture. Spread the bread mixture in a buttered baking
pan.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together eggs, half-and-half, salt and pepper. Pour over
the bread, submerging the bread in the custard so it absorbs the
liquid. Let stand for 5 minutes. After standing, there should be
enough custard to just skim the top of the bread.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 350-degree oven until the custard is set and the top
is browned, about 1 hour. Cool briefly on a rack before cutting and
serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Maria Cianci &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
