r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOURCE-CHEES-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-CHEES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers, 
 anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary 
 wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field 
 to forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients 
 stocking our larders. As a bonus, Georgeanne Brennan will offer 
 tips for using the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.  
   
   
   
 AT THE SOURCE: Creme de la Creamery _ Marin Maker Specializes in 
 Delicate Fresh Cheeses  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 POINT REYES STATION, Calif. _  Remember the diet plate of the '70s?
Hamburger patty, iceberg lettuce, tomato slices and a scoop of
cottage cheese? And in midcentury, cottage cheese and canned fruit
salad?
 &HT;    ``Cottage cheese was popularized in Great Britain and America _
and then it went out of fashion,'' Sue Conley says. After a moment,
the former chef/partner of Bette's Oceanview Diner in Berkeley, who
is co-owner with Peggy Smith of Tomales Bay Foods, adds with a
chuckle, ``It's my favorite.''
 &HT;    It also has become the favorite of customers who have
rediscovered this simple fresh cheese from Tomales Bay's Cowgirl
Creamery, which Conley runs.
 &HT;    She makes all cheeses from organic milk shipped from the Straus
Family Creamery in Marshall 10 miles to the north, not in tanker
trucks but in old-fashioned 10-gallon stainless-steel cans.
 &HT;    Identified as clabbered cottage cheese, it is made in small
batches from cooked curds with buttermilk cultures, resulting in a
fresh, slightly tangy taste and creamy texture that are a far cry
from standard grocery-store cottage cheese.
 &HT;    Similar but a little drier is nonfat quark, a central and
northern European cheese made from uncooked curds with yogurt and
buttermilk cultures. Bill Straus remembers it from his German
childhood as ``a thick, tart spread ... smeared on toast in the
morning, plopped on baked potatoes in the evening and scooped onto
fresh fruit for dessert.''
 &HT;    Cowgirl labels its product Ellen's Nonfat Quark, named for Bill
Straus' wife, who bakes cheesecakes for Tomales Bay Foods most
weekends, using a mixture of quark and creme fraiche.
 &HT;    Cowgirl's creme fraiche has the rich and buttery, slightly nutty
quality that distinguishes this traditional soured cream in France.
 &HT;    The other French-inspired cheese, fromage blanc (literally
``white cheese''), is a cousin of American cream cheese. Made from
uncooked curds with buttermilk cultures, vegetable rennet and a
little creme fraiche, this has found its way onto the menus of many
Bay Area restaurants. Because it is made from whole milk rather
than cream, it has less fat than mass-produced cream cheese _ a
fact you wouldn't guess from its rich taste.
 &HT;    A favorite with supply-shopping picnickers is Olema Valley
Rounds. These cute little cheeses are fromage blanc coated with
organically grown parsley, tarragon and thyme, plus a little
pepper. When a wedge is cut from a cheese, a layer of herbs is
revealed like a bright green ring.
 &HT;    Just the other week, Conley reintroduced mozzarella, which she
stopped making in the fall: ``Can't have tomato season without
mozzarella,'' she says, laughing.
 &HT;    Cowgirl Creamery operates in the front of the charming, barnlike
Tomales Bay Foods store in Point Reyes Station. Depending on the
time of day, visitors can watch Conley at work through big windows.
A deli, presided over by Conley's business partner, former Cafe at
Chez Panisse chef Smith, is toward the back of the long space, near
a wine shop and shelves with packaged specialty organic foods and
bread from next-door neighbor Bay Village Bakery.
 &HT;    Almost as an afterthought, Conley points to a freezer chest with
half pints of house-made ice cream _ chocolate, blood orange and an
ethereal vanilla the day of our visit.
 &HT;    The use of top-notch organic ingredients and the labor-intensive
hand production methods mean that Cowgirl's offerings cost more
than mass-produced dairy products _ the ice creams are $2.75 each;
cottage cheese retails for $6 to $7 a pound _ but quality is of the
old-fashioned kind that would win the approval of the dairy
ranchers who pioneered west Marin in the 1800s.
 &HT;      Cowgirl Creamery products are sold at Tomales Bay Foods, 80 
 Fourth St., Point Reyes Station. Open 11 a.m.-6 p.m. 
 Wednesday-Sunday. Some cheeses are available at Ferry Plaza 
 Farmers' Market in San Francisco and stores including Whole 
 Foods branches throughout the Bay Area, Rainbow Grocery in San 
 Francisco and the Pasta Shop in Berkeley and Oakland. For 
 mail-order and more information, call (415) 663-9335. 
 &HT;     
 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 
 A SHORT HISTORY OF CHEESE  
 
Fresh soft cheeses are probably the world's oldest: Some
prehistoric householder found a bowl of milk that had gone sour. It
didn't smell bad; in fact, it smelled rather pleasant. So somehow,
she got the idea to drain off the watery stuff, separating curds
from whey. &HT;    Add cheese to the human food chain.
 &HT;    Today, some form of soured milk product can be found in
practically all societies that raise milk-producing animals, from
yogurt to cottage cheese, quark and ricotta; sour cream and its
sophisticated cousin, creme fraiche to plain old clabbered milk or
cream.
 &HT;    So Cowgirl Creamery, the dairy branch of Tomales Bay Foods in
Point Reyes Station, Calif., builds on a long tradition. However,
with its all-organic commitment, it actually goes back in history,
creating soft cheeses as they were made before mass production
methods introduced animal rennet, stabilizers and all manner of
additives.
 &HT;    Sue Conley, co-owner with Peggy Smith of the 2-year-old west
Marin store, is a chef who became so fascinated with cheese making
that she took a course on the subject at Washington State
University.
 &HT;    Conley likes to make these dairy products _ about 300 pounds a
week _ and she also loves to eat them. Her idea of a perfect
breakfast is cottage cheese, a piece of toasted hearty bread and a
drizzle of honey. She says cottage cheese and quark are agreeable
companions to any kind of fresh fruit; fresh mozzarella has great
affinity for tomatoes; fromage blanc is equally suited to fruit or
fresh vegetables _ think cucumbers and radishes.
 &HT;    Quark, or fromage blanc, is the main ingredient of Liptauer, a
Hungarian/German spread that also contains creme fraiche (or sour
cream), sauteed onions, a stronger-flavored cheese (Camembert or
Gruyere), salt, pepper and paprika.
 &HT;    In addition, many fresh cheeses take to hot dishes. Quark is a
standard European companion to baked or boiled potatoes and also
works well as an addition to enchilada or taco fillings. Conley
loves the German-Austrian combination of buttered wide noodles with
cottage cheese, often accompanied by stewed dried fruit. In some
Eastern European kitchens, the noodle-cottage cheese combination is
enhanced with poppy seeds lightly cooked in browned butter.
 &HT;    At Bette's Oceanview Diner in Berkeley, where Conley was a chef/
partner for many years, cottage cheese pancakes are a favorite. In
West Marin, Ellen Straus of the Straus Family Dairy, which provides
Cowgirl with organic milk, bakes a European-style cheesecake for
Tomales Bay Foods on weekends. She started with quark and a little
creme fraiche, ``but now she's using a 50-50 mixture,'' Conley says
with a laugh. ``It's fabulous.''
 &HT;     
_ Karola Saekel &HT;     
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN: Mix It Up  
 
 By Georgeanne Brennan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Fresh cheeses, such as quark, cottage cheese and fromage blanc, can
be mixed with savory ingredients, such as herbs, salt and pepper,
and vegetables. They also may be combined with sweets.
<P>
   &UR; Quark and Sour Cherries.  &LR; Toast a piece of rye bread, then
spread it with quark and top with sour cherry or other cherry jam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Savory Cottage Cheese.  &LR; Mix cottage cheese with salt, pepper,
chopped parsley or basil, minced cucumber and a little red chile
powder. Serve on a leaf of butterhead lettuce topped with several
tomato slices, or fill a scooped-out tomato with the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fromage Blanc With Honey.  &LR; Thin fromage blanc with a little
milk or cream to an easily spoonable consistency. Drizzle over it a
distinctively flavored honey, such as lavender or eucalyptus, and
serve for breakfast or dessert with thin slices of walnut bread.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roasted Peppers Stuffed with Garlicky Fromage Blanc.  &LR; Drizzle
several heads of garlic with olive oil; sprinkle with salt, pepper
and fresh thyme, and roast at 275 degrees until tender, about 45
minutes to an hour. Remove the soft interiors of the cloves. Mash
together the soft garlic with some fromage blanc, fresh thyme, salt
and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Roast a red bell pepper or two. Remove the skin, slit in half
lengthwise and remove the seeds. Spread each half with a layer of
the fromage blanc mixture. Broil the pepper halves for a few
moments, just to warm the cheese through. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fresh Mozzarella, Chicken and Bread Salad.  &LR; Dust small pieces
of boneless, skinless chicken with a seasoned breadcrumb mixture,
then fry in vegetable oil. Drain, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely chop several tomatoes; put in a bowl with fruity
extra-virgin olive oil, chopped fresh basil, minced garlic and a
little salt and pepper. Mix well. Add some freshly made
garlic-rubbed croutons and the cooked chicken; toss. Add cubed
fresh mozzarella, and turn gently. Add more olive oil if desired.
Garnish with basil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo
County, Calif., is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food and
Flavors of Haute Provence.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
