   The New York Times is planning a five-page package of stories
and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Its carefully laid bombing plans still
unsuccessful in forcing Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
stop his attacks against ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo, the
NATO alliance wrestled Tuesday with the question, what next? By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Brussels) _ Stung by the relentless Serbs assault
in Kosovo, the United States urged the NATO alliance today to
expand its list of targets. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Listening to the stories of
the refugees: In the darkness, the little villages in the rolling
hills and river valleys around the Kosovo city of Dakovica emptied
out this morning, rushing _ literally, for their lives _ to beat
the 5 A.M. deadline set by Serbian forces. Yesterday, even as some
60,000 ethnic Albanians streamed into this border town, mostly from
around a main highway to the northeast, Serb forces were
methodically going from village to village in an entirely different
area to the northwest, the Has District, telling the villagers they
must leave or they would be killed in the morning. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV (Dateline to kum) _ Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic is ready for negotiations if NATO stops its air strikes,
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said here Tuesday. But
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder rejected the proposals as
unacceptable for a Kosovo peace deal. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EXODUS (Washington) _ As nearly 10,000 refugees poured
out of Kosovo today, NATO officials said that about a third of the
population had fled either into neighboring countries or into the
countryside. The overall exodus, one of the worst since World War
II, has brought the seeds of destablization to Albania and
Macedonia, a crisis the allies had said their bombing campaign
sought to avert. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
