 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Brown Sugar From Cane Draws Sweet Critiques  
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  We know that baking with cane or beet sugar yields
different results, but can you see and taste differences in the
sugar itself?
<TEXT>
<P>
   We put our tasting panelists to the test, giving them samples of
each of five brown sugars _ two cane, two beet and one that
alternates between cane and beet based on availability. The panel
also tasted each sugar incorporated into a creme anglaise made
without vanilla so the flavor of the sugar would dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists admitted that all but one of the sugars looked and
tasted very similar, but the remaining panelists found dramatic
differences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C&AMP;H Pure Cane Sugar Golden Brown &LR;   &UR; Sugar &LR;  (2-pound plastic bag,
$1.39 at many supermarkets) took top honors. One panelist described
the flavor as deep and rich with a pleasant molasses taste. All
would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Safeway Light Brown Sugar &LR;  (2-pound
plastic bag, $1.19), cane sugar made by C&AMP;H, according to Debra
Lambert, public relations manager for Safeway. One panelist
complained that it was a bit dry; another thought it was pale in
color. Others liked the granular texture and pleasant caramel
flavor. Four would buy it; one might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to &UR; Lucky Golden Brown Sugar &LR;  (2-pound plastic
bag, $1.39). This sugar is sometimes made from cane and other times
from beets, according to Judie Decker, spokeswoman for Lucky
Stores. We do not know which was used for the sugar our panel
tasted. One panelist thought it lacked flavor, but two others
particularly liked the mildness. One also liked the way the
granules separated. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were divided on  &UR; Springfield Light Brown Sugar &LR; 
(1-pound box, $1.19 at Andronico's), which is made from beets. Two
thought it tasted too mild, and another detected a ``stale
finish.'' Two would buy it, two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Best Yet Light Brown Sugar &LR;  (1-pound box,
89 cents at Piazza Fine Foods in San Mateo), also made from beets.
Even the panelists who noticed little difference between the other
sugars didn't care for this sugar; they thought it had an
artificial quality. One panelist noticed the caramel color could be
rubbed off with his fingers. One would buy it, one might buy it,
and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
