 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses 
 more than a half-century old. 
 &HT;       
   
 BAY AREA CLASSICS:  
 Palo Alto Grill Keeps Shaking and Rolling  
   
 By Tilde Herrera  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PALO ALTO, Calif.  &LR; _ A word to the wise: Don't take any wooden
nickels unless they were issued by the Peninsula Fountain and
Grill. These babies will get you a thick, ambrosial milkshake, the
same sort of shake that has been thrilling customers for seven
decades.
<P>
   Customers like 86-year-old Orman McGill, who as a 10-year-old
attended the grill's grand opening in 1923. He's stopped in for a
milkshake nearly every day for 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-blended milkshake is Peninsula Fountain's claim to
fame. Servers in the 1940s-style eatery even wear kitschy
customized T-shirts alluding to it (``I'm All Shook Up,'' ``Still
Shakin''). And the fountain itself takes the soda fountain decor to
the max _ checkered floor tiles, &UR;  &LR; Formica tables and oldies music
played on a 1957 Seeburg jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   This Palo Alto landmark at the corner of Hamilton and Emerson
streets has been peddling ice cream and its famous milkshake since
it wasopened by Howard Cobb and Axel Raven, who operated it as a
counter-service fountain, then known as the Peninsula Fountain and
Creamery. In 1936, cold sandwiches and cold breakfast dishes were
added to the menu, and in the 1960s, omelets and other hot
breakfast dishes joined the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The fountain was sold in 1987 to Diane Naylor, &UR;  &LR; a local hair
salon owner who, ironically, introduced the fountain to Rob Fisher,
the present owner. Naylor told him about the business during a
haircut, they became friends, and he bought the fountain from her a
year later. He changed the name to the Peninsula Fountain and Grill
so it wouldn't be confused with the Peninsula Creamery, which
operates today as an ice cream distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher credits the celebrated milkshake for ``introducing'' him
to his wife, Jan. After Fisher purchased the restaurant, she became
a fan of the milkshakes and a fountain regular. ``The rest is
history,'' Fisher says sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, Fisher has made several changes, such as renovating
the building and introducing table service. He introduced a dinner
menu featuring comfort food like Yankee pot roast, updated
favorites like a ``salad'' version of Southern fried chicken and
hash brown pie (a delightful potato, bacon, tomato and cheese
concoction, served with two eggs), and homemade pies, buns and
rolls. Beef comes from quality producer Niman Ranch _ and often at
prices much lower than the same cuts served at fancier restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Families, who flocked to the grill after it became a non-smoking
restaurant in 1989, before the law required, still make up the bulk
of the clientele. Stanford University students, Palo Alto residents
and downtown business people are also frequent customers.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher marvels at the feeling of ``public ownership'' expressed
by the community. &UR;  &LR; ``We have such a great clientele, the people of
Palo Alto have been so supportive,'' he says. ``I've heard people
describe this place as the `center of the universe,' a melting pot
where people of all walks of life can converge.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to keep intact the long-lived motto _ ``Great Food,
Great Shakes, Reasonable Prices'' _ because it's led to success for
nearly a century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
