<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORILLA-WARFARE-ART-2     03-30 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORILLA-WARFARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN WARFARE THREATENS RARE MOUNTAIN GORILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BWINDI IMPENETRABLE FOREST, Uganda _ The wound on the old male's
silver back, inflicted in a fight with another group of gorillas,
looked like it was healing. He studied his fingertips. Two of the
little ones raced up and down a tree, stripping loose a shower of
leaves that fell to the jungle floor.
</P>
<P>
   This band of 16 mountain gorillas _ among the last 620 alive in
the wild _ seemed healthy. But their future is far from guaranteed
since the war in the Great Lakes region of East Africa spread to
their neighborhood here in early March and took its latest victims:
a game warden and eight foreign tourists, including two Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists and people living around the park, still
stunned by the killings, are also trying to determine what it will
mean for this place, the last corner on Earth where scientists and
tourists could safely see mountain gorillas in the wild. In the
last several years, a complex relationship had evolved that made
local people's survival largely dependent on the money the gorillas
attract.
</P>
<P>
   The gorillas' survival is in turn largely dependent on the good
will of local people who have, at times reluctantly, agreed not to
cut trees or clear land for farming, in exchange for a share of
that money.
</P>
<P>
   If tourists stop coming, will local people stop helping to
preserve the gorillas' habitat? And will the gorillas' numbers thus
dwindle even further toward extinction?
</P>
<P>
   There are already hints of the answer. Ignatius Byamugyisha, 30,
who was beaten and held at gunpoint when Hutu rebels attacked the
park, said he was not about to put the gorillas' welfare above his
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are important when they bring in tourists,'' said
Byamugyisha, who watched the attackers loot and swig beer and soda
from his tourist shop just outside the park's gates. ``If not, they
are not. If the tourists don't come, we will try our luck in the
forest. Before this, we were good timber cutters.''
</P>
<P>
   The countries of the African Great Lakes _ Uganda, Rwanda,
Burundi and Congo _ have been at war in various ways since the
early 1990s. This region holds some of the world's most precious
forests, with rare plants and animals, but it has also seen some of
the worst human tragedies in recent times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, in Rwanda, more than half a million Tutsi and moderate
Hutu were killed in 100 days by Hutu extremists. Two rebellions
have sprung up in eastern Congo, most recently last August. It was
Hutu who fled Rwanda after the 1994 massacres, now loyal to Congo's
president, who attacked the tourists here March 1, saying they
wanted to punish Uganda for aiding Congolese rebels, and the United
States and Britain for being allies with Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on tourism, which the rebels aimed to cripple, was
immediate: Though Uganda quickly beefed up security, both the
United States and Britain issued strong travel advisories against
visiting. Abercrombie &AMP; Kent, one of the largest tour companies in
Uganda, reported that three-quarters of its 1999 bookings had been
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest are not looking too confident at all,'' said Patrick
Shah, general manager for Abercrombie &AMP; Kent Uganda, whose camp at
Bwindi was one of three attacked that night.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on conservation will probably be immediate as well.
Gorilla tourism subsidizes all 11 of the national parks in Uganda,
providing 70 percent of the revenue to the fledgling national park
system.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on previously peaceful Bwindi underscored how badly
conflict has ravaged wild areas. Refugees have settled in
two-thirds of Akagera, the largest park in Rwanda, conservationists
say. The forests on the Congo side of Bwindi and its smaller sister
park to the south, Mgahinga National Park, are slowly losing their
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Wabbes Candotti, a program officer for the World Wildlife
Fund in East Africa, compared the Great Lakes' natural areas to
``someone half sinking but still breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are areas on the brink of being spoiled and damaged
irreversibly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several mountain gorillas have also been killed in Rwanda and
Congo, one possibly by a land mine and several others caught in
crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   Worry about the gorillas prompted Uganda, along with many
foreign governments and international aid groups, to develop a
program over the last decade to give residents a stake in the
animals' well-being. About 300 gorillas are in Bwindi and another
320 in the forests around the Virunga volcanoes, a spectacular
range that runs through Uganda, Rwanda and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy sell. Local people barely scraping by had
been accustomed to farming in the forests, fishing, cutting timber,
rooting for mushrooms and cutting bark for medicine to kill
intestinal worms. Farmers were evicted from the park. In heated
meetings, many asked: Are gorillas more important than people?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not happy,'' said Gabriel Muhigirwa, a 60-year-old
farmer outside Kisoro, near Mgahinga National Park. ``We became
poorer because we lost our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Muhigirwa has been elected to supervise one of 33 spigots
that bring clean water from inside Mgahinga to 40,000 people
outside the park. The water system was one of many projects aimed
at using money from the parks and donations from international
groups to improve local people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   In projects coordinated by CARE International, schools, roads
and health clinics have gone up. At Bwindi, local people earn money
as porters and drivers for tourists tracking gorillas, sell
tourists food and stage traditional dances. In Kisoro, which was
empty when gorilla tourism began here six years ago, there is a new
airstrip and regular flights from Kampala, a new gas station, a row
of shops and even a satellite dish on one of the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Mutebi, a biologist and local project manager for CARE,
said that before the attack, people around Bwindi and Mgahinga had
begun to see tangible benefits of tourism.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``They had seen conservation as something that is contributing
to their welfare,'' Mutebi said. ``Now tourism stops, and the money
stops. At this time we can't tell what is going to be the reaction
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bakinahe, a 40-year-old farmer standing on a slope that
leads up to Mgahinga park, summed up the ambivalence: ``It is good
to have gorillas; I would like to have even more.'' But, he added,
``if I were allowed, I would go back to farm'' in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Kagoda, permanent secretary for the Ministry of Tourism,
Trade and Industry, said Uganda is committed to preserving the
forest and protecting the gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an international obligation to insure the safety and
security of these animals,'' he said. ``And precisely because of
that, we have decided that we will do whatever it takes to conserve
this species, even if we do not receive a single visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that may be difficult in a poor country.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack, Uganda suspended tourism for a month, in
respect for the dead and to improve security. Tourism is scheduled
to begin again on April 1, though it is far from clear how many
visitors will come.
</P>
<P>
   In the month since the killings, the guides who track the
gorillas with the tourists have been following animals that have
slowly become accustomed to the presence of humans, to make sure
they have not been harmed. On a recent day five trackers, protected
by two Ugandan soldiers with machine guns, spent nearly five hours
hiking the steep slopes of Bwindi, hacking through the bush with
honed machetes, until they found one of the groups of gorillas in a
dark and chilly patch of the forest buzzing with millions of flies.
</P>
<P>
   The old male, Riuhondeza, was lazing on his back, with his legs
crossed genteelly. One of his sons, an 8-year-old named Madaraka,
rushed playfully close to the trackers, then beat his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in good shape,'' said one of the guides, Steven
Migyisha, 34. ``They have not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how long can that last?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could declare them _ what is it? _ war-free zones,''
Stephen Asuma, the warden in charge of tourism at Bwindi, said
before his voice trailed off. ``It is the only dream we can have.
It is very disheartening to see species that are almost extinct
further threatened by wars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
