<P>
   The Times will choose from the following Kosovo-related stories:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Brussels, Belgium) _ Stung by the relentless Serbs
assault in Kosovo, the United States urges the NATO alliance to
expand its list of targets. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Listening to the stories of
the refugees: In the darkness, the little villages in the rolling
hills and river valleys around the Kosovo city of Dakovica emptied
out this morning, rushing _ literally, for their lives _ to beat
the 5 a.m. deadline set by Serbian forces. Even as some 60,000
ethnic Albanians streamed into this border town, mostly from around
a main highway to the northeast, Serb forces were methodically
going from village to village in an entirely different area to the
northwest, the Has District, telling the villagers they must leave
or they would be killed in the morning. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With New York Times photos of refugees in Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EXODUS (Washington) _ As nearly 10,000 refugees pour out
of Kosovo, NATO officials say that about a third of the population
has fled either into neighboring countries or into the countryside.
The overall exodus, one of the worst since world war II, has
brought the seeds of destablization to Albania and Macedonia, a
crisis the allies had said their bombing campaign sought to avert.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The government of
Macedonia says it is swamped and has to send some refugees back
into Kosovo. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-CHARITIES (Undated) _ As Americans become increasingly
comfortable shopping online, it's a pitch many succumb to: Buy an
Elmo toy or Stephen King novel through our Web sites, and part of
the purchase price will go to the charity of your choice. These Web
sites claim to have raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for
charitable groups, but once you buy Elmo online, what happens to
the few dollars you thought was speeding its way to a good cause?
While many charities are getting checks directly from these sites,
it is impossible to know in every case. It may not end up in the
charity's hands as fast as you imagined _ if at all. By Reed
Abelson.
</P>
