<SLUG> BC-NEWINDUSTRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech companies look to do business with learning institutions
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes said Tuesday that Georgia will spend
$1.7 million to quickly double the number of software developers
graduating from Georgia Tech and aid high-tech companies struggling
to find enough workers.
</P>
<P>
   Three companies that pushed for a bigger pool of graduates say
the governor's decision bolsters their plans to expand in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree, an electronic payment processor, will spend $20
million to expand its Norcross headquarters and will hire 300 new
technology workers over the next five years, Chief Executive Pete
Kight said.
</P>
<P>
   Kight took part in the governor's announcement, along with the
CEO of Internet Security Systems and the general manager of Nortel
Networks, a Northern Telecom unit that has nearly 2,000
telecommunications employees in Alpharetta. The three companies
worked closely with the state and suggested what skills their
workers most need.
</P>
<P>
   Kight said without the additional funding and the help of
businesses ``there isn't any possibility that the educational
system by itself can keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Noonan, the chief executive of ISS, said he expects his
company, based near Perimeter Mall, to grow from 200 to 600 metro
Atlanta workers within two years _ if he can find enough high-end
workers here.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage in the high-tech labor pool is a national problem
and has pushed employers to intensify their search for employees.
</P>
<P>
   ISS opened research and development operations last year in
California, Britain and Japan in order to tap other labor pools.
But Noonan said, ``Our preference is to expand here.'' He wrote to
University System of Georgia Chancellor Stephen Portch a year ago
warning of shortages in the number of graduates his business
depends on.
</P>
<P>
   New funding announced by the governor will help grow Georgia's
technology business, Noonan said, but he said millions of dollars
more will be needed to come close to keeping pace with the demand
for graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is listening. ``We will invest whatever is
necessary to ensure we have high-tech graduates to fill the
high-tech jobs'' Georgia attracts, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditure Barnes announced Tuesday will allow Georgia Tech
to buy additional equipment and hire new faculty members, some of
whom have already recently joined the school. Some of the funding
began a month and a half ago. Georgia Tech president Wayne Clough
said that by the spring of 2001 the school will graduate 200
computer science students annually, double what it now produces.
The first additional graduates may include part-time students and
people who left school without completing their studies.
</P>
<P>
   Half the school's computer science graduates now leave the state
for jobs elsewhere. Georgia Tech officials say they hope to raise
the percentage of graduates who stay to 65 percent by spring of the
year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ISS, CheckFree and Nortel have committed to hire at least 40 of
Georgia Tech's computer science graduates each year and create 50
new coop positions for the school's students. The companies also
agreed to have their senior executives give lectures at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The funding will come from the existing budget of a
three-year-old program that allows the university system to break
out of slow-moving academic cultures so that it can quickly educate
people to meet specific needs of companies creating so-called
knowledge jobs. The program is shaped as a public
private-partnership to satisfy high demand for graduates in low
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Intellectual Capital Partnership Program, or ICAPP,
the program was the biggest carrot Georgia used in 1996 to convince
credit card processor Total Systems Services to remain in Columbus
and build a new $100 million headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prototyping how to quickly adapt and meet the needs of
quickly changing 21st century companies,'' said Annie Hunt Burriss,
an assistant vice chancellor of the University System and architect
of the ICAPP program.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's announcement is his second in three months that
involves major efforts to expand Georgia's pool of high-tech
workers. In January, the state unveiled the Yamacraw Mission, a
campaign to make Georgia a center for high-paying, fast-growing
microchip design firms for the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
