<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CIRCUS-REVIEW-ART-     03-30 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CIRCUS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE RINGS OF WOWS FOR ALL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an age when television shrinks the globe and
transports the world's wonders into the living room, the circus,
like grand opera and kabuki, may exist more as an embodiment of
cultural tradition and spectacle than as a source of novelty.
</P>
<P>
   But still, as proved by ``The Living Carousel,'' the 129th
presentation of the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus,
it remains a grand tradition and a lavish spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   This polished and glittering Feld Entertainment production, at
Madison Square Garden through April 11, is replete with top-of-the
line performers, including a few guaranteed to wow circusgoers
young and old who think they've seen everything.
</P>
<P>
   While a warring world waits for the lion to lie down with the
lamb, the cat and the bird coexist peacefully and acrobatically in
Svetlana Shemsheeva's menagerie, where a dove rides a Persian cat
that jumps through a hoop; a cat crosses a high wire on its front
paws, and doves and cats otherwise defy the probabilities of
friendship while extending the boundaries of amusement.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to remarkable feats on high wires, there is no
rival to the Cloud-Walking Carillos, who perform backward leaps and
backward somersaults and compound the customary perils by risking
life and limb over a cage filling with Bengal tigers.
</P>
<P>
   These days, while flashing an occasional fang, flailing a clawed
paw or emitting an ominous growl, the sleek tigers sit, roll over
and array themselves on the command of young Mark Oliver Gebel,
smoothly carrying on the family tradition under the watchful eye of
his father, Gunther Gebel-Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition continues, too, with graceful equestrian acts,
mischievous dogs, masses of teeterboarders, clowns in a (shaving)
cream pie fight, and the Wuhan Flyers, an aerial act from China
whose members ratchet up the complexity of their trapeze work till
it reaches the triple inverted pirouette.
</P>
<P>
   In the more modern vein of circus arts, there are the Urias,
spinning on motorcycles like angry bumblebees inside a latticed
globe, and Wilson Dominguez, trying to keep his balance 40 feet
over the ring on his spinning, gleaming Wheel of Wonder. And there
is plenty more.
</P>
<P>
   With three rings going most of the time, the circus' new
ringmaster, Johnathan Lee Iverson, keeps the proceedings moving
briskly. He draws the crowd into the action and provides a generous
helping of singing to accompany the parades that circle the arena
with the armies of glittering-costumed performers, camels,
elephants, alpacas, ostriches, zebras and other exotic animals and
props that make this venerable circus a generous and rewarding part
of springtime in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
