<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASSOVER-ORTHODOX-ENT     03-30 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER-ORTHODOX-ENTHUSIAST-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilgrimage to Passover: A tireless Orthodox rabbi calls faithful
to Palm Beach
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A Passover package in Palm Beach allows
the faithful to check in for the weekend and cover all the ritual
bases.
</P>
<P>
   They can celebrate the ancient Jewish festival that begins at
sundown tonight and stay through Sabbath on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Passover seder, all other meals and services are part of the
plan. And no one has to drive on the holidays, which is forbidden
to observant Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Orthodox Synagogue meets in the ballroom of the
Palm Beach Hotel on the resort island. Rent a room for three days
and immerse yourself in the rituals of Orthodox Judaism for the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passover is Thursday and Friday and then we go into Shabbat,''
said Rabbi Moshe Scheiner, 30, the energetic rabbi serving his
first synagogue. ``So we're going to offer all the meals in
addition to services. We have a kosher-for-Passover plan from
Wednesday night through Saturday lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   That is part of Scheiner's aggressive campaign to market his
faith and promote Orthodox Judaism as a user-friendly religion
available to all Jews.
</P>
<P>
   He expects about a dozen people will rent rooms and that more
than 100 will take part in the Passover celebration at the hotel.
They are part of the community of 140 families and single Jews that
came together less than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passover is the birth of our nation,'' Scheiner said. ``That's
when we became a people. God brought us out of Egypt and said, `You
will no longer be servants of man. You'll be servants of me.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Scheiner, who this year marks his first Passover as a
full-time rabbi, has wrestled with a personal passover to determine
whose servant he was to be.
</P>
<P>
   He began his pilgrimage as a medical equipment salesman
commuting from Miami to a Palm Beach minyan of about 10 men who met
for prayer once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he lives in Palm Beach and offers daily services morning
and night. A religious school meets twice a week. He runs home
Torah study groups, an educational program called ``Tea and
Torah,'' bar mitzvah and bat mitzvah instruction for youngsters,
and the Torah Learning Center, which exists to reach out to
nonmembers.
</P>
<P>
   Scheiner has helped raise more than a $1.5 million to build or
buy a place for a synagogue on the island and faces the challenge
of another Orthodox synagogue setting up shop on the island. But
his fans are loyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're there because of the rabbi,'' said Lisa Schierer, a
synagogue member from North Palm Beach. ``He's phenomenal. He's
incredibly intelligent. He's nonjudgmental, and he has the ability
to create a link between the Torah and our everyday life. It's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheiner was born into an observant Orthodox family in Boro
Park, Brooklyn, the son and grandson of rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   One brother is a rabbi in Colorado. Another is in school
preparing to be a rabbi. His sister is married to a rabbi. Scheiner
also prepared to be a rabbi and was ordained, but only to keep his
options open, he said. He planned to help part-time in a synagogue,
but he wanted to work in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He met his wife, Dina, 26, through a matchmaker. She grew up in
Crown Heights and was also raised in the Lubavitch Orthodox
tradition in which contact between single boys and girls is
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marriage is not prearranged,'' Scheiner said. ``A
matchmaker is someone who knows you and knows her and says I think
you'd be good together.''
</P>
<P>
   They were married in 1993 and came to Miami the following year.
Scheiner took a job with a medical equipment company supplying
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, he was called to Palm Beach to lead a weekend
service for a group of people starting a synagogue. His
Colorado-based brother had given his name to a Palm Beach resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for exactly that,'' Scheiner said. ``Bingo. But
I was looking for something close to Miami, not an hour and a half
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly he drove to Palm Beach and took the service, spent
the night and returned Sunday. That went on for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Then the synagogue began to grow. He was needed more often.
Still a part-time rabbi, he moved to Palm Beach and commuted every
day to his full-time job in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   That arduous journey went on for nearly four years as the
synagogue grew apace. In July, he gave into his destiny, quit his
daytime job and became a full-time rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a good job,'' said Rabbi Leonid Feldman at the
Conservative Temple Emanu-El on Palm Beach. ``He's very loved and
respected. It's not easy to create a community on Palm Beach. He
deserves credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most members of his congregation are not observant Orthodox
Jews. Many drive to services on Sabbath. Others are observant in
only some parts of Orthodox life.
</P>
<P>
   Scheiner welcomes them all, urges full obedience to Orthodox
tradition but accepts whatever degree of observance each person
follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some rabbis throw barriers between you and the pulpit,'' said
Bill Matheson, 63, from Palm Beach. ``This rabbi reaches out. I can
learn more and do more here.''
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Judaism has become so popular on Palm Beach that other
rabbis may be planning to start congregations. Rumors abound that a
socially popular New York Orthodox ``rabbi to the stars'' may be
coming to the island for winter seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rabbi, Marc Schneier, feels strongly that he has a
following here,'' Feldman said. ``It will be a fascinating
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheiner, understandably, sees no need for a second Orthodox
congregation and is concerned that his community may be falsely
described as an ultra-conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're modern. We're open,'' he said. ``I am Lubavitch. The
synagogue is not. Most of our members come from Conservative and
Reform traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scheiner is committed to helping each member find a fuller
expression of Judaism as God leads them to deeper understanding.
And that, he suggests, has roots in the ancient festival they
celebrate tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passover is an ongoing process,'' Scheiner said. ``Any time a
person reaches a greater degree of spirituality in their life, it's
a sort of passover.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
