<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRIMAKOV-HNS &LR;      03-30 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRIMAKOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMAKOV OFFERS A HELPING HAND _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton found himself Tuesday in the same
situation as President George Bush in 1991 _ weighing the impact of
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's dramatic rush into a war
zone to talk peace with a Soviet-era ally.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo crisis, Clinton rejected any suggestion that the
Primakov's six-hour summit with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic in Belgrade Tuesday had yielded enough concessions for
the allies to call off their bombing campaign against Yugoslav
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when Primakov flew to Iraq eight years ago seeking to
avert an allied ground war against Saddam Hussein's forces by
securing concessions from Saddam, Bush said that the effort ``falls
well short of what would be required.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose administration said it welcomed Primakov's
diplomatic foray into Yugoslavia, nevertheless condemned Milosevic
for continuing to press his ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign against
``completely innocent'' ethnic Albanian Muslims in Kosovo. More
than 120,000 refugees have fled the onslaught to neighboring
nations in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rejected as ``unacceptable'' Milosevic's statement
following his summit with Primakov in which he pledged to ``accept
Russia's suggestion'' to ``start decreasing the presence'' of
40,000 Yugoslav forces in the breakaway province of Kosovo ``after
the bombing stops.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton argued that ``President Milosevic began this brutal
campaign; it is his responsibility to bring it to an immediate end
and embrace a just peace. There is a strong consensus in NATO that
we must press forward with our military action.''
</P>
<P>
   In words similar to those used by Bush in 1991, State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said Milosevic's offer fell ``far short of
what is necessary in order for NATO to stop its air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added, ``Our position is clear: Milosevic must halt the
offensive against the Kosovar Albanians, withdraw his forces, and
embrace a settlement based on the (peace plan that Milosevic
rejected before allied bombing began last Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Milosevic, Primakov flew to Bonn to brief
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, chairman of the 15-nation
European Union, who called Clinton about Milosevic's blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also rejected Milosevic's response as ``no basis for a
political solution'' after hearing from Primakov that the Yugoslav
leader had agreed to cease attacks on ethnic Albanians and withdraw
some forces from Kosovo only if the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) halts its airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, a former Russian foreign minister and chief of the old
Soviet spy organization, the KGB, has built his career in the
post-Cold War era by sweeping into hostile settings to try to
negotiate dramatic peace agreements with the leaders of nations
once allied with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Serbs were allied with Russian Serbs to fight
Ottoman Turkish rule for six centuries before World War I. Both
Serb populations are Orthodox Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this decade of communal bloodshed in the former
republics of Yugoslavia, the Russians have worked to ease western
allied pressure on the Yugoslav Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking over as Russia's foreign minister in 1996,
Primakov flew to Belgrade to urge Milosevic to keep the promises he
had made in conjunction with the U.S.-brokered Dayton peace
agreement for Bosnia in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After having lunch with Milosevic in Belgrade on May 30, 1996,
Primakov said the Yugoslav leader was ``doing his best to fulfill
completely all the Dayton agreements'' including turning over
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and the Bosnian Serb military
commander, Gen. Ratko Mladic, who had been indicted as war
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But now, almost three years later, the two remain free.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's most dramatic missions came before and during the
Persian Gulf War, when he repeatedly flew to Baghdad to urge Saddam
Hussein to withdraw his occupation forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1990, the U.N. Security Council _ giving Primakov
one last chance to persuade Saddam _ delayed its proposed Jan. 1,
1991, deadline for the withdrawal of Iraqi troops from Kuwait until
Jan. 15 of that year.
</P>
<P>
   But Primakov's last-ditch mission failed, and the Soviet Union
did not exercise its veto in the U.N. Security Council so that the
15-member council could approve the use of force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the allied air war against Saddam got under way on
Jan. 17, 1991, Primakov continued his efforts to avert the
impending allied ground attack on Iraqi forces. Primakov helped
draft a new rendition of the Soviet peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined to Iraqi Prime Minister Tariq Aziz in Moscow on Feb.
18, 1991, the plan called for a cease-fire, complete withdrawal of
Iraqi occupation forces from Kuwait and cessation of international
economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The United States rejected the proposal. Bush, poised to launch
a massive ground campaign to evict Iraqi forces from Kuwait,
faulted the plan for failing to require Iraq to pay reparations to
Kuwait or to restore Kuwait's royal family to power.
</P>
<P>
   While saying Primakov's effort fell ``well short'' of what he
would accept, Bush said he did ``appreciate'' the Russian effort.
But he added, in tones similar to Clinton's on Tuesday: ``Let me
just reiterate, as far as I'm concerned there are no negotiations.
The goals have been set out; there will be no concessions. We're
not going to give.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
