<SLUG> BC-MARKET-DECLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET BACKS OFF A DAY AFTER TOPPING 10,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after finishing above 10,000 for the first time
in history, the Dow Jones industrial average slumped Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The index declined 93.52 points to 9913.26, erasing half the
gains that propelled it to a record high of 10,006.78 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The market's inability to sustain this milestone for even one
day prompted money managers and investment specialists to revisit a
question they have asked themselves over and over in recent months:
How strong is the bull in this market?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the narrowness of this market is healthy. I
don't think it's good that 50 or 100 companies have propelled the
S&AMP;P 500 over the past two years,'' said Claudia Mott, director of
small-company research for Prudential Securities Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While blue-chip stocks, led by US computer companies, have
soared nearly 8 percent this year, small-company stocks have not
been lifted by the rally. In fact, they have actually declined.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000, an index that tracks the performance of small
companies, has lost 5 1/2 percent this year, while the Dow is up
nearly 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 9.42 points, closing at 1300.75,
while the Nasdaq, the index of the country's booming technology
industry, was down 12.55 points, closing at 2480.29. The S&AMP;P's and
Nasdaq's declines, like the Dow's, amounted to less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mott said investors who are profiting from the blue-chip bull
market are defying the age-old investment advice to diversify. They
``own a bunch of Internet stocks and a bunch of blue chips and
think that's all they need.'' At some point, she said, this
``economic nirvana is going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But pessimistic voices like Mott's are being drowned out by a
chorus of Wall Street money managers, economists and stock gurus
who see few reasons why a sky-high market cannot continue rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, after its periodic meeting Tuesday to
discuss interest rates, said there would be no changes. The agency
also did not reveal whether it was leaning toward tightening or
loosening the money supply at a time when asset-price inflation and
a booming market are as much a concern as the fear the economy
could slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no meaningful changes'' in the factors driving
the market, said Easton Ragsdale, director of quantitative research
for State Street Research &AMP; Management Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters is that the economy here in the US has
been strong. If anything, it's been going from strength to
strength,'' Ragsdale said, citing low interest rates, low
inflation, and higher consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The good news rolls on. The Conference Board reported that
consumer confidence leaped more than expected in March to 133.9,
from a revised 133.1 in February.
</P>
<P>
   If investors perceived that ``the economy couldn't keep growing
or the Fed would tighten a lot, the market would be worried,'' said
Robert Mellman, a vice president and senior economist in New York
for J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   A hint of economic weakness came on Monday with a slip in
February US new-home sales, the third straight month numbers have
fallen after a strong performance in 1998. Economists said the
housing market may be cooling, though there is little evidence of
that in Boston's surging real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   Housing ``has been strong but now it looks like it's starting to
roll over,'' in part because interest rates have risen slightly,
said Ragsdale. ``If rates come up a little bit, that's also
something that's negative for the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that is crystal clear in this market is that big
companies keep charging ahead. Although the reasons for it are less
clear, analysts have some theories.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the huge increase in recent years in the amount of
money is flowing into stocks, from baby boomers saving for
retirement and from from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Just as prospects that the Dow would hit 10,000 have been a
powerful magnet for Americans, Mellman says it has also attracted
money from Europeans, Asians, and other overseas investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
