A9975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-KIDNAP-HNS &LR;      03-30 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-KIDNAP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REINSTATES CONVICTION IN MULTISTATE KIDNAPPING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A drug deal that went bad in Houston five years ago
ended at the Supreme Court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The justices ruled that the revenge kidnapping of a mid-level
dealer, whose boss stole 30 kilograms of cocaine from a Houston
drug distributor, can be tried in any state through which the
kidnapper drove his hostage. In its 7-2 decision, the high court
broadly interpreted a federal criminal law, as well as
constitutional provisions that require trials to be held in the
same state and district where the crime was allegedly committed.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, ruling in a case that wound up in New Jersey, said
kidnapping is a continuing offense that can be tried in any state
where the hostage was held. Based on that rationale, the high court
said violations of the federal law barring gunplay ``during and in
relation to'' a kidnapping can also be tried in any state where the
hostage was held _ even if the weapon was actually used in a
different state involved in the kidnapping, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   The multistate odyssey that the justices resolved began when a
New York drug dealer stole the cocaine in 1994. The angry drug
distributor hired Jacinto Rodriguez-Moreno to kidnap the dealer's
middleman, Ephrain Avendano, and find the thief.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Moreno, a few cohorts and Avendano drove from Texas to
the hostage's New Jersey apartment, then to a house in New York and
finally to a home in Maryland. By this time, Rodriguez-Moreno was
ready to abandon the search for the New York drug dealer and just
kill Avendano.
</P>
<P>
   So Rodriguez-Moreno took possession of the homeowner's .357
Magnum revolver and held it against Avendano's neck, but withdrew
the weapon at the request of his cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   Avendano later escaped through the back door and ran to a
neighboring house. The neighbors called the police, who arrested
Rodriguez-Moreno and his cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Moreno was charged with, among other offenses, using
and carrying a firearm ``during and in relation to'' the kidnapping
of Avendano. The federal government tried Rodriguez-Moreno in the
U.S. District Court for New Jersey, which convicted him. He was
sentenced to seven years in prison for kidnapping, and 5 years in
prison for the gun offense.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Moreno appealed his conviction, arguing that the New
Jersey federal court had no authority to rule in his case because
he had committed the gun crime in Maryland, not New Jersey. The 3rd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed and overturned the district
court's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court reinstated Rodriguez-Moreno's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The justices conceded that he had used the gun in Maryland but
said the weapon was used ``during and in relation to'' a kidnapping
that occurred not just in Maryland but also in New Jersey, Texas,
New York and states in between. Hence, the defendant was properly
tried in New Jersey, the court said in United States vs.
Rodriguez-Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kidnapping, once begun, does not end until the victim is
free,'' Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the court's majority.
``It does not make sense, then, to speak of it in discreet
geographic fragments.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting from the decision, Justices Antonin Scalia and John
Paul Stevens assailed their colleagues for their broad reading of
the federal law, saying the statute limits criminality to the use
of a gun during a kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   The only state in which Rodriguez-Moreno used a firearm was
Maryland, and that is the only place where he can be tried, the
justices said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
