u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-CITIZENS-BOS     03-30 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG RULING STYMIES IMMIGRANTS FROM MAINLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 KONG-CITIZENS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a ruling intended to block an influx of hundreds
of thousands of new immigrants, a local court said Tuesday that
mainland Chinese who can claim Hong Kong citizenship must go home
and wait their turn. The system involves years of delays.
</P>
<P>
   The decision drew an outcry from plaintiffs who have lived
separately from their families for more than 20 years, and who had
hoped to stay here on temporary visitor's permits while applying
for resident cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge says he `understands' that I applied to come here 22
years ago and have not yet been able to join my father, my mother,
my siblings, and now my husband,'' said Lin Li, 28, holding back
tears after the ruling was announced. ``For 20 years of suffering,
he uses one word: `understand.' Is that all? How many 20 years does
one have in a life?''
</P>
<P>
   The final decision on this case will have broad constitutional,
social, and economic implications for this rich, free-wheeling
former British colony that reverted to Chinese rule in 1997 under
an agreement that it would enjoy a ``high degree of autonomy.''
Hong Kong and Chinese authorities worry that a flood of poor
mainlanders seeking a better life would drag down this prosperous
financial center that has been an engine for growth on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court, 100 demonstrators claiming to be eligible
migrants or relatives of eligible migrants waited quietly for the
ruling and mourned the result. Many wore placards indicating the
years they have waited. Last month, 382 mainlanders who overstayed
visas held a two-week vigil outside government offices until they
were permitted to stay pending Tuesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the ruling, Hong Kong immigration authorities
detained 132 of an estimated 1,200 mainlanders who have overstayed
visas and announced plans to deport them. Another 28 agreed to
voluntarily return. Authorities warned illegals of penalties of up
to three years in prison. The 17 plaintiffs are appealing Tuesday's
ruling, and can stay pending its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids should have the right to be with their families _ they
haven't done anything wrong,'' said Lam Shiao-lian, 49, a legal
resident of Hong Kong whose 26-year-old daughter, Cheng
Liang-liang, has been applying to leave China since 1978. Of Lam's
four children, only one has received permission to move here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit letting us all come would have an impact on the
economy, but what about my rights and what's guaranteed in the
Basic Law?'' Lam said, referring to Hong Kong's post-colonial
constitution, which says children of Hong Kong's permanent
residents have the right to live here.
</P>
<P>
   With estimates of eligible migrants ranging from 300,000 to 3
million people, many here fear mainland migrants with little
education and menial skills could not contribute to a modern,
high-tech economy. Critics say they would strain schools,
hospitals, and other services in a city of 6.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of migrants point out that Hong Kong has always
been a city of migrants, that it grew from the sweat of mainland
refugees. Hong Kong evolved from a trading port to an industrial
center thanks to refugees from the mainland's communist revolution
50 years ago, and recent migrants have manned the territory's
service sector.
</P>
<P>
   Today, half of Hong Kong's residents are refugees from the
mainland, and the other half are descendants of mainland refugees.
Last year, under the daily quota of 150 mainland migrants, more
than 50,000 settled here legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we do in the '50s and '60s with all those
immigrants?'' asked Pam Baker, an attorney for the migrants. ``We
need those kids. Birth rates are dropping, people are living
longer, there aren't going to be any taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The migrants' case was filed after Hong Kong's highest court
ruled two months ago against the government's attempt to limit
migrants' eligibility. The Court of Final Appeal said even children
born out-of-wedlock or before a parent became a permanent resident
have the right to live here. The court added that it had ``a duty''
to strike down any Chinese laws that conflict with Hong Kong's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   That sparked a row with Beijing and a virtual constitutional
crisis that was settled only when Hong Kong's high court issued a
``clarification'' last month stating that they were not challenging
China's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had a constitution before _ we've always envied
you guys,'' said Baker, a longtime Hong Kong resident. ``Now that
we've got one, we've got to jolly well defend it. And this ruling
is unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Yash Ghai, a law professor at the University of Hong Kong, said
it was inappropriate for a court to balance the rights of
prospective migrants against the welfare of the city. ``Some kinds
of rights can be balanced _ like free speech and public safety. But
in this case, either you're a citizen or you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mainlanders, ethnic Chinese from the United States,
Canada, Taiwan, or nearly anywhere else in the world are allowed to
come here and apply for rapid residency, raising questions about
discrimination against one group.
</P>
<P>
   It is also widely acknowledged that corruption plagues the exit
system in China, enabling people with money and connections to come
here faster, creating a two-tiered system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are many who see the logic of Tuesday's lower court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Legislator David Chu, who grew up partly in Boston, compared
Tuesday's ruling to regulations on Americans' constitutional right
to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to carry a weapon, you have to get a permit. These
children clearly have the right to live in Hong Kong, but in order
to do that, you must get the permit. And according to the rules,
this must be done in China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
