<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAURUS-DESIGN-ART-2TA     03-30 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAURUS-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD GOES GENERIC WITH ITS NEW TAURUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GM-OUTLOOK) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember the first Ford Taurus? When the car was
introduced in late 1985, its smooth, aerodynamic curves shook up
the design of midsize sedans. And despite fears that its radical
look would turn off car buyers, sales took off almost immediately.
Moreover, its success was one of the early signs of the resurgence
of Ford Motor Co. that has brought it today to the brink of
surpassing General Motors Corp. as the largest automaker in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Ford unveiled the new Taurus on Tuesday at the New York
International Auto Show. But do not look for any surprises. While
it may sell well if it is priced cheaply enough, it is unlikely to
win any contests for style. Indeed, the most distinctive thing
about the new Taurus is probably how indistinguishable it is from
all the other look-alike midsize sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives, while acknowledging that the design of the
Taurus is cautious and conservative, say it will offer the comfort,
competitive price and numerous safety features that consumers want
in midsize cars these days. ``More than the styling, it's the total
package: quality, value, safety,'' said James O'Connor, Ford's
president for Ford brand cars and light trucks. ``I think the
consumer in general doesn't make styling the No. 1 preference in
that segment, as opposed to, say, the Mustang segment.''
</P>
<P>
   Automotive design experts say that the 2000 model year Taurus
represents something of a milestone. It is the last of the once
stylish, high-volume midsize sedans to take on a new, more generic
look as Ford and other automakers put most of their automotive
styling efforts elsewhere. After reigning for decades as the main
focus of automotive design in the United States, midsize sedans are
losing their primacy to sport utility vehicles and to an ever
growing array of so-called crossover vehicles that combine features
of sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks, station wagons and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from the 2000 Taurus are many of the quirky external
features that made earlier models, including a 1996 redesign, so
distinctive. The oval rear window, oval dashboard and many of the
other features that distinguished the Taurus sedan for the last
three years have been replaced with plain, rectangular designs for
windows and dashboard alike.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the sheet metal, remarkably little has been changed,
allowing Ford to avoid hundreds of millions of dollars in expenses
for engineering work and new factory tooling. The whole underbody
of the vehicle has been left virtually untouched, while the engine
is the same other than a few tweaks to improve its horsepower. Ford
did not even bother with the time and cost of designing a new rear
window for the wagon version of the new Taurus, leaving an oval
rear window on it even while the rest of the vehicle has assumed a
more rectangular look.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons, experts say, why midsize cars have
become so indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Americans who value distinctive automotive styling are
increasingly choosing sport utility vehicles and crossover
vehicles, like Toyota Motor Corp.'s Lexus RX-300, rather than
buying midsize sedans. A growing proportion of new cars are also
being purchased by households with three or more vehicles, and
these households tend to choose plainly designed sedans to go with
more fashionable vehicles in their fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, midsize car prices are slowly falling because of an
excess of factory capacity and a glut of late-model sedans coming
off leases or being sold by rental companies. This encourages
automakers to cut engineering costs and limits their ability to add
fancy styling touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't as many people in sedans who are willing to pay
for styling,'' said Susan Jacobs, the president of Jacobs &AMP;
Associates, an auto consulting firm in Rutherford, N.J. ``It's wise
for the styling dollars to go into the fun vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   In marketing focus groups, buyers of midsize cars also tend to
disagree with each other about what they want, unlike buyers of
sport utility vehicles, so car designers must make many compromises
between conflicting demands, said Jerry Hirshberg, president for
North American design at Nissan Motor Co. ``We've gotten a bit
risk-averse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, of course, say they are not especially
interested in automotive styling and would be perfectly happy with
vehicles that simply provide comfortable, reliable transportation.
But auto executives and market analysts say that Americans' buying
decisions do not back up such statements.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles sell briskly even though most buyers do
not use them for off-road driving, while vehicles that evoke the
image of sport utilities, like the Pontiac Montana minivan, are
increasingly popular. A few imaginatively styled midsize sedans,
like the Volkswagen Passat and Pontiac Grand Prix, have been
successful, garnering praise from the automotive media and consumer
evaluators alike. But they occupy relatively low-sales niches in
the overall market for midsize sedans.
</P>
<P>
   John Waraniak, a managing director of Benchmarking Partners, an
automotive consulting firm in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., said he had
spread out photographs in his kitchen of four new, high-sales
sedans going on sale this year and early next year: Ford Taurus,
Oldsmobile Aurora, Chevrolet Impala and Nissan Maxima. His wife,
Terri, was unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `They all look the same to me,' and she's the kind
of person, about 40 years old, who might switch from a sport
utility if there were something exciting to switch to,'' Waraniak
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth sedan, Saturn's first midsize car, will also go on sale
soon but GM has not released photographs of it. The midsize Saturn
LS, which is being introduced Wednesday at the New York auto show,
has styling that does not depart significantly from other similarly
sized sedans on the market, according to John Middlebrook, GM's
vice president for vehicle brand marketing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Midsize cars are important. Close to $100 billion worth are sold
each year in the United States, making it the biggest single
segment of the American auto market. It is almost as big a business
as the world's passenger airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the midsize sedan market has been eroded by the success of
sport utility vehicles and minivans, falling to 27 percent of the
family vehicle market last year from 33 percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Auto engineers object to suggestions that their midsize cars are
boring, but they seldom suggest that their offerings are on the
cutting edge, either. David Marinaro, the chief program engineer
for the 2000 Taurus, said the car ``was designed around
functionality, the whole car was designed around that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Taurus is also designed so that Ford can build it and
sell it for no more money than a current Taurus and possibly for
less. Although Ford has not yet decided on the actual price,
everything is geared to keeping down costs. By keeping the
underbody and the door openings the same as for the previous
Taurus, for instance, Ford can continue to use a lot of the same
factory equipment to build it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to be actually equal to or lower in cost'' for
manufacturing the new model, Marinaro said.
</P>
<P>
   The more modest design of the new Taurus partly reflects the
difficulties Ford had in selling the model that is about to be
phased out. Ford spared no expense in redesigning the Taurus for
the 1996 model year, hoping to repeat the success of the original
1986 Taurus. The 1986-style Taurus produced enormous profits for
Ford, becoming the nation's best-selling car from 1992 through
1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1996 redesign bombed. Many people complained that the
new vehicle looked too unusual. Perhaps more seriously, Ford also
had to raise the price by $1,000 to cover the extensive engineering
expenses and the cost of features like waves in the sheet metal on
the side. Ford was not prepared to compete on price a year later
when Honda Motor Co. and Toyota, respectively, introduced
less-expensive models of the Accord and the Camry.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of radical styling and an increased sticker
price soon cost Taurus its leadership of the American car market.
The last two years, it has trailed the Accord and the Camry _ two
sedans renowned for reliability and functionality over distinctive
design _ by a large and widening margin.
</P>
<P>
   While the new midsize cars may be dull, that does not mean that
automakers are producing bland vehicles overall. Ford, GM, Nissan
and other automakers are all making separate plans, for example, to
start selling sport utility vehicles with open pickup truck beds at
the back. Indeed, soaring sales of sport utility vehicles,
minivans, pickups and crossover vehicles have produced a wave of
innovation in these market segments.
</P>
<P>
   All of these vehicles, including the crossovers, are regulated
as light trucks, which means they are partially or entirely exempt
from the regulatory straitjacket _ rules on fuel-economy, air
pollution, bumper-heights and the like _ that tends to produce car
designs that fit the same mold.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto designers think that midsize cars can be made exciting
again. DaimlerChrysler AG already makes the striking Dodge Intrepid
and Chrysler 300M, which are actually full-size cars, and is
putting a lot of effort into redesigning midsize cars, like the
Plymouth Breeze, to make them more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Subtle changes like changing the curve of the windshield or the
width between a car's wheels could make a styling difference
without necessarily hurting affordability, said Thomas Gale, the
executive vice president for North American design at
DaimlerChrysler. ``You have to find ways which make things
exciting,'' Gale said, ``and still do it in ways which are
perceived as adding value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirshberg of Nissan said it would take a completely new yet
practical midsize sedan design to revive one of the oldest segments
in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's dead,'' he said. ``It's just going to take
someone who comes in and nails something fresh, as Ford did with
the first Taurus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
