<HEADER>
A9992 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-     03-30 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS REFUGEES OVERWHELM MACEDONIA, SOME ARE TURNED BACK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos, and a graphic _ tracking the number of refugees
_ are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(AC) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ The flow of refugees from Kosovo is
overwhelming neighboring countries, leading to long delays at the
borders and, in some cases, refugees are being ordered to turn
back.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian refugees who fled Kosovo for Albania have been
spilling into Macedonia, where border officials have turned them
away, and there were reports on Tuesday that a trainload of people
coming from Kosovo was also sent back.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Radmila Kiprijanova, speaking at a news
conference on Tuesday in Skopje, the capital, said that the country
could not cope with more refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Security Council of Macedonia has said we can
accommodate 20,000 refugees, not more,'' she said. ``We are waiting
for other countries to take refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that some 23,000 had already arrived in Macedonia.
Beyond those who have fled to Macedonia and Albania, refugees from
Kosovo have also entered the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing our best to try to accommodate them all,'' Ms.
Kiprijanova said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and photographers said that they saw an unscheduled
train arrive from Kosovo at mid-morning on Tuesday. It was inside
the country when it was surrounded by armed riot police in helmets
and bullet-proof vests who trained their weapons on the passengers,
preventing them from leaving the carriages.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists watched as the engine was detached from the front,
and placed on the other end; the train was then sent back the way
it had come. Photographers followed it back to the border and
watched it return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official explanation for the turning back of the
train, according to an article in Dnevnik, the local daily
newspaper. The article also said that the train carried 1,000
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kiprijanova said that she did not know anything about the
train and denied that the Macedonian border had been closed down.
</P>
<P>
   An American diplomat making a visit to the border played down
the Macedonian reaction to the flow of refugees. ``It is a typical
reaction of any government suddenly being swamped by refugees,'' he
said. ``They say they cannot cope with the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But aid workers were more forthright, suggesting that the
Macedonian government had a lot to fear from a large influx of
ethnic Albanians, which could upset the delicate ethnic balance in
Macedonia, where, according to the government 25 percent of the
population is ethnic Albanian and 45 percent is Macedonian. Ethnic
Albanians, however, assert that they comprise 35 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt about it, they don't want them here,'' said
one aid official visiting the border area, who asked to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   At the border on Tuesday, ethnic Albanian refugees fleeing a
five-day ordeal of terror and bombing in Kosovo, were put through a
final test of endurance by Macedonian police.
</P>
<P>
   Two sisters, Luljeta and Nafie Hamdiu, struggled through on foot
with heavy bags and five small children. Their faces creased with
strain, eyes hollow, they said they had waited 28 hours to pass
into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Cars were backed up at least five miles, said Berat, a
22-year-old engineering student who walked out of Kosovo. He
estimated at least one thousand cars were waiting, with some five
people to a car sleeping overnight in their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gutmann, a doctor with the aid group International Medical
Corps said on Tuesday: ``It is worse than yesterday; it is hardly
moving at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, a Serbian anti-aircraft gun opened up, firing
away over the heads of the refugees into the hills behind.
</P>
<P>
   The border police at Blace refused to comment on their slow
processing of arrivals, referring all questions to the Interior
Ministry in Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   For the refugees it was a cruel test. Ali Muriqi, an assistant
at the engineering faculty of Pristina University, said:
``Virtually everyone who had the possibility wanted to get out of
that nightmare. For me, none of the choices were safe. I thought we
should go, if we could survive the journey. Because if we stayed,
there was a big chance of dying, or being taken by the police. That
was a constant possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Leman, both ethnic Albanians, had not dared
leave the house for five days, as they listened to Serbian police
and paramilitaries driving around, loosing bursts of automatic
gunfire and setting off explosions around the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just waiting for the police to come and take me, to
finish me off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Pristina, the capital of Kosovo province, all tell
the same story. At 6:30 every evening, the electricity would go
out, leaving the city in blackness. They would wait for the NATO
bombing, and as soon as the first explosions came, the Serbs would
begin to shoot and set off explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was afraid of the NATO bombings, the problems were from
the Serb side,'' Muriqi said.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who would only identify himself as Berat, had
mounted a lookout with his neighbors in Kosovo and described
watching civilian jeeps driving around town, apparently setting off
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw came on Tuesday morning when they watched houses
in the suburb of Dragodan, across the hill, burning. They gathered
with neighbors to form a convoy to drive out.
</P>
<P>
   Still frightened and unsure whether to risk the checkpoints on
the one hour drive to Macedonia, they made up their minds quickly
when loud gunshots rang out nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The journey was uneventful. A single police checkpoint extorted
money from them, but at others, the army and border guards waved
them through.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the Macedonians who would not let the car through.
The Muriqis came through on foot, exhausted, hungry and
traumatized. Their car and their friends were still stuck in no
man's land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
