<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-     03-30 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND-RAISING DEADLINE POSES EARLY TEST OF CANDIDATES' STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Presidential candidates, who always seem
desperate for money, have been racing around the country even more
feverishly in the last several days, hitting up contributors at
back-to-back fund-raising events and twisting arms even tighter
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 15 days, former Vice President Dan Quayle has hopped
to big money events in Orlando, Naples and Sanibel Island, Fla.;
Chicago; New Orleans and Lafayette, La.; Louisville, Ky.; Omaha,
Neb.; Scottsdale, Ariz.; and, Tuesday night, Portland, Ore. In the
past week, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has hunted for money at
events in New York, Washington, New Orleans, Los Angeles and Santa
Ana, Calif., and, on Tuesday night, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopefuls are scrambling to meet a daunting
deadline: They want to amass as much money as they can by the close
of business on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This frenzy has been set off because first quarter fund-raising
reports that candidates file with the Federal Election Commission
cover the period through March 31. Since there are few tangible
ways to gauge a candidate's strength 10 months before the first
votes are cast, these first filings have taken on outsized
importance.
</P>
<P>
   The hope among campaigns is that they can demonstrate, through
raw dollars, their credibility among party leaders and in the
press. Even before most voters have focused on the campaign,
candidates are trying to spur further donations and political
support in the crucial early months of the presidential season.
Early money is particularly vital in the 2000 race because with a
compressed calendar of contests, most contenders will have to
collect the bulk of their war chests this year.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are highest, of course, for the two early
favorites, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore.
It is in their interest to play up the importance of early money.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview here Tuesday how crucial the first quarter
report will be, Bush said, ``It's the first bit of real hard news
there is in a campaign.'' His finance chairman said Bush would
probably take in about $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Quayle, whose advisers said expects to raise $2
million, played down expectations. ``We're going to have the
necessary money to get our message out,'' he said. Recalling how
former Texas Gov. John B. Connally spent $13 million in the
Republican primaries in 1980 and won just one delegate, he added,
``This idea that you need to be No. 1 in fund raising _ well
President Connally found out that wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as in the case of Connally and another Texan Republican
four years ago, Sen. Phil Gramm, reading too much into these
reports can be an arbitrary exercise. Many campaigns have just
gotten underway. Elizabeth Dole, for one, has scheduled her first
big fund raiser for late April.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sometimes these early filings are quite telling. ``It shows
you're in the game,'' said Rick Wright, the national finance
director for former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Michael Dukakis collected more money, earlier, than any
other Democrat. His fat bank account forced political professionals
and prospective supporters to take him seriously _ and those early
perceptions helped him win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all want to look good,'' said Stan Huckaby, a consultant
who is advising several Republican presidential candidates on how
to set up their fund-raising structures. ``But I don't think in the
first quarter you really know anything. If you had a candidate who
raised a small amount of money by the 31st of March, to know how
he's really doing you should ask specific questions such as: Does
he have major fund raisers planned in April or May that didn't show
up in the report?''
</P>
<P>
   That has not stopped campaigns from instructing their staffs to
be sure to deposit every check by March 31. (The quarterly reports
do not actually have to be filed with the Federal Election
Commission until April 15.) And it has not stopped campaigns from
trying to lower expectations about how much they will raise.
Advisers to Gore, for example, have been telling reporters in
recent days that his only rival for the Democratic nomination,
Bradley, has been wildly successful in raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, chairman of Bush's national finance committee, said
in an interview Tuesday that he expects to report roughly $4
million by the end of the quarter. That would likely be higher than
other Republicans. Evans said the Bush campaign did not begin
soliciting contributions until three weeks ago. The second quarter
will be even more telling, he said, explaining that he hoped to
raise ``between 10 and 20'' million by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, an old friend of Bush who runs an oil and gas business in
Midland, Texas, said there was such enthusiasm for the governor
that people are giving money without even being solicited. At a
meeting with the governor nearly two weeks ago, he said, 500 people
showed up to volunteer to help him solicit money in Texas alone. He
said he expects to pull in a record $10 million from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not twisting arms _ we're responding to the energy and
enthusiasm for the governor,'' Evans said. ``There's people calling
in, saying, `Can I send money?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the importance of early money, Bush said, ``People
said, `Oh we're for you.' It's important for me to see what, `I'm
for you' means. Will people step up and write a check?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been raising money longer than Bush, and his advisers
said they expect to take in as much as $7 million. As part of the
vice president's end-of-the-quarter hectic push for money, his
campaign mailed a solicitation to 500,000 people on March 17 and
held fund raising events in Chicago and Birmingham, Ala., on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most other campaigns have had to hustle even more bluntly.
McCain, for one, integrated the quarterly reports into his pitch.
``At the end of March, we will file an FEC report,'' he said at a
breakfast in Washington last week. ``That will be the next judgment
that the chattering class around here will make. We will have
raised a sufficient amount of money to be credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever mindful of Bush, he added, ``We're not going to raise the
most money.''
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate, Sen. Robert Smith, R-N.H., also was already
making excuses even before the end of the filing period.
``Unfortunately, we didn't start raising money until the end of
February, literally.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he could get by anyway because ``I'm a very frugal
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate seeking the Republican
nomination, can afford to watch the rush for money with detached
amusement: He is financing his campaign mostly with his own
fortune. He plans to turn down federal matching subsidies so he
does not have to adhere to spending limits _ something Bush is also
considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all scrambling to show, `We are credible. We are in
the game,' '' Forbes said. ``So you do get what I call artificial
stimulants. Instead of doing a fund raiser in April, you get it in
March.''
</P>
<P>
   It reminded him, he said, of corporate executives trying to take
quick action before their next stockholders' meeting. ``It's like a
fund manager getting rid of his dog holdings,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
