<HEADER>
A9994 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-WATER30-PA     03-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WATER30-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  BOTTLED WATER NOT SAFER OR CLEANER THAN TAP WATER, STUDY SAYS.
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The picture on the bottle shows pristine mountain
tops. The label says ``pure.'' Your faucet does neither. So you pay
around a $1 to drink bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   But a study released yesterday says bottled water is not
necessarily any better than the nation's tap water. In fact, it
might even actually BE tap water, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because water comes from a bottle doesn't mean it's any
cleaner or safer than what comes from the tap,'' said Erik Olson,
the study's principle author and a senior attorney for the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, a Washington D.C.-based
non profit group of scientists, lawyers and environmental
specialists, reported that 33 percent of the 103 brands of bottled
water they tested exceeded some industry and state guidelines for
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The study found 22 percent of brands violated guidelines from
California, which has the most strict regulation of all states.
</P>
<P>
   The violations were caused by contaminants found in the water
including: synthetic organic chemicals, bacteria and arsenic. If
consumed over long periods of time, some of these contaminants can
cause cancer or other health problems, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the water was high quality and did not threaten the
health of the general population. But the study's authors said the
water with contaminants that exceeded guidelines may be hazardous
to people with weakened immune systems - the frail elderly,
infants, AIDS patients. Officials from the International Bottled
Water Association said bottled water is safe to drink and the study
itself pointed out that most was high quality.
</P>
<P>
   We know it comes from a bottle. But before that? The study said
that marketing techniques sometimes mislead consumers about the
source of the water.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 to 40 percent of bottled waters are re-packaged tap
water, which may have been purified further, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi Co.'s ``Aquafina,'' features a picture of mountains on
the label and does not mention the fact that its source is tap
water from 11 different cities including Houston, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   If a company takes tap water and does no further treatment to
it, the FDA requires it indicate on the label that it's from a
municipal or community source. But Aquafina is ``purified'' tap
water, and therefore exempt from that rule, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization said if a bottle's label says ``from a
municipal or community water system,'' it means tap water. Also the
study's authors recommend that consumers call or write the bottler
for the information if it is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The bottled water industry suffered a blow in the early 1990s
when benzene contamination was found in Perrier water, which was
recalled from stores.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Americans drink an estimated 4 billion gallons of bottled
water a year.
</P>
<P>
   The group, conducted the study as part of its efforts to
petition the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to have the agency
step up its oversight of bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA regulates only about 30 percent of bottled water, and
does not cover carbonated water - or water sold within a single
state, which makes up about 65 percent of bottled water.
Frequently, regulation falls mostly to the individual states.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA does not require bottlers to report any violations of
contamination problems to state or federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Tap water is regulated by the Environmental Protection Agency,
not the FDA. The organization asks the FDA match federal standards
for tap water.
</P>
<P>
   States have widely varying water bottle regulation programs.
California's is the most stringent and accepts lower levels of
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection did a
survey from 1992 to 1995 of 50 brands of water. It found no
violations of federal standards. But the survey raised ``concerns''
over three brands that showed elevated nitrate levels.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrates at elevated levels can cause harm to infants.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials responded to the organization's study by saying
bottled water is safe to drink and does not present a significant
health risk.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
