<HEADER>
A9995 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-CHIEF-KAN &LR;      03-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-CHIEF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJ. RICK EASLEY CHOSEN FOR KC POLICE CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ The Kansas City Board of Police
Commissioners on Monday chose Maj. Rick Easley over two
higher-ranking finalists to become the city's 40th police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Easley will succeed Chief Floyd Bartch. He beat out Deputy
Chiefs James Nunn and Dennis Shreve.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting final interviews, the board voted 5-0 for
Easley. It was the first time since 1973 that the board picked
someone beneath the rank of deputy chief to be police chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just the best of the candidates,'' said Commissioner
Joe Mulvihill. ``I think he's going to be someone the police
officers respect and he'll be innovative and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley said the appointment would take a while to sink in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of overwhelming,'' he said Monday night. ``It puts a
whole new meaning on March Madness.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley said his first goal as chief is to meet the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be one of those chiefs who are out in the community
on a regular basis,'' he said. ``I'm going to attend some community
meetings as soon as I can and get to know community leaders across
the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley said he always knew he had a chance because he was
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A leader's a leader,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter whether
you're a major or a colonel.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, Easley will shadow Bartch for a week to learn
more about the job. A swearing-in ceremony is scheduled Friday
morning at police headquarters. The board had not decided on a
salary package for Easley.
</P>
<P>
   The three finalists were picked from a list of 42 applicants and
then six semifinalists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Jeff Simon said he hoped the deputy chief finalists
would support Easley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Nunn and Dennis Shreve have both put in 27 years to the
department, and the success of this department is going to depend
on their contributions in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   During the search, Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, a board member, and
some community members said the next police chief should be a
minority or someone with connections to minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Easley, who is white, has said he has connections with minority
groups and, as chief, will strengthen those relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from my neighborhood remember him,'' said Acting Board
President Stacey Daniels-Young, who is black. ``He has the
contacts. He's not afraid to go out into the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officers say he gets along well with minority officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter that he's not a minority, because he's
viewed as being fair,'' said Homicide Capt. Darryl Forte, who is
black. ``I worked for him in the personnel division and he made
decisions based on qualifications and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood and civic leaders, in general, supported the
board's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming City Councilman Alvin Brooks, with the Ad Hoc Group
Against Crime, acknowledged that there has been a widening gap
between black neighborhoods and the law enforcement community, but
he said communities now need to work with the new chief.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 Northland residents were debating a concealed-weapons
proposition in the Northland Neighborhoods Inc. office when word
came about Easley's selection. Neighbors who had been arguing
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a wonderful person. He will do a great job,'' said
Executive Director Carolyn Vellar, who recounted that Easley helped
form roughly 50 neighborhood watch groups.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Hartsfield, the minister at Metropolitan Missionary
Baptist Church, said he was disappointed that Nunn was not chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that we had gotten to the point where a minority
would be selected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral candidates George Blackwood and Kay Waldo Barnes said
they would have supported any of the three finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a new chief began Dec. 22, after Bartch announced
his intention to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, news broke that Nunn had paid a $35 traffic ticket in
February for Cleaver's wife. Cleaver said he didn't know that Nunn
paid the ticket until reporters started looking into the matter. He
said Nunn's favor did not affect his vote on chief. A department
spokesman said Nunn's action did not violate department policies.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting publicity prompted Daniels-Young to ask that the
board restart the search process. She said people were leaking
sensitive department information to try to kill Nunn's candidacy.
Daniels-Young initially said she wanted a leader from outside the
department, but changed her mind Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels-Young has suggested Nunn was a frequent target because
he is black, but Nunn's critics disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   They said Nunn was unpopular because of poor judgment that they
say was exhibited in Cleaver's traffic ticket and a botched
undercover investigation in 1983. That incident resulted in Nunn
receiving a 10-day suspension. Nunn said he learned from the
episode and became a better police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Shreve's career suffered a setback in 1991 when police officers,
under his command, raided the wrong house. Shreve said he changed
his management style to avoid similar mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   To help select a chief, the board surveyed officers about whom
they liked among the semi-finalists. Of the three finalists, Shreve
garnered the highest percentage of support at 25.3 percent, Easley
received 12.7 percent and Nunn 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Easley, who grew up on the city's East Side, joined the Kansas
City Police Department in 1974 and held various positions in the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said Easley possessed all the qualities the board wanted
in a chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the needs of the department. He's accomplished
and experienced in community policing,'' Simon said. ``He also has
a demonstrated ability for dealing with state and local government
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Dennis Eckold said Easley was very clear-cut in his
plans for the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably had the most specific ideas and the most ideas
overall,'' Eckold said. ``He's just a solid person. A policeman's
policeman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
