<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY WOMEN OFTEN DISCOURAGED BY LACK OF JOB OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent survey of minority women at Fortune 1000 companies
confirmed what a lot of us suspected _ that a lot of talented
people are leaving corporations because of racism, lack of
opportunity and difficulties balancing work and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real wakeup call,'' said Leslie R. Wolfe, president
of the Center for Women Policy Studies, which recently released
``No More `Business as Usual': Women of Color in Corporate
America.'' ``The women in our study who are the most dissatisfied
are the high flyers. These are the ones who are likely to say, `I
don't have to do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 women from 17 Fortune 1000 companies completed
the survey. The average age of respondents was 37, average income
$51,000, and average tenure with their companies nine years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most alarming figures was that 42 percent of the
women believed that they do not have the same opportunity to be
promoted as others with similar qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Another disturbing finding was that the women with the most
training and seniority also were the ones most frustrated and
likely to leave their companies. Nearly half the women poised to
crack the glass ceiling said they felt they had to play down their
race or ethnicity to succeed, and 37 percent believed they had to
play down their gender.
</P>
<P>
   Another shocking finding was that despite several lawsuits, the
majority of the women _ 61 percent _ said they heard sexist and
sexual jokes. More than 50 percent also reported hearing racial and
ethnic jokes. Even women in senior management and executive
positions experienced this.
</P>
<P>
   Like most women in the workplace, those surveyed said their
greatest challenge was balancing work and family responsibilities.
Nearly two in three women (62 percent) reported that limited career
advancement opportunities are a big barrier to balancing their work
and personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations need to realize that the brain power that is
walking out is having a real impact,'' said Linda Cooper Kee,
president of LGC &AMP; Associates, a Kansas City, Mo., firm that
specializes in diversity management training, consulting and
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   So what can companies do? Two-thirds of the women said flexible
scheduling would make a significant difference. Women also wanted
career advancement programs, mentoring programs and increased
educational and training opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Companies who don't implement these policies will, in the long
run, pay a far greater price. They will lose the money they have
spent training these talented individuals, along with the earnings
lost because these women won't be there to provide new solutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
