<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-TV-KAN &LR;      03-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-TV-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEDNESDAY MARKS THE END OF A CABLE TV REGULATION ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) It's been six years since the federal government
began, with considerable fanfare, deregulating cable television
rates. On Wednesday, the effort will come to a quiet end.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission will no longer control how
much cable companies charge for expanded basic cable packages. That
service, which typically includes local channels and such popular
add-ons as CNN and TNT, is the package that most cable TV
subscribers buy.
</P>
<P>
   Though the end of federal controls is near, the debate simmers
over how consumers will fare. It will be up to free-market
competition _ not regulators _ to price the popular tier of
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor the approach say the growth of satellite
television proves that consumers are getting a choice. By contrast,
government controls allowed cable rates nationally to go up 22
percent in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to let the government back off a little bit,'' said
Carol Rothwell, a vice president for Time Warner Cable in Kansas
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are those who say that little competition to
cable TV exists. Satellite television is an option, but equipment
costs and rules that bar satellites from offering local broadcast
stations have kept it from becoming a full-fledged competitor,
these critics say.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of Consumers
Union's Washington office, people will end up with two choices:
paying higher cable rates or dropping the service. To him, it's
appropriate that the first full day of deregulated rates is April
Fools' Day.
</P>
<P>
   If rates increase, most area consumers won't see them for a
while. The area's two largest cable systems _ Time Warner and Jones
Intercable _ say that their rates went up earlier this year for
various program packages and that it will be next year before they
can go up again.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increases earlier this year were permitted under the
price controls that cable companies have been operating under since
1993. Those rules were required by Congress when it passed
legislation to re-regulate the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation reversed federal laws of the early 1980s that
deregulated the cable industry. The intervention enjoyed wide
support amid complaints about rising cable TV prices as the number
of cable subscribers continued to soar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, 18 million households were cable TV customers. In 1993,
the number more than tripled to 59 million households, or nearly
two-thirds of homes with televisions. Last year, it reached 68
million households.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional initiative gave the FCC the responsibility to
control charges for the expanded-basic packages. Local governments
have a say in the charges for basic cable, equipment and
installation, and those responsibilities will continue.
</P>
<P>
   The brave new world of cable rates resulted from the
Republicans' taking control of Congress and in 1996 pushing
legislation to again deregulate the cable industry. The Clinton
administration signed on, and the changes became law.
</P>
<P>
   The cable industry is approaching the new era carefully for fear
that prices will sharply escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our companies are very much aware that they need to act with
restraint,'' said Decker Anstrom, president of the National Cable
Television Association.
</P>
<P>
   But in the longer run, economics will have its say. The
three-year wait was designed to give the cable TV industry a chance
to develop competition to keep cable rates down.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that Martha Hogerty, Missouri's public counsel, has
heard before in other industries. Not long ago there was talk about
telephone companies offering cable TV, but not much came of it, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hype,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, satellite television is cable's competitor. Tom
Krewson, a spokesman for Jones Intercable in Independence, Mo.,
said that the majority of customers who decided to stop their cable
service with Jones said they were buying a satellite dish and that
more probably would do so if cable rates became too high.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite television has grown in the past five years with a new
service called direct broadcast, which allows pizza-size receiving
dishes to capture satellite signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a viable competitor to cable,'' said Robert Mercer, a
spokesman for DirecTV, the largest provider of satellite
television. Last year DirecTV bought a competitor, United States
Satellite Broadcasting Co. Inc., and DirecTV is in the process of
buying another one, Primestar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But satellite customers have equipment costs that cable
subscribers don't have. These receivers originally cost as much as
$700, but they are now available for less than $200 and often come
with discounted installation fees. Additional equipment costs can
be imposed when more than one television is equipped to receive
satellite signals.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite television also doesn't deliver local stations. A
separate antenna has to pick them up. Congress is considering
legislation that would permit satellite television to carry local
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman, of Consumers Union, said that because of some of
those costs and obstacles, satellite television was a more suitable
option for the economic ``upper tier'' cable customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only when satellite television or other providers offer the
vast majority of cable subscribers an alternative that meets their
needs will cable companies be forced to bring down prices,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
