<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCOY-COLUMN-PARRISTR     03-30 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN-PARRISTRADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major leagues a major letdown for Parris
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ The harsh and unfair realities of the business
side of baseball snarled at Steve Parris Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, the Cincinnati Reds decided they
didn't like Par(r)is in the spring-time.
</P>
<P>
   And this time it was undeserved.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after Parris held the world-champion New York
Yankees to no earned runs, two hits and struck out five in five
innings, he was handed the proverbial bus ticket to Indianapolis _
optioned to the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Parris wasn't facing a bunch of minor-leaguers, either, during
the Reds 4-2 victory in front of a standing-room only crowd of
7,517. Chuck Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez,
Jorge Posada, Shane Spencer, Chad Curtis and Scott Brosius waved
bats at Parris.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-year-old right-hander was victimized by two factors:
The Reds are keeping only 10 pitchers and Parris has options left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I won a spot, thought I pitched well enough to win a
spot,'' Parris said. ``Apparently not. I can't say what I really
think _ it'll get me in trouble. But I'm very disappointed. Because
I have options. . .no doubt that's why I'm out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   In six appearances this spring, Parris gave up only 10 earned
runs in 22.2 innings (3.97 earned run average), 26 hits, walked
only one until his six more Tuesday, and struck out 16.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, yes, Parris deserved the bus ride.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched twice for the Reds, giving up 11 hits and 10 earned
runs in only 1.1 innings, a 67.50 earned run average. Rather than
curse his misfortune, Parris lit 'em up in Indianapolis _ 6-1, 3.84
in 13 starts and was summoned back to Cincinnati, where he thought
he established squatter's rights.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last season, he was the most reliable starter _
5-2, 2.61 ERA in his last eight starts and that, alone, should have
placed him in this season's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Reds added Denny Neagle and Steve Avery, and they
need only four starters for nearly the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they needed to get me out of here now, because you
have to stay in the minors 10 days after you're optioned out, so if
they later need 11 pitchers they can get me back,'' Parris said.
``(General manager) Jim Bowden told me I would spend a lot time in
the big leagues this year. But I might not spend another day here
if they make another trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his start Tuesday against the Yankees, Parris said, ``It was
a rough one. I struggled. Six walks is terrible and my curve was
awful. . .and you can quote me. I'm not disappointed, though,
because I made pitches I had to make and got away basically
unscathed.''
</P>
<P>
   He did give up two unearned runs in the fifth when a wind-blown
drive by Jeter to right bounced off Dmitri Young's glove. But a
home run by Mark Sweeney tied it, 2-2, in the fifth, and the Reds
scored twice in the sixth on a two-run single by catcher Eddie
Taubensee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parris threw pretty good,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``He
walked too many guys, but he pitched a strong five innings. All of
our guys pitched pitched well. As I've said, we get decent
pitching, we win. . .even if we make too many errors (three) and
give up too many walks (six).''
</P>
<P>
   John Hudek pitched a scoreless inning, Danny Graves put up two
scoreless innings, and 23-year-old rookie Scott Williamson closed
it out in the ninth for his third save.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Parris pitched well. Now he'll have to do it in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
