<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0004 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-NOW-KAN &LR;      03-30 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NOW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR Y2K GLITCHES MAY OCCUR THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Forget about year 2000 computer problems causing
havoc at your New Year's Eve party or disrupting bowl games on Jan.
1, 2000. The biggest Y2K glitches may come this year around the
Fourth of July and Columbus Day.
</P>
<P>
   Although many computer problems are likely to occur on or after
Jan. 1, about 25 percent of all year 2000 computer problems will
occur before the new year, said Lou Marcoccio, one of the leading
researchers studying Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get asked all the time, `If I get up at 4 a.m. on Jan. 1, am
I going to see the lights going out for miles?' '' Marcoccio said.
``The failures are not going to happen at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, problems that occur this year _ including a few
possibly on Thursday _ have the greatest likelihood of disrupting
business.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of U.S. corporations and 46 states have fiscal
years that begin July 1. Marcoccio believes that will spark Y2K
problems that could disrupt key functions like payroll, billing and
inventory control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In July, the volume (of Y2K failures) is going to go up
dramatically, and in October it's going to go up even more,'' said
Marcoccio, research director for GartnerGroup, a Connecticut-based
research firm that has nine researchers studying the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, the federal government begins its fiscal year _ as do
another third of American corporations. In addition, three-month
computer forecasting programs will kick in, causing computers that
haven't been reprogrammed to get sidetracked while trying to make
sense of a new calendar year ending in ``00.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcoccio believes American companies are planning for problems
and shortages on Jan. 1 but haven't taken their planning to the
next step.
</P>
<P>
   He said about 5 percent of Y2K problems occurred before Jan. 1,
1999, 25 percent will occur this year, 55 percent will occur
throughout 2000, and 15 percent will crop up during 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 8 to 10 percent will be occurring within a two-week
period of Jan. 1, 2000,'' Marcoccio said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with four other Y2K specialists found that
in-the-trenches programmers are as concerned about the last six
months of the year as they are about Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts are watching more than 30 ``trigger dates'' but
several already have passed with few, or no, problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``1-1-99 was always a wild card,'' said Roleigh Martin, a
Minnesota consulting software engineer and Y2K author who has
listed 31 potential trigger dates.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems occurred as companies, government agencies and
schools made projections for the coming 12 months, ``but the word
on the programming street was that it was containable,'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Jan. 1, the focus shifted to Feb. 5, the day when travel
agents could begin selling airline tickets for Jan. 1, 2000. But
the nation's complex airline, hotel and cruise line reservation
system made the shift without a glitch.
</P>
<P>
   But experts aren't particularly encouraged that trigger dates
have caused few severe problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have rather seen a strong wakeup call on 1-1-99, so
that it would be an alert for Y2K, instead of being lulled into
thinking that nothing is going to happen,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts now are watching for some problems on Thursday, when
both the state of New York and Canada begin their fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
   New York has repaired six key computer systems that could have
been affected by the fiscal year changeover, said Gary Davis, a
spokesman for the New York State Office for Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Davis expects the day to pass without incident. ``We're most
focused on the end-of-year date,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another trigger date occurs on April 9, but experts believe the
rumors and speculation are far worse than the potential reality.
</P>
<P>
   April 9 is the 99th day of the year, and older computer programs
that ignore the month and only look at the number of days in the
year will read that as 1999-99.
</P>
<P>
   In some computer programs, especially older programs, a string
of nines is a signal for the computer to stop processing
information _ or even purge data.
</P>
<P>
   Another trigger date being discounted by experts is Sept. 9 _
``9-9-99.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sept. 9 has become urban legend,'' said Jim Lord, a Maryland
software consultant and author of ``A Survival Guide for the Year
2000 Problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because computers look for six numbers in the date field, Lord
said, they will read that date as 09-09-99, not as a string of
nines.
</P>
<P>
   But some trigger dates could cause problems:
</P>
<P>
   The first of every month for the rest of the year, as corporate
fiscal years begin.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1, as schools and colleges deal with records for classes
that will be completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31, 1999, which may have been used by programmers to
terminate programs or clear out data files.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also will be watching for problems throughout the last
quarter of 1999, particularly in December, as software companies
are forced to release Y2K-compliant software upgrades that haven't
been properly tested or debugged.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe many companies already have experienced year
2000 problems, but most of those have been minor and haven't
generated any notoriety outside information technology departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's going on in computer rooms around the
country,'' said Lane Core Jr., a Pennsylvania computer programmer
who writes about the Y2K problem. ``The last thing corporations
want anyone to know is that they're having Y2K problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Information Technology Association of America reported that
about half of American corporations had experienced some kind of
Y2K problem by March 25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond Jan. 1, researchers are focusing on one date in
particular _ Feb. 29, 2000, leap day.
</P>
<P>
   Computers that haven't been programmed to recognize the extra
day in February are likely to lock up, or refuse to process data
that day.
</P>
<P>
   But Lord said leap year 2000 isn't worth worrying about.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that time,'' he said, ``we are either likely to realize Y2K
is not a serious problem, or be so jaundiced to all these systems
failing it doesn't matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
