<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NUHNCOLUMN-FINAL4     03-30 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHNCOLUMN-FINAL4FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Same story, different teams
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ We have seen this story before, as
recently as two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coach brings his team to the Final Four. Coach has reputation
that he can't win the big one. Coach wins game anyway and expunges
the tag he didn't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago it was Lute Olson and Arizona. The Men of Cactus
had a long history of losing when they should and losing when they
shouldn't in the NCAA Tournament, the common thread being the
losing.
</P>
<P>
   But one magical March night in Indianapolis, Arizona beat
Kentucky in overtime, and Olson's career was notarized.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night in Tropicana Field, the dome with the Leaning Tower
of Florida roof, Jim Calhoun rewrote Olson's story almost word for
word. Calhoun's Connecticut Huskies took down favored Duke for
college basketball's national championship and removed the shroud
that had been fastened to his resume (12 NCAA appearances, 12
exits).
</P>
<P>
   The two coaches have more in common than just winning national
titles after repeated failures.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's father died when he was 5; Calhoun's when he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   Both were college basketball stars in obscure places _ Olson at
Augsburg College in Minneapolis; Calhoun at American International
College in Springfield, Mass. Both traveled the high school
coaching trail before finding a hole and crawling into the college
game, Olson at Long Beach (Calif.) City College; Calhoun at
Northeastern in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, although players win games, Calhoun
outcoached Duke's Mike Krzyzewski, the man considered college
basketball's best.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was able to both double-team Duke's inside hulk,
Elton Brand, and also defend the three-point arc. In general, a
team can do one or the other but not both. That Coach K hasn't yet
taught Brand to pass figured prominently.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Krzyzewski was a victim of his allegiance to his
favorite player, Trajan Langdon. ``Absolutely, positively, we were
going to win or lose with Trajan,'' Coach K said.
</P>
<P>
   But that strategy ignored Langdon's single weakness _ quickness.
Langdon is a great college player, but he's not going to beat a
good, quick defender one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Duke had been in so few close games _ its average margin
of victory was 26 _ that it had almost no experience in tight,
end-game situations.
</P>
<P>
   So down one point, 75-74, inside 20 seconds, Coach K went to his
leader, Langdon, for better or worse. The problem is that didn't
take into account that UConn's Ricky Moore is one of the nation's
best defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon dribbled to the left of the key, but Moore cut him off.
Langdon then turned his back to the basket and tried a spin move
into the lane, but picked up the ball too quickly and traveled as
he spun.
</P>
<P>
   With one more chance, down 77-74, Duke repeated the same
mistake. With 5.2 seconds left, the ball was inbounded in the deep
backcourt, again to Langdon, again with Moore harassing him.
</P>
<P>
   The only ways to get the ball upcourt in 5.2 seconds are with a
long pass or with a quick guard who can't be cut off. Langdon was
cut off twice by Moore, forced to change directions and he
eventually lost the ball just after coming across centercourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no better coach than I was three weeks ago and no worse,''
Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   No, but like Olson in 1997, he's a lighter one. The rap of not
being able to win the big one has been left in the hot sun of
Florida, never to be seen or heard again.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
