<HEADLINE>
DON JOHNSON'S SAN FRANCISCO SINECURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Don Johnson &LR; 's coasting along in ``Nash Bridges,'' wrote  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Brownfield &LR;  in a profile in Sunday's Los Angeles Times, but his
acting career's in a ``peculiar state of limbo.'' Never mind: He's
engaged, he's employed, he's edgy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnson on Johnson's work: ``There aren't any of those
(expletive) actors that are better than me. None of them. Nobody.
Not De Niro, not Brando, not Jack, not anybody. I have the goods.
They have the material.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnson on Johnson's drinking rehabs: ``Life's too short not
to enjoy a good bottle of wine. ... One of the definitions of
alcoholism is, does it make your life unmanageable. ... For me, and
only for me, I have found a place that I'm comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnson on Johnson's fiancee, Kelley Phleger: ``That woman
doesn't care about anything else in the world except me. And her
love for me and my love for her and our babies. My babies, with any
of my other relationships. She's an angel woman.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnson on Johnson's admirers: ``You walk out there on that
street right now, go up to two people, ask them what they feel
about Don Johnson. You got a 50-50 chance of someone saying, `Who?'
and the other person saying, `He's a god.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONNIE CHUNG LENDS HIM HER EAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A ``very special moment'' on the A &LR; pril 1 &LR;  installment of
``Maury'' is described in an advance press release:
</P>
<P>
   Host Maury Povich's guest is Adam, a 13-year-old dyslexic boy
who says he has no friends. ``The only thing Adam's confident about
is playing the piano, and his one lifelong dream has been to play
the piano for  &UR; Connie Chung &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Through the magic of television and the miracle of
marriage, ``Adam gets the surprise of his life when Maury walks
Connie into the studio.'' Much puddling up is forecast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chris Jehle  &LR; and his partner were having dinner at Spago in
West Hollywood over the weekend when the maitre d' stopped by their
table to ask how everything was. They reported that the food was
excellent but the waiter had too much attitude.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later the waiter stopped by to offer his apology:
``I'm sorry if you think I'm cold and aloof, but I'm in the midst
of an apartment search.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Raquel Welch &LR; , who said she was an expert because she'd been
taking them for years, testified last week about the regulation of
nutritional supplements to a House subcommittee on government
reform.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sir  &UR; Nigel Hawthorne &LR; , a British actor, revealed to the Mirror
last week that when he was knighted by  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR; , she
thought he was the character he had played _ Sir Humphrey Appleby,
a civil servant _ in a British TV series that had a long run in the
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   The actor said that when the queen encountered him at theatrical
events after that, she would ask him what he was doing there. ``And
I'd say, `I work here,' and she'd say `You do? ''
</P>
