u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      03-30 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRO APPEALS FOR HUMANITARIAN AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ As NATO warplanes roared overhead in an
intensified bombing campaign against the regime of Slobodan
Milosevic, the republic of Montenegro appealed Tuesday night for
humanitarian aid to cope with the masses of refugees flooding
across its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Help is needed to feed, shelter, and provide emergency medical
care for the ethnic Albanian refugees pouring in from the
neighboring province of Kosovo, said officials here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is getting so much worse it is now impossible to
care for the huge numbers of innocent people,'' said Health
Minister Miomir Mugosa, as air-raid sirens blasted and the
occasional crack of anti-aircraft fire reverberated from nearby
mountains. ``We cannot especially cope with even those who have
come to us in just the past 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugosa implored the American Red Cross to provide ``urgently and
desperately needed'' aid, an explicit request and a signal that
Montenegro regards the Serb-dominated regime in Belgrade, not
American warplanes, as the real villain in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing numbers of refugees surging into Montenegero seemed
to confirm reports that the neighboring nation of Macedonia to the
south was closing its borders to desperate Albanians seeking to
flee the killing grounds of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rampaging Serb paramilitary forces have uprooted tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanians and killed numbers of them in a
brutal campaign of ethnic cleansing that NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
described as ``a modern-day great terror,'' according to refugee
accounts and scattered reports from inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Podgorica and Western diplomats said Tuesday that
the greatest numbers of refugees are now apparently heading to
Montenegro, not Macedonia or their ancestral homeland of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible change,'' Mugosa said, ``and if the world
will not come to the rescue of the victims we are trying to help,
the suffering will be even more terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some international relief agencies appeared to be responding
Tuesday to the human disaster spiraling out of control in the
Balkans. Most aid workers fled Yugoslavia at the outset of
hostilities on March 24, but Tuesday a small column of vehicles
from the UN High Commissioner for Refugees made its way Tuesday
into the war zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Yugoslavia is going from bad to disastrous,''
said Jann DeKerk, a Dutch aid worker in a convoy of relief
vechicles that crossed at dawn into the embattled country at a
remote mountain pass from Croatia. ``In a sense, we are hoping to
do the same thing the military from the US and Europe is hoping to
do _ save Albanians from the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it may be the world is again too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling along on foot or carried by horse-drawn cart, dazed
refugees from Kosovo were crossing into Montenegro at an estimated
rate of about 1,000 per hour, a stunning influx for a tiny province
with a population of only about 600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro officals fear that the arrival of so many ethnic
Albanians will trigger violence in a region that thus far has been
spared the murderous furies that have made the Balkans a byword for
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees entering the province have generally been treated
kindly by local officials and guarded by police. But tensions have
been exacerbated by NATO airstrikes against military facilities in
Montenegro, and by increasing numbers of people starting to despise
the US and Western Europe as a common enemy _ and blaming Kosovo
Albanians for bringing on the attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
