<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-TAX-REJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE HOUSE REJECTS INCOME TAX BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire's House of Representatives, facing
a Thursday deadline to come up with a plan to fund public schools
more equitably, rejected a bill Tuesday to impose the state's first
income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The 211-to-168 vote all but ensures that the state will not meet
the April 1 deadline imposed by the state Supreme Court 15 months
ago when it ruled that the current system of paying for public
education mainly through local property taxes is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   With defeat of the income tax measure in the House, where
Republicans hold the majority, the Democrat-controlled Senate will
now try to fashion a compromise that may include business taxes, an
increase in the cigarette tax, and an expansion of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Any plan will either have to win the approval of Governor Jeanne
Shaheen, or muster enough support in the Legislature to sustain the
two-thirds majority needed to override a Shaheen veto. In both her
campaigns for governor, Shaheen took New Hampshire's traditional
pledge to veto any broad-based tax, and during the current crisis
she has repeatedly said she would reject any income tax proposal.
But Shaheen also has been under intense pressure from longtime
supporters who consider an income tax the fairest way to reform a
system that has led to some of the highest property tax rates in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Representative Elizabeth Hager, a prime sponsor of
the income tax bill, which would have established a 3.5 percent
levy, said Shaheen deserves 90 percent of the blame for Tuesday's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes we are losing are people who all say that they know
this is the best solution but they don't want to delay things, or
they'll say, `I don't want to embarass the governor.' And those are
Republicans saying that,'' Hager said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's proponents tried to persuade legislators to vote for
it despite the governor's opposition. Tuesday, subdued lawmakers
slowly took their places before the vote to hear Representative
Jean Wallin, an income tax supporter, say, ``Today, we do the
political equivalent of a root canal.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wall Street bond rating services watching and the
collection of the school portion of local property taxes due to
become illegal Thursday, a plan based on one proposed by Shaheen
has been evolving, but is not yet on paper.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said to contain increased taxes on business,
legalization of video slot machines, increased cigarette taxes, a
capital gains tax, and an unspecified entertainment tax. Despite
Tuesday's vote, all options, including an income tax, remain at
least remote possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the House narrowly passed a version of the
income tax bill. The Senate then modified it and returned it to the
House. This time, however, Shaheen joined Republican House Speaker
Donna Sytek to help kill a measure that would have ended what many
call ``the New Hampshire advantage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
