<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE.COM GOES WHERE NO WEB COMPANY HAS GONE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Priceline.Com, the Web site that hired Star Trek's
William Shatner as its pitchman, saw its stock price fly off to a
distant galaxy in its first day of trading Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's shares jumped from an offering price of $16 a share
on the Nasdaq market to a high of $85 before setting at $69, a more
than fourfold increase. That gives Priceline, which lets consumers
bid on airline tickets, cars and other items, a market value of
$9.8 billion, the highest first-day value ever achieved by an
Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline, which lost $114 million last year selling $35 million
worth of airline tickets, is now worth more than United Airlines,
Continental Airlines and Northwest Airlines combined. That value is
all the more astounding because Priceline has only been in business
for 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   That did not stop Morgan Stanley, the lead underwriter, from
doubling the proposed price, to give the company a value of $2.3
billion in the offering of 10 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has accorded Jay Walker, Priceline's founder,
paper wealth of $4.3 billion. Walker's previous claim to fame was
that he started Newsub services, which sells magazine subscriptions
in credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   The offering comes amid a buying frenzy in the shares of nearly
any company involved in the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what these companies do or how they are
priced,'' said David Simons, who runs Digital Video Investments, an
advisory service. ``Each new Internet IPO is nothing more than red
meat to the mad dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   But a number of analysts praised the company for its unique
sales method. Priceline calls itself a ``demand collection system''
in which customers name the price they want to pay for a trip to a
certain city, for a certain model car and so on. If Priceline can
find someone willing to sell what the customer wants at the
specified price, the customer is committed to buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Priceline's business model,'' said Peony Kao, an
analyst with Renaissance Capital, which runs a mutual fund that
invests in initial public offerings. ``It can be expanded from
airline tickets to loans, cars and a lot of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kao said she was impressed with Priceline's growth, with
revenues expected to increase fivefold this year to $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has a lot of potential,'' she said, ``but whether
it's worth $10 billion remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet companies, Priceline has spent far more on
building its systems and marketing than it has generated in
revenue. But the nature of its business adds a number of unusual
risks.
</P>
<P>
   It's biggest constraint has been the unwillingness of most major
airlines to undercut their existing prices by selling through
Priceline. Priceline had tried to make the restrictions for buying
tickets so onerous that it would not attract any high-margin
business travelers. For example, buyers have to be willing to fly
at any time on the travel day they specify, on any airline, and to
accept at least one change of planes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, only TWA and America West sold tickets through the
service at first. Last fall, Northwest and Delta agreed to
participate. But in order to induce Delta to join, Priceline
granted it warrants to buy 18.9 million shares of the company's
stock, a stake worth $1.3 billion on Tuesday, or 13 percent of
Delta's $10 billion market value.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the addition of these airlines, Priceline was only
able to sell about 25 percent of what it termed ``reasonable
bids,'' which it defines as those no more than 30 percent less than
the lowest fare for a particular route. And to satisfy even that
many customers, the company has had to sell many of its tickets for
prices below what it pays the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to make up some of those losses selling credit
cards and other products to people while they are bidding. The
company's prospectus indicates that even these moves may not be
enough to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are unlikely to make significant profits unless we make new
or complementary products and services and a broader range of
existing products and services available through the Priceline
service,'' the company wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other people have found near instant paper wealth as
a result of the Priceline offering.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Braddock, the former president of Citicorp, who became
Priceline's chief executive last August, now owns shares worth $980
million.
</P>
<P>
   General Atlantic Partners, a venture capital firm in Greenwich,
Conn., saw its $28 million investment turn into a stake worth $1.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Nicholas Jr., the former co-cheif executive of
Time-Warner, owns stock worth $264 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
