<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HINTS AT INDEPENDENCE FOR KOSOVO AS ULTIMATE AIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE,
KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton warned Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic on Tuesday that he was increasingly jeopardizing
his claim to keep Kosovo as a province of Yugoslavia with his
assault on the ethnic Albanian population there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that atrocities by Serbian forces in Kosovo would
put at risk international support for a plan that would keep Kosovo
an autonomous part of Serb-dominated Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The president said, ``He will see that his military will be
seriously diminished, key military infrastructure destroyed, the
prospect for international support for Serbia's claim to Kosovo
increasingly jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to pursue air attacks against Serbian targets in
Yugoslavia until Milosevic ceases the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever any doubt about what is at stake in Kosovo,
Mr. Milosevic is certainly erasing it by his actions,'' Clinton
said at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the culmination of more than a decade of using ethnic
and religious hatred as a justification for uprooting and murdering
completely innocent peaceful civilians to pave Mr. Milosevic's path
to absolute power,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a later statement, the president firmly rejected a proposal
from Milosevic to withdraw some of his forces from Kosovo in
exchange for a halt in allied bombing. Clinton called the offer
``unacceptable'' and said peace would come only when Milosevic
ended what the United States says is a campaign of terror in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of a peace agreement signed this month at
Rambouillet, France, by Kosovar Albanians but not by Milosevic,
Kosovo would gain autonomy for three years from the central
Yugoslav government in Belgrade. NATO forces would guarantee the
agreement. After that, the two sides would negotiate Kosovo's
long-term status.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and European nations who oversaw the peace
talks have consistently opposed immediate independence for Kosovo,
a province whose population is 90 percent ethnic Albanian. Western
leaders have said they do not want to see the further dismemberment
of the remnants of Yugoslavia into a collection of small ethnic
states with limited economic prospects and no history of
self-government.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said previously that the only way to
guarantee that Kosovo remained part of Yugoslavia was for Milosevic
to accept the autonomy arrangement that was being negotiated at
Rambouillet. The alternative, officials have said, is continuing
insurgency by Albanian separatists and intervention by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton suggested publicly for the first time since the
allied bombing began last week that the Western position was
shifting toward independence for Kosovo under some sort of
international protection.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said that Clinton did
not intend to announce a new policy Tuesday. Rather, Lockhart said,
the president was describing a change in world opinion as Serbian
fighting spreads through Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not our policy that Kosovo should be independent,''
Lockhart said. ``But Milosevic's continuing on a campaign of
atrocities had radicalized the people to such an extent that he
forfeits any claim to it and loses international support for Kosovo
remaining part of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivo Daalder, a Balkan specialist at the Brookings Institution
who formerly served on the National Security Council, said that
Clinton was making an implicit promise to protect ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo from Serbian atrocities. The only realistic way to
accomplish that, Daalder said, is by creating an enclave in Kosovo
protected by NATO and American forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a widening of the war aims, but bringing the war aims
to their logical conclusion,'' Daalder said. ``The only way we can
fulfill our political objectives is by giving the Kosovars a
territory of their own. My only regret is that we should have made
this an explicit claim from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also said Tuesday that the American and NATO air
attacks would continue until Milosevic's ability to carry out his
campaign of repression was ``seriously diminished'' and critical
parts of his military machinery were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allies are united in our outrage over President
Milosevic's atrocities against innocent people,'' Clinton said
Tuesday. ``We are determined to stay with our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the Serbian offensive was planned before the
NATO air strikes began a week ago. He accused Milosevic of
pretending to negotiate with Kosovar Albanians and European leaders
this winter even as he moved ``from village to village and atrocity
to atrocity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is clear that as the Kosovar leaders were saying yes to
peace,'' Clinton said, ``Mr. Milosevic was planning a new campaign
of expulsions and executions in Kosovo. He started carrying out
that plan as the talks ended, increasing our sense of urgency that
the air strikes NATO had threatened for some time must begin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
