<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CLINICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING IN SALVI ATTACKS IS CALLED POSITIVE FOR CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART AND PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jury verdict this week absolving a landlord of liability in
the December 1994 attack on two Brookline abortion clinics sends a
powerful message that clinics _ and the property owners who rent to
them _ are not responsible for the unpredictable acts of
``terrorists,'' providers and advocates said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinics are prepared for levels of violence, but can you say
that such an act is foreseeable?'' said Vicki Saporta, executive
director of the National Abortion Federation in Washington, D.C,
which has more than 350 members. ``Clinics should not be held
liable for the actions of terrorists, which by their nature are
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   In a swift verdict, a Norfolk, Mass., Superior Court jury on
Monday absolved the owners of a Brookline building of
responsibility for gunman John Salvi's attack on abortion clinic
security guard Richard J. Seron of Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated for slightly more than two hours, including
the lunch hour, before ruling that 1842 Beacon Street Associates
was not negligent for failing to ensure that Preterm Health
Services, where Seron worked, had a uniformed police officer on
duty at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at the clinics in December 1994 was a violent
tragedy,'' said Ellen Zucker, a Boston lawyer and president of the
local chapter of the National Organization for Women at the time of
the shootings. ``The question is who should bear the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Seron, 49, the security guard who was wounded by a .22-caliber
bullet fired by Salvi on Dec. 30, 1994, claimed in a lawsuit that
the landlord should have enforced a condition of its lease with
Preterm requiring the clinic to hire a uniformed police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Walton, a second security guard on duty that day who was
not wounded, settled with the landlord for an undisclosed amount
before the case went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Seron nor his lawyer, Michael J. Heineman, returned
telephone calls Tuesday seeking comment. But in an interview with
The Patriot Ledger, Seron said the landlord tried to settle out of
court for $200,000, but Seron wanted $350,000. Seron said his
numerous media interviews, as well as a proposed book and
screenplay and his prison correspondence with Salvi, turned the
jury against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have been cheated and I am bitter about it,''
said Seron, adding that he has not been able to work since the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Franchek, the attorney who represented 1842 Beacon
Street Associates, declined to comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the rampage, Seron was guarding the second clinic
Salvi invaded that day. Earlier, Salvi had gone into the Planned
Parenthood Clinic, also on Beacon Street, and killed receptionist
Shannon Lowney. He then drove to Preterm and killed receptionist
Leanne Nichols. He also wounded five people, including Seron. Seron
fired at Salvi but missed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits that target clinics and their landlords are a new, and
distasteful, phenomenon, said advocates. But Saporta and a lawyer
for the federation said they were unaware of suits like Seron's,
where juries were asked to decide whether clinics or their
landlords are liable for violence by a third party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
