<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS WORRIES FORCE DOW TO RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average retreated from its
one-day perch above 10,000 Tuesday on renewed concerns about
corporate earnings, as other major market measures also slipped.
</P>
<P>
   The worries about first-quarter earnings were set off when
Coca-Cola told securities analysts after the closing bell on Monday
that it expected world-wide sales to show a slight decline in the
first quarter. It cited weakness in each of its international
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Later, an analyst at Goldman Sachs lowered her first-quarter
sales estimates for Gillette, citing weak demand in foreign
markets. And investors were not pleased to read in The Wall Street
Journal on Tuesday that at a meeting with securities analysts,
General Motors' president, G. Richard Wagoner, had said that the
automaker was not likely to meet its most optimistic target for net
income for its European operations.
</P>
<P>
   Additional weakness developed in the afternoon, when an Oregon
jury ordered Philip Morris to pay a record $81 million to the
family of a man who died of lung cancer after smoking Marlboros for
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Those developments outweighed the Federal Reserve Board's
announcement that its policy-making committee had voted to leave
short-term interest rates unchanged. The decision had been widely
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are coming under pressure,'' said Anthony Conroy, head
of stock trading at Bankers Trust. ``Traders and portfolio managers
are looking for earnings to support these prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals are fairly strong,'' he added. ``Inflation is
low, and so are interest rates. But I would not be surprised to see
a 2 percent to 3 percent correction before the market moves
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow had fallen 93.52, or 0.93 percent, to
9,913.26. Meanwhile, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index dipped 9.42,
or 0.72 percent, to 1,300.75, and the Nasdaq composite index lost
12.55, or 0.50 percent, to 2,480.29. The Russell 2000 index of
small company stocks declined .98, or 0.2 percent, to 398.79.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was quite light, with about 729.03 million shares
changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange. With equity markets
scheduled to be closed on Good Friday, the pace of activity is
likely to slow further as the week, which includes Passover,
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when the Dow closed above 10,000 for the first time,
``it was almost as if investors decided for one day to ignore all
the problems we face,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer
at First Albany Corp. ``Coke's announcement means the global
economic crisis was still around in the first quarter, and was a
reminder we are entering the earnings season, which can be a very
treacherous time.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke, down 1 9/16 at 63 1/4, and Philip Morris, off 3 7/16, to
37 3/4, were the biggest contributors to the Dow's drop Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gillette, a component of the S&AMP;P 500 index, shed 3
3/8, to 60 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of America Online, the most active stock on the New York
Stock Exchange, soared 12 points to close at 144 1/2, after the
company announced an Internet commerce alliance with Sun
Microsystems. Sun Microsystems gained 1 7/16, to 125 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet stocks also gained.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com jumped 15 1/16 to 164 11/16 on optimism about its
fledgling online auction business.
</P>
<P>
   And Priceline.com, which runs an Internet site where consumers
bid for airline tickets and hotel rooms, catapulted 53, to 69 a
share, in its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous activity and strong demand in the Internet
stocks,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, which was the lead manager on the Priceline
offering. ``But with prices quite high in certain sectors of the
market, it is quite reasonable to seem some consolidation,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
