<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      03-30 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYMIED, U.S. URGES BOMBING OF BELGRADE SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Acknowledging that airstrikes have failed to
halt the assault in Kosovo or sufficiently damage the Serb
military, the United States on Tuesday urged NATO to authorize an
escalated campaign that could target government buildings in
downtown Belgrade, Western officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such attacks, which could include government centers like the
interior and defense ministry buildings in the Serbian capital as
well military targets elsewhere in the country, would represent a
major change in tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, NATO has largely limited its bombing to air defense
systems, factories and defense installations on the outskirts of
Belgrade and forces directly involved in the Kosovo campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that even an expanded bombing campaign would be
considerably less violent than the airstrikes aimed at the
political leadership of Iraq during the Gulf War when American
bombers targeted Saddam Hussein's palaces and the headquarters of
his political party. Officials said, however, that any attacks on
the densely populated center of Belgrade would require pinpoint
accuracy to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   American officials appeared hopeful that the request for
authority to bomb a much broader range of targets throughout
Yugoslavia, made at a closed door meeting of NATO ambassadors,
would be granted, diplomats reported. But NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana said in an interview that he was not convinced the
time had come to dramatically broaden the strikes, reflecting
continued strains within the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The American move to escalate the combat came on a downbeat day
here, as NATO's commanders received bad news from every direction.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces continued to advance virtually unopposed on the
battlefield and the refugee crisis threatened to spiral out of
control, with NATO officials estimating that one-third of the 1.8
million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo had been forced from their
homes. The alliance was forced to beat back an attempt by Russian
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to open negotiations on terms
dictated by President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO official said Tuesday night that the alliance
raids had been stymied by a Yugoslavian air defense that has proved
more resilient than anticipated, new tactics that involved
dispersing Milosevic's forces in the field and extremely bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the alliance was eagerly waiting to deploy
A-10 ground attack planes that they hoped would strike directly at
Serbian troops in Kosovo and knock out tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The A-10s took off Tuesday but returned without attacking their
targets because of thick clouds and rain, a NATO official said. The
A-10s could not fly below the clouds because of the risk of
exposure to anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had an impact on the infrastructure, but the impact on
their operations is a different matter,'' the NATO official said.
``Whether we can stop it or not we'll find out. A lot of people
have real doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   With the alliance excluding the use of ground forces, airpower
appeared to be the only tool NATO has to influence the Yugoslav
leadership. But the air attacks have been constrained by political
considerations, despite the West's increasingly vociferous charges
that Milosevic is engaged in a brutal campaign of ``ethnic
cleansing'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the bombing plan was developed months ago
when alliance officials anticipated that a modest air raid or two
would be enough to nudge a recalcitrant Milosevic back to the
negotiating table. But the scale and intensity of the Serb attacks
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have caught the alliance by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even we have been shocked by the sheer enormity of what is
going on in Kosovo at the moment,'' said Jamie Shea, the NATO
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with hundreds of thousands of refugees and reports of
murders, NATO's planners have begun to talk belatedly about the
need to ``adapt'' their bombing plan.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, officials say, has a three-part bombing plan. The
first stage is to attack Yugoslav's anti-aircraft systems, an
effort that is still under way.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase, which has recently been launched, involves
strikes on the Serb forces south of Yugoslavia's 44th parallel,
units which have been pressing the attack against the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a third, more aggressive phase of the NATO
bombing plan, which officials here have been reluctant to discuss
in detail and which had not previously been approved.
</P>
<P>
   It would give NATO commanders the authority to launch a broader
range of attacks against Yugoslavia's military leaders, command and
control centers, weapons depots, heavy weapons and fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The American proposal to expand air attacks came as Serb forces
continue to press their attacks against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, NATO officials estimated that 118,000 ethnic Albanians
had been forced out of Kosovo since March 24. Serb tanks have been
surrounding villages and towns. Women and children have been
separated from the men and then forcibly bused to the frontier.
Afterwards, their homes are burned to the ground so that they
cannot return.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Pec, which used to have a population of some
100,000, has now been almost totally destroyed. Along with the
daily handouts touting its airstrikes, the NATO press office now
distributes a daily report on ``City Torching'' by Serb forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0331-     03-30 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO TARGETING SERB TROOPS, POLICE WITH LOW-FLYING HARDWARE IN
'PHASE III'
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia entered
their second week on Wednesday, the weather-hampered mission
appeared to be shifting dramatically from a surgical campaign
targeting equipment and buildings to a harrowing assault on flesh
and bone.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of the supersonic B-1 and its cargo of
armor-piercing cluster bombs, ground-buzzing A-10 tank busters,
weather-proof surveillance drones and possibly even Apache attack
helicopters, NATO seems ready to take its punches directly to the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   After a week in which harsh weather conditions have given
Serbian troops and thugs cover to rampage across the towns and
villages of Kosovo, the landscape is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   With NATO and American officials continuing to rule out the use
of ground troops in Kosovo, the new mix of NATO aircraft into the
war zone suggests the next phase of the assault on Yugoslavia will
target enemy soldiers in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are increasingly going after the (Serbian) army and the
(Serbian) police,'' Rear Adm. Thomas Wilson, director of
intelligence for the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, said at the
Pentagon late Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's comments came hours after it was disclosed that five
B-1B Lancer bombers are being sent from Ellsworth Air Force Base,
S.D., to beef up the NATO bombing mission and that A-10 Warthog
planes are being moved from European locations to an area closer to
Kosovo, Yugoslavia' southernmost province.
</P>
<P>
   Both aircraft would significantly enhance NATO's ability to
strike at troops on the ground in Kosovo. The B-1B is capable of
carrying 30 anti-armor cluster bombs and is effective in striking
concentrations of troops. The low-flying, hard-diving A-10 carries
up to eight tons of ordnance and is extremely effective against
slow-moving ground targets, such as tanks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO is enhancing its surveillance capabilities in
the region to help pinpoint targets and monitor Serb troop
movements. It soon will begin using Predator surveillance aircraft,
computer-controlled drones that transmit live images to ground
controllers. It already has at least two E-8C Joint Stars, an
airborne surveillance system capable of detecting troop movements
as far away as 120 miles. The Joint Stars system was instrumental
in tracking Iraqi troops and Scud missiles in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon's acknowledgement that it is considering the
use of Apache helicopters in Kosovo is the clearest indication that
the smaller units of Serbian ground troops are to be struck harder
in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Apache comes the closest to being a firepower system that
would be able to find and engage small units effectively without
having ground troops there,'' said David Ochmanek, a former Deputy
Assistant Secretary of Defense for Strategy and currently a senior
defense analyst at the Rand Corp.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell Douglas's Apache helicopter, which was used heavily
against Iraqi tanks in the Gulf War, is widely regarded as the most
lethal and survivable helicopter in military aviation history. It
is capable of operating during the day or night. It is equipped
with anti-tank missiles, rocket launchers and a 30 millimeter
automatic cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the Apache helicopter in Kosovo would require approval by
NATO's political arm, the North Atlantic Council, according to
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. Introducing the Apache to the
Kosovo war zone would indicate an escalation of the conflict, a
``Phase Three'' of ``Operation: Allied Force,'' the formal name of
the NATO bombing mission.
</P>
<P>
   All of the new weapons en route to Kosovo -- or under
consideration by NATO for use against the Serbs -- are capable of
operating in adverse weather conditions, an increasingly important
factor in NATO planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather has not been great, but there are pockets of
better weather, or less bad weather, that allows us to attack
certain targets under certain conditions,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Admiral Scott Fry, director of operations for the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said weather and geography have been the
``two main allies'' of the Serbian ground troops. He acknowledged
that the weather has gotten ``more difficult'' with each successive
night of bombing, with laser-guided weapons affected the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had instances where sorties were unable to complete
their missions in their target areas because they were weathered
out,'' he said during the Pentagon briefing with Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he insisted, ``we have managed to get packages into the
target area every night.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
