<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GENOCIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENOCIDE TREATY COULD BE BASIS FOR MILITARY INTERVENTION, EXPERT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(th) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Genocide, which the State Department has accused
Yugoslavia of committing in Kosovo, is one of the most
emotion-laden words in diplomacy and international law.
</P>
<P>
   It is defined in a treaty that was promulgated after World War
II in response to the Holocaust and signed by both the United
States and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, known as the Convention on Prevention and Punishment
of the Crime of Genocide, defines genocide in such a way that
offenses need not rise to the level of the Holocaust to be covered.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations made genocide a crime in 1946, and the treaty
went into force in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty's critics have contended that the definition is too
broad and open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   Genocide is defined in the treaty as ``any of the following acts
committed with intent to destroy, in whole or in part, a national,
ethnic, racial or religious group, such as: a) killing members of
the group; b) causing serious bodily or mental harm to members of
the group; c) deliberately inflicting on the group conditions of
life calculated to bring about its physical destruction in whole or
in part; d) imposing measures intended to prevent births within the
group; e) forcibly transferring children of the group to another
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Although rape is not explicitly included in the behavior covered
by the treaty, most scholars have come to accept it _ especially
systematic rape of a population _ as a form of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty allows individuals charged with genocide to be
prosecuted as war criminals and obliges signers to prevent genocide
within their borders. It does not provide for any armed
intervention by a country or alliance to prevent or stop genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Gidon A.G. Gottlieb, a professor of international law at the
University of Chicago, said, however, that the treaty could be
useful in defining the kind of violations of human rights that
would justify armed intervention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0043 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNEEZE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNEEZE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A Nose for Business
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A boutique is set to open next week on San Francisco's upscale
Union Street that specializes in something other than antiques,
apparel and edibles.
</P>
<P>
   Gazoontite, the brainchild of former Clorox brand manager
Soon-Chart Yu, will sell a full line of products to help folks
breathe better.
</P>
<P>
   The allergy business is nothing to sneeze at. Each year,
Americans spend more than $6 billion on medications, respiratory
devices, cleaners, filters and other products to clean the air and
clear their lungs and sinuses.
</P>
<P>
   But the launch of Gazoontite is not so much a tale of numbers as
it is about what it takes to create a new business. For Yu, 33, it
culminates years of planning and sacrifice. It meant switching
careers, returning to school to get an MBA degree, becoming a
manager at a giant consumer products company and then taking a job
as a low-paid retail clerk to gain sales experience.
</P>
<P>
   His persistence illustrates the extent to which people will go
to become entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Yu didn't always dream of waging war against allergens. He was
born in Taiwan, and at 3 he moved to Davis, where his dad was an
agricultural geneticist. Yu received a degree in electrical
engineering from the University of California at Davis and then
worked at Advanced Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   But he yearned to deal more with people than computers, and he
went to work at the Bain &AMP; Co. consulting firm in San Francisco.
For nearly two years, he thought it was fun wearing a suit and tie
and having an office in a downtown highrise. But it slowly dawned
on Yu that he wanted to create his own business.
</P>
<P>
   But before doing so, he figured he needed a lot more experience.
Yu received an MBA from Stanford University's vaunted business
school in 1993 and then went to Clorox to gain more general
management experience.
</P>
<P>
   As a brand manager for toilet bowl and Formula 409 cleaners for
four years, Yu said he enjoyed not only the profit-and-loss
responsibilities, but the pressure to stay on top of consumer
trends. One of these, he discovered, was America's increasing
interest in air quality.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the time Yu, who comes from a family of allergy
sufferers, began to think of opening his own business to help
people with their allergies.
</P>
<P>
   But before he could do that, Yu figured there was one more
important lesson he needed to learn, namely how to be a salesman.
So in late 1997, he left his management position at Clorox to take
a ``sales associate'' job for six months at Crate &AMP; Barrel. Yu said
he took an 85 percent pay cut but gained a wealth of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you get into a new field like retailing, it is
important to try it out,'' he explained. ``I was surprised by how
demanding it was both physically and emotionally. After seven hours
on your feet, you still have to treat the person coming in the door
the same as you would the first customer of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   To assure himself that his allergy-products concept would work,
Yu then conducted market research. Rather than paying someone else
to conduct a survey and paying malls for the right to interview
their patrons. Yu simply showed up at shopping centers in Corta
Madera, Stonestown and Stanford and queried shoppers until mall
managers kicked him out.
</P>
<P>
   Next was the challenge of what to call the business. Gesundheit,
which in German means health, was Yu's first choice. But most
people couldn't pronounce or spell it correctly, so he went with a
phonetic translation.
</P>
<P>
   Then he wrote a business plan and sounded out investors. Yu
raised $1.1 million, largely from wealthy individual investors and
Baccharis Capital, a Menlo Park venture capital firm that
specializes in socially responsible, consumer-product related
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Yu maintains that his shop will fill an important niche in the
market. Although many products _ from inhalers to vacuum cleaners
to bedding supplies _ are available to allergy sufferers, he said
it is difficult to find them all at the same store.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the online side of the business to compete with.
One-stop shopping now is possible through a dozen or so catalog,
mail-order and online merchants such as Allergy Control Products
and Priorities. Yu, however, said there's a drawback to the online
approach: Consumers can't touch and test the products before they
buy, or get quick answers to their questions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Abba Terr, a medical adviser to the company and director of
the allergy clinic at the Stanford University Medical School,
believes that there is a real need for a store like Yu's. ``Twenty
to 30 percent of the population is allergic to something and need
gadgets as well as medications,'' he said. ``They can get these
things by mail order, but I think it's important that a retail
store can also provide information.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazoontite's tiny staff includes Cindi Ersek, another former
Clorox brand manager.
</P>
<P>
   Among its wares, Gazoontite will sell Honeywell's new Quietcare
air purifier, which reportedly is 30 percent more quiet than other
models, for $160; Miele and Nilfisk vacuum cleaners, including
backpack models for $399 to $549; silky pillow covers for $17; and
hypoallergenic stuffed toys like Gund's Classic Pooh for $20.
</P>
<P>
   Although vacuum cleaners and filters marked HEPA (for high
efficiency particulate arresting) are more expensive than
conventional models, they do a much better job in trapping
bacteria, mold, dust mite scat and other particles as small as 0.3
microns. Traditional vacuum cleaners without special filters simply
blow microscopic allergens out the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Gazoontite plans to launch its catalog and Web site in May and
then open additional stores, starting in a Peninsula or East Bay
shopping mall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
