<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Golden State Bancorp to Cut 1,100 Jobs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Golden State Bancorp, the corporate parent of California Federal
Bank, cut about 1,100 jobs in connection with its $1.8 billion
takeover in September of Glendale Federal Bank, the thrift
disclosed in a regulatory filing earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the job cuts took place when Golden State shut Glendale
headquarters and its data centers in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The thrift got rid of only nine slots in the Bay Area,
spokeswoman Mary Rische said.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks, equaling 13 percent of Cal Fed and Glendale's
combined workforces, took place through a combination of firings
and attrition. They were in line with projections that Cal Fed of
San Francisco made in February 1998 when it agreed to buy Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State's purchase of Glendale created the second-largest
savings and loan in the United States, with $55 billion in assets.
Ronald Perelman, the New York financier who also owns big stakes in
Revlon and Sunbeam, holds about a third of the thrift's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State used to be the name of Glendale's parent company.
Cal Fed took the title for its own corporate parent when it
completed the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   After closing 56 overlapping Cal Fed and Glendale branches in
November, the thrift has 358 offices in California and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 16 branches, including five in the Bay Area, will
be shut in May, Rische said.
</P>
<P>
   In another matter, the Internal Revenue Service has told Golden
State it owes additional taxes in connection with Glendale's
federal tax returns from 1993 to 1997, the thrift also disclosed in
its annual 10-K report filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS is challenging tax losses Glendale took in connection
with its 1993 secondary stock offering, a recapitalization that
saved it from insolvency and a federal takeover near the peak of
California's economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State said the IRS position is ``preliminary'' and that
discussions with the agency are still taking place. It said it
doesn't how much, if anything, it will owe in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still investigating and they don't have a number,''
Rische said.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gray, an analyst with the New York brokerage Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co., said he didn't know about Golden State's tax
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would change our investment opinion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray rates Golden State ``outperform,'' Bernstein's highest
grade, based on what he said was the thrift's strong earnings
potential and its attractiveness to potential acquirers, mainly
large banks that want to come in to California on a big scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
