<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Scouting Out Executive Positions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  For 24 years, I was general manager of a wholesale
distribution company that I ran from startup to sales of $30
million with 60 employees. It was sold last year, and I would love
to find another entrepreneur who has started or is starting a
business and needs someone to handle day-to-day operations. Have
you any suggestions on how to get in front of these types?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It sounds as if your networking skills might have
gotten a little rusty. But that's an easier problem to fix than
someone who has lots of contacts but few business skills.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what type of business you were in or feel
comfortable with, but most every industry has a national
organization with regional chapters. Elaine Biech, a Wisconsin
business consultant who published ``The Business of Consulting''
last fall, suggests attending the next local, regional or national
meeting. If you built a company, you also might have a good story
to tell. If so, contact the conference committee and submit a
proposal for a presentation before the group or write an article
for the organization's trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   If you did a great job at your previous company, Biech suggests
that you might ask former colleagues or the new owners for
introductions or tips about potential chief operating officer jobs.
The same applies to former competitors, bankers, accountants and
others you have dealt with over the years.
</P>
<P>
   You also might narrow your search by checking out specific
companies online, in the library or through news publications and
business journals. When you find ones for which you might like to
work, write a short letter summarizing: 1) why you like the
company, 2) what you have done and 3) what you can do for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Local chambers of commerce and other small-business
organizations also are a good way to make contacts. They are easy
to find online and in the phone book. You might want to check out
the Service Corp.  &LR; Corps of Retired Executives, which is sponsored
by the U.S. Small Business Administration. No doubt you could
volunteer your services and find interesting leads to new
management opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   You also might check out executive search firms, which help
companies find seasoned executives and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capital Search
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a venture capital group to take a look at a
concept I have developed on the Internet. Where can I find a
listing of firms and their special interests? And beyond the names
and addresses, how do I get in the door?
</P>
<P>
   A: A good source of contact information is
PricewaterhouseCoopers' quarterly Money Tree Survey of close to 500
venture capital firms and their latest investments
( &LR; www.pwcmoneytree.com &LR; ). Unlike many other databases, it's free
and it contains a wealth of information, including ``custom
searches'' by industry, region, state of development and stage of
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent source is the Venture Capital Resource Library
 &LR; (www.vfinance.com &LR; ), which provides an extensive directory of
resources, including links to venture firm home pages, and related
services and articles. The National Venture Capital Association
 &LR; (www.nvca.com &LR; ) provides similar information.
</P>
<P>
   There also are subscription services that provide annual
directories and monthly newsletters for a price. Technologic
Partners  &LR; (www.tpsite.com),  &LR; publishes a handy $195 VentureFinance
directory of venture capital firms specializing in high-tech
investing, including names of partners, investment categories and
recent initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capital Journal ( &LR; www.nvst.com./vcj &LR; ), published by
Securities Data Publishing in New York, produces a $385 directory
of VC firms, including their areas of expertise and criteria for
making investments.
</P>
<P>
   Several publications such as Red Herring ( &LR; www.herring.com &LR; ) and
Upside ( &LR; www.upside.com &LR; ) also cater to entrepreneurs seeking
capital and building companies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are organizations that try to connect entrepreneurs
with wealthy ``angel'' investors. The Small Business Administration
is trying to do this at its fledgling ACE-Net Angel Capital
Electronic Network ( &LR; www.sba.gov &LR; ). Another popular site is
Garage.com, started in Palo Alto by former Apple executive Guy
Kawasaki to help connect entrepreneurs with investors
( &LR; www.garage.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Now, the second and more difficult part of your question:
getting through the door and getting money. If you are an
entrepreneur with a string of successes, have an MBA from Stanford
University and know all the VCs on Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park,
it's no sweat. But for entrepreneurial first timers without
credentials and contacts, it's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   You might try venture firms that specialize in early stage
investments, like Sausalito's Artemis Ventures as well as angel
investor groups and various forums.
</P>
<P>
   MIT/Stanford Venture Lab is a public forum where entrepreneurs,
managers and executives can learn about starting and growing
companies. The Lester Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation at
the University of California at Berkeley's Haas School of Business
has monthly forums where budding entrepreneurs are given 60 seconds
to pitch their ideas to venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Garage.com CEO Kawasaki suggests that regular forums held in the
Peninsula by the Churchill Club and Band of Angels are good places
to make contact. He also offers these ``guerrilla'' tips for
getting past the receptionist at the venture capital firm:
</P>
<P>
   _Shorter is better. I've never seen a company not get financing
because the business plan or executive summary was too short.
</P>
<P>
   _Have someone else do the heavy lifting. Top law and accounting
firms that work with VCs may be expensive, but they don't just
print documents, they open doors. If you want a hearing with
potential VC or angel investors, don't hire Uncle Joe the divorce
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
