<HEADLINE>
UNEXPECTED HIT: SO NOW WHAT? 
WHERE THE YOUNG ARE 
THE IRAN PRECEDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: bylines follow notebook items.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can setting a ratings record with a new show ever create a
sticky dilemma for a television network?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask executives at the Fox network, who find themselves with
what ought to be the supremely pleasant problem of pondering how to
take best advantage of the unexpectedly strong performance last
Sunday of its new animated comedy, ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   The new show from Matt Groening, the creator of Fox's perennial
(and basically only) comedy hit, ``The Simpsons,'' not only built
on the rating for that show as its lead-in but also scored the best
rating of any comedy following ``The Simpsons'' in the network's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' was the highest-rated show in all of television
last week among male viewers between the ages of 18 and 49, one of
the most important categories for advertisers. It was also the most
popular show of the week among all teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   So where's the problem with any of this?
</P>
<P>
   Only in the fact that virtually no one at Fox expected this of
``Futurama.'' Several of the network's program executives had
considered the show something of a disappointment, especially when
compared to the two other animated shows the network had in its
plans for this season, ``The PJs'' and ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Groening had fought vocally inside Fox executive suites for the
right to place his show on Sunday after his other hit and was
rather grudgingly (said one executive) granted a two-week window on
Sundays before ``Futurama'' was shipped off to Tuesdays, where for
the rest of this season it is to play adjacent to the now
struggling ``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The animated show Fox executives have been far more enthusiastic
about is ``Family Guy.'' How much better an indicator of true love
than the fact that ``Family Guy'' got the designated hit spot after
Fox's coverage of the Super Bowl this season?
</P>
<P>
   Fox is bringing back ``Family Guy'' on April 11, after
``Futurama'' gets one more Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if it doesn't put up the kind of rating numbers
that ``Futurama'' has? Will Fox be forced to reconsider its early
lukewarm reaction to Groening's new comedy?
</P>
<P>
   Groening can surely be counted on to remind the Fox executives
whose show has been a hit on their network for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The next few weeks will give the Fox programmers some thorny, if
potentially cheery, questions to ponder when they put together
their schedule for next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ABC programmers are much happier this week that they may have
some additional shows to fit into their thinking for next fall. Two
new ABC comedies, ``The Norm Show'' and ``It's Like, You Know,''
scored promising ratings in their first outings last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Norm Show'' held onto most of the audience that watched
ABC's hit ``Drew Carey,'' something few ABC shows have been able to
do. ``It's Like, You Know'' had a tougher time because it had to
follow President Clinton's address on the bombing in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ABC was thrilled because the show brought in hordes of young
female viewers who had shown no interest in bombs or ethnic
cleansing once they learned their favorite, ``Dharma and Greg,''
was being pre-empted.
</P>
<P>
   They did return for ``It's Like, You Know,'' however, which ABC
executives foresee as a good sign for the network, if not the
nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hyams, the vice president for audience analysis at ABC,
said the network ``can really use these shows'' in light of the
fact that its biggest hit comedy, ``Home Improvement,'' will be
gone next season.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE YOUNG ARE
</P>
<P>
   The major broadcast networks are wringing their hands about the
loss of hordes of 18-to-34-year-old viewers this season _ at least
6 percent of that age group _ and even accuse Nielsen Media
Research of faulty measurement (a charge Nielsen denies).
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word of where at least some of those young viewers
have gone: to Univision, the Spanish-language network. Sparked by
its hugely popular prime-time ``telenovellas,'' Univision is the
fastest-growing network, broadcast or cable, among
18-to-34-year-olds. And Nielsen research has helped it grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nielsen has only been measuring Spanish households for around
seven years, and we're learning to use the numbers to understand
the Hispanic consumer better,'' said Mario Rodriguez, Univision's
vice president of programming. ``As we learn what they like and
don't like, we tailor our programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilingual Hispanic viewers used to watch the same prime-time
sitcoms and dramas on ABC, NBC, CBS or Fox as English-language
viewers; now Univision typically attracts 92 percent of prime-time
viewers in Hispanic households.
</P>
<P>
   Creating this appeal are three telenovellas. Commonly, and
mistakenly, described as Spanish soap operas, they are actually
dramatic mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like TV novels, not soap operas,'' Rodriguez said.
``Soap opera is Susan Lucci having hundreds of boyfriends or
husbands. The novellas change stories every four months, with a new
book, a new tale, new actors and actresses. Also, they are
original, first-run episodes year round _ no repeats ever _ and our
viewers know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the average audience each quarter-hour during prime
time, the Univision study of Nielsen data showed Univision had an
average of 960,000 viewers among 18-to-34-year-olds this season, up
from 719,000 last season, an increase of 241 percent. The next
fastest growth came at the WB network, which was up 154 percent, to
1,265,000 from 1,111,000.
</P>
<P>
   The next fastest-growing networks among that age group were, in
order, ESPN, VH1, the Sci-Fi Channel and TBS.
</P>
<P>
   Although they still have by far the largest audiences, the
broadcast networks had the biggest losses among 18-to-34-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   THE IRAN PRECEDENT
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams should beware: This is how Ted Koppel began, in
1979, with a late-night show intended to provide news of the
American hostages being held in Iran. ``ABC News Nightline'' has
been on the air ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Now Williams, the anchor of a regular 9 p.m. newscast on the
cable network MSNBC, has added a half-hour program at 11 p.m.
designed to give updates on the fighting in Yugoslavia. For a
self-described news addict like Williams, it is a welcome addition
to his schedule, in part because he enjoys the jolt of providing
live news.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night was the program's first night (it replaces a rerun
of an earlier talk show, ``Equal Time''), and Williams, as he had
anticipated, found himself ignoring the Teleprompter to read
breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we came on the air, and within seconds I was
reading a Reuters flash bulletin that Serb radio claimed they had
shot down a British Harrier jump jet,'' Williams said Tuesday,
referring to Monday night's debut of the 11 p.m. program. ``Within
two minutes, we went to the Pentagon, which knocked down the story,
and we continued the broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is the only star on MSNBC, the cable network started by
Microsoft and NBC News almost three years ago. The network's
prime-time ratings have declined this season, and the Fox News
Channel (available in nine million fewer households) has begun
outranking it, with an average of 223,000 households during prime
time in the first quarter of 1999, to an average of 201,000 for
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   But since the crisis in Kosovo began, MSNBC has seen its ratings
jump by a bigger margin than Fox's or CNN's; for the first five
days of NATO bombing, the prime-time average audiences were 367,000
for MSNBC, 264,000 for Fox and 1.18 million for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mindful that this is how our good friend Koppel
started,'' Williams said. ``However, I don't expect to be saying,
`This is Day 247' of this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if this is about to become a regular feature on our
prime-time schedule I have yet to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
