<HEADLINE>
EYE-POPPING `MATRIX' IS FIRST-RATE SCI-FI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood has not given us a futuristic, action-filled,
special-effects-o-rama as imaginative and fun as the Wachowski
Brothers' ``The Matrix'' in quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a rare example of a big science-fiction film that's
actually based on an intriguing premise. Indeed, it demands a
certain level of concentration _ and mental toil _ to even
completely ``get'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, this premise is that our world _ everyone, everything
we see around us _ doesn't exist. It's a ``computer-generated
wonderland,'' an illusion, a ``matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, this is not 1999. It's the late-21st century, after a war
between human beings and artificial intelligence _ machines run
amok _ has devastated the planet, and the machines have won.
</P>
<P>
   But since the machines need people for ``energy'' _ consuming
them like batteries _ people are bred in giant hatcheries, and
deluded into thinking they're still living in the lost paradise of
the pre-war, late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the tip of the iceberg of the highly original story
idea, which could be as intricate as any sci-fi movie plot ever
concocted, and just keeps getting more involved as it moves along.
</P>
<P>
   And we discover the premise in stages, through the eyes of a
computer nerd named Neo (Keanu Reeves), who is kidnapped by a band
of rebel humans who have escaped the Matrix and battle their
mechanized overlords.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the resistance (Laurence Fishburne) believes Neo
is the ``chosen one'' _ the messiah foretold by a great oracle _
who will beat the machines and lead the human race to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   So Neo is gradually indoctrinated into the reality behind the
Matrix, and programmed to be a fierce warrior capable of going
one-on-one with the humanoid machine-men who police the virtual
world.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, it all works. Even though they have zero background
in sci-fi, Andy and Larry Wachowski (``Bound'') turn this premise
into a genuinely thrilling, smartly acted, and only occasionally
silly sci-fi genre piece.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Joel Silver has loaded down the proceedings with his
typical blazing action sequences, and noted Hong Kong fight
coordinator Yuen Wo Ping provides a succession of dizzying martial
arts sequences.
</P>
<P>
   The film's lavishly gritty, space-noir production design (by
Australia's Owen Paterson) evokes films such as ``Blade Runner''
and ``Alien,'' and its range of visual effects are both eye-popping
and integral to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most memorable thing about ``The Matrix'' is its
challenging storyline _ which is laid before us with such
originality, visual flair and cerebral dexterity that the film
often seems positively Kubrickesque.
</P>
<P>
   The Matrix. Directed and written by the Wachowski Brothers.
Produced by Joel Silver. Cast: Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne,
Carrie-Anne Moss, Hugo Weaving, Joe Pantoliano. Warner Bros. 120
minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
