<SLUG> BC-FED-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED MAINTAINS STEADY STANCE ON RATE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve's top officials left interest
rates unchanged Tuesday, and passed up an opportunity to signal any
concern about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the Fed's governors and regional bank presidents,
all members of the policy-setting Open Market Committee, came at a
time when inflation has been remarkably tame despite the robust
economy. And there is unlikely to be much upward pressure on prices
as long as labor costs do not accelerate significantly and Europe
and Asia remain in the economic doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure most members of the committee think everything is
going rather beautifully,'' said Alan Blinder, a Princeton
University economist and a former Fed vice chairman. ``They have
not allowed themselves to be provoked into some sort of pre-emptive
action against inflation and, in hindsight, their patience has
proven to be correct.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Fed sometimes raised interest rates before any
rise in the inflation rate, contending that an increase was
necessary to discourage borrowing and thus slow a strong economy
before companies raised prices in response to shortages and rising
wage pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy has boomed for over three years and forecasts of
higher inflation have proved wrong time after time. So Fed
officials have switched tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they take any action, they are going to wait for the
inflation rate to actually pick up,'' said David Jones, chief
economist at Aubrey Lanston &AMP; Co., a Wall Street firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has another tool at its disposal that it chose not to
use Tuesday. At times, even at sessions when it did not change
rates, the central bank has signaled its future intentions through
a directive stating that it was shifting its ``bias'' in one
direction or another. Traditionally, such preferences have been
kept secret until the minutes of each meeting are published six
weeks later. But recently the Fed said it would usually announce
such directives when they were adopted, rather than make the
financial markets guess. There was no announcement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed affects a whole range of interest rates by changing its
target for the federal funds rate, the overnight borrowing cost
that banks and other financial institutions charge each other.
Rates on car loans, mortgages and home equity loans, for example,
tend to move up and down with the federal funds rate. The central
bank left its target at 4.75 percent, the level it has been since
the Fed last cut rates by a quarter of a percentage point in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market may also have been a factor in the Fed's
decision not to take any action Tuesday. While a small rise in the
federal funds rate might slow the rise in stock prices, it might
also provoke a sharp, damaging decline, said Albert Wojnilower, a
Wall Street economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries Fed officials when the stock market runs away,'' he
said. Still, ``they don't see it going up in a runaway fashion, but
even if it were,'' Wojnilower added, ``they prefer the market
running away than taking a dive, which they would have to do
something about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The stock market, in the view of many economists, has been a
major driver behind the economic boom, encouraging people to borrow
and spend and fostering a high level of consumer confidence. The
Conference Board reported Tuesday that its index of consumer
confidence rose in March by eight-tenths of a point, to 133.9 from
a revised 133.1 in February.
</P>
<P>
   For all the strong growth, low unemployment and labor shortages,
the inflation rate has fallen over the last two years, defying
traditional relationships. Many economists explain the conundrum by
pointing to a weak global economy and a relatively strong American
currency, which has resulted in a flood of inexpensive imports that
helps to hold down the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things may be beginning to turn around overseas,'' said
Kenneth Matheny, a senior economist at Macroeconomic Advisers Inc.,
a forecasting service in St. Louis. ``But the Fed has time before
there is any real improvement and Fed officials will wait until
they get much stronger signals before they consider tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   A competing explanation for the unusual combination of strong
growth and shrinking inflation has been offered by Alan Greenspan,
the Fed's chairman. He has suggested that the nation's productivity
growth rate _ which measures the ability of workers to turn out a
greater quantity of goods and services in a given period of time _
has finally started to improve after a quarter-century of
stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity statistics issued by the government do show recent
improvements, thus allowing workers, in effect, to pay for their
own wage increases rather than force employers to raise prices or
squeeze their profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   But while many economists say the improvement is probably
temporary, Greenspan has argued that it reflects the growing
effectiveness of computers and other new technologies in the
workplace. And lately some other Fed governors have expressed the
same view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
