<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REJECTS MILOSEVIC'S CALL FOR CEASE-FIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO leaders Tuesday rejected Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's call for a cease-fire as the alliance warned
that the aerial bombardment, in its seventh day, could be lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remain steady and determined with the will to see this
through,'' President Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said NATO was ``prepared to go
as long as it takes'' to wear down Milosevic's military and police
forces and to stop their rampage against ethnic Albanians in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will take much longer to degrade the forces as much
as we think we need to do,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said that Milosevic,
during talks in Belgrade, proposed reducing his troops in Kosovo in
exchange for a halt to NATO airstrikes on his Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov flew from the Yugoslav capital to Bonn, where the
proposal was rejected by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany,
whose nation currently holds the rotating presidency of the
15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no basis for a political solution,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   His view was endorsed by other leaders of NATO nations,
including Clinton, who renewed the call for Milosevic to accept the
alliance-dictated truce that ethnic Albanian leaders have signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I share the view of Chancellor Schroeder that President
Milosevic's proposal is unacceptable,'' Clinton said in a statement
issued by the White House. ``President Milosevic began this brutal
campaign: It is his responsibility to bring it to an immediate end
and embrace a just peace. There is a strong consensus in NATO that
we must press forward with our military action.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, speaking at a State Department ceremony, Clinton
indicated that the current NATO view that Kosovo should be an
autonomous province of Serbia, within Yugoslavia, could change.
Clinton said that as a result of aggression in Kosovo, Milosevic
will see ``the prospect of international support for Serbia's claim
to Kosovo increasingly jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac suggested that Milosevic may
become a NATO target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe cannot accept on its soil a man and a regime that for
10 years has conducted ethnic cleansing,'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, said Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering,
Milosevic is ``a prime candidate'' for indictment as a war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground in Kosovo, ``Serbian ethnic cleansing has reached
new heights,'' said Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain's Royal
Air Force, the NATO air commander.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Pec, Kosovo's second largest city
and once home to about 100,000 people ``has been almost totally
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Shea said, 570,000 Kosovar Albanians, or
about 30 percent of the province's population, ``have been uprooted
from their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   He accused Milosevic's forces of ``burning whole cities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems particularly mindless,'' Shea said. ``What he's
doing is simply vastly increasing the cost to Yugoslavia of having
to reconstruct the place one day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the air attack, despite some poor weather, the chief target
quickly has become Serbian military and police forces in Kosovo,
NATO and Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have basically shown, through a combination of strikes and
electronic suppression flight tactics, that we can achieve a degree
of air superiority with acceptable risk, which allows us to carry
out our missions as planned, if the weather permits,'' Bacon said.
``We are now beginning to focus more precisely on the troops on the
ground in Kosovo and the troops stationed just outside of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton will fly Thursday to Norfolk, Va.,
to meet families of U.S. sailors and Marines participating in the
NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia, the White House said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the president's message is expected to be that the
mission will not be a short one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that a knockout punch would not come quickly,'' said
Bacon, one of several NATO and Clinton administration officials who
spoke about the length of the engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to warn everybody against expecting an instant
solution,'' Shea said. ``This situation is complicated. It's been
going on for a long time. It predates the beginning of NATO's air
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the State Department ceremony, spoke about NATO
solidarity and determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allies are united in our outrage over President
Milosevic's atrocities against innocent people,'' Clinton said.
``We are determined to stay with our policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever any doubt about what is at stake in Kosovo,
Mr. Milosevic is certainly erasing it by his actions.'' Clinton
said. ``The NATO air campaign is designed to raise the price of
that policy. For a sustained period, he will see that his military
will be seriously diminished; key military infrastructure
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
