<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKE     03-30 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO LEADERS WONDER WHAT TO DO IF BOMBING DOES NOT WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map-graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Increasingly dejected by the inability of
their dazzling weapons to bring Slobodan Milosevic to heel and stop
the ethnic purge of Kosovo, NATO leaders are wondering, what next?
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president has been impervious to a week-long
battering by cruise missiles, smart bombs, stealth planes,
high-tech bombers and other state-of-the art weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   An armed invasion has been effectively ruled out, NATO officials
said, and the existing strategy has only one more option left --
bombing the Yugoslav president's nerve centers in the heart of
Belgrade, with all the risks that carries of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, NATO's top civilian official said Tuesday,
would be to acknowledge that the basic premise behind the bombing
strategy, that a sufficient show of air power would batter
Milosevich into accepting Western prescriptions for Kosovo, was
fatally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in turn, would mean admitting that the world's most
powerful alliance, with the world's most powerful air force at its
disposal, was helpless to curb the authoritarian leader of a small
Balkan country from killing and victimizing his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have the means to stop it, but we have shown we
have the will to try,'' NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana,
said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, other allied officials here began talking
privately about the possibility that the bombing strategy might not
work. That was not the view of Gen. Wesley Clark, the top allied
commander, who would not comment Tuesday on reports that he had
requested but not been given permission to strike the ministries in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telephone interview, he acknowledged that Milosevic had
proved to be no pushover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up against an intelligent and capable adversary who is
attempting to offset all our strategies,'' General Clark said.
``There are risks and no certainties in this.''
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty, the general said, was that the Serb police
and military forces would continue to be ``attacked, degraded, and
disrupted'' by the bombing unless Milosevic called off the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the failure of this strategy so far to check Milosevic,
General Clark maintained a resolute stance. ``The political
consensus is building, political will is building, and resolution
is strengthening,'' he said of the allies.
</P>
<P>
   But with that allied strategy coming under question in many
European media, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov made a
lightning diplomatic mission to Belgrade on Tuesday to see if
Milosevic was ready to talk peace. He was, Primakov reported this
evening to German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in Bonn, but with
the defiant condition that the allies would first have to stop
bombing. The proposal was summarily rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core of the proposals was: Stop NATO attacks first, then
we'll negotiate,'' Schroeder said after the Russian Prime Minister
left Bonn to fly back to Moscow. ``We could not accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   That left the allies where they have been for the past week,
hoping that punishing attacks from the air would persuade Milosevic
that he had no choice but to accept their terms.
</P>
<P>
   But if that did not work, as Solana explained in the interview,
there was little NATO could do except say that at least it had
tried. It was too late, Solana said, for NATO to send in ground
troops to fight the marauding Serbian forces even if any of the
allies wanted to do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not prepared for a force on the ground,'' he said,
except after a peace settlement agreed to by the Serbs. Planning
for a combat operation to fight their way in, he said, would take
time the allies couldn't afford if they hoped to spare further
agony to the civilian population of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, from Washington to London, Paris, Bonn and Rome,
President Clinton and other allied leaders have repeatedly promised
their publics that it would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   The only way U.S. and European troops would be prepared to enter
Kosovo, the allies all agree, is as part of an allied peacekeeping
force, with the consent of both the Albanians who live in Kosovo
and the Serbs who rule over it.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's refusal even to discuss peacekeepers dashed American
efforts to mediate such a deal, including an 11th-hour mission to
Belgrade by an American special envoy, Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago, they were insisting that Milosevic withdraw his
forces from Kosovo and sign the peace agreement that was worked out
in France last month in negotiations at Rambouillet castle, outside
Paris. The agreement, not accepted by the Serbs, provided for
autonomy for the province, under Serbian rule, for a three-year
transition period, and 28,000 NATO peacekeepers to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Serbs rejected the agreement, Milosevic's forces
stepped up operations in Kosovo, systematically driving Albanians
out of towns and villages. Even as NATO bombs began falling, Serb
army soldiers and police continued laying waste to Albanian
settlements, pushing tens of thousands of people into Albania,
Macedonia, and Montenegro, and leaving the fate of thousands of
others unclear.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Now, Solana said, ``All our energy should be concentrated now on
stopping the killing and helping the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to continue the bombing until we can guarantee
that the killings stop and will not restart,'' he said. ``The first
objective was always to stop the killing on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solana suggested that the allies might no longer insist that
Milosevic would have to sign the Rambouillet agreement before the
bombing stopped. ``I think the Rambouillet agreement was a good
agreement, and probably the best chance Milosevic had to get a good
agreement, but we will have to see how it evolves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Reuters reported that a White House official
said, ``We wouldn't wait for a signature to stop the bombing
necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   (END TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some NATO diplomats here suggest that so much has happened on
the ground in Kosovo since the Albanian negotiators signed the
accord March 18 that the Rambouillet agreement may no longer be
applicable anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL GRAF FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Far from backing off when the bombs started falling, as he did
four years ago in Bosnia where he showed little evidence of
sentimental attachment to the Bosnian Serb cause, Milosevic is
instead doing his best to turn the bombing to his advantage. The
wholesale flight of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo has led many NATO
officials to suspect that Milosevic's scheme is to claim much of
the province in any future peace deal as Serb-only territory.
</P>
<P>
   (END TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials here are on the defensive, insisting day after
day that it was not their bombing that sparked the Serbian attacks,
or the huge civilian forced exodus from Kosovo, but a long-planned
Serbian ``ethnic cleansing'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a master plan that was conceived and well on its
way to being executed before the first NATO bomb was on its way to
a military target,'' the alliance's spokesman, Jamie Shea, said
Tuesday, comparing the Serb campaign to Stalin's Great Terror purge
in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the alliance's plan was to prevent that scheme and bring
Milosevic to his knees through bombing, it was based on a
misjudgment of his determination.
</P>
<P>
   He caved in Bosnia but, as Holbrooke made clear in his memoir on
that war, Milosevic appeared to have nothing but contempt for
Bosnian Serb leaders and, most importantly, did not feel much
emotional attachment to the lands they were fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly does feel emotionally attached to Kosovo, where he
celebrated the 600th anniversary of a Serb defeat at the hands of
Turkish invaders in 1989 with a ringing appeal to Serbian
nationalism. As President of Serbia then, he also ended the
province's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long the impasse might continue, Solana said that he
was sure the bombing would be over before the planned April 23
start of a summit meeting in Washington to celebrate NATO's 50th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a problem that was created in 24 hours,'' he said,
``and it will not be solved in 24 hours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
