<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-REPORT-ART-400     03-30 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-REPORT-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGER SOLVENCY FOR MEDICARE AND SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Relieving some of the political pressure for
reform, the government released new actuarial studies Tuesday
extending the date at which Medicare can be expected to run out of
money by seven years and Social Security insolvency by two years.
</P>
<P>
   The improved financial position of the Medicare and Social
Security trust funds is largely the result of the strong economy
over the last year, the trustees of the funds said in their annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the latest long-range estimates of factors like
national economic growth, worker productivity, inflation,
unemployment, immigration and birth rates and retirement patterns,
the actuaries still expect the government's two largest programs to
require more tax money or a reduction in benefits as the number of
baby boomers in retirement mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But without any changes in law, the trustees found, the Medicare
system should have enough money to pay full benefits until 2015 and
the Social Security system should be in the black until 2034. Last
year at this time, they projected the insolvency dates to be 2008
for Medicare and 2032 for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony in the Rose Garden, President Clinton insisted
that despite the good news, legislation strengthening the programs
should still be enacted this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time to make those changes,'' Clinton said. ``Now
when our economy is strong, now when our people have renewed
confidence and now when we have time on our side so that modest
changes today can have major impacts in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading Republicans in Congress issued similar statements. ``We
cannot let this good news make us complacent,'' said Sen. William
Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance Committee, which
has jurisdiction over Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, economists of all political persuasions generally
agree that the sooner the necessary changes are made to shore up
Social Security and Medicare, the less abrupt and painful those
changes will seem to taxpayers and retirees.
</P>
<P>
   But the president and the Republicans who control Congress are
so far apart on how the two programs should be fixed and the
politics of the matter are so delicate that the odds are already
against enactment of comprehensive legislation this year. The
effect of Tuesday's announcement postponing a crisis was to make a
search for compromise less urgent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``These are actuaries from heaven,'' said James A. Thurber,
director of the Center for Congressional and Presidential Studies
at American University here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes pressure off all the players on the Hill and the
president,'' Thurber said, and makes it safe for them to leave the
problem for the next president and the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, the politically savvy lobbyist for the American
Association of Retired Persons, which favors enactment of Social
Security legislation this year, said, ``I'm not going to throw in
the towel.'' After a pause, Rother added, ``Publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   The six trustees of the trust funds include three Cabinet
members: Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman and Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala. The
others are Kenneth S. Apfel, the Social Security commissioner, and
two experts who were appointed by Clinton: Stephen G. Kellison, an
actuary, and Marilyn Moon, an economist who specializes in health
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are political appointees, their annual report is,
by and large, the work of career government actuaries and
economists. The reports were also reviewed by outside actuaries who
signed statements saying the methodology and assumptions were
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The projections that the Medicare fund would be insolvent in
2015 and the Social Security fund in 2034 were based on what the
trustees called an intermediate set of estimates about the economic
and demographic factors.
</P>
<P>
   The economic assumptions were quite conservative. The trustees
estimated, for instance, that economic growth between 2010 and 2050
would average less than 1.5 percent a year. That is approximately
half the average growth rate of the last 75 years, but the trustees
were taking into account the fact that the country's labor force is
not expected to grow as fast in the 21st century as it has in the
20th.
</P>
<P>
   The report offered for comparison's sake two other projections.
One based on less favorable assumptions showed Medicare running out
of money in 2007 and Social Security in 2028. Another based on more
favorable conditions showed that neither program would become
insolvent in the next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, projections indicated that the
Medicare fund would run out of money in 2001. Shalala said Tuesday
that the improved situation was the result of a stronger economy
and of changes the president and Congress made in the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997. That law shifted some of the cost of home
health care out of the hospital insurance trust fund and reduced
Medicare payments to doctors, hospitals and other health-care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 report forecast that Social Security would become
insolvent in 2029. Last year's report said the reserves would be
exhausted in 2032. The brighter picture is almost entirely the
result of the flourishing economy over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Even with reduced pressure to act, the president and Congress
are sure to continue to debate what to do with Social Security and
Medicare _ right through the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Social Security, the president and the
Republicans favor setting aside much of the budget surplus over the
next 15 years to strengthen the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans want to use the money to allow workers to
establish private retirement accounts that they would invest in
stocks and bonds. The president wants to allow some Social Security
money to be invested in the markets, but he would have the
government control the investments.
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare, Republicans are generally supporting a marketplace
system under which retirees would be given a fixed amount of money
that they could use to buy private health insurance or the
government's program.
</P>
<P>
   The president and most Democrats oppose this idea and favor
setting aside money from the budget surplus to strengthen Medicare
and provide new funds to cover prescription drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
