<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HATE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE OF BARD'S CLASSIC DETERIORATES INTO FORMULAIC PAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh woe! Petrucchio and Katherine from Shakespeare's ``The Taming
Of the Shrew'' these kids are not. Yet this modernized version of
the Bard's classic, which has been made into a film five previous
times and was adapted into the musical, ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' by Cole
Porter, certainly has its merits.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it was shot in Seattle and at Tacoma's Stadium High
School, and shows both cities off to their best advantage. But it
doesn't follow Shakespeare's bawdy comedy very closely. It's more
akin to the recent teen angst movie, ``She's All That,'' in which
an unpopular girl is transformed into a beauty and the plot
climaxes with a confrontation at the prom.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Baz Luhrmann's ``Romeo + Juliet'' made a splash at
the box office, the Bard has been fodder for every interpretation
imaginable. There's a version of ``Othello'' called ``O'' in the
works, as well as Ethan Hawke's update of ``Hamlet.'' As a film,
the least popular of Shakespeare's plays, ``Titus Andronicus,''
stars Jessica Lange and Anthony Hopkins and bears an
ultra-high-tech tone. ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' opens in
theaters later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' which starts quite well, owes
more to its adult cast than its teenagers. The quartet of young
talent pales next to Allison Janney as the scene-stealing Ms.
Perky, the libidinous high school guidance counselor, and comic
Larry Miller, who plays Walter Stratford, father to two very
different daughters, Katarina and Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   Katarina (Julia Stiles) is a rebellious, anti-social brain. Her
younger sister, Bianca (Larisa Oleynik), is pretty and popular and
desperately wants to date. But dad has a rule: Bianca can date when
Kat does. With Kat's alienating personality, that doesn't seem
likely any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca hatches a scheme to pair her big sis with an equally
petulant suitor: Patrick Verona (Heath Ledger). He's walking bad
news whose reputation precedes him. Was he in prison for a year?
Did he really sell his own liver on the black market? Why is he
always in detention?
</P>
<P>
   He's a perfect match for the dour Kat. With the help of Joey
Donner (Andrew Keegan), a vain egomaniac who wants to date Bianca
for one reason only, the plan is put into action. Joey enlists
Cameron (Joseph-Gordon Levitt), the boy who really likes Bianca, to
make contact with Patrick. Cash exchanges hands, sparks fly and
Bianca is on her way to the prom and Kat is about to have her
sullen personality re-arranged.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, what begins as a rowdy, clever, even a little
racy movie soon deteriorates into formulaic pap. Oleynik and Levitt
have little chemistry or presence and only Julia Stiles, who played
Harrison Ford's daughter in the dismal ``The Devil's Own,'' makes
much of an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gil Junger, who is best known as a TV director of tepid
series such as ``Empty Nest,'' falls into every trap in the teenage
movie genre halfway through. We've seen this stuff in ``16
Candles'' and ``Can't Hardly Wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the film opens with bite and acerbic, scathing wit, it
quickly erodes into mediocrity with its betrayals and romantic
break-ups and predicatable make-ups.
</P>
<P>
   10 Things I Hate About You. Directed by Gil Junger. Written by
Karen McCullah Lutz, Kirsten Smith. Cast: Julia Stiles, Heath
Ledger, Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Larisa Oleynik. Touchstone Pictures.
91 minutes. Rated PG-13 for language, sexual content. Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-NYT &LR;      03-30 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN WANTS TO STAY OUT OF WARFARE IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin told Russian political leaders
Tuesday that the country ``will not allow itself to be drawn into
military conflict'' in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The president's words came at the start of his annual speech to
lawmakers and Cabinet members on the state of the nation. He
presented Russia as a country at a critical and historic juncture,
in danger of being relegated to a second rank of nations if it
failed to overcome its political divisions and economic weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin again condemned the NATO strikes against Yugoslavia,
which in the last week have drawn a belligerent reaction from
Russian opposition leaders. They have called for renewed military
aid to Yugoslavia and for the sending of volunteers to fight on the
Serbs' side in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the president appealed Tuesday for responsible actions,
rather than ``emotional assessments.'' He added, ``More and more
political leaders understand that in such situations brute force
does not achieve anything. Russia has made its choice.''
</P>
<P>
   As Yeltsin spoke in the Kremlin before both houses of Parliament
and members of his government, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
arrived in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, accompanied by top diplomatic,
military and intelligence officials, on a mission to bring about a
political settlement of the Kosovo warfare.
</P>
<P>
   While the outcome of those talks hung in the balance, Yeltsin
told his audience that in trying to bring peace to the Balkans,
Russia was not neglecting its ``prime duty,'' which he said, ``is
to prevent any discord inside the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our weight in the world arena depends on how we solve our
problems at home,'' he said. ``This means that we need order in
government, accord in society, stability in the economy and the
social sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Yelstin's appeal came as the first wave of anti-Western
outbursts, which peaked on Sunday with the shelling of the American
Embassy here, seemed to be subsiding.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder of Russia's dependence on international good will,
Primakov on Monday struck an agreement with Michel Camdessus,
managing director of the International Monetary Fund, on the broad
outlines of a plan to relieve Russia's foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   And in Russian newspaper and television reports Tuesday, more
information was provided about the reasons for the mass exodus of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, as refugees gave eyewitness accounts
of being rounded up by Serbian policemen and forced out of their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, official Russian spokesmen insisted that the refugees
were fleeing NATO bombs and that reports of ``ethnic cleansing''
were nothing but Western rumors and propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a steady voice, Yeltsin described Russia Tuesday as
a country ``stuck halfway'' between two economic systems. ``We've
created a freakish model,'' he said, ``a hybrid of the two
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on the Primakov-led Cabinet, which he credited with
having stopped an economic downturn, to move ahead with an economic
program. ``It is just six months before the start of elections,''
the president said. ``This time will have to be used not only to
patch up holes. It is high time to identify the new priorities,
chief among them Russia's economic competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing the causes of Russia's financial collapse last summer,
he pointed the finger at Parliament's Communist-led lower house,
which he said had sent ``a bad signal to investors'' in rejecting
the government's fiscal program.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other remarks did not go down well with leaders of the
opposition to Yeltsin's government, who criticized the speech for
its empty phrases and finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the old song about how everything was done right and
how the Duma spoiled everything,'' said the Communist Party chief,
Gennadi Zyuganov, using the Russian name for the lower house.
Nikolai Ryzhkov, a former Soviet prime minister, described the
speech as ``absolutely useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin pledged to keep his distance from political battles as
Russia prepares for critical elections, first for Parliament in
December, and next year for the presidency, which he is obliged to
vacate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that clean, unstained people will come to the
new Parliament, not professional patriots but patriotically minded
professionals,'' he said pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to many today that Russia has grown weak, that it
doesn't have the strength even to deal with its own problems, and
therefore one can discount it,'' he said. ``They are mistaken. No
temporary difficulties can put Russia in the category of
second-rate powers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
