<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-DISABLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES AIRLINES ON TREATMENT OF THE DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (no byline cq) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Disabled air travelers are often mistreated by
airline personnel and denied special accommodations including
access to wheelchairs and escorts in violation of a 1986 law,
according to a report by the National Council on Disability.
</P>
<P>
   The federal advisory agency's report recommends changes in the
law and in enforcement efforts by the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the National Council on Disability, released last
week, said that enforcement of the 1986 law, the Air Carrier Access
Act, was ineffective, that public education efforts on the needs
and legal rights of disabled air travelers was inadequate, and that
there was not enough money or staff at the Department of
Transportation dedicated to investigating complaints.
</P>
<P>
   And according to the council, there are weaknesses in the law
and the fines are not effective. Under the law, the maximum civil
penalty is only $1,100 for each offense.
</P>
<P>
   When an individual files a complaint with the enforcement office
of Transportation Department and the airline responds, the complain
is either dismissed or the department may file its own complaint
against the airline and try to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, an administrative hearing is held. From 1987
to 1998, $28,000 in civil penalties have been imposed on airlines
under the Air Carrier Access Act.
</P>
<P>
   People with disabilities are often unwilling to file a lawsuit,
especially when compensatory damages and even lawyer fees are not
assured. Of 17 formal complaints filed in the last 12 years, a
dozen have garnered a total of less than $150,000 in damages,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   John M. Meenan, senior vice president for industry policy at the
Air Transport Association said: ``This is an extensive report
dealing with a wide range of complicated issues. We are very
interested in resolving those concerns regarding air travelers with
disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The report followed an 18-month review by the council of the
treatment of disabled air travelers. That review revealed serious
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative experiences of disabled travelers go beyond the
typical hassles all air travelers encounter,'' said Marca Bristo,
chairwoman of the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are dropped or mishandled by poorly trained staff who
treat you like an inconvenient piece of luggage, when you can't get
critical information because it is not in an accessible format, you
are left with the feeling that you don't count, that your dignity
as a human being has been violated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the first in a series of four that will review
overall enforcement not just transportation of civil rights laws
for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bristo, in her introduction to the report, noted some of the
basic accommodation problems that disabled people face: deaf
travelers who continue to miss flights when last-minute flight and
gate change information is announced only through public address
systems, children with disabilities who are often denied seating
next to companions on whom they rely for assistance and blind or
visually-impaired people who must often request wheelchairs to
obtain assistance or an escort.
</P>
<P>
   For some people with disabilities, ``flying is so unbearable
that any alternative means of transportation will be used,'' Ms.
Bristo said.
</P>
<P>
   In a progress report sent to President Clinton and Congress in
February, a prelude to last week's report, the council found the
the Department of Transportation ``critically lacking in key areas
of compliance monitoring, complaint handling, and leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bristo said, ``Although things have improved since ACAA was
passed in 1986, people with disabilities continue to encounter
frequent, significant violations of their civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the disability council officials did work with
Secretary Rodney E. Slater of the Department of Transportation
during the review. And in a March 18 letter to Ms. Bristo, Slater
wrote that he would ``assure that disabled travelers will not face
discrimination or barriers in using our transportation system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
