<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-CEO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON CHIEF WAS PAID $26.8 MILLION FOR SIX MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon chief executive Daniel P. Burnham received about $26.8
million in compensation last year for the six months he worked at
the Lexington, Mass., defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who joined Raytheon July 1, received a salary and bonus
of $1.9 million last year, according to the company's proxy
statement filed Tuesday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. His other compensation included a stock grant worth
$21.8 million, which Burnham will receive over the next seven
years, regardless of how the company's stock performs.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said much of Burnham's pay package replaced
compensation he was to have received at his previous job as vice
chairman of Allied Signal Inc., and was needed to lure him. Toni
Simonetti, Raytheon's spokeswoman, said Burnham's pay should be
weighed against that of chief executives at other large companies.
Compared to them, she said, ``Dan Burnham is a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pay details come at a sensitive time for the company,
which faces accusations that a recent layoff of 1,200 workers
violated the spirit of an agreement under which it obtained a state
tax cut in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Susan Fargo, a Democrat from Lincoln, charged that
the compensation package, and one given to Raytheon chairman Dennis
Picard, showed the company could afford to hire back many
employees. She is sponsoring a bill in the Legislature that in
effect would require it to do so to keep the tax break. ``They're
making out like bandits,'' she said. The company's 1998 executive
pay ``underlines the need for them to do more for their workers,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Simonetti reiterated the company's position that the layoffs are
needed to help it remain competitive with rivals like Boeing Co.
and Lockheed Martin Corp. Asked about Fargo's comments, Simonetti
said, ``I don't see the connection at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham's annual salary was set at $850,000, of which he
received $425,000 after joining Raytheon. He also received a $1.5
million bonus and the $21.8 million in stock awards, most of which
was meant to replace stock benefits he was due to receive at Allied
Signal, Simonetti said. In addition, he received options to buy
250,000 Raytheon shares at set prices, which the company valued at
$2.76 million.
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal, a compensation expert and critic of executive
pay, said it was ``reasonable'' of Raytheon to compensate Burnham
for benefits he lost by leaving Allied Signal. However, Crystal
said he was surprised by the amount of stock granted to Burnham
outright rather than given as options, whose value depends on
management boosting the company's stock price. ``To pay him that
much strikes me as being rather outlandish,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   Picard earned $4.5 million in salary and bonus last year. He
also received options to buy 450,000 shares of Raytheon stock at
set rates, which the firm valued at about $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's annual shareholders' meeting will be held April 28 in
Tucson. Shares of Raytheon fell 7/8 to close at 56 7/8 in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
