u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-US-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      03-30 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
350 US SOLDIERS FIND THEMSELVES CLOSE TO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROVEC, Macedonia _ If Sergeant William Ellis needed any
reminder that he was in one of the most dangerous corners of the
world, one slammed into a hillside a few miles from the ridge where
he and other members of the 1st Squadron of the 4th US Cavalry were
standing Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Two cruise missiles, fired by NATO forces, exploded into the
forest of southern Kosovo, where Serb troops may or may not have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that loud,'' Ellis said nonchalantly. ``They were
pretty far away.''
</P>
<P>
   But, suddenly, the 350 US troops here at Camp Able Sentry, not
far from the Kosovo border, find themselves close to the cutting
edge of a Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from 100 US Marines temporarily guarding the US Embassy in
the Macedonian capital of Skopje, the Army soldiers and airmen at
Camp Able Sentry are the only US troops on the ground near Kosovo.
Since the NATO bombing began, they have dropped their roles as UN
border observers to become responsible for protecting some 11,000
NATO troops on the ground in Macedonia from Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   At this former Yugoslav air base, they are literally peeling the
blue UN patches off their uniforms and repainting their armored
vehicles standard Army green from UN white.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they have assumed a position of importance in much
greater proportion to their numbers or military capabilities. The
British, French, German, Italian, and Dutch soldiers who have been
here for the past month believe the presence of the Americans
deters even further the threat of a Serb attack.
</P>
<P>
   The American commander, Lieutenant Colonel James Shufelt Jr.,
acknowledged as much Tuesday, sitting in his office, the constant
drone of CNN in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at risk. If they decide to hit us, we're in range,''
Shufelt said. ``I don't think they'll do that. But we're ready if
it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, there will be hell to pay, soldiers at Camp Able
Sentry say. It is an opinion informed not so much by swagger as by
the belief that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has already
realized his mistake in defying the Western powers, and that he'd
be, as one soldier put it, ``crazy to make it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers and airmen here are well aware of geopolitics.
Since 1993, their mission here had been to man the observation
posts along the Macedonian border with Kosovo. Although troops from
Nordic countries carried out the same duties, it was the American
presence that provided the ultimate deterrent to Milosevic trying
to recapture Macedonia, which quit the Yugoslav Federation in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the squadron is available to provide protection
to the NATO forces here is because the Chinese, as members of the
UN Security Council, vetoed renewing the squadron's mission in
retaliation for Macedonia's recognizing Taiwan. The squadron took
up their new duties the day the NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Harking back to their frontier origins, cavalry soldiers are
known in military parlance as scouts, surreptitiously checking
enemy positions. While they do that, they also keep alert for Serb
sympathizers who regularly stone their vehicles as they drive
through Serb strongholds in Macedonia, such as Kumanovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three weeks, we saw more than we did in the
previous three years,'' said Shufelt. ``Before, you'd see a
smuggler with three mules. A few weeks ago, we saw the Yugoslavs
put a battalion of 500 to 600 men into position. They wanted us to
see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the NATO bombing began, Camp Able Sentry has gone on
heightened alert. Soldiers are required to wear their flak jackets
and helmets, and to always have their weapon at their side.
Tuesday, soldiers walked to and from the 24-hour gym, equipped with
treadmills and two full-length basketball courts, their M-16 rifles
at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   First Lieutenant Kimberly Nash, 24, a self-described Army brat
from Kansas, said soldiers call their state of readiness ``full
battle rattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash, a West Point graduate and three-year veteran of the Army,
said there is little nervousness, despite being within easy
striking distance of the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pick on Americans, you'll have a whole lot of mad coming
down on you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   First Lieutenant James Tighe, a Massachusetts native, is
similarly convinced that the Serbs would be foolish to fire across
the border. Still, Tighe said his fiancee worries about him.
</P>
<P>
   Tighe, 24, a platoon leader who flies Blackhawk helicopters,
said he knows that his aunts and uncles back in Massachusetts watch
the news and see a threat that he thinks is not there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tighe said he just finished reading a book on the Balkans
and was overwhelmed by the history of conflict, and how it was
still playing out centuries later. He said he is bothered by the
pictures of refugees fleeing Kosovo and wishes he could do more to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting here, eating chow, we have shelter, and you see
these people with absolutely nothing, running for their lives,'' he
said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   US soldiers admit they cannot fathom the depths of hatred that
fuel the perpetual instability of the Balkans. One of them who
can't understand it is Specialist Bounheng Insisiengmay, 23, from
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Insisiengmay is the son of Laotian immigrants. One generation
after Americans bombed his parents' country, he was among the first
20 American soldiers to restore order at the US Embassy in Skopje
after it was attacked by Serb sympathizers last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we have to do here,'' Insisiengmay said, wearing
gym clothes and carrying his M-16 after a weightlifting workout.
``We're ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
