A0075 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Robertson Stephens Snatches a Bevy of Bankers
From  Montgomery 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
And now for another edition of ``As the Investment Banks Churn.''
</P>
<P>
   In our latest installment, it is NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities' turn, yet again, to be raided. BancBoston Robertson
Stephens (soon to be plain ol' Robertson Stephens after Fleet
Financial finalizes its purchase of BankBoston) is hiring away a
top-producing team of private bankers from BankAmerica's Montgomery
unit, says managing director Joe Piazza, who heads Robertson
Stephens' financial services business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hired a group of people that have worked together for a
number of years, (and) they are substantial producers,'' says
Piazza, who was hired in November to build Robertson Stephens'
nascent private banking business.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Montgomery founder Thom Weisel left the bank in
September, the BankAmerica unit has been roiling. Various bankers,
brokers and financial analysts have been abandoning ship as
Montgomery's new management under BankAmerica attempts to chart a
new course.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest group of defectors is Robert Tishman, a
seven-year Montgomery veteran who will stay in Boston and manage
Robertson Stephens' private client business there. A senior
managing director at Montgomery, he is being brought on board as a
managing director at Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Tishman in the switch from Montgomery is John Schnugg,
who also was hired as a managing director. Schnugg will work in San
Francisco with two other former Montgomery colleagues, Matthew
Klein and Michael Vigo. Together, the three bring more than 30
years of Montgomery experience with them.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, Andrew Blau, a 10-year veteran of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, is being hired to run the division's New York office.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens' Piazza is no stranger to the Montgomery
crew. He built that bank's private client business during his
five-year stint at Montgomery earlier this decade. Piazza, who
spent three years with ING Barings between his Montgomery job and
current post, says if his new hires produce at the levels they did
at their previous employers, Robertson Stephens' financial services
unit should see a 75 percent increase in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The entire private banking services sector is on fire. It
targets high net-worth individuals who are often top officers of
companies that they run or helped start. With so much personal
wealth being created in the stock market, investment banks are
trying to persuade their corporate customers to also do their
personal banking with them or consult them on such things as
employee stock plans.
</P>
<P>
   To put it succinctly, ``we want to be all things to certain
people,'' Piazza says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAT FEES &LR; : CS First Boston expects to rack up some sweet fees
for being the sole adviser on Computer Associates' proposed $3.5
billion cash purchase of Platinum Technology.
</P>
<P>
   CS First Boston's technology group, which is led by Frank
Quattrone, is expected to grab more than $20 million in advisory
fees from the deal, investment bankers say. The acquisition is
billed as the largest (non-Internet) software transaction ever.
</P>
<P>
   While Platinum was advised by CS First Boston, Computer
Associates negotiated without a Wall Street banker. However, CS
First Boston was the only underwriter of a $4.5 billion credit line
for Computer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Is it rare to double dip in the M&AMP;A advisory game?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen every day of the week,'' notes Joe
Josephson, a CS First Boston banker who worked on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROUND THREE: &LR;  Looksmart of San Francisco, an Internet
directory, has completed its third round of funding _ a $60 million
private equity placement. Looksmart says it's the largest amount
ever raised by a private Internet media company, bringing the
company's funding to $79.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the most recent round include: Amerindo Investment
Advisors, Citicorp Equity Capital, Cox Interactive Media, Essex
Investment Management, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, Macquarie Bank (an
Australian investment bank that acted as an adviser), New
Millennium Partners and Sand Hill Capital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IPO CANAPE: &LR;  Is hedge-fund manager Jim Cramer setting the table
for Goldman Sachs' initial public offering?
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, yes. Cramer is the co-founder of TheStreet.com
financial Web site, which is expected to go public this spring. As
it turns out, TheStreet's shares are slated to get priced during
the week of April 26, according to SEC filings.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs, the lead manager in TheStreet's offering, is
expected to take itself public just about a week after Cramer's
venture floats its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like a little Internet hors d'oeuvre to whet Wall
Street's appetite prior to the main course, eh?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
