<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DONATIONS MADE ON LINE MAKE IT TO CHARITIES
</P>
<P>
   In a new twist on Internet commerce, at least a half-dozen Web
sites are offering to sell goods to online shoppers and send a
portion of the purchase price to charity. Although the sums have
been modest thus far, many charities see it as an important
fund-raising development. But it is impossible to know in every
case what happens to the few dollars that customers thought were
going to a good cause. Though many charities are getting checks
directly from the sites, money may not end up in the charity's
hands as fast as shoppers might imagine _ if at all.
</P>
<P>
   NO PLANS FOR RENAULT NAME IN U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Having agreed last week to buy a little more than a third of
Nissan Motor, Renault may start selling Renault cars under the
Nissan name in the United States someday. But it has no plans to
revive the Renault name in the American market because its
reputation is so weak, the company's chairman and chief executive,
Louis Schweitzer, said at the New York International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
   LARGEST AWARD EVER IN SMOKING SUIT
</P>
<P>
   A state jury in Portland, Ore., ordered the largest award in a
smoking-related lawsuit, ruling that Philip Morris must pay $81
million to the family of a man who smoked Marlboro cigarettes for
four decades before he died.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT TALKS BEGIN
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks began between Microsoft and the federal and
state authorities who filed antitrust charges against the company.
Both sides emphasized before the discussions started that they
would talk in complete secrecy, but it was clear from the opening
positions of both parties that a vast gulf divides them, making a
settlement difficult at best.
</P>
<P>
   DOW TUMBLES FROM 10,000 PERCH
</P>
<P>
   Just a day after the Dow Jones industrial average surpassed
10,000, it and other market gauges retreated on concerns about
sales and earnings at big companies. The Dow fell 93.52 points, to
9,913.26, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dipped 9.42
points, to 1,300.75. The Nasdaq composite index lost 12.55 points,
to 2,480.29. Bond traders bid up prices on the Federal Reserve's
announcement that it would leave interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE FUND TO PAY BACK RESCUERS
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management, the giant hedge fund that Wall
Street firms saved from collapse during the turmoil in stock and
bond markets in September, has recovered robustly and plans to
start paying back its rescuers as early as June.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI BOTTLING PLANS TO GO PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi Bottling Group is going public in one of the biggest
public offerings ever, but not necessarily the hottest. Market
Place.
</P>
<P>
   U S AIRWAYS TO BUY BACK STOCK
</P>
<P>
   U S Airways Group, the nation's sixth-largest airline, said that
it would buy back $500 million in stock to lift its lagging shares.
The company also said that its first-quarter earnings would be in
line with analysts' recently reduced estimates. Shares of US
Airways rose $3.3125, or 7 percent, to $49.8125.
</P>
<P>
   EQUANT EXPANDS ITS DATA SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   Helping to expand the digital world to some of the globe's
least-wired corners, Equant plans to announce that it will offer
advanced data services in 25 additional territories.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK OF EXPRESS SCRIPTS SURGES
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts, a pharmacy benefits management company that has
a customer base of more than 36.5 million people, announced plans
for an on-line drugstore, and its shares surged $17.8125, or 24.1
percent, to $91.875.
</P>
</TEXT>
