<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0078 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEREG-SFCHRON &LR;      03-30 1821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEREG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Power Deregulation _ A Year Later
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
California entered uncharted waters one year ago today, when it
deregulated the electric industry and let an open market set
competitive prices for power.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge undertaking. Lawmakers cast aside the tightly
regulated system in which utilities built and operated power plants
and had exclusive access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In its place, they created a system that dispersed power plant
ownership, put control of the electricity superhighway in the hands
of a disinterested third party and created an open auction where
power can be purchased at the lowest price. For the first time
since the industry's earliest days, consumers can pick their own
power suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Mainline utilities like Pacific Gas and Electric Co. were
reduced to power-delivery companies and their unregulated sister
companies went on a power plant buying binge in other deregulated
states.
</P>
<P>
   Most participants feel the first year went remarkably well _
``especially if you remember the objective was to get the new
system up and running and seek perfection later,'' says Gordon
Smith, chief executive of Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   On the first anniversary, the unabashed goals of the bold move _
lower prices for all, greater reliability and robust technical
innovation _ are within reach. However, observers now think it was
unrealistic to expect to achieve the desired end without perfecting
the means.
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that the tool for change, the state's 1996
deregulation law, was less a blueprint than an Etch-a-Sketch.
Deregulation still is very much a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The new system has worked flawlessly from an engineering
standpoint. Getting a smooth-running market has been trickier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want things to be perfect from the start but we don't have
a finished product yet,'' says state Senator Steve Peace, D-El
Cajon (San Diego County), one of the authors of California's
deregulation law. ``Even so, it's been a spectacular success.''
</P>
<P>
   On the price front, results are mixed. &LR;   &LR; Small consumers got a
10 percent rate cut 15 months ago, but it was achieved by
refinancing their share of utility debts.
</P>
<P>
   Only green marketers have gone after small consumers in
meaningful numbers, and they've been surprised by how slowly the
market has developed. Only 1 percent of residential customers have
switched suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected a `California effect' that would supercharge the
green power movement and sweep across the country,'' says Kevin
Hartley, an executive vice president at Green Mountain Energy, the
biggest marketer of renewable power. ``We've learned that we have
to convince people to care.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, green power cost 10 to 20 percent more than generic
power. Last week, Green Mountain said it would begin selling its
power at a 5 percent discount to generic power.
</P>
<P>
   Green devotees think that will catalyze consumers and make it
easier to ``aggregate'' or combine the load of many small users
under a single contract. The Episcopal Diocese of California, for
example, is negotiating for the best deal, right now, that it can
take to its 87 Bay Area churches and 15,000 parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churches aren't wealthy institutions. The fact that prices are
coming down helps,'' says the Rev. Sally Bingham, head of
environmental ministries at Grace Cathedral in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Big users haven't needed much convincing to switch. They have
had plenty of companies offering them volume discounts. Nobody
knows how much money big users have saved, since most contracts are
confidential, but 1,000 industrial customers representing 30
percent of the state's industrial load have switched so far.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, utilities have divested $3 billion worth of power
plants at prices that far exceeded expectations. That's
significant, since _ dollar for dollar _ the money obtained through
asset sales reduces the utility debt that ratepayers must shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Asset sales have gone so well, in fact, that San Diego Gas &AMP;
Electric Co. says it expects to lower rates 20 percent for its
customers this summer, a year earlier than policymakers expected.
</P>
<P>
   With electricity now a market-based commodity, power generating
companies are rushing to build new plants. Twenty plant proposals
have come forward. That's more in-state generation than has been
planned in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing things are happening,'' says Daniel Yergin, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning economist whose latest book, ``The Commanding
Heights,'' recounts the rejection of centrally planned economies
around the globe for free markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most complex industry to go through the hard
process of becoming market-based,'' says Yergin. ``Since it
controlled 10 percent of all the fixed assets in this country, the
legacy of New Deal regulation persisted longer than in any other
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The inefficient system set aside was one in which consumers paid
a hand-picked group of utility generators whatever it cost them to
make electricity. That ``cost of service'' regulation meant
consumers paid for botched projects like PG&AMP;E's Diablo Canyon
nuclear plant with $5 billion worth of cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, if huge mistakes are made in the future, it'll be
investors who bear the cost, not ratepayers,'' says Alfred E. Kahn,
the ``father of deregulation'' and Cornell University economist
who's been watching California's grand experiment with keen
interest.
</P>
<P>
   That experiment has resulted in the expenditure of $400 million
to create two new power agencies to run the state's high-voltage
transmission grid and conduct a daily electricity auction. For both
the Independent System Operator in Folsom (Sacramento County) and
the Power Exchange in Pasadena (Los Angeles County), the mandate is
to ensure fair competition and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Just how well the market is working is debatable. Prices at the
Power Exchange appear slightly high. An analysis by economists at
the Energy Institute at the University of California at Berkeley
concluded that prices have been 17 percent higher than what a truly
competitive market would have offered. The report says that
resulted in a $500 million windfall to generators.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's unclear whether that's due to a market power problem
posed by having too few bidders or the inexperience of market
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Power generators, who once produced electricity with little
concern for costs, now must decide how to price their product and
where to sell it _ a daily market, an hourly spot market, an
emergency market or a soon-to-be-launched futures market.
</P>
<P>
   Even designers of this new market now see that electricity is
unlike any other commodity. Unlike corn and wheat, electricity
can't be stored in a silo. It must be consumed when it's created.
There aren't ready substitutes and demand doesn't track prices, at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Without a good model from other commodity markets, the designers
are trying to fashion one that works for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people went into deregulation thinking electricity
was just another commodity,'' says Severin Borenstein, head of the
Energy Institute at UC Berkeley and a member of the power auction's
governing board. ``It turns out it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   When market problems are identified, it's hard to make fixes
since there's no longer a single central regulator like the state
Public Utilities Commission that is in charge. Rules governing the
operations of the Power Exchange and Independent System Operator
are created by the organizations' governing boards that seek
consensus among 25 to 30 members and then must garner approval of
the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which regulates
interstate power sales.
</P>
<P>
   Although the boards are balanced to represent different
interests _ utilities, generators, power marketers and consumers _
the consensus approach has slowed the decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you have people benefiting from flaws in the market who
have great ability to slow down fixes,'' says Mike Florio, an
attorney for the consumer group The Utility Reform Network in San
Francisco and a member of both boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The composition of these boards has me concerned,'' says state
Senator Debra Bowen, D-Marina del Rey (Los Angeles County), chair
of the Senate Energy, Utilities and Communications Committee. ``I'm
leaning toward believing there's too much industry involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Many participants believe that, given time, these issues will be
resolved. Both agencies _ the ISO and Power Exchange -_are engaged
in talks with neighboring states to see about expanding their reach
to become regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had one year of a market versus 100 years of
regulation,'' says Elena Schmid, a supervisor in the PUC's Office
of Ratepayer Advocates and a member of the ISO board.
``Participation of so many players is messy. It was easier when
regulators were making the calls. But a variety of players will
mean a variety of choices for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the markets are perfected, big questions remain about
where the industry is headed.
</P>
<P>
   Mega-mergers are a strong possibility in America's largest
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very fragmented industry,'' says Kenneth Lay, chairman
of Enron Corp. of Houston, the biggest marketer of electricity in
America. ``Name me another major industry with 300 major players.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the potential for unlimited profits in a deregulated
market, unregulated affiliates of utilities are shopping for
divested plants. Last week, an affiliate of Southern California
Edison agreed to pay a staggering $5 billion for the cast-off
plants of Commonwealth Edison in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   US Generating Co., an affiliate of Pacific Gas and Electric,
already has bought &UR;  &LR; $1.6 billion worth of New England power plants
and is angling to buy the utility's vast hydroelectric generating
system in California.
</P>
<P>
   Power companies aren't the only ones sorting out what their
roles are in the new marketplace. State regulators are trying to
figure out what authority is left to them and how best to regulate
the commodity that doesn't act like other commodities.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is grappling with what the role should be of the
state PUC, the California Energy Commission and the new power
agencies. Peace, chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, is
conducting hearings to clarify future roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced we need a merger or something between some of
these agencies,'' says Peace. ``What you don't want is a lot of
agencies only able to tackle little pieces of a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much in motion, some consumer advocates worry about the
voyage on which California has embarked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it looks like utilities are on a luxury cruise,''
says Nettie Hoge, executive director of TURN. ``Meanwhile, small
consumers are on a raft with a small-craft warning up ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331-C     03-30 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGAINST BACKDROP OF ATROCITIES, MILOSEVIC DEFIANCE, NATO PRESSES
ON WITH BOMBINGS WITH NO END IN SIGHT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MILITARY-0331; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331;
KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0331.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After pounding Serb targets for seven days, NATO
officials admitted Tuesday that they were shocked and surprised by
the continuing atrocities ravaging Kosovo, warning grimly that
there was no quick military solution to the humanitarian
catastrophe unfolding there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody could have anticipated that it would be
quite as bad as it seems now to be becoming,'' NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea told reporters in Brussels, as hordes of horrified and weary
refugees streamed toward the borders of neighboring countries. ``I
think we can talk about a modern-day Great Terror going on in
Kosovo at the moment,'' Shea said, in a reference to purges by
Joseph Stalin that left some 2 million Russians dead six decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing their campaign of violence, pillage and destruction to
the heart of Kosovo, Serb troops and special police forced
thousands of ethnic Albanians to abandon their homes in the
provincial capital of Pristina, even as around-the-clock NATO air
strikes punched at the forces underpinning the repression.
</P>
<P>
   As the air assault entered its second week, however, U.S. and
NATO officials conceded that poor weather, difficult terrain and
the threat of Serb air defenses continued to hamper the mission,
forcing bombing runs to be scuttled in mid-air and blunting the
effectiveness of high-tech weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never supposed or reported that we had a silver bullet that
would bring this to a halt,'' asserted U.S. Naval Vice Adm. Scott
Fry, director of operations for the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was going to be hard,'' Fry told reporters at the
Pentagon. ``We are grinding it out.''
</P>
<P>
   With a NATO victory not yet in sight, President Clinton told the
nation to brace for ``a sustained period'' of continuing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the 19-member NATO alliance to stick with the
mission, saying the wholesale persecution of Albanians since the
allied attacks began has only underscored the necessity of striking
the forces commanded by Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever any doubt about what is at stake in Kosovo,
Mr. Milosevic is certainly erasing it by his actions,'' Clinton
said. ``We must remain steady and determined with the will to see
this through.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, military officials said future strikes would
bear down increasingly on the individual troops and tanks carrying
out the hostilities on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In strikes Monday and Tuesday, NATO warplanes bombed Serb army
garrisons in Pristina, army barracks just north of Kosovo and an
array of fuel and ammo depots scattered across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington and London showed reporters images of
the Pristina headquarters for the Serb special police and also for
the army, both of which have conducted brutal campaigns against
ethnic Albanians. Both headquarters operations appeared to be
destroyed by coordinated strikes from multiple NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sort of treatment which Milosevic can now
increasingly expect,'' said Gen. Sir Charles Guthrie, chief of
staff for the British Defense Agency. ``The focus of the air
strikes has now shifted firmly towards military forces in Kosovo
and the facilities directly supporting them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British officers said, however, that heavy cloud cover
and the continuing threat of Serb air defenses had seriously
compromised the pace of the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Low-flying U.S. A-10 tank busters, for instance, flew missions
Monday night but returned without firing on their targets, said
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. pilots have at times been unable to fire laser-guided
bombs, which perform poorly in cloudy conditions, out of fear of
unleashing a bomb that could land wide of its target and perhaps
injure civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Low-flying Harrier attack jets were able to strike their targets
on only two nights out of the first six of the campaign, British
officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart technology is affected by poor weather, and we have
had a run of very poor weather,'' Guthrie told reporters in London.
``What we do not want to do is to create any more collateral damage
than we have, we do not want to kill innocent civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing as ``unacceptable'' a tepid Russian-brokered offer by
Milosevic to talk peace in exchange for a halt in the bombing,
Clinton instead upped the diplomatic ante for Belgrade, saying
Milosevic risks losing Kosovo altogether by persevering with a
military sweep that has put an estimated 600,000 ethnic Albanians
to flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a sustained period, he will see that his military will be
seriously diminished, key military infrastructure destroyed, the
prospect of international support for Serbia's claim to Kosovo
increasingly jeopardized,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is opposed to independence for
Kosovo, a province of 2.2 million, 90 percent of whom are ethnic
Albanians, in southern Serbia, and State Department spokesman James
Rubin stressed that this position hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments, however, were clearly meant to send the
message to Milosevic that the longer he stands up to NATO, the
greater the chance that his defiance and oppression will ultimately
cost him the province at the center of his dispute with the
powerful U.S. and European alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plea for NATO tenacity -- made during a State
Department ceremony to unveil a portrait of former Secretary of
State Warren Christopher -- echoed earlier statements from the
British government, in what appeared to be a coordinated effort to
demonstrate NATO unity and resolve in the face of a difficult and
widening air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has got the determination and the stomach to see this
through,'' British Defense Secretary George Robertson assured
reporters in London. ``The killing fields of Kosovo are not going
to remain as some memorial for Milosevic to sneer over, and we are
determined to make sure that the violence is stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   As Robertson and Clinton spoke, however, much of Kosovo was in
flames. Serb troops under Milosevic's command were pressing forward
with a concerted program of terror that invited flashbacks to the 3
1/2-year war between Serbs and non-Serbs in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials displayed intelligence photographs of
buildings burning near the town of Brestovac, where special Serb
police units were active, and Dobrido, where Serb army troops were
operating.
</P>
<P>
   Other images were shown documenting the forced evacuation of
towns and villages across a wide swath of north-central Kosovo,
where fleeing civilians left their homes to be destroyed by the
torches of Serb forces, and of similar activities near towns in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   NATO received unconfirmed reports of artillery and tank attacks
on large groups of refugees fleeing toward the Albanian border from
population centers in southwest Kosovo. By late Tuesday, U.S.
officials said they could not confirm those reports.
</P>
<P>
   The stories told by tens of thousands of fleeing refugees,
however, are being largely confirmed through intelligence sources
-- U.S. spy satellites and three high-altitude U-2 spy planes are
actively monitoring the region, as are, presumably, U.S. and NATO
contacts on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the evidence points to a catastrophe of epic
proportions unfolding across the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know President Milosevic's record, but I think that
even we have been shocked by the sheer proportions of what we see
happening in Kosovo today,'' Shea, told reporters at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``In whole towns and villages, tanks are first surrounding the
site, then paramilitaries are going in, rounding up civilians at
gunpoint, separating young men from women and children,'' Shea
said, describing in hauntingly familiar detail a reprise of the
pattern Serb troops and paramilitary thugs used to force an
estimated 3 million Muslims and Croats from their homes during the
civil war in Bosnia. ``The women and children are then expelled
from their homes and then sent towards the border. And after they
have left, the villages, the towns, the homes, are looted and then
systematically torched.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) said the movements of ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo and
along its borders had become so widespread and frenetic that
accurate numbers on displaced people were no longer attainable.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimated, however, that roughly 94,000 ethnic
Albanians had fled the country just since the NATO air strikes
began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR estimated -- guessed, really -- that nearly 600,000
Kosovar Albanians have been displaced in 15 months of conflict.
Roughly half are believed to be hiding inside Kosovo or desperately
trying to get out, and the rest have made their way to neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that we haven't seen since the forced
evacuation of Phnom Penh in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge in the mid
1970s,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
