<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-ECONO     03-30 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SOCIAL PROGRAMS GET A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Social Security and Medicare will run out of money
later than previously projected, trustees of the two programs said
Tuesday in a report that could take pressure off Congress to enact
money-saving reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks largely to the robust economy, Medicare's hospital
insurance trust fund will remain solvent until 2015, seven years
later than in last year's forecast. It was the second year in a row
that the trustees added seven years to the expected life of the
fund, which pays for hospital, hospice, and home health care for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security will remain solvent until 2034, two years later
than in the trustees' previous forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, secretary of the Department of Health and Human
Services, called the report ``excellent news.'' Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin said it resulted from ``our current strong economic
conditions, what many consider to be the best in recent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress and President Clinton are trying to find ways to shore
up Social Security and Medicare, which will face severe financial
strains early in the next century as the wave of baby boomers
begins to retire. But there are few signs that they can reach an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A congressionally chartered Medicare study panel recently
disbanded without making a recommendation to Congress. The group
split largely along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   To shore up Social Security, Congress and the president have
agreed to divert $2.8 trillion of future budget surpluses to the
retirement program, which would keep it solvent until 2055. But
Clinton and lawmakers have not begun serious talks on other
changes, such as benefit cuts or a higher age of eligibility, which
might be needed to keep the program stable longer.
</P>
<P>
   Though an economic downturn could bring back the earlier, less
optimistic, forecasts for the two programs, Tuesday's report could
reduce the urgency for lawmakers to make tough political decisions
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the pressure off a Medicare agreement in the sense
that lawmakers will say, `We have seven more years than we thought
to develop a solution to this very complex problem, and let's not
act hastily,' '' said Robert Reischauer, a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office, who is now with the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Reischauer said the trustees' report will not affect the Social
Security debate much, because the two-year delay in insolvency is
minor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the prospects for a deal on long-term changes to
Social Security are ``between nil and very, very small.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have made similar comments in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there's less than a 50 percent chance'' for a Social
Security deal, Representative Nick Smith of Michigan, a leading
Republican advocate of Social Security overhaul, told the
Associated Press last week.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security's projected insolvency was pegged for the year
2029 before the trustees moved it to 2032 a year ago, and then to
2034 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Apfel, commissioner of the Social Security
Administration, said the latest change was mostly because of the
booming US economy, as lower unemployment, higher wages, and low
inflation are expected to put more tax dollars into the trust fund.
About one-quarter of the new forecast was because of changes in the
way the government measures inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The new projection also cuts the size of Social Security's
unfunded obligations to retirees in the next 75 years to 2.07
percent of taxable payroll, compared with last year's estimate of
2.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said three factors were responsible for the big delay in
the date of Medicare's insolvency. They include the strong economy
and a crackdown on waste and abuse by hospitals and other service
providers, which she said returned $1.2 billion to the Medicare
trust fund in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The third factor was the Balanced Budget Amendment of 1997,
which cut Medicare payments to hospitals, home health providers and
service providers.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, hospital groups have claimed that those
cutbacks have been too severe, leading to layoffs and financial
losses, particularly at teaching hospitals. The cutbacks enacted in
1997 cost Massachusetts hospitals an estimated $1.7 billion over
five years, the Massachusetts Hospital Association has said. On
average, hospitals rely on Medicare for 30 percent of their
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security and Medicare trustees include Shalala,
Rubin, Apfel, and Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, as well as two
public members.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement Tuesday, the two public members urged a
go-slow approach to changing Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The recent collapse of the bipartisan Medicare commission
``raises the issue of whether it is wise to focus on finding one
overarching solution to the problems these programs face, or
whether to seek instead incremental changes,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Without endorsing the idea, the two public members also
suggested lawmakers consider indexing Social Security benefits to
changes in population trends or the economy. For example, if US
life expectancy rises, Social Security might raise its age of
eligibility. Or if wages rise slowly, Social Security benefits
might rise at the same slow rate. This approach might end the
``political gridlock'' paralyzing the debate, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The two public members are Stephen Kellison, chief actuary and
vice president of a Houston life insurance company, and Marilyn
Moon, a senior fellow at the Urban Institute in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
