<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-800(2     03-30 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BELGRADE, EVEN MILOSEVIC FOES CRITICIZE WESTERN MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BRITAIN, KOSOVO-YELTSIN,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Frustrated by the war propaganda that
passes for news here, a small but significant minority of Serbs
spend long hours every day watching satellite television,
exchanging e-mail and surfing the Internet. But few find the
Western version wholly convincing.
</P>
<P>
   They say that NATO's media manipulation is simply more subtle
than Belgrade's official blunderbuss, that Serbian interests in
Kosovo are ignored or trivialized and that Serbs are being
demonized to justify the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Vesna Kostic, an economic journalist and an open opponent of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, spends several hours a day
watching Sky News, BBC televsion news and CNN, listening to the
banned Belgrade independent radio station, B-92, on satellite,
exchanging e-mail around the world and reading Western newspapers
on the Web, through her two Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is offering free use of the Internet during the war,
and Mrs. Kostic fears that the Milosevic government will find some
way to shut the providers down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, ``the West is not pushing a campaign against
just Milosevic anymore, but against the entire Serb people,'' and
she is offended by the content and the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the West is more reliable, but it's not wholly reliable
_ that I also know,'' she said. ``It's better than our stupid
propaganda, but it's obvious the West is also conducting a
propaganda war, a public relations war, and it knows how to do it
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliable information is scarce, she said. ``You can't know
what's true. How many planes have been shot down? Is Fehmi Agani
dead or alive?'' she said, referring to the moderate Albanian
professor and negotiator who NATO says was killed by Serbs in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kostic was arrested by Milosevic's government in 1994 and
sentenced to three months in jail, which was reduced to a year's
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Serb police are terrible,'' she said. ``I'm
frightened of them. But it's not only Albanian human rights at
stake, it's mine as well. Milosevic is already moving against the
independent press and the opposition. This bombing will mean
keeping that creature in power another 100 years and destroying the
opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she believes Western accusations of atrocities in
Kosovo, she sighed. ``I do believe Serb forces are pushing out
Albanians,'' she said. ``I hope they are not slaughtering
civilians, but I do believe they are intimidating them to go out. I
don't approve of it, but I understand it. When you're in a war, you
can't afford to have people shoot you in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   To watch the Western news stations, she said, ``You wouldn't
know that there is an Albanian army fighting against the Serbs,'' a
reference to the guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's terrible now,'' she said, ``but Milosevic didn't
create Kosovo. He made it worse, but the riots started in 1981. The
Albanians had a state within a state already, but they wanted more.
Now the West is fighting for their independence while claiming that
Serbia will keep sovereignty. It's the hypocrisy I hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusan, 21, a student of electrical engineering in Novi Sad,
northwest of Belgrade, spends hours on the Internet, exchanging
information with friends about what sites are hit by the bombs,
tracking down rumors and monitoring Western media. He is a
pro-democracy demonstrator, a member of Otpor, the Student
Resistance Movement. He was reached by telephone after he attached
it to an e-mail message, but fearing mobilization into the army, he
insisted that his surname not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against Milosevic, and I don't think I'm a victim of
propaganda by either side,'' he said. ``I watch and read our media
and the international media, including The New York Times and The
Washington Post, and I'm in touch with students all over the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dusan complains that Serbs are being demonized and that the
world talks of Nazis now to justify an act of aggression on a
sovereign country fighting an insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO says this is the worst humanitarian crisis in Europe
since World War II,'' he said, ``but three years ago a half-million
Serbs were cleared out of Krajina. But it wasn't in the interests
of the U.S. to put Croatia down, so there was less information and
no outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand NATO must justify its actions, but the bombing of
Yugoslavia is wrong. I know Slobodan Milosevic is doing bad things,
and lots and lots of people in Serbia hate Milosevic. But there are
also a lot of innocent people here, and now his regime is stronger
than ever. Horrible things are happening, but horrible things have
happened all through the Balkans.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Radio 021, the only independent media outlet in Novi Sad,
Serbia's second-largest city, was also shut down. ``Everything will
be shut down, and then what?'' Dusan asked. ``It will be another 20
years before democracy comes here, and there's a bigger
humanitarian crisis than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Micovic, like Dusan, is a student leader who published his
phone number on the Internet. Students use the World Wide Web and
e-mail almost exclusively to exchange information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the authorities don't even know what e-mail is,'' he
said. ``During the student protests our Web page was popular, and
the police broke in and said, `Where is that Internet?' as if they
could confiscate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Micovic, 23, uses the Yugoslav Internet service provider EUnet
and a university provider called Afrodite. In Novi Sad, he said, it
can take four hours to get a connection.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many people in Yugoslavia use the Internet or
e-mail. A study financed by the U.S. Agency for International
Development suggested that perhaps 50,000 in this country used
e-mail; Belgrade alone has nearly two million people.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for EUnet, who would not give his name, said that
his company and the various other providers had about 60,000
subscribers in Yugoslavia, and that at least 100,000 people used
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   They include the Serbian Orthodox Church, which has sent e-mail
to contacts around the world. An impassioned recent message from
the Rev. Sava Janjic of the Decani Monastery, for example, appealed
for an end to NATO bombing, which, it said, ``will only make things
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Many more Serbs have access to satellite receivers that enable
them to watch Western television, including German and Italian
channels.
</P>
<P>
   But Micovic, too, finds his access to information no easy guide
to reality. ``Either way I go, I stand to lose,'' he said.
``Supporting the bombing is stupid, because it makes everything
worse. Most people in the West don't understand the mentality that
exists here. The bombing has weakened any chance to turn Serbia
into a democratic country.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time here we have been trying to build connections
between students and other groups, and we were making some
progress, but after the bombing it's largely destroyed. Milosevic
now has the power to do what he pleases, and some of my friends
have already been drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a professional television journalist here, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, says no one can believe in the state media,
which cycle rumors and propaganda in a crude way. ``We joke that if
so many NATO planes have been shot down,'' he said, ``their pilots
must already speak Serbian and are hiding in a village tending the
cows, because no one can find them.''
</P>
<P>
   He watches a lot of Western television and surfs the Internet
for six or seven hours a day, he said. ``But there is a lot of
nonsense there, too. On CNN they said that 8,000 to 12,000 Albanian
refugees were crossing the border every hour,'' he said, laughing.
``First, it's impossible to know. But in 10 hours that's 100,000
people, and in four days that's a million people. And in seven
days, all of Kosovo is empty.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he believe that Serbian forces are committing
atrocities in Kosovo? He sighed. ``I think they do it,'' he said.
``I think they'll do whatever is necessary to stay in power, and
they try to destroy the KLA and expel as many people as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he said, the point is not the percentage of
Serbs who live in Kosovo. ``What's important is that for centuries
Kosovo was part of the Serbian state. And if we say that now Serbia
will give it up and be smaller, fine, but we must agree to do it.
NATO has put the whole region on the edge of a real eruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
