u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-VALENTI-670&AMP;ADD     03-30 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VALENTI-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE WANT MORE U.S. FILMS, MOVIE BUSINESS EXECUTIVE REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Hollywood has received its first sign in years that
China may be willing to allow more American films into its
theaters, a movie industry leader said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And as a sweetener in its campaign to open up the potentially
giant market here, the U.S. movie industry plans to stage a Chinese
film festival in New York and Los Angeles in October.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, chairman of the Motion Picture Association of
America, made the offer of a film festival in talks with senior
Chinese cultural officials here over the last two days. In the
talks he urged China to open its doors not only to more American
movies _ currently no more than 10 are allowed in each year _ but
also to American investment in studios, co-productions and
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said in an interview Tuesday night that he had been
heartened by his reception, which he described as the most positive
in four visits over the last three years. He met with Ding Guangen,
who is the Communist Party's chief of propaganda, and Sun Jiazheng,
the culture minister.
</P>
<P>
   While they made no specific commitments, both officials
indicated they wanted to see more American films in China, Valenti
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in all my visits that they've given me
a hopeful sign,'' he said. Still, without an agreement there is no
way to know how soon China's policies might change.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials made no public comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our companies are ready to invest millions of dollars here if
they are allowed to,'' Valenti said. ``We'd like to come in and
build multiplexes,'' which could attract more consumers to both
Chinese and American films.
</P>
<P>
   The officials did not bite on the multiplex idea, but they did
express interest in having American companies help renovate some
theaters, and they liked the idea of a film festival to promote
Chinese-made films abroad, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti is in a trade mission led by secretary of commerce
William M. Daley.
</P>
<P>
   By an unwritten rule, only about 10 foreign films per year,
virtually all of them American, are allowed to play inside China on
a basis of shared box-office revenues. China's concerns are partly
ideological: the Communist Party worries about ``spiritual
pollution'' from the West. But the country also wants to protect
its own weak film industry.
</P>
<P>
   China has not offered clear criteria for its choices but
generally avoids films with nudity or that delve into politics.
</P>
<P>
   Last year only seven American films were released here,
including ``Titanic,'' which was a sensation and grossed more than
$35 million in China, and ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which had modest
results.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999 eight films have been approved so far, including ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' ``The X-Files,'' ``A Bug's Life'' and ``The Truman
Show.'' Only the Disney animated film ``Mulan'' has been released,
though, and it is suffering because of widespread pirating.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance of ``Mulan'' was delayed last year because of
Chinese anger over the Disney Corp.'s involvement with a film
glorifying the Dalai Lama. But Disney has patched things up with
the government, and three more of its films also have been approved
for release.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other foreign films, most from Hong Kong and Taiwan,
play in China for a flat fee, an arrangement that is not
interesting to Hollywood studios, said William Brent, president of
China Entertainment Network, a consulting concern based in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   China's own film industry produced about 80 films last year,
Brent said. But these are made under conditions of censorship with
outdated technology, and they seldom strike a chord with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   China does have some directors of international stature like
Zhang Yimou and Chen Kaige, whose films are respected if not always
commercially successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what the Chinese are afraid of,'' Brent said. ``
`Titanic' and `Saving Private Ryan' alone probably accounted for 30
percent of the total box office in China last year, and if 30
American films come in, their own industry could be totally wiped
out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Valenti proposed that from June 1999 to June 2000 China allow 17
American movies in, then about 25 in the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the plan for a film festival, which will showcase 10 to
12 Chinese films with commercial potential on cable television if
not in theaters, American companies are willing to help develop the
Chinese film industry if China wants that.
</P>
<P>
   The American companies could provide training for Chinese
studios in high-technology production methods, marketing and
distribution and hold classes in directing and writing, Valenti
said. Interns could work in American companies, and Chinese
students could be helped to enter American film schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their studios are in the Mesozoic Era, and they know it,''
Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged officials here to allow competition in film
distribution, now controlled by an inefficient monopoly, and to
reduce the heavy taxes on film revenue.
</P>
<P>
   En route to China the trade mission stopped in South Korea,
where Valenti urged President Kim Dae Jung to drop a quota that
requires every screen in every theater to show Korean films at
least 146 days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a stern and unforgiving rebuttal,'' Valenti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
