u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      03-30 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG ECONOMY, REFORMS DELAY MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY CRISES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A robust economy and previously enacted reforms
have pushed back the looming financial crisis for Social Security
by two years and Medicare by seven years, according to an annual
assessment released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings that the two benefit programs for the elderly are
more sound than previously envisioned could lessen the pressure on
Congress this year to make major changes urged by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But anticipating the political impact of the new findings,
Clinton warned that reforms should still be enacted promptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might say this good news means we can simply delay
reforms. Nothing could be further from the truth,'' Clinton said in
a Rose Garden appearance. ``Now is the time to make those changes.
Now, when we have time on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress to use most of the federal budget
surplus to ensure that Social Security and Medicare funds will be
available when the vast Baby Boom generation retires early in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional Republicans have clashed with the White House
over the approaches for overhauling the programs. Those differences
led to the failure this month of a bipartisan commission on
Medicare to agree on a plan to change the health insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Republicans are pushing for large tax cuts, which
Democrats have warned could use surplus money that is needed to
shore up Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The financial assessment of the two entitlements was included in
the annual report of the Board of Trustees for Social Security and
Medicare, which is composed of four Clinton administration
officials and two presidential appointees.
</P>
<P>
   The report projected that Social Security would be able to pay
full benefits until 2034, two years later than had been estimated
in last year's trustee's report.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that Medicare, which had been projected to run out
of money in 2008, would remain financially sound until 2015.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year in a row that the report has extended
the life of Medicare. Last year, the trustees moved back the
bankruptcy date for the health insurance program by seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials attributed the improvement to the booming economy and
changes in the way the benefits are administered. The economy has
boosted the revenue generated from payroll taxes that fund both
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security benefits also will last longer, in part because
of adjustments in the consumer price index, which determines
benefit levels.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare has benefited from legislative changes that reduced
payments to medical providers and governmental efforts to crack
down on fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We vigorously managed Medicare,'' said Health and Human
Services Secretary Donna Shalala, a Medicare and Social Securities
board member. ``I'm talking about management that is hands on,
holds people accountable, introduces new systems and responds to
changing systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Medicare has been more successful in recent
years in halting a common practice by medical providers of slipping
patients into more expensive reimbursement categories that did not
correspond to the treatment they received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providers of Medicare have been able to game the system to
their advantage. But over time, that has become harder to do,''
said Marilyn Moon, an economist and a Medicare trustee.
</P>
<P>
   While about 6 million of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries
are now enrolled in managed-care plans, officials said that trend
has not generated the cost savings that some have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Moon said the government has been overpaying managed-care plans,
which charge a fixed sum regardless of whether the beneficiaries
use the services. She said that healthy beneficiaries often enroll
in managed-care plans and then switch to the traditional
fee-for-service plans when they become chronically sick.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Medicare officials predict that greater numbers of
beneficiaries will enroll in managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the breathing room for action, the initial response from
Republican chairmen of committees with jurisdiction over the
programs was that lawmakers should proceed to make difficult
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let this good news make us complacent in our efforts
to improve the ability of Medicare to meet the needs of seniors,''
said Senate Finance Committee chairman William Roth, R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Houston, who was
traveling in Australia, also issued a statement on the report:
</P>
<P>
   ``That Social Security and Medicare each have a few more years
of projected solvency should not come as a surprise, given the
continued strength of the economy. Nor does it mean we should stop
considering solutions to the inevitable crises _ due to changing
demographics _ that these programs face in their long-term
funding.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ability to reach a political consensus this year may be
tough, particularly with the collapse of the bipartisan commission
on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, led by Sen. John Breaux, D-La., had developed a
plan that would raise the eligibility age for Medicare, from 65 to
67, and would have the government pay a fixed sum for each Medicare
beneficiary, rather than pay separately for each medical service.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rejected the plan, however, because it did not provide
for pharmaceutical benefits and did not set aside 15 percent of the
surplus for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would propose his own plan to fix Medicare, and
his advisers said that the revised estimates had not changed his
intentions to submit that blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux also said he intended to put the commission's
recommendations into legislation despite the president's
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said lawmakers must ``go beyond the same old legislative
fix that will extend Medicare's solvency only by further cutting
reimbursement payments to hospitals and providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding fixes for Social Security also has not proved easy, as
lawmakers debate whether to privatize a portion of the retirement
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has advocated letting the federal government invest a
portion of the retirement funds in the stock markets to boost
revenue. Republicans want to give individuals the ability to invest
some of the funds in the market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
