u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-MARKETPLACE-550     03-30 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-MARKETPLACE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: IPO COULD USE A DOT-COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another environment, the initial public offering
of Pepsi Bottling Group might be one of the hottest stock deals of
the year, driven by an international brand name and a consumer
franchise with great opportunity to expand abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year of the Internet, investors have been rather
uninterested in offerings by companies lacking ``dot-com'' in their
names.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the announcement late Monday by Coca-Cola Co. that
its sales, measured in cases, took an unexpected drop in the first
quarter, and the result could be a tepid reception for the Pepsi
Bottling offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is the largest manufacturer, distributor and
seller of Pepsi-Cola beverages, provided the details of its
long-awaited separation from Pepsico late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is selling 100 million shares of common stock for $23 a
share, raising $2.3 billion before expenses _ the fifth-largest
initial public offering by an American corporation, according to
Securities Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And if Pepsi Bottling exercises its option to issue an
additional 15 million shares under its overallotment clause, it
could rise as high as No. 3, behind last year's offering by Conoco
and the 1996 issue of Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The price, though, is at the bottom of the $23-to-$26-a-share
range that the company had previously said it was considering, most
likely reflecting caution after Coca-Cola's surprise announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold shares of several beverage companies Tuesday
following the Coca-Cola news, with Coke shares falling $1.5625, to
$63.50. Shares of Pepsico, which after the offering will own 35
percent of the bottling company's common shares and 43 percent of
the voting power in all classes of stock, fell 81.25 cents, to
$39.875.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coca-Cola Enterprises, Coke's largest bottler and the
company whose structure most closely reflects that of Pepsi
Bottling, fell $1.8125, to $31.50.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts played down any connection between Coca-Cola's
weakness and Pepsico's largest bottler. Roy Burry, an analyst at
Brown Brothers Harriman, noted that Coca-Cola's loss of market
share presumably meant a gain for Pepsi, which would be good news
for the bottler.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the only area in which Coca-Cola eked out a sales
gain in the first quarter was North America, meaning that the
domestic soft-drink market might not be as weak as in the rest of
the world. About 92 percent of Pepsi Bottling's case volume is sold
in North America, and the company handles about 55 percent of
Pepsi's U.S. volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to look at Coke's volume numbers and deduce how
they will affect Pepsi,'' said Richard Joy, an analyst at Standard
&AMP; Poor's equity group. Pepsi Bottling could still see some weakness
in the small part of its business that is overseas: 8 percent of
its sales volume, measured in cases, comes from Spain, Greece and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been an extremely weak market for multinational
corporations like Coke and Pepsi ever since last year's devaluation
of the ruble. Spain offers a potential base for expansion into
neighboring European Union countries, but that market is not
growing very rapidly itself. Greece, meanwhile, offers relatively
little opportunity for regional expansion, given its proximity to
the war-torn Balkan nations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All that said, Pepsi Bottling has certain attractions. For one,
it is likely to trade at a lower valuation than Coca-Cola
Enterprises. Standard &AMP; Poor's, in its Emerging and Special
Situations newsletter, calculated that at the midpoint of the
projected price range, Pepsi Bottling would trade at about nine
times earnings before noncash charges like depreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises trades at about 10 times that earnings
measure. And since Pepsi Bottling is pricing at the low end of the
range, the discount grows that much larger.
</P>
<P>
   With its offering, Pepsi is following the trail blazed by Coke
and Coca-Cola Enterprises _ a surprising fact given that a number
of analysts and customers of the bottler have questioned just how
independent those two companies are.
</P>
<P>
   But the offering will give Pepsi Bottling the financial strength
to expand its vending operations and to continue an overhaul of its
manufacturing and distribution network. Those combined efforts
could help the company's profit margins in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should not expect the shares, which begin trading
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol PBG, to
replicate the sharp rise recorded by recent offerings like that of
Priceline.com, which rose $53 Tuesday, to $69, from its initial
offering price of $16.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is it preordained, though, that Pepsi Bottling will draw
as little interest as the February offering of Del Monte Foods,
which went public at $15 a share and closed Tuesday at $11.75.
Investors with long-term horizons, and a thirst for Pepsi over
Coke, might find the offering has some appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
