<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART     03-30 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN TRIUMPH, CALHOUN STILL REMEMBERED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ He was at the top of his profession _ 10
feet high, technically, but a career's worth of success in cosmic
measurement. In a moment like this, an egomaniac might blurt
something about being king of the world, or dance around like the
proverbial decapitated chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Calhoun thought about somebody else. After Connecticut
outplayed Duke, 77-74, for the national college basketball
championship Monday night, there were a few strands of net hanging
from the rim, a civilized version of two ears and a tail in
bullfighting.
</P>
<P>
   He could have claimed all the spoils for having devised a
defense that helped his team finish three points ahead of Mike
Krzyzewski's team. Even though this burly basketball lifer had
never coached in the Final Four, he must have had something to do
with the victory, no?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the victory did exorcise Christian Laettner's
shot that killed Connecticut in the 1990 East Regional, after
Krzyzewski changed the play after a second timeout. This time, with
Laettner in attendance, Calhoun sent his co-captain, Ricky Moore,
out to stop Trajan Langdon one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ladder and the scissors, Calhoun clipped a fragment of
net but left something hanging from the rim, left it for the man
with ``the best seat in the house,'' Calhoun would say in a husky
voice.
</P>
<P>
   The last piece was for the family of Joe McGinn, who was once
his manager but came down with kidney disease so severe that he
died on March 9, at the age of 26.
</P>
<P>
   This moment of generosity was not something he had scripted a
day or two earlier _ no crafted victory speech in his jacket
pocket. As he climbed the ladder, he suddenly thought of Joe
McGinn, whom he had counseled through his terrible last years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like,'' he said later in the steamy locker
room. ``I was called in from the outfield when I was 15, and found
out my father died of a heart attack. My coach then helped me get
through it. That's how I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not going to change, he insisted. He is still going to be
this self-styled ``stubborn Irish guy'' from Boston. He did not
need to win the Final Four to feel good about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now he joins the roster of coaches who won this jamboree:
Valvano. Haskins. Rupp. Richardson. Thompson. Massimino. Tarkanian.
Pitino. A couple of unrelated Smiths. A couple of unrelated
McGuires. Coach K. All the others. And somebody named Wooden, who
won it 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it now includes my name, but it doesn't validate me,''
Calhoun said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understood that stuff,'' he added. ``It's like all
that baloney about the Super Bowl, where you lose four of them and
you're a loser. Does this mean you're better off going 10-8 and
getting knocked out in the first round?''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said he was the same person after 554 victories and 257
losses in 27 years. He specifically mentioned Eddie Sutton, who has
taken four teams to the tournament but never won it. The lifers
don't get to be lifers without knowing some stuff, do they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches cheat sometimes,'' Calhoun disclosed to an amazed
audience from the media. ``We do. We tell you things, and you use
them. You know that. I kept talking about how great Duke was _ and
they were. But I told my team, `This is the first time all year
that I'm telling you, they are as good as you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   He also told his players they could beat Duke. He schmoozed with
30 or 40 coaches, and thought he could throw in a lot of players,
make Duke run. His ace card was the sense of being an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun is from the distinctly nonscale American International,
and learned to coach at Northeastern, a bootstrapper's school in
urban Boston. When his Connecticut team overwhelmed a game Eastern
Michigan team a few years ago, Calhoun raved about the heart of the
two little opposing guards. They were his kind of guys.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he counted 17 of his former players in the stands _
men who took time off from their jobs in business or basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Gwynn, Lyman DePriest, Spider Usry, Scotty Burrell, Ray
Allen, all of them,'' Calhoun said. ``Howie Dickenman, who used to
be my assistant, who laid the groundwork by recruiting a lot of
these guys, was here.''
</P>
<P>
   They filed into the borrowed office to hug the man who had
yelled at them so many times. Calhoun said he felt ``humbled'' by
the night, and the presence of his old boys, and in his celebration
he remembered to save a souvenir in honor of his late team manager,
the one with ``the best seat in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
