<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-HI-SPEED-AMTRA     03-30 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HI-SPEED-AMTRAK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED AMTRAK BEGINS TO ROLL, SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(SUBS 7th graf to change million to billion)  (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, when Florida Gov. Jeb Bush ended state financing for
the proposed 320-mile high-speed rail project that would have
linked Miami, Orlando and Tampa, the future of high-speed train
service in the United States suffered an apparent major setback.
</P>
<P>
   But an unlikely savior _ make that an unlikely  &UR; possible &LR;  savior
_ rode toward the rescue in March: Amtrak, that much maligned
national passenger rail system created by Congress in 1971, which
has lost money every year since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (While the cause of the recent Amtrak crash south of Chicago
that killed 11 people and injured more than 100 after colliding
with a truck at an intersection has not yet been determined, it did
not involve high speed rails or high speed trains. And the train
was not exceeding the 79 mph limit.)
</P>
<P>
   In February, Amtrak unveiled the first of 20 high-speed trains
that will go into service later this year along the Northeast
Corridor, the 470-mile strip linking Washington, New York and
Boston. The new trains, renamed Acela, to suggest a combination of
excellence and acceleration, will race along at 150 mph, Amtrak
officials said; their top speed today is 90 mph between Boston and
New York and 125 mph between New York and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The higher speed, a result of track improvements and technology
that allows the new trains to tilt into curves with little danger
of derailment or of disrupting passengers when the trains bank,
would cut 30 minutes from the present four-hour New York to Boston
trip and up to 30 minutes between New York and Washington. As an
added lure, Amtrak officials said that fares will be 30 percent
lower than walk-up fares on US Airways' and Delta's shuttle
flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That saving presumably would make Acela more attractive to
passengers, especially business travelers. In addition, the new
cars will offer electrical outlets for laptop computers and audio
entertainment, televised news updates, tables to spread out papers
or hold meetings, enlarged lounges and bathrooms, and better food,
drinks and luggage storage.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Amtrak's ambitious plans for the Northeast Corridor succeed _
enabling the line to become self-sufficient by 2002, when its
federal subsidy is scheduled to end _ the railroad next plans a $25
billion network of high-speed trains linking nine Midwestern states
from Ohio to Nebraska, with Chicago as the hub. Then it hopes to
add other regions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those trains are still some years down the road. Meanwhile,
about a dozen other high-speed routes are already on the drawing
boards or under construction. They range in length from 85 miles,
between Chicago and Milwaukee, to 676 miles, the so-called
California corridor that would link San Diego, Los Angeles, San
Francisco and Sacramento. Projected costs for the projects range
from $29 billion for the California corridor to $315 million to
link the Buffalo-Albany portion of the 430-mile Empire corridor
between Buffalo and New York City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trains are expected to exceed 100 mph, with the fastest in
California. One of the two types of train under consideration there
would be capable of 220 mph; the other could run at speeds up to
310 mph. Unlike other projects, which would use existing tracks,
California's proposes a new rail line solely for high-speed
trains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed projections assume that signals are improved,
curves straightened and stations rebuilt. So far improvements have
progressed only in the Northeast Corridor, which carried more than
9 million passengers in fiscal 1997 (7 million on the New
York-Washington portion). Electrification of the final link,
between New Haven and Boston, is scheduled for completion late this
year, with high-speed service to follow soon afterward.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other potential high-speed corridors include Eugene, Ore., to
Vancouver, Canada, and Washington to Charlotte, N.C. There is a
proposal to link Philadelphia and Harrisburg, and one for
Birmingham, Ala., and New Orleans, eventually hooking up with
Houston. The wide-ranging Midwestern project envisioned by Amtrak
would encompass three smaller corridors in which Chicago would be
the linchpin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent General Accounting Office report to Congress said that
most of the proposals for high-speed corridors are unclear about
where the money is coming from and some are still developing
feasibility studies. The agency cautioned that ``high-speed rail
systems are costly, and thus ridership levels may not be high
enough in the United States for systems to cover their costs.''
Equally discouraging, Amtrak has only 0.3 percent of the nation's
total passenger traffic, according to the Amtrak Reform Council,
established by Congress in 1997 to monitor the railroad's progress.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the pessimistic GAO report was issued more than a month
before Amtrak officials pulled the high-speed rabbit out of their
hats. And since that report, Amtrak officials have pointed to the
news from their recently completed fiscal year _ e.g., their
largest ridership increase in a decade, their best on-time
performance in 13 years and their first $1 billion-plus passenger
revenues ever _ as strong evidence that they have turned the
corner.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, especially those in Congress, will probably say they
have heard that before from Amtrak. About the best that supporters
of high-speed rail can do is hope that this time Amtrak is right.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
