<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331-1     03-30 1693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0331-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: adds news 20-24th grafs on Primakov visit
 &HT;    AGAINST BACKDROP OF ATROCITIES, MILOSEVIC DEFIANCE, NATO PRESSES
ON WITH BOMBINGS WITH NO END IN SIGHT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MILITARY-0331; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0331;
KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0331.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After pounding Serb targets for seven days, NATO
officials admitted Tuesday that they were shocked and surprised by
the continuing atrocities ravaging Kosovo, warning grimly that
there was no quick military solution to the humanitarian
catastrophe unfolding there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody could have anticipated that it would be
quite as bad as it seems now to be becoming,'' NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea told reporters in Brussels, as hordes of horrified and weary
refugees streamed toward the borders of neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can talk about a modern-day Great Terror going on
in Kosovo at the moment,'' Shea said, in a reference to purges by
Joseph Stalin that left some 2 million Russians dead six decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing their campaign of violence, pillage and destruction to
the heart of Kosovo, Serb troops and special police forced
thousands of ethnic Albanians to abandon their homes in the
provincial capital of Pristina, even as around-the-clock NATO air
strikes punched at the forces underpinning the repression.
</P>
<P>
   As the air assault entered its second week, however, U.S. and
NATO officials conceded that poor weather, difficult terrain and
the threat of Serb air defenses continued to hamper the mission,
forcing bombing runs to be scuttled in mid-air and blunting the
effectiveness of high-tech weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never supposed or reported that we had a silver bullet that
would bring this to a halt,'' asserted U.S. Naval Vice Adm. Scott
Fry, director of operations for the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was going to be hard,'' Fry told reporters at the
Pentagon. ``We are grinding it out.''
</P>
<P>
   With a NATO victory not yet in sight, President Clinton told the
nation to brace for ``a sustained period'' of continuing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the 19-member NATO alliance to stick with the
mission, saying the wholesale persecution of Albanians since the
allied attacks began has only underscored the necessity of striking
the forces commanded by Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever any doubt about what is at stake in Kosovo,
Mr. Milosevic is certainly erasing it by his actions,'' Clinton
said. ``We must remain steady and determined with the will to see
this through.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, military officials said future strikes would
bear down increasingly on the individual troops and tanks carrying
out the hostilities on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In strikes Monday and Tuesday, NATO warplanes bombed Serb army
garrisons in Pristina, army barracks just north of Kosovo and an
array of fuel and ammo depots scattered across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington and London showed reporters images of
the Pristina headquarters for the Serb special police and also for
the army, both of which have conducted brutal campaigns against
ethnic Albanians. Both headquarters operations appeared to be
destroyed by coordinated strikes from multiple NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sort of treatment which Milosevic can now
increasingly expect,'' said Gen. Sir Charles Guthrie, chief of
staff for the British Defense Agency. ``The focus of the air
strikes has now shifted firmly towards military forces in Kosovo
and the facilities directly supporting them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British officers said, however, that heavy cloud cover
and the continuing threat of Serb air defenses had seriously
compromised the pace of the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Low-flying U.S. A-10 tank busters, for instance, flew missions
Monday night but returned without firing on their targets, said
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. pilots have at times been unable to fire laser-guided
bombs, which perform poorly in cloudy conditions, out of fear of
unleashing a bomb that could land wide of its target and perhaps
injure civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Low-flying Harrier attack jets were able to strike their targets
on only two nights out of the first six of the campaign, British
officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart technology is affected by poor weather, and we have
had a run of very poor weather,'' Guthrie told reporters in London.
``What we do not want to do is to create any more collateral damage
than we have, we do not want to kill innocent civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed as ``unacceptable'' a Russian-brokered offer
by Milosevic to talk peace in exchange for a halt in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, whose government
adamantly opposes the NATO strikes, reported the offer to NATO
officials after meeting in Belgrade with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted, however, that the only way to end the strikes
is for Milosevic to withdraw his troops, end the violence and
accept the outline of an international peace plan that calls for
putting 28,000 NATO peacekeepers, 4,000 of them Americans, in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic began this brutal campaign,'' Clinton said
in a prepared statement. ``It is his responsibility to bring it to
an immediate end and embrace a just peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising the diplomatic ante for Belgrade, Clinton said Milosevic
risks losing Kosovo altogether by persevering with a military sweep
that has put an estimated 600,000 ethnic Albanians to flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a sustained period, he will see that his military will be
seriously diminished, key military infrastructure destroyed, the
prospect of international support for Serbia's claim to Kosovo
increasingly jeopardized,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is opposed to independence for
Kosovo, a province of 2.2 million, 90 percent of whom are ethnic
Albanians, in southern Serbia, and State Department spokesman James
Rubin stressed that this position hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments, however, were clearly meant to send the
message to Milosevic that the longer he stands up to NATO, the
greater the chance that his defiance and oppression will ultimately
cost him the province at the center of his dispute with the
powerful U.S. and European alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plea for NATO tenacity -- made during a State
Department ceremony to unveil a portrait of former Secretary of
State Warren Christopher -- echoed earlier statements from the
British government, in what appeared to be a coordinated effort to
demonstrate NATO unity and resolve in the face of a difficult and
widening air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has got the determination and the stomach to see this
through,'' British Defense Secretary George Robertson assured
reporters in London. ``The killing fields of Kosovo are not going
to remain as some memorial for Milosevic to sneer over, and we are
determined to make sure that the violence is stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   As Robertson and Clinton spoke, however, much of Kosovo was in
flames. Serb troops under Milosevic's command were pressing forward
with a concerted program of terror that invited flashbacks to the 3
1/2-year war between Serbs and non-Serbs in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials displayed intelligence photographs of
buildings burning near the town of Brestovac, where special Serb
police units were active, and Dobrido, where Serb army troops were
operating.
</P>
<P>
   Other images were shown documenting the forced evacuation of
towns and villages across a wide swath of north-central Kosovo,
where fleeing civilians left their homes to be destroyed by the
torches of Serb forces, and of similar activities near towns in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   NATO received unconfirmed reports of artillery and tank attacks
on large groups of refugees fleeing toward the Albanian border from
population centers in southwest Kosovo. By late Tuesday, U.S.
officials said they could not confirm those reports.
</P>
<P>
   The stories told by tens of thousands of fleeing refugees,
however, are being largely confirmed through intelligence sources
-- U.S. spy satellites and three high-altitude U-2 spy planes are
actively monitoring the region, as are, presumably, U.S. and NATO
contacts on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the evidence points to a catastrophe of epic
proportions unfolding across the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know President Milosevic's record, but I think that
even we have been shocked by the sheer proportions of what we see
happening in Kosovo today,'' Shea, told reporters at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``In whole towns and villages, tanks are first surrounding the
site, then paramilitaries are going in, rounding up civilians at
gunpoint, separating young men from women and children,'' Shea
said, describing in hauntingly familiar detail a reprise of the
pattern Serb troops and paramilitary thugs used to force an
estimated 3 million Muslims and Croats from their homes during the
civil war in Bosnia. ``The women and children are then expelled
from their homes and then sent towards the border. And after they
have left, the villages, the towns, the homes, are looted and then
systematically torched.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) said the movements of ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo and
along its borders had become so widespread and frenetic that
accurate numbers on displaced people were no longer attainable.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimated, however, that roughly 94,000 ethnic
Albanians had fled the country just since the NATO air strikes
began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR estimated -- guessed, really -- that nearly 600,000
Kosovar Albanians have been displaced in 15 months of conflict.
Roughly half are believed to be hiding inside Kosovo or desperately
trying to get out, and the rest have made their way to neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that we haven't seen since the forced
evacuation of Phnom Penh in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge in the mid
1970s,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
