<HEADER>
A0101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-VENUE-NYT &LR;      03-30 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-VENUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT ENDS CONFUSION ON PROSECUTING GUNMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal offense of using a gun during ``any
crime of violence'' may be prosecuted anywhere the underlying crime
took place and not only where the gun itself was used, the Supreme
Court ruled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision resolved confusion in the lower federal courts
over how prosecutors should handle what is in effect a two-part
offense: one that requires both the use of a gun and a connection
between that use and other behavior that, standing alone, would
still be criminal.
</P>
<P>
   The gun offense carries a mandatory five-year sentence in
addition to the sentence for the underlying crime.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant in this case, Jacinto Rodriguez-Moreno, had
committed the federal crime of kidnapping, in a venture that began
in Texas and continued into New Jersey, New York and Maryland.
Having been hired by a cocaine distributor to find a drug dealer
who had stolen 30 kilograms of cocaine, Rodriguez-Moreno took
captive the middleman in the deal to help him in his search.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Moreno used a .357 magnum revolver only once, to
threaten his captive's life at the end of the journey in Maryland,
after which the captive escaped. The defendant was tried and
convicted in New Jersey on the kidnapping and accompanying gun
charge.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia
overturned the conviction on the gun charge, on the ground that the
gun offense had occurred only in Maryland and could not be
prosecuted anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion on Tuesday that reinstated the conviction, Justice
Clarence Thomas said the gun crime was not a ``point-in-time
offense'' but had to be viewed in the context of the crime to which
it was connected. ``A kidnapping, once begun, does not end until
the victim is free,'' Thomas said, adding that it made no sense
``to speak of it in discrete geographic fragments.'' As long as the
kidnapping could properly be charged and tried in New Jersey, so
could the gun offense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Antonin Scalia, joined by
Justice John Paul Stevens, said that the court's interpretation
violated the defendant's constitutional right to be tried where his
crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Scalia said, the defendant was prosecuted ``for
using a gun during a kidnapping in a state and district where all
agree he did not use a gun during a kidnapping.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If to state this case is not to decide it, the law
has departed further from the meaning of language than is
appropriate for a government that is supposed to rule (and to be
restrained) through the written word.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was U.S. vs. Rodriguez-Moreno, No. 97-1139.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
