<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT &LR;      03-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO QUICK CHINESE ENTRY SEEN INTO TRADE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Dampening hopes for a quick agreement on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization, American officials said Tuesday
that ``difficult and complex issues remain across all areas of
trade'' after a visit by the White House trade representative.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese and American officials have negotiated intensively for
the last week here over the scale of market-opening concessions
that China must make to qualify for membership in the global trade
forum, which sets rules and arbitrates disputes.
</P>
<P>
   China has long sought entry, and after years of impasse,
officials from both countries now seem eager for the Chinese to
join. They are trying to put the outlines of a deal together by the
time Prime Minister Zhu Rongji arrives in Washington for an
official visit next week.
</P>
<P>
   More than just a trade deal is at stake. The American and
Chinese governments both see a potential accord as a rare political
breakthrough in a relationship increasingly strained by disputes
over such issues as human rights, nuclear espionage and the NATO
bombing in Yugoslavia, which China condemns.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that agreement might be near on entry into the trade group
were raised over the weekend when President Clinton's trade
representative, Charlene Barshefsky, left Washington for a quick
trip to Beijing, in hopes of pushing Zhu to make last-minute
concessions on market access for foreign companies in agriculture,
financial services and other areas that the Chinese have long been
protected.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Barshefsky said she did not plan to go home with a
deal, she hoped for breakthroughs. It is unclear whether she got
any, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she spent five and a half hours talking with a senior
trade official, Wu Yi, and with Zhu. But Tuesday night, as Ms.
Barshefsky headed home, she issued a written statement saying that
although there had been ``important progress today in narrowing the
issues,'' there remained ``substantial gaps in critical areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States will set no artificial deadlines in these
negotiations,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Commerce William Daley, who is also here on a trade
mission, said he believed that a deal would be reached some time
before the fall. But by then, many in Washington believe, it will
be too close to next year's election campaigning for the
administration to submit China's offerings to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   According to American officials, China has offered some major
concessions. Daley said Zhu told him that his government would
permit the sale of cellular telephones that operate on technology
used by Motorola and other American phone makers. Until now, the
Chinese system favored European producers. China has also indicated
that American companies could buy minority stakes in
telecommunications businesses, but so far it has refused to allow
them to take majority stakes.
</P>
<P>
   China has also not agreed on a resolution of disputes that have
blocked the importing of most types of American wheat. ``Based on
what we have right now,'' an American official said, ``we couldn't
send this thing to the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief China negotiator on Ms. Barshefsky's staff, Robert
Cassidy, will stay on for ``a couple of days,'' an official said,
and then talks are expected to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans seem uncertain whether China plans last-minute
offers _ something not uncommon in trade negotiations _ or whether
its leaders doubt that President Clinton has the will or the
political strength now to get a deal through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Along with membership in the trade organization, the Chinese
want the protection for their own exports that it would bring. But
with rising unemployment and farmers' protests at home, and
inefficient domestic industries already reeling, they have been
reluctant to cut tariffs and other protective measures as quickly
as Western nations demand.
</P>
<P>
   While China's accession to the trade organization requires the
consent of many countries, satisfying the United States is the most
crucial step. Washington is concerned about a growing deficit with
the Chinese, estimated at $57 billion last year, and officials
believe that lower tariffs here would increase American exports. At
the same time, many American companies have been frustrated by
rules that severely limit their ability to invest or operate.
</P>
<P>
   As anti-China sentiment rises in Congress, officials say, no
agreement can survive without enthusiastic corporate support and
lobbying. And while congressional approval of a China accord is not
required, under the trade body's rules, Congress would have to
rescind a law that requires annual renewal of China's
most-favored-nation trading status.
</P>
</TEXT>
