</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEN-PHEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL DISALLOWS `PHEN' PART OF FEN-PHEN AS EVIDENCE IN DIET DRUG
LAWSUITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A three-judge panel in Harris County, Texas, on Monday
became the first court in the nation to disallow evidence that the
``phen'' part of the ``fen-phen'' diet drug combination has helped
cause heart defects.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision was heralded Tuesday by manufacturers of
the ``phen'' drug as precedent-setting, plaintiffs lawyers said
they did not oppose the motion to disallow the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pirtle of the Houston law firm O'Quinn and Laminack said
Tuesday that the ruling was actually a victory for fen-phen
plaintiffs because it has always been clear that the ``fen'' part
of the combination caused the alleged health problems. The ruling
by the judges means that the manufacturers of fenfluramine,
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of Philadelphia, a division of American
Home Products, will not be able to claim that the health problems
were caused by phen.
</P>
<P>
   The panel consists of state District Judges Harvey Brown, Tad
Halbach and Katie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Pirtle said plaintiffs' lawyers in fen-phen cases throughout the
country have been routinely dismissing the manufacturers of phen
from their lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, the Food and Drug Administration withdrew
from the market fenfluramine, sold as Pondimin, and a purer version
of the compound, known as dexfenfluramine, or Redux.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA withdrawal did not include phentermine, the ``phen'' of
the drug combination, manufactured by several companies, but
primarily by Interneuron Pharmaceuticals of Lexington, Mass. No
studies linked this drug with the heart valve disease.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pirtle said phentermine manufacturers were also
initially sued in Harris County because they marketed phentermine
to prolong the usage of either ``fen`` compound from the usual
period of 12 weeks to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Esnouf, spokesman for Fisons Corp. in Collegeville, Pa.,
which had bought a manufacturer of phentermine in 1995, denied that
phen manufacturers promoted the use of their drug with fen. He said
phentermine is a weight-reduction drug that should be taken on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Harris County) decision should exonerate the phentermine
manufacturers and the physicians who prescribed phentermine,'' said
a press release jointly prepared by Fisons and Medeva
Pharmaceuticals, another manufacturer of phentermine.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products has denied that their drugs have caused
heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
