work faster as an at-home travel agent. ``When I don't use a
headset it hurts my back too much,'' says Ms. Boeckman. ``If I try
to hold a handset phone on my shoulder it runs pains through the
right side of my neck.'' (Elisabeth Heimlich/Cox News Service
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- SUSANNAH-OPERA, 3-30 --
Carlisle Floyd, who wrote the biblically derived ``Susannah,'' and
Phyllis Curtin, who created the title role in a 1956 New York City
Opera production. It's not often that composers live long enough to
see their operas enter the repertory and to hear successive
generations of singers perform them. Floyd - now in his 70s - is a
notable exception. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- NY-CIRCUS-REVIEW, 3-30 --
Taking a load off their feet at the circus at Madison Square
Garden. As proved by ``The Living Carousel,'' the 129th
presentation of the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus,
it remains a grand tradition and a lavish spectacle. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HAVANA -- March 30, 1999 -- CUBA-MUSIC, 3-30 -- Luis de
la Cruz of Cuba with the Indigo Girls as part of the Music Bridges
concert in Havana. Leading up to the event, Music Bridges, an
organization that specializes in concerts in politically sensitive
countries, had spent a year and a half pulling together the legal
and practical permission from the United States and Cuba. (Marcelo
Duek/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 30, 1999 -- SEA-PARSELY, 3-30 -- Sea
parsley is adaptable to many uses. The tiny, curly leafed,
burgundy-colored seaweed is a miniature version of dulse, the red
marine plant best known to diners as an ingredient in seaweed
salads in Japanese restaurants. (Michael Rogol/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 1999 -- PASSOVER-ARGENTINA, 3-30
-- Diego Guelar, the Argentine Ambassador, spent childhood
Passovers on a ranch in Entre Rios Province. Buenos Aires is home
to the largest concentration of Jews in Latin America, and
Argentina has the seventh-largest Jewish population by country in
the world: 206,000. Most came fleeing the pogroms of Russia,
although about 15 percent are Sephardic, from Syria, Turkey and
North Africa. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- FISH-STRANGE, 3-30 --
Patricio Osses, right, with Rick Moonen, Oceana's chef, who holds a
merluza, aka an Antarctic queen. Osses, a 33-year-old Chilean,
survives by offering chefs the kind of fish they cannot get
anywhere else. Over the last 10 years, he has built up his business
slowly, selling door to door, opening up his van and bringing out
boxes of fish that make chefs stop and scratch their heads. (David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- FISH-NY-2, 3-30 -- ``Man, I
have got some ugly fish,'' says Patricio Osses, who imports only
Chilean fish like the pompano he is holding. Today, on restaurant
menus, hamachi from New Zealand, opah from Hawaii, rouget from the
Mediterranean and branzino from Greece have become as familiar as
cod or striped bass from New England. (David Corio/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- SUB-FISH-NY-1, 3-30 -- An
array of fish at Estiatorio Milos typifies the exotic variety sold
in New York. ``It has become a progressive kind of improvement over
the last five years,'' says Costas Spiliadis, the owner of the
midtown restaurant. More affordable cargo flights from all parts of
the world, with more efficient ground transportation from ports to
airports, have transformed the business. (Kiyoshi Togashi/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
