<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CLINTON, 3-30 --
Marie Christopher, left, wife of former Secretary of State Warren
Christopher, President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright at a ceremony Tuesday unveiling Christopher's official
portrait. Clinton warned Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that
he was jeopardizing his claim to keep Kosovo as a province of
Yugoslavia with his assault on the ethnic Albanian population
there. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) STORRS, Conn. -- March 30, 1999 -- BKC-UCONN-DUKE, 3-30
-- Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun and his Huskies showing off their
NCAA championship trophy at a pep rally on campus Tuesday in
Storrs. The Huskies carved out a pulsating 77-74 victory Monday
over a Duke team that had the title of One of the Best Ever in
recent history bestowed upon it by most observers. (Michelle V.
Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- March 30, 1999 -- SOCSEC-REPORT, 3-30 --
President Clinton greeting guests in the Rose Garden on Tuesday.
Clinton urged that Social Security and Medicare be shored up,
despite a report that they will last longer. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- March 30, 1999 -- TAURUS-DESIGN-2, 3-30 --
The 1986-style Taurus produced enormous profits for Ford, becoming
the nation's best-selling car from 1992 through 1996. But the 1996
redesign bombed. Ford was not prepared to compete on price a year
later when the Honda Motor Co. and Toyota, respectively, introduced
less expensive models of the Accord (top) and the Camry. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 30, 1999 -- TAURUS-DESIGN-1, 3-30 --
Ford unveiled the new Taurus on Tuesday at the New York
International Auto Show. But do not look for any surprises. While
it may sell well if it is priced cheaply enough, it is unlikely to
win any contests for style. Indeed, the most distinctive thing
about the new Taurus is probably how indistinguishable it is from
all the other look-alike midsize sedans. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- March 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-4, 3-30 -- An ethnic Albanian woman arriving in
Albania on Tuesday at the Morini Border Crossing. On Monday, the
Serbian forces methodically went from village to village in what is
called the Has district, the refugees say. The troops told the
villagers that they had to leave or they would be killed in the
morning, and so the villagers fled toward Albania. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- March 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-3, 3-30 -- Dull Gunxi, an ethnic Albanian refugee
from the town of Denjan in Kosovo, arriving in Albania at the
Morini Border Crossing with his family Tuesday. His face shows
injuries sustained when his house got hit by a Serbian tank shell
Sunday. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- March 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2, 3-30 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
arriving in Albania aboard tractors Tuesday near the Morini Border
Crossing. On Monday, the Serbian forces methodically went from
village to village in what is called the Has district, the refugees
say. The troops told the villagers that they had to leave or they
would be killed in the morning, and so the villagers fled toward
Albania. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
