<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-BOS &LR;      03-30 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ALLIES, UN RUSH AID TO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States rushed hundreds of tents,
thousands of pounds of high-protein biscuits, and numerous pairs of
thermal underwear to northern Albania, while Macedonia awaited
39,000 blankets and 20,000 personal hygiene kits from the United
States as waves of terrified refugees flooded across the Kosovo
border.
</P>
<P>
   International efforts to stem the humanitarian disaster
unfolding in the Balkans kicked into high gear Tuesday as the UN
High Commissioner for Refugees estimated the number of people
spilling across Kosovo's border at nearly 96,000 since NATO's
bombing campaign began a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 185,000 more people beyond the reach of relief
efforts may have been displaced within the Yugoslav provinces of
Montenegro, Serbia, and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This is in addition to the 459,500 people _ amounting to about a
quarter of the population of Kosovo _ already made homeless since
the conflict between the Kosovar Albanians and Yugoslavian
government forces erupted a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a very serious refugee crisis, which is
worsening by the hour,'' said Kris Janowski, spokesman for the UN
commissioner. ``People are arriving exhausted, traumatized, and
terrorized.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States has publicly pledged $8.5 million to
the UN refugee commission, at least an additional $20 million will
be funneled into relief efforts from the State Department and the
US Agency for International Development. More money and assistance
will be announced by the White House as early as Wednesday, and UN
relief officials are meeting Thursday to draw up a new relief plan
for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But US government officials coordinating the relief effort say
money is the least of their concerns as Europe, still in the grip
of cold winter winds and snow, tries to cope with the gravest
humanitarian disaster it has faced in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will always cover whatever the costs are for the United
Nations agencies and the NGO,'' or nongovernmental organizations,
said Julia Taft, assistant secretary of state. ``Right now, we have
two big problems. The first is getting the agencies and their
people on ground so they can tell us what they need, and two, to
get the assistance there.''
</P>
<P>
   Airports from Tuzla to Skopje are shut down, forcing the United
States, Britain, and UN to ferry supplies in by boat, and shuttle
them through to northern Albania and into Macedonia by truck.
Bosnia and Montenegro are also suffering from refugee overflows.
Airlifts are a distinct possibility, Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   Provisions are pouring in from US emergency stockpiles in Pisa,
Italy, but they are a small part of the massive relief operation,
headed by the UN refugees commission. The UN refugees commission
relies on organizations such as the international Red Cross, CARE
International, Catholic Relief Services, and Doctors Without
Borders.
</P>
<P>
   These groups have already swung into action, helping distribute
staples provided by the World Food Program to families hosting
refugees in Macedonia. In Albania, they handed exhausted refugees
packs of high-protein drinks and food as they crossed the border at
Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are facing are bread and butter issues like how to
feed and house people,'' said Jonathan Frerichs, communications
director of Lutheran World Relief Services.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, the European Union released $10.7 million. The
British government supplied a transport plane to the Albanian
capital of Tirana and donated $800,000 to the international Red
Cross. The Danish government released more than $1 million for
Danish charities in the area. Norway granted $2.7 million in aid,
and Sweden's International Development Agency contributed $300,000
in cooperation with the Swedish Red Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
