A0132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     03-30 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES QUIET ABOUT SETTLEMENT TALKS IN MICROSOFT ANTITRUST
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Settlement talks began on Tuesday afternoon between
the Microsoft Corp. and the federal and state authorities who filed
antitrust charges against the company almost a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides emphasized before the discussions started that they
would talk in complete secrecy, and they stuck with that vow on
Tuesday. But it was clear from the opening positions of both
parties that a vast gulf divides them, making a settlement
difficult at best. The case has been in trial since October but is
now in recess until the middle of April.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state officials have said they believe no settlement
will be effective that does not result in a restructuring of the
company in some way that will change Microsoft's business
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft executives have said they are not willing to
consider the general proposals that have been discussed so far _
forced licensing of the Windows operating system, or breaking up
the company.
</P>
<P>
   As its opening position, Microsoft offered more modest proposals
last week, including the elimination of certain restrictive
contract provisions for computer manufacturers and Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both sides also have strong incentives to try for a
settlement. In Microsoft's case, even friends of the company have
been saying the trial has not gone well, and a settlement would
forestall a more severe remedy that could be imposed should
Microsoft lose the case.
</P>
<P>
   Settling now would also cut off one possible result of the trial
_ a judicial declaration that Microsoft holds a legal monopoly in
personal computer operating systems, a declaration that could
significantly complicate Microsoft's business decisions in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   For the plaintiffs _ the Justice Department and 19 states _ a
settlement would obviate appeals, should they win, that would take
years to litigate. A final ruling would probably come long after
many of these elected or appointed officials have left office.
</P>
<P>
   As one senior government official involved in the case said:
``When you look at an antitrust case, finality becomes a very
important factor in itself. These things can be appealed forever.
But with a settlement, the rule of law is imposed immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0315 </DOCNO>
