<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES REJECT LIMITED SERB TRUCE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dismissing the first Serbian cease-fire proposal in
weeks as unacceptable, President Clinton joined NATO allies Tuesday
in repeated condemnations of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
then raised the stakes with an unprecedented suggestion: Further
atrocities could lead to US support for Kosovo independence.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic offered only to withdraw some troops from Kosovo after
NATO ended its air campaign against the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long backed Milosevic's claim to the southern
province, considered the cradle of Serbian civilization. Kosovo's
leaders have been urged during peace talks to seek only autonomy,
and not full sovereignty. Albanian Kosovars signed a treaty last
month that agreed to a period of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   But following Tuesday's unsuccessful peace mission to Belgrade
by Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Clinton suggested he
might use the issue of independence as a powerful negotiating tool.
If the violence continues, Clinton said, Milosevic could expect to
see ``the prospect for international support of Serbia's claim to
Kosovo increasingly jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remain steady and determined with the will to see this
through,'' Clinton said of NATO's goal to destabilize Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The thinly veiled threat came as new waves of ethnic Albanians
fled torched villages to safety in neighboring regions, bearing
fresh stories of massacres by Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials described the violence against the Kosovars in
increasingly outraged terms, comparing it to the bloodiest
campaigns of the 20th century. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea,
describing the ``modern-day terror going on in Kosovo,'' said the
busloads of ethnic Albanians being rounded up served as proof
Milosevic had mapped out a strategy to expel the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that we haven't seen since the forced
evacuation of Phnom Penh in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge in the
mid-1970s,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by Primakov appeared to yield no progress. After
meeting with Milosevic in Belgrade for six hours, Primakov, along
with a group of top Russian aides, flew to Germany, where he
explained to Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder the peace agreement
Milosevic had laid out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yugoslav proposal, in which Milosevic agreed to begin
withdrawing some Serb forces if NATO airstrikes stopped at once,
was instantly rejected by Schroeder. He then called Clinton, who
concurred, saying, ``President Milosevic's proposal is
unacceptable.'' Both Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema and
British Prime Minister Tony Blair refused to consider the proposal
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who made the trip to Belgrade at the urging of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, held out hope the conflict might yet be
resolved. Indicating that he might personally play a role in
brokering a future deal, Primakov told reporters in the airport in
Bonn that Milosevic ``even now thinks that all the peaceful
refugees that have left their territory . . . could get back to
their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And in general, we think this is a good start,'' Primakov
said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have opposed the air campaign against
Yugoslavia, and Yeltsin repeated the condemnation Tuesday in his
annual state-of-the-union address. Saying the airstrikes were
``continuing to bypass the United Nations Security Council, in
violation of the UN Charter, reason and common sense.'' Yeltsin
promised ``to put an end to military actions in Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian president stopped short of pledging aid to
Yugoslavia. Allaying earlier fears that Russia might offer
extensive political help to the Serb leader, Yeltsin said, ``The
tragic mistake of the United States on the Kosovo issue should not
turn into a prolonged crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has made its choice,'' he said. ``It will not allow
itself to be drawn into the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, protests continued around the world against the
airstrikes. Nearly 6,000 demonstrators converged outside the US
Embassy in Athens on Tuesday, carrying candles and burning British
and American flags at an all-night anti-NATO protest.
</P>
<P>
   A similar demonstration also took place in Spain, and in
Bosnia's Serb-controlled republic, three bombs have exploded
outside Western organizations since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As political leaders carried on their discussions, NATO
continued its own round-the-clock attacks, sending low-flying
planes into the region to target ground troops and tanks, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials did so at the risk of attack from Yugoslav
surface-to-air missiles, which have hardly been seen during combat,
and which Milosevic is believed to be hoarding for use on
low-flying planes in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO forces faced a severely weakened Yugoslav Air Force,
Pentagon officials said. In addition to decimating half of the air
force's best planes in the first days of the air strikes _ gunning
down five Russian-made MiG-29s in less than 72 hours _ NATO
warplanes so far have destroyed several MiG-21 and helicopters,
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts have drawn some limited criticism from analysts in
the United States, as well as several elected officials, who
believe the military may not be acting quickly enough to stop the
ethnic cleansing on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, one of the chief critics of the US decision
to rule out sending in ground troops, said the air war may not be
damaging the ground war as efficiently as the military would have
liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we anticipated that Milosevic would dramatically
increase the ethnic cleansing if we increased the airstrikes,''
said McCain, Republican of Arizona. ``I think we thought the
airstrikes would have a more debilitating effect than they have...
We got a little spoiled by Desert Storm, when things went exactly
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's increased military activity was matched by heightened
fears of instability in the region around Kosovo. Of particular
concern was the neighboring republic of Montenegro, where it was
reported that Milosevic intended to encourage a coup against the
local government. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright phoned
Montenegro's president, Milo Djukanovic, to express her concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any attempt by Belgrade to overthrow the democratically
elected Montenegran government would only ...escalate the conflict
with NATO,'' said State Department spokesman James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it was Kosovo itself that continued to attract almost
all the international attention, as world leaders and military
officials struggled to explain the NATO strategy for stopping a
wave of atrocities that has only increased since the airstrikes
began one week ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this context that Clinton raised the specter of
supporting the Kosovo drive toward independence. Although he did
not explicitly threaten to back the Kosovo Liberation Army, and he
seemed to make the suggestion almost in passing, Clinton did
indicate what may be the next phase of political negotiations with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever any doubt what is at stake in Kosovo,''
Clinton said, ``Mr. Milosevic is certainly erasing it by his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   But with that strategy could come a separate set of problems,
both at home and abroad. Even if it served as a useful bargaining
tool with Milosevic, such rhetoric might in the long-term spark
revolution in any number of enclaves, said Senator Jack Reed, a
Rhode Island Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been the ultimate trump card with Milosevic,
because it's what he cares about most,'' Reed said. ``He doesn't
care that he's reviled. He's got this image of greater Serbia. But
the problem is, to what extent do you set off a frenzy in the
region of all ethnic minorities? And while you might win on the one
hand, you might lose on the other. The whole reason for this drill
is to prevent instability in the Balkans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
