<SLUG> BC-FOUND-INTERNET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABDUCTED CHILDREN HEADING HOME TO CALIFORNIA AFTER BEING FOUND WITH
MOTHER IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  NOTE: names of children (Aja, 12; Syna, 10; and Alixander, 7) all
cq. 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENEFICK, Texas _ Three children, abducted by their mother two
years ago during a custody dispute in California, were headed back
to their father Tuesday, after being found hiding in a home in this
southeast Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   Eugia Morse, 36, was huddled with the children in a closet when
investigators found them late Sunday, authorities said. The woman,
who had been using the alias Gabriella Escada, remained in the
county jail Tuesday in lieu of a $1 million bond, after being
charged with three counts of child abduction.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morse, a drywall construction company owner from La Mesa,
Calif., was making plans to be reunited today with the children he
has not seen in more than two years _ Aja, 12; Syna, 10; and
Alixander, 7.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Tracy Morse, said he will give them the Christmas
presents that have remained unopened since their abduction on Dec.
13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, described as an actress from La Mesa, and her
children had been staying recently with a woman identified as Sandy
Hayes, of Kenefick, about 45 miles east of Houston, authorities
said. Hayes declined to comment, but investigators said she had
given them lodging for a few days after befriending them at a
church revival meeting and did not know about the abduction case.
</P>
<P>
   Eugia Morse _ who had lost all custody and visitation rights
several weeks earlier _ snatched the children as they were getting
off their bus at their elementary school in California, said Gayle
Falkenthal of the San Diego County District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Morse had lost her parental rights after the courts found that
she had made false claims that her ex-husband had beaten her and
molested the children, Falkenthal added. She said Morse also was
diagnosed with serious psychological problems.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morse and his current wife said they normally drove the
children to school because their mother had threatened to steal
them. That morning, however, their car wouldn't start and they let
them ride the bus, Tracy Morse said.
</P>
<P>
   As the children were leaving the bus, their mother had a singing
telegram delivered to the school's principal, creating a
distraction while she shuttled the children into her car and drove
away, Falkenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person delivering the telegram had a costumed dog and a
bunch of helium balloons,'' she said. ``It was also `Pajama Day'
and a lot of the kids were in their night clothes. It was quite a
diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody saw what happened except the two stepchildren of the
father, who were also on the bus, but then it was too late,''
Falkenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morse never gave up searching for his children, his wife
said, and he recently contacted legislators for help. A photo of
one of the children was distributed nationwide on a direct-mail
flier.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he sued the La Mesa-Spring Valley School District
for failure to adequately protect his children and won a $50,000
judgment in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The children finally were located through photos posted by the
National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, at www/missing
kids.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The photos were seen by a relative of a Houston-area man who
recently married Eugia Morse and then separated from her after a
few months, said Texas Department of Public Safety investigator
Mike Buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This relative was suspicious of the story (Morse) told about
being in the witness-protection program. The photos confirmed it,''
Buck said. ``From what we know, she never told people that she was
divorced and had abducted her children. She usually gave two
stories _ the witness-protection one, or that her husband had
sexually abused her children and she had to remain in hiding
because he was very well off and connected to police.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck said Morse apparently has been in the Houston area since
February 1998, but has not held a steady job. He said she accepted
donations from ``religious people who'd take up collections.''
</P>
<P>
   After separating from her new husband, she rented an apartment
in January north of Houston, authorities said. She left the
apartment, however, after learning that authorities knew she had
been visiting her dying mother at a Houston-area hospital,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The children had not been enrolled in school, but Buck said he
found literature for home-schooling at her apartment. He said he
also found a journal she kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``In it, she would be writing and ask a question of God, and
then there'd be an answer from God in her own writing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Morse said her husband had not sought full custody of the
children after the divorce in 1994 until he learned that the
children had missed half a year of school and were suffering from
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   When the courts began ruling in favor of the father and
stepmother, allegations of abuse began, she said. A court-appointed
evaluator was able to get the children to admit that they had lied
for their mother, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
