<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EXODUS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION SEES HOPES FOR PEACE FADE AS REFUGEE RANKS GROW 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: New York Times photos of refugees in Albania and
Macedonia are being sent to NYT photo clients.; a map-graphic,
tracking the number of refugees, is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (See also: KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN, KOSOVO-YELTSIN,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(ac) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The growing exodus of refugees from Kosovo _ now
nearly one-third of the ethnic Albanian population of the province
_ has left Clinton administration and NATO officials wondering
whether they will be able to achieve their goal of of Serbs and
ethnic Albanians living together peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a third of the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
have been forced from their homes by Serbian troops, and many of
those refugees have left Kosovo for neighboring Macedonia, Albania
or Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, State Department spokesman, said Tuesday that the
strategy of forcing ethnic Albanians from their homes, under the
direction of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, has
crystallized the animosity between the two groups. This
``radicalization'' of the province, he said, was making it ``all
the more difficult to imagine a circumstance where the peoples can
begin to live together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin insisted on Tuesday that the administration stood by the
framework of the Rambouillet accord, which called for Kosovo to
stay within Serbia as an autonomous entity.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials have already started talking about other
outcomes, including talk Tuesday that Kosovo could wind up as a
separate entity under international protection _ if the allies
actually succeed in subduing the Serbian military.
</P>
<P>
   Sketching the outlines of a protectorate, a NATO planner said
that NATO troops would oversee the return of ethnic Albanian
refugees to Kosovo and guarantee their safety under an arrangement
in which the Serbs would have virtually no power.
</P>
<P>
   In London, British officials said the refugees should be allowed
to return home. The defense minister, George Robertson, said that
Milosevic should not be rewarded for ejecting ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees must be allowed to go home, their homes must be
rebuilt,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others were not specific about who would rebuild the
villages or pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The outflow of refugees, many of them traumatized by the
executions they said they had witnessed, could easily destabilize
the fragile countries of Macedonia and Albania, as well as the
Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Given the speed at which the Serbian forces have pushed the
ethnic Albanians out of their homes, a Balkans specialist in the
administration predicted Tuesday that by the end of the week, half
the Albanian population could be outside the province and the
remainder left crouching in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   In his televised speech last Wednesday, outlining the reasons
for NATO's intervention in Kosovo, Clinton said the conflict
between the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians had ``no natural
national boundaries.'' It was necessary, he said, to intervene to
contain its spread.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a map with bold arrows showing the movement of
refugees, Clinton said on the evening of the bombing: ``Already
this movement is threatening the young democracy in Macedonia,
which has its own Albanian minority and a Turkish minority. Already
Serbian forces have made forays into Albania, from which Kosovars
have drawn support. Albania has a Greek minority. Let a fire burn
here in this area, and the flames will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the bombing started, Milosevic had purposely pushed
refugees to Macedonia and Albania in an effort to throw into
turmoil the very countries that the bombing was supposed to help
protect, a Clinton administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the two million inhabitants of Macedonia are
Albanian and a large inflow of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo could
tip the balance into a majority Albanian population, the official
said. Macedonia has about 40 percent unemployment and a new
democracy. Government officials there were appealing Tuesday to the
European Union to take some of the ethnic Albanian refugees, and
foreign ministers from Germany, Austria and Finland said they would
meet Thursday near Bonn to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Albania is the poorest country in Europe, barely able to look
after its own people, and certainly not able to care for the tens
of thousands of new refugees, the Clinton administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible, the official said, that NATO troops would have
to be sent to Albania as well as Macedonia _ where a 10,000 strong
NATO force has been poised as peacekeepers for Kosovo _ to help the
two countries control increasing tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to end up with troops in Albania and
Macedonia,'' the Clinton administration official said. ``For
Macedonia these refugees make big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing began last week, NATO officials said they
believed almost 150,000 ethnic Albanian refugees had left the
province. and gone to Albania. Another 22,500 had fled to Macedonia
and 42,500 were now in Montenegro, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the more than 400,000 that had fled their homes
beginning in January of last year when the conflict began, the
number of refugees forced either into neighboring lands or left to
seek shelter in the countryside had reached 570,000 refugees, Jamie
Shea, the NATO spokesman said Tuesday. Kosovo has about 2 million
people, of which 90 percent are ethnic Albanian, and the remainder
Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the border at Macedonia on Tuesday, said that a
line of cars and people on foot stretched for six miles inside
Kosovo, as people tried to leave.
</P>
<P>
   From inside Kosovo, there were reports of a large gathering of
refugees huddled for safety in a valley being shelled by Serbian
artillery and of a forced mass exodus along the eastern road out of
Pristina, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Pec, a town of 100,000 was virtually empty and the
houses, mosques and stores destroyed, NATO said. With Pristina now
a target of ethnic cleansing, there was only one town of any size
-- Gnjilane, south east of the capital -- that had not been
attacked by the Serbs, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of the continuing purge of the population were eked
out by satellite phone and in some cases landline phone. But most
were impossible to verify especially after the departure Monday of
the last Western aid groups, the International Committee of the Red
Cross and Medecins Sans Frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had no doubt that the people
were being forced from their homes at gun point, and that there
were what Rubin called ``mass murders.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An ethnic Albanian living in Washington, who spoke on condition
of anonymity because of fear of reprisals against his family, said
he spoke to his parents, and two brothers in Pristina Tuesday by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there's lots of panic because people have fled to
Macedonia and those who are left don't know what to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The villages of Sosali and Matican to the east of the city had
been shelled, leaving a line several miles long of people in cars
and on foot heading for the border of Macedonia, he said. ``My
mother is very concerned about my brothers and their kids. How are
they going to leave and how are they going to leave together?''
</P>
<P>
   There were wild rumors in the city, the Albanian said. There
were stories that more members of the intellectual elite of
Pristina, which before the conflict started had masterminded a
parallel government in an effort to outwit the Serbian repression,
had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO, Air Commodore David Wilby, said that ``large numbers of
refugees'' were being attacked by artillery in the Pegarusa Valley,
about 20 miles north of the town of Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Rubin said a report had been received
for the second day in a row from the Kosovo Liberation Army leader,
Hashim Thaci. Thaci, who initially refused to sign the peace
settlement at Rambouillet and then after two weeks changed his
mind. Rubin said that Thaci, calling from Kosovo on Tuesday, said
``the situation is worse today than it was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also said that Thaci reported ``that the killing is more
widespread, that there's shelling of a whole series of towns, that
the Kosovo Liberation Army is doing the best it can under the
circumstances, but that it's becoming increasingly difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to help the refugees with blankets, food and other
essentials, the State Department said tonight that the Pentagon
would air lift supplies to Tirana, the capital of Albania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
