<HEADER>
A0146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-30 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`10 THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU': IT'S LIKE, YOU KNOW, SONNETS AND
STUFF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among the crop of recent teen-age movies whose plots
parody stories from classic literature, ``10 Things I Hate About
You,'' a high-school ``Taming of the Shrew,'' tries the hardest of
any to season its screenplay with authentic Shakespearean touches.
Students in a writing class at Padua High School (somewhere around
Seattle) are asked to create sonnets. There is an Elizabethan-theme
prom that inspires some fancy hairdos and fetching costumes. And
every now and then the banter among the characters incorporates
actual Shakespearean quotations.
</P>
<P>
   If it's all very clever for a teen-age film, it also feels
terribly forced. One of the many delightful things about
``Clueless,'' the movie that started it all, was a glove-smooth fit
of Jane Austen's ``Emma'' on a teen-age comedy of manners. You
barely sensed Austen's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``10 Things I Hate About You'' has its charms, most
notably Julia Stiles' brash, cheeky portrayal of Katarina Stratford
(known as Kat), the proud, nonconforming ``shrew'' who is ``tamed''
by Heath Ledger's Patrick Verona. A spirited feminist who doesn't
date and sneers at the conformism and idiocy of teen-age social
life, she is a breath of fresh air in the stifling materialistic
atmosphere of today's Hollywood teen-age movies. Ms. Stiles, whose
slightly rushed, impatient delivery sometimes recalls the young
Jane Fonda, lets enough sweetness seep into her portrayal to lend
even the nastiest retort a hint of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick, a rough-edged outsider, is a soft-focus teen-age rebel
with an Australian accent. How rebellious is he? He hangs out at a
seedy pool hall and is rumored to have eaten a live duck. But when
all is said and done, he seems awfully mild-mannered. His idea of
impressing Kat is to commandeer the high-school's outdoor sound
system and sing ``Can't Take My Eyes Off You'' to her as the
school's marching band clumsily oompahs along behind him. This is
not an act to challenge the transgressive style of Marilyn Manson.
And Kat is utterly delighted with it. Her taming is so easily
accomplished that it's almost a piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Kat and her drippy younger sister Bianca (Larisa Oleynik) live
under the thumb of their divorced father, Walter (Larry Miller), an
insanely overprotective obstetrician. When he tells Bianca that she
is not allowed to date boys unless her man-hating sister does, he
thinks he has secured Bianca's chastity for the foreseeable future.
Kat's taming, which involves cash bribes to Patrick, is part of an
elaborate scheme to liberate Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   The plot and its repercussions almost duplicate the setup of
another recent teen-age film, ``She's All That.'' Both films
involve bribery and the heroine's deception. Both feature a
ludicrously vain preening teen-age ladies' man who is shown up as a
fatuous narcissist. Here he is Joey Donner (Andrew Keegan), a model
who can't resist striking a different pose every few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Gil Junger from a screenplay by Karen
McCullah Lutz and Kirsten Smith, gets in trouble by stirring in too
many subsidiary characters and sketchy subplots. It doesn't help
that Ms. Oleynik's Bianca and Joseph-Gordon Levitt as Cameron, an
ardently devoted classmate who tutors her in French, are
irritatingly blank, colorless screen presences. For off-center
comic embellishment, the movie throws in a writing teacher who's a
rapper, played by Daryl (Chill) Mitchell, and a sex-crazed guidance
counselor (Allison Janney) who writes steamy novels and asks
students to come up with synonyms for words like engorged.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the other recent teen-age comedies, ``10 Things I
Hate About You'' takes place in a super-affluent, all-American
never-never land where high schoolers drive fancy new cars and have
lavish wardrobes. This hothouse world suggests a vintage sitcom
larded with sex and cushioned with money. It isn't anymore real
than ``The Brady Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten Things I Hate About You'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It abounds with off-color humor.
</P>
<P>
   TEN THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gil Junger; written by Karen McCullah Lutz and
Kirsten Smith; director of photography, Mark Irwin; edited by O.
Nicholas Brown; music by Richard Gibbs; production designer, Carol
Winstead Wood; produced by Andrew Lazar; released by Touchstone
Pictures. Running time: 94 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Heath Ledger (Patrick Verona), Julia Stiles (Katarina
Stratford), Joseph-Gordon Levitt (Cameron James), Larisa Oleynik
(Bianca Stratford), David Krumholtz (Michael Eckman), Andrew Keegan
(Joey Donner), Susan May Pratt (Mandella), Gabrielle Union
(Chastity), Larry Miller (Walter Stratford), Daryl (Chill) Mitchell
( Morgan) and Allison Janney (Ms. Perky).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
