<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-DUKE-ART-68     03-30 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-DUKE-ART-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT'S VICTORY PLAN WAS IN THE CARDS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BKC-UCONN-IMPACT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun knew his
Huskies believed they were the best team in the nation. On the eve
of Monday night's championship game, Calhoun gathered his players
and brandished a stack of blue index cards that he had compiled on
Duke this season. The blunt-talking coach told them emphatically
and without bluster how the title game was going to play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first team you'll face all year that's as good as
you; but here's what they can't do,'' he said, holding up the
cards, ``and that's how we're going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Those meticulous notes yielded three tactics that Calhoun
promised would beguile Duke, snap the Blue Devils' 32-game winning
streak and bring a national championship to Storrs, Conn., on the
Huskies' first trip to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   All the Huskies had to do was execute.
</P>
<P>
   They did for 40 thrilling minutes, carving out a pulsating 77-74
victory over a Duke team that had the title of One of the Best Ever
bestowed upon it by most observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say it,'' said Ricky Moore, UConn's defensive
stopper. ``We have great players on this team and we showed it
today.''
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, the Huskies (34-2) wanted Trajan Langdon to
bring the ball up court. So that meant pressuring the sophomore
point guard William Avery, who is a better ball handler and
penetrator than Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   The risk was putting the ball into the hands of an all-American
and the best shooter in college basketball. Langdon scored a
team-high 25 points _ 15 on spectacular 3-point bombs from beyond
21 feet _ but not without feeling the wrinkles and sweat of Moore's
jersey.
</P>
<P>
   With Avery watching from the perimeter, the Blue Devils (37-2)
were forced to shoot 24 times from beyond 15 feet _ including 19
3-pointers. In having to hurry long-range shots, Duke looked human
_ shooting a season-worst 41.1 percent over all from the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 25 seconds, it was apparent how Moore's full-court
pressure had worn down Langdon. The Duke senior guard tried to win
the game by taking Moore to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed solid and stayed down; I was right there,'' Moore
said of how he forced Langdon to travel with 5.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After Khalid El-Amin sank two free throws to make the score
77-74, Langdon tried to dribble down the court for a game-tying
score. But Moore and company were there to strip the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job funneling me toward the sideline,'' a
dejected Langdon said of the play that ended the game. ``There were
three people there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Langdon would never have been placed in such a desperate
situation if the Huskies had failed to execute the second part of
their strategy: double-team all-American and player of the year,
Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, Calhoun gave his 6-foot-11-inch center Jake Voskuhl
one instruction _ don't foul. He told the 245-pound Voskuhl to bang
Brand and wait for help.
</P>
<P>
   So whenever Duke tried to get the ball inside, 6-7 Kevin Freeman
fronted Brand while Richard Hamilton and El-Amin rotated to the
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great team defense,'' said Voskuhl, whose two points
and three rebounds could not illustrate how strong a wall he put up
inside. ``We got help from everyone and everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brand, 6-8 and 265 pounds, would not have been held to just
eight shots and 15 points if Connecticut didn't keep throwing fresh
players at Duke. Calhoun intended to run as many of his players at
the Blue Devils as possible to keep everybody fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were deeper offensively,'' he said. ``But I thought we
were deeper defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Souleymane Wane, Albert Mouring, Edmund Saunders and Rashamel
Jones played a combined 43 minutes for the Huskies. The Blue
Devils' bench of Nate James, Corey Maggette and Chris Burgess
played 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' bench outscored the Blue Devils', 17-8,
outrebounded it, 8-1, and Wane and Saunders spent a combined seven
fouls battering Brand on the double teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it really tough to get open looks,'' Brand said.
``They were fighting every time I touched it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Calhoun counted on his all-American, Hamilton, and point guard,
El- Amin, to carry the offensive load. And they did. Hamilton spun,
slashed, rained 3-pointers and created his own shots on the way to
27 points. El-Amin added 10 points in the second half. Together,
the duo scored 26 of Connecticut's 40 second-half points, including
the final 11.
</P>
<P>
   But that alone isn't what brought the Huskies a championship at
Tropicana Field. It was Connecticut's confidence and Calhoun's
index cards that did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this club says about loving and caring for each other,
they mean,'' said an emotional Calhoun. ``When you have that kind
of group you don't even know that you have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like their stopper, Moore, says, you have a college basketball
team that deserves to mentioned among history's very best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
