<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VILLAGES, SERBS SET DEADLINES GIVING ALBANIANS JUST HOURS TO
FLEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS lede to correct spelling of village to Djakovica.) 
 (ART ADV: New York Times photos of refugees in Albania and
Macedonia are being sent to NYT photo clients.; a map-graphic,
tracking the number of refugees, is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (See also: KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN, KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S.,
KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(ac) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ In the darkness, the little villages in the
rolling hills and river valleys around the northwestern Kosovo city
of Djakovica emptied out Tuesday morning, with the residents
rushing _ literally for their lives _ to beat the 5 a.m. deadline
set by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Serbian forces methodically went from village to
village in what is called the Has district, the refugees said. The
troops told the villagers that they had to leave or they would be
killed in the morning, and so the villagers fled toward Albania.
</P>
<P>
   They joined the 60,000 ethnic Albanians who came the day before
and who had apparently been forced to flee from another area of
Kosovo, to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Mehdi Halilaj, 27, came to the border today. ``They came
yesterday at 2 o'clock in the afternoon,'' he said. ``They said if
we were still there at 5 o'clock in the morning, `We will kill
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   And so in Damjan, and the other villages, ethnic Albanians
packed what they could _ wooden baby cradles elaborately painted in
folk patterns were common _ and climbed into carts pulled by farm
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m., about 10,800 had crossed the border and officials
estimated they were coming at the rate of 2,000 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As the long columns of tractors, a very few cars and people on
foot came across the border, the only difference in their accounts
was the time the Serbs arrived. They were told to leave, they were
robbed, their identity documents were taken away and they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came at 10 o'clock in the morning,'' said Gezim Sela of
the village of Gershin. ``They said if somebody was found in the
village after 5 o'clock in the morning, they would be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the accounts were virtually identical, pointing to
the methodical, well-organized nature of what appears to be a
government campaign to drive ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo, who
make up 90 percent of the population. The refugees fear the troops'
past record of atrocities. There was no question in the villagers'
minds that they had to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had 10 tanks and 5 military minibuses,'' said Ymer
Pnishi, 65, from Damjan, driving one of the tractors in a long
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers told us to leave the village by 5 o'clock,'' he
said. ``We have nothing with us, no bread, no water. Nobody was
killed, but they burned the village. They looted the homes and took
everything of worth, and after, they burned the village.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo thus far have
been attributed to special Interior Ministry policemen or
paramilitaries or to the private armies of ultra-nationalists like
Zeljko Raznjatovic, who is known as Arkan. But some refugees today
said they thought that some of the warnings were delivered by
soldiers of the regular Yugoslav Army. This could not be
independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   While the warnings alone were enough to set off the exodus of
villagers, refugees also gave accounts of killings and other
atrocities in the last few days, giving weight to their fears.
While these also could not be independently confirmed, there
appeared to be a pattern of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They killed my 10 brothers, and I am alone,'' wailed Naxhije
Zymi, 55, as a group of refugees rested by the side of the road
leading from the border.
</P>
<P>
   Her account of a mass killing in the village of Krushe Evogel on
Friday conformed with other accounts given by refugees and with
accounts that the observers from the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe here have also heard from refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday the police came early in the morning _ they executed
almost 100 people,'' Ms. Zymi said, mimicking the spraying of an
automatic rifle. ``They killed them all _ men, women and children.
They set a fire and threw the bodies in the fire and put car tires
on the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Halilaj, a university graduate in economics, said three of his
cousins, all with the family name of Osmani, had been executed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, he said, as the NATO bombing was beginning,
a group of six Serbian men wearing ski masks over their faces
entered one neighborhood in the city of Dakovica and burned down
about 50 Albanian-owned shops and 35 houses.
</P>
<P>
   They separated the men from the women and children and killed 11
men, he continued, leaving their bodies in the street in the
morning for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city was very scared,'' he said, and added that more than
10,000 people in the city of roughly 60,000 had fled southward, but
he said that most of them are trapped on the road near the village
of Raqa, about a mile away from Dakovica, surrounded by Serbian
forces and unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   Under gray, chilly skies at the border post, 64-year-old Dull
Gunxi lay on a tractor cart, wrapped in a blanket, his face a mask
of cuts and crusted blood from a tank shell that hit his home in
Damjan on Sunday. His wife and children had similar wounds.
</P>
<P>
   They fled to the home of friends in the nearby village of
Tepnish seeking safety.
</P>
<P>
   In Tepnish, Monday's order to leave came at 4 in the afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
