<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA SENATE ENDS FEUD ON LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR'S POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After more than a month of fierce factional deadlock
and ridicule, the Alabama state Senate on Tuesday found its way out
of the procedural chaos that had prevented any legislation from
being passed and threatened to paralyze state government.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a deadline that was jeopardizing Gov. Donald
Siegelman's first-year legislative agenda, the governor's
Democratic allies agreed to return some of the power that they had
stripped from Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, a Republican. In exchange,
Windom agreed to share control over the Senate with Democratic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the compromise, senators agreed to end the
lawsuits, the talk of impeachment, and the personal recriminations
that many legislators said represented a new low in Alabama
politics, which has never been known as a model of high-minded
public policy. When the Senate reconvenes next Tuesday, it will
have 18 days to pass a state budget and consider the governor's
plan for a state lottery. (State law limits the Legislature's
session to 30 working days, 12 of which were used up in the
dispute.)
</P>
<P>
   The paralysis began in January, when Democrats backed by
Siegelman _ who have a slight edge in the Senate _ voted to strip
the lieutenant governor of the power to make committee assignments
and direct the flow of legislation (the lieutenant governor had
five Democrats supporting him). That power has traditionally been
vested in the lieutenant governor, but when Windom was elected in
November as the first Republican in that office this century, he
threatened to hold up some of Siegelman's legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his power, Windom took some unusual actions to
regain it. On March 3, after an ally in the Senate moved to restore
his power, Windom declared that the Senate had unanimously approved
the measure on a voice vote, despite a platoon of screaming
Democrats voting no. The noise, which frightened one little girl in
the gallery to tears, also scared the governor, who realized that
his agenda could be threatened if Democrats, who began to boycott
the Senate sessions, could not reach agreement with Windom's
faction.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman called an unusual special session of the Legislature
to solve the dispute, but tension ran so high that Windom refused
to leave the chamber even for a bathroom break during the
round-the-clock session lest Democrats find a way to replace him.
To illustrate his plight, Windom announced on Sunday that he felt
obliged to urinate in a jug behind the podium during the
negotiations, and the remark was picked up by headline writers,
radio talk shows and national television programs, making the
situation appear ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   But after Tuesday's compromise, Windom declared that all the bad
publicity was worth it, and even took what he called a ``people's
gavel victory lap'' by plane around the state to announce his
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people won a great victory,'' he said in an interview on
Tuesday. ``The governor tried to take tremendous power, but the
lieutenant governor has been restored to an office that does wield
the people's gavel and protects the state.''
</P>
<P>
   His chief antagonist in the Senate, President Pro Tem Lowell Ray
Barron, said that Windom was wrong to call the compromise a
personal victory, agreeing only that the people would benefit from
an end to the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to fly around the state declaring a victory is about
as embarrassing as what he did behind the podium in the jug,''
Barron said. ``This is only a victory in that the people's business
can now be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the compromise, Windom will not be able to bottle up
legislation or approve any more voice votes, but his faction will
retain some power over budget bills and some authority over
committee assignments. He said he would not block the governor's
principal legislative goal _ a state lottery with proceeds
designated for education _ even though he opposes it. The lottery
will go before the voters if it is approved, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Stewart, chairman of the political science
department at the University of Alabama, said the episode showed
that Democrats must take more seriously the growing power of
Republicans in Alabama. But Stewart said it also demonstrated that
the Legislature had a great deal of work to do if it is to rise
above a dysfunctional level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature still has such a limited agenda, and such a
limited conception of what the basic policy-forming institution of
the state should be about,'' Stewart said. ``They're still not
identifying the state's real problems, or coming up with solutions.
They're still responding to interest-group pressures. But at least
now, they'll be able to function, for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
