<SLUG> BC-BOTTLED-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLED WATER NOT NECESSARILY BETTER THAN TAP WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (mk) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People who buy bottled water cannot be sure that it
is purer or safer than tap water, an environmental advocacy group
said in a report issued Tuesday after sampling 1,000 bottles of
water sold under 103 brand names.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the group, the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said samples of bottled water contained bacteria or chemicals in
levels that were considered unsafe because they might cause cancer
or other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most bottled water tested was of good quality, but some
brands' quality was spotty,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contamination posing immediate risks to healthy people is
rare,'' it said. ``However, blanket reassurances from the bottled
water industry that bottled water is totally safe and pure are
false. No one should assume that just because water comes from a
bottle it is necessarily any purer or safer than most tap water.''
</P>
<P>
   The council is seeking stricter federal controls on bottled
water, either by tightening the regulations imposed by the Food and
Drug Administration or by transferring jurisdiction to the
Environmental Protection Agency, which regulates tap water.
</P>
<P>
   In 23 of the 103 brands tested, at least one bottle violated
California's strict limits for some contaminant, usually arsenic or
one of several cancer-causing man-made organic chemicals. In 18 of
the brands, at least one bottle was found to contain more bacteria
than would be allowed under guidelines for microbial purity that
are recommended by some states.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the EPA has reported that in 1996 about one in 10
community tap water systems, serving about one-seventh of the U.S.
population, violated tap water treatment or contaminant standards.
</P>
<P>
   The International Bottled Water Association, an industry group,
said the environmental group's testing ``confirms the quality
results of the industry's own testing program.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade association said that under the FDA, which has the
authority to recall and seize tainted products, there were no
confirmed reports in the United States of illness or disease linked
to bottled water in 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Environmental Law Foundation, a
nonprofit group based in Oakland, Calif., filed a lawsuit against
eight bottled-water companies alleging that their brands had
violated California laws by advertising the purity of their
products and by failing to provide notification to consumers of
possible contamination. The complaint was based on the Natural
Resources Defense Council's report.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of bottled water have tripled in the last 10 years, to
about $4 billion annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
