<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS ARENA BECOMES LAGOS-LAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Sports Arena, rarely (if ever) confused for an
amusement park, became Lagos-land on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos, the capital of Nigeria, is the birthplace of the starting
centers for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon grew up in Lagos, attended the
University of Houston, and was the first player selected in the
1984 NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, the Clippers used the league's first pick
to choose Michael Olowokandi, the University of Pacific star whose
father is a Nigerian diplomat. Olowokandi grew up in England.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian centers aren't exactly unacquainted, although
Tuesday's game was their first official on-court meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers did play in Houston earlier this month, but an
ankle injury limited Olowokandi to participation in the morning
shoot around. But he did cross paths and exchange pleasantries with
Olajuwon, who looked at the rookie's shoes and announced that they
were quite ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Numb and numbers: An examination of league-wide statistics
reveals that Clipper Maurice Taylor is looking up at the rest of
his power-forward peers when the subject is rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pulling down 20 in a double-overtime loss to Vancouver,
the 6-8, 250-pound Taylor is averaging a disappointing (not to
mention puzzling) five rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the Clippers rank 21st in the league in
rebounding, meaning eight other teams are worse at rebounding than
they are.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers take a back seat to no team when it comes to
allowing the other team to make a high percentage of its field-goal
attempts. Clipper foes are connecting on 47.7 percent of their
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Point of no return?: The Clippers' next game date is Thursday in
Dallas, where point guard Sherman Douglas is eligible to bring his
sore thigh off the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas is expected to remain on the IL until the wheel is
fully healed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday also happens to coincide with the end of Troy Hudson's
10-day contract. Hudson, who arrived from the CBA when injury and
circumstance found Douglas and Pooh Richardson on the IL at the
same time, could be signed to another 10-day deal.
</P>
<P>
   At the completion of the second 10-day contract, the team would
have to sign Hudson for the remainder of the season or give him the
boot.
</P>
<P>
   But the latter option seems risky, because Hudson has provided
an end-to-end spark rarely seen this season at the point. Not to
worry, faithful Clips fans; the team is expected to give Hudson and
second 10-day run, then sign him for the remainder of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
