<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      03-30 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT NAME NOT TO BE REVIVED IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TAURUS-DESIGN) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having agreed last week to buy a little more than a
third of Nissan Motor Co., Renault SA may start selling Renault
cars under the Nissan name in the United States someday, but it has
no plans to revive the Renault name in the American market,
Renault's chairman and chief executive, Louis Schweitzer, said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Renault may start selling vehicles using its own name in
Mexico and possibly build these cars at a Nissan factory in that
country, Renault has no intention of using its own name in the
American market because its reputation is so weak, Schweitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Renault brand image in the U.S. is poor, that's a fact,''
he said. ``It reminds people of cars that rusted, which was true
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer's plans, including his blunt assessment of Renault's
reputation in the United States, were another sign of the enormous
importance of brand names in the consolidation of the auto
industry. The purchased companies have been those with strong
brands, not just big factories or strong engineering staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer said that Renault might try to sell Nissan sport
utility vehicles in Europe under the Renault name. But in the
United States, Renault will try to use Nissan's reputation for
quality cars at reasonable prices, while trying to enliven Nissan's
designs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try, Nissan and Renault, to bring products that have
not already been done by a competitor. I do not believe in a me-too
attitude,'' Schweitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. bought the car operations of Volvo this year
mainly because Volvos have a strong worldwide image for safety and
are popular with women and baby boomers. Part of Chrysler Corp.'s
attraction for Daimler-Benz before the companies formed
DaimlerChrysler last November was the strength of Chrysler's Jeep
and Dodge brands.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president, said the Japanese
automaker planned to step up efforts to cut costs after the
business consolidation with Renault and was not looking at the
partnership as a way of avoiding difficult moves. ``This
restructuring plan will be front-loaded and brought forward,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanawa and Schweitzer spoke at a briefing for automotive writers
at the New York International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
   At other events for the news media on Monday night and Tuesday
morning, executives of General Motors Corp. acknowledged that it
may take longer than originally predicted for the company to
replace some small car factories with new assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   G. Richard Wagoner Jr., GM's president and chief operating
officer, said that because GM was mainly interested in increasing
light-truck production, he was not especially concerned about the
growing likelihood that the company would have to delay the
construction of new small-car factories.
</P>
<P>
   GM had been close two months ago to an agreement with local
units of the United Automobile Workers union on work rules for the
new factories, which would rely heavily on snapping together large
pieces of vehicles that would be manufactured by outside suppliers.
Many of these suppliers are not unionized.
</P>
<P>
   But the union's national leadership stopped the talks last month
after becoming concerned that local union units were competing with
each other to be more generous to the company. Stephen Yokich, the
union's president, said on Sunday that the union had deep concerns
about so-called modular assembly techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner said that GM would have to discuss these concerns with
the union. GM's national contract with the union expires in
September.
</P>
<P>
   GM needs to replace assembly plants to lower its production
costs in the small-car market, a swiftly shrinking and unprofitable
market segment that GM dominates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
