<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLSTEN-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLSTEN TO PAY $61 MILLION IN MEDICARE BILLING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Md., Ga., Fla.)   (af)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Olsten Corp., a big provider of home health care
and temporary office workers, said on Tuesday that it would pay $61
million, including $10 million in fines and penalties, to settle
federal investigations into Medicare billing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the details of which are still being
negotiated, Olsten said that its Kimberly Home Health Care unit
would plead guilty to criminal charges. Both the fine and the
guilty plea were related to Olsten's former arrangements with the
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp., the embattled hospital chain.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to the guilty plea, Olsten, based in Melville, N.Y.,
may be preparing to divest itself of Kimberly to keep the Medicare
business of the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew V. Roswell, a securities analyst in Baltimore with Legg
Mason Wood Walker, said he expected that Olsten would sell, spin
off or close its entire home health business, which he said had had
operating losses since early last year.
</P>
<P>
   David Fluhrer, a spokesman, said there were no plans for Olsten
to divest itself of the home health business.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimberly unit, which managed home health services for
Columbia and other hospitals, generated less than 1 percent of
Olsten's 1998 revenue of $4.6 billion. Total home health operations
generated about 30 percent, and office and other staffing about 60
percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Retaining the right to serve patients under Medicare and
Medicaid, the government health programs, is essential for hospital
and home health care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Olsten and Columbia/HCA have said that they are cooperating
with federal investigators, who are also pursuing a broader inquiry
into Medicare billing by the hospital chain.
</P>
<P>
   In another health care investigation, the Centennial Healthcare
Corp. said Tuesday that the inspector general's office of the
federal Health and Human Services Department had subpoenaed
portions of its records. Centennial, based in Atlanta, operates 107
nursing homes. Centennial shares fell $7.0625 Tuesday, more than 44
percent, to $8.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Centennial, which was acquired last year for $16 a
share by Welsh, Carson, Anderson &AMP; Stowe LP, a New York buyout
firm, had dropped more than 30 percent in the 12 months preceding
the subpoena. Nursing home stocks have tumbled after changes in
Medicare payments and government investigations of the industry,
including Beverly Enterprises Inc., the largest nursing home chain.
</P>
<P>
   Olsten's shares have lost about 70 percent of their value since
July 1997, when the Medicare billing investigation was disclosed.
Tuesday, the shares fell 62.50 cents to $6 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Olsten also said on Tuesday that it would take a $70 million
charge, or 86 cents a share, against earnings in the current first
quarter. Fluhrer, the company spokesman, said the charge included
the $61 million payment, as well as restructuring charges. He
declined to specify the after-tax amount of the Medicare
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it expected first-quarter earnings,
excluding the charge, would be 10 cents a share, disappointing
analysts who had projected earnings of 14 cents to 15 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Olsten bought back some of the home health agencies
it had sold to Columbia under the arrangement that federal
officials later challenged
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Justice Department joined a lawsuit in federal
district court in Tampa, Fla. The suit contends that Columbia paid
Olsten artificially low prices for home health agencies and
inflated the fees that Columbia paid Olsten for managing them. The
management fees were charged to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   John Hindelong, a Wall Street analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said that health-care companies were having difficulty
adjusting to the change in Medicare payments for home health and
nursing home services. Medicare established a fee for each type of
service or patient instead of paying on the basis of customary
costs. He said it took half a dozen years for hospitals to adjust
to a similar change in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office is conducting more than 1,200
investigations of providers of Medicare and Medicaid. Judy Holtz, a
spokeswoman for the inspector general, confirmed that negotiations
with Olsten were under way. federal officials declined to discuss
the status of the Columbia/HCA investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
