<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TOMMY JOHN: DON'T SET TARGET DATE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since a tendon from Tommy John's right forearm was
transplanted to replace a ruptured ligament in his left elbow in
1974, the operation has been known as ``Tommy John surgery.''
Dozens of ballplayers, mostly pitchers, have needed it. Now the
Cubs' phenom, Kerry Wood, needs it. So does Paul Wilson, the Mets'
right-hander who is scheduled to be wheeled into surgery on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing to undergo Tommy John surgery. It's quite
another to pitch again as well as he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most successful surgery, in the sense of coming back to
throw the way you did before, was the first one,'' Tommy John was
saying, meaning himself. ``Doctors say they know more about it now,
but then I say, `If you know more about it, why aren't guys coming
back and pitching as well?' I say that because I never lost a day,
not one day, because my arm hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   When his 26-season career ended with 288 career victories, John,
at 46, had won more games, 164, in 14 seasons after the surgery
than he did before it, 124. And now, as a 55-year-old broadcaster
and director of community relations for the Charlotte Knights of
the International League, he's still throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``On April 7,'' he said, ``I'm throwing batting practice for our
sponsors, patrons, sportswriters and sportscasters. I'll throw
about 1,500 pitches that day. I also throw batting practice every
day to our high school team, 350 to 500 pitches. At least 25
pitches to each kid, 15 kids on the team. Add it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And his arm doesn't hurt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If only Wood and Wilson and Matt Morris, the Cardinals'
right-hander who also needs the operation, were sure of being able
to say that eventually. Also in that group are Jason Isringhausen,
the Mets' farmhand right-hander who missed last season, and Bill
Pulsipher, once a Mets left-hander who missed the 1996 season and
is now with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked why more pitchers haven't returned from Tommy
John surgery as successfully as John himself did, he had a theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make a mistake putting a target date on when they want to
be back,'' John said. ``If you're ready to come back, come back. If
not, take however long it takes. I just think longer is better. I
can't prove it, but I know the way I did it. Wait until your arm is
absolutely back to full strength in the biceps and the triceps and
the forearm, then you start throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   John was 13-3 with the Dodgers in 1974 when he suddenly needed
surgery in September. Although on the disabled list throughout the
1975 season, he made all the Dodgers' road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go to the ball park early and jog six or seven miles,'' he
recalled. ``Then I'd soak my arm in a hot whirlpool for three
minutes, then put it in ice for 30 seconds. I'd take eight of those
hot-then-cold treatments, then take ultrasound treatments. And when
I wasn't doing anything else, I'd squeeze Silly Putty to strengthen
my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 1975 season John was pitching batting
practice, then he pitched in the Arizona instructional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the rest of the winter off,'' he said. ``But from the
day spring training started that year and for the rest of my
career, I threw every day. I didn't pitch, but I threw to make my
arm strong. I'd throw off a mound to a catcher to the outside
corner because I wanted to be able to throw the ball to the outside
corner every time.''
</P>
<P>
   John was 10-10 in his return with the Dodgers in 1976, then 20-7
with a 2.78 earned run average, and 17-10. Joining the Yankees as a
free agent in 1979, he was 21-9, then 22-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have Kerry Wood pitch in 2001 and have him pitch
until he's 35,'' he said, ``than come back in 2000, pitch spotty
and be out of the game at 26. Because he can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think that a pitcher about to undergo or recuperate
from Tommy John surgery would phone Tommy John to ask what he did
to be so productive after the operation. But he remembered only one
pitcher calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Palmer, a young right-hander with the Expos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who had been 24-13 with the Expos before surgery, missed
the 1983 season. Over the next six years, he struggled to a 40-46
record with the Expos, Braves, Phillies and Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   But if Kerry Wood and Paul Wilson should call him now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell 'em, `Don't be in a hurry,''' Tommy John said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
