<HEADER>
A0176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRODUCTIVITY-STUDY-NY     03-30 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRODUCTIVITY-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DATA MAY UNDERSTATE PRODUCTIVITY GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of maintaining that its statistics on
the labor productivity growth rate were generally reliable, the
government agency that produces the numbers now says they may be
somewhat underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   In research to be published on Wednesday, the Labor Department's
Bureau of Labor Statistics says that the current economic
prosperity, and rising profits ``do not seem fully consistent with
slow productivity growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The new studies focused on four industries _ banking, insurance,
construction and health services _ that seem robust but have
registered no improvement in official productivity statistics in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin R. Dean, chief of the bureau's productivity division,
wrote in one of three articles that will appear in the Labor
Department's Monthly Labor Review that the published data do not
appear to understand productivity gains ``by a large order of
magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said there appeared to have been at least some
underestimate, mostly because of measurement problems in the vast
service sector.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected expression of doubt from the Bureau of Labor
Statistics gives a fresh twist to perhaps the most important
economic debate in the United States today: whether corporate
America has become sufficiently efficient to keep the current
economic boom going without having to raise prices or sacrifice
profits.
</P>
<P>
   National well-being depends on productivity, which measures the
output of goods and services by the amount of time per worker. That
is because corporate revenue rises when workers produce more in a
given hour than they did before.
</P>
<P>
   A factory worker makes more bottle caps, for example, or a
telephone operator handles more calls, or an air traffic controller
more flights. The additional revenue can then be divided up as
extra profit or higher wages or both. That feeds into spending and
investment, and more jobs, and the economy flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity growth rate rose smartly until 1973 and then
the statistics registered a sharp decline that has persisted since,
except for temporary upticks during boom periods, including the
current boom, which started in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While some economists contend that the official productivity
numbers are accurate, others insist that they have failed to
capture the improvements made possible by computers and other
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, has repeatedly
argued that the national economy once again enjoys a productivity
growth rate reminiscent of the quarter-century after World War II.
And now the Bureau of Labor Statistics, for the first time, has
publicly expressed doubt about its own figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had careful discussions with prominent economists in
recent years,'' Dean said in a telephone interview, ``and we have
felt under an obligation to conduct probing studies of this issue
and these studies have now been completed.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's studies fail to address an issue considered crucial
by some economists _ whether the findings in three or four
industries can be generalized to the economy as a whole.
Underestimating productivity in some industries may be offset by
overestimating productivity in others, said Barry Bosworth, a
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if we are dealing with an allocation problem,''
he said, ``or a change in total national productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's new studies examined not only labor productivity
but also a broader measure, known as multifactor productivity,
which measures the output or dollar value of the production that
results not only from a worker's efforts but also from other
inputs, such as the computers and machinery that workers use.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the bureau found that the biggest problem lay in
accurately measuring output. Often it has to be roughly estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's studies also cited difficulties in adjusting output
for inflation, and in defining in the service sector what
constitutes input and output in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the production of services,'' Dean wrote in an article that
summarized the other findings, ``the consumer often supplies an
essential input. For example, it may not be possible to define
medical output adequately without considering whether the patient
follows the doctor's advice, or ignores it. Similar issues arise in
the fields of education and entertainment. For example, the output
of a jazz band may not be well defined without considering whether
the audience was 1,000 people, 10 people, or no one at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the bureau's studies covered the last 20 years, too
short a time to determine whether the productivity growth rate was
similarly underestimated in its heyday before 1973. If so, then the
sharp decline in productivity growth after that year would be
roughly unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990330.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-30 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GORE-1STLD-WRI     03-30 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKE OTHER CANDIDATES, GORE IS TIED TO KOSOVO POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with Gore pressing administration to begin
bombing   before Primakov visit; Pickup 4th graf pvs, Gore has
...) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While some Republican presidential candidates are
trying to avoid the thorny subject of American involvement in
Kosovo, Vice President Al Gore does not have that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic vice president is inextricably entwined with the
Clinton administration policy for the bombing campaign. Indeed, he
describes himself as an ``active participant'' in the
decision-making and he has been a strong advocate of the bombing
while he campaigns and raises money across the country _ a
political pursuit that Republicans have called ``a disgrace'' for
an administration official while Americans are risking their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Gore has been influential in helping set
priorities since the situation inside Kosovo deteriorated. For
example, he pressed administration officials to move more quickly
with plans for NATO air strikes rather than delay until after a
visit by Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov, officials
said. And he called Primakov to tell him that NATO was beginning
the bombings, prompting Primakov to cancel a meeting in Washington
and turn his flight around over the middle of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also notified former Presidents George Bush, Gerald R. Ford
and Jimmy Carter of the impending air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been meeting privately with President Clinton and
participates in military briefings at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While he campaigned in New Hampshire on Saturday, he received
seven updates from one of his military advisers, Cmdr. Kevin Scott,
a Navy helicopter pilot. And in his hour-long flight back to
Washington, he received three updates on the effort to rescue the
Air Force pilot whose plane went down near Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   A second military adviser, Maj. Steve Kwast, an Air Force
fighter pilot, provided updates as Gore campaigned Monday in
Chicago and Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing his support for the airstrikes, Gore said in
Alabama, ``Despite the risks, in my opinion, we are doing the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say that Gore has always carried weight
on foreign affairs in the White House, partly because of his
military service _ he worked as an Army journalist for seven months
in Vietnam _ and because he specialized in subjects like arms
control during his eight years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president always comes to the table prepared and with
strong views,'' said Joe Lockhart, Clinton's spokesman. ``I know
the president relies on him. He's the one who has no institutional
representation; he doesn't represent the Pentagon, he doesn't
represent the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   During this particular crisis, Gore has felt the absence of his
longtime national security adviser, Leon Fuerth, who had a mild
heart attack last Wednesday. Fuerth, who is recuperating at home,
has a secure telephone line and participates in classified
briefings. His place at the table with the president's national
security team is being filled by his deputy, Col. Richard M.
Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has largely been using Gore, though, as a public
spokesman on the American-led NATO bombings. ``One of the best
roles he can play is articulating the policy,'' one administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bombing began last week, Gore's team considered
scrapping a long-planned political trip to New Hampshire. But they
concluded that the amount of press attention that Gore would
attract _ this was his first trip where he mingled with small
groups of voters _ would be useful in helping to advance the
administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as he was tucked away in remote North Conway, N.H., in
the White Mountains, on Friday night, his interviews about Kosovo
with local television stations were broadcast by the national
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In between every stop, my national security staff conversed
over the secure line with my military aide,'' Gore told reporters
Saturday night as he flew back to Washington, ``and I relayed my
advice on pending questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that while the initial decision to begin airstrikes
was a difficult one, ``it was not an especially controversial
decision internally'' because the administration was convinced that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia was committing
atrocities. ``Everybody understands this guy is a butcher,'' Gore
said, adding that he expected the bombing to continue for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-dozen speeches throughout his two-day swing across New
Hampshire, Gore talked about the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering of about 70 people in a living room in Concord,
he described Milosevic this way: ``He's one of these junior-league
Hitler types who tries to hold on to power by stirring up hatred
among his own people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of American participation in the bombing, ``If we stood
by and did nothing while this kind of activity occurred, we would
not be true to our values.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Gore said: ``I do not support the
introduction of ground troops in combat settings in the Balkans. I
believe we can achieve our objectives through the use of air
power.'' That comment was a clearer formulation than other
administration officials, including Clinton, have offered in their
briefings and speeches, when they have taken care to say they have
``no plans'' for ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is virtually the only presidential candidate who, whether
by design or duty, has tied himself so definitively to the NATO
mission, and if it turns sour and loses support, he would have the
most difficult time extricating himself politically. ``Even if he
wanted to separate himself, he couldn't,'' one administration
official said. ``But he has always been hawkish on the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's only rival for the Democratic nomination, Bill Bradley,
the former senator from New Jersey, has raised red flags about the
effort, saying that the administration has no clear exit strategy
and that the nation runs the risk of a Vietnam-like quagmire. Of
the several Republican presidential candidates, about half support
involvement in Yugoslavia and the other half do not.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have freely questioned the propriety of Gore's
discussing policies that endanger American troops during his
campaigning. Steve Duprey, chairman of the New Hampshire Republican
Party, called Gore's campaigning ``a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Forbes, a Republican candidate for president who was
also touring New Hampshire last weekend, criticized the ``dithering
and drift'' of the administration on Balkan policy.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism followed Gore on Monday on his fund-raising trips.
Winton Blount 3rd, the Republican chairman in Alabama, said,
``Gore, who is running in a practically uncontested primary, has
put dollar signs ahead of our men and women in the armed
services.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president canceled plans this week for a six-day ski
vacation, during which he and his wife, Tipper, were to celebrate
his 51st birthday. But he is still planning a three-day
fund-raising trip to California next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
