u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SPONSORS-NYT &LR;      03-30 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SPONSORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH DECLINES INVITATION TO TESTIFY BEFORE SENATE COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:: Ariz.) (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president of the International Olympic Committee has refused
to testify before a U.S. Senate Committee hearing investigating the
Salt Lake City bribery scandal that led to the expulsion of six IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   Without an explanation, Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC
president, declined the invitation to testify before the Senate
Commerce Committee on April 14, but suggested that it invite Anita
DeFrantz, an IOC vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, Samaranch doesn't understand the gravity of the
situation for the future of the Olympic movement,'' Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a committee chairman, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the committee invited DeFrantz and James Easton, the
two U.S. members of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate committee, which scheduled its hearing before the IOC
expelled six members and created ethics and reform commissions two
weeks ago, wants to be certain that the IOC is doing enough to
guarantee accountability in the way it conducts business.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the committee was particularly interested in how
Samaranch, who had resisted change until the Salt Lake City scandal
exploded beyond his control, had placed himself in charge of the
ethics and reform panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC has taken serious action to deal with the past and
intends to continue to work with a number of people, including
yourself, to set the IOC on the right course for the future,''
Samaranch wrote in his March 29 letter to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate committee is considering legislation that could strip
the IOC of its tax-exempt status in the United States and possibly
shift control, from the IOC to the U.S. Olympic Committee, of the
cash raised domestically from nine of the 11 worldwide sponsors and
NBC, which holds the American Olympic television rights through
2008.
</P>
<P>
   Those expected to testify are William Hybl, the USOC president;
George Mitchell, the former senator who was chairman of an
independent USOC investigation into the Salt Lake City scandal; and
other members of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's refusal to testify was made public on the same day
that the IOC's chief marketers met with representatives of its 11
sponsors to assure them of the viability of the committee's plans
to reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them: `This is the blueprint of what we're working on.
Now we have to implement it,''' Richard W. Pound, an IOC executive
board member, whose investigation led to the six expulsions, said.
``I think they were satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour meeting, at a Manhattan hotel, lacked the urgency
of a similar one in mid-February, when restless sponsors urged the
IOC to take greater responsibility for the scandal, which
implicated as many as 30 members in the Salt Lake City organizing
committee's improper cash and gift-giving spree to get the 2002
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   One person in the meeting, who asked not to identified, said
some of the sponsorship officials said their top management and, in
some cases, their franchisees, are resistant to participating in
Olympic marketing programs because they feel the IOC, which is
based in Lausanne, Switzerland, has not proposed serious enough
reforms. Also, the person said, sponsors were told not to expect
the Senate hearing to lead to the most serious changes contemplated
in the possible legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy expressed by the Olympic officials was to bide time
with the Senate by promising that the IOC reform commission would
eventually make changes that would parallel those recommended by
the Mitchell commission.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Pound said he believed the steps taken by the
IOC addressed the most serious concerns of the Senate. The
legislative proposals, he said, ``are more likely ideas that had a
certain currency at a certain time and that time may have come and
gone.'' He said he had not been invited to testify.
</P>
<P>
   John Krimsky Jr., deputy secretary general of the USOC, who
attended the meeting, added, ``We'll know a lot more after the
testimony is heard.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for one sponsor, John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance,
which has been sharply critical of the IOC, said the company let a
deadline lapse last Friday to be the exclusive insurance advertiser
on NBC's Olympic broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the scandal broke, Hancock halted its talks with
NBC about buying $20 million in Olympic advertising.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
