<SLUG> BC-LONG-TERM-CAPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM CAPITAL EXPECTS TO START REPAYING RESCUERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-Term Capital Management, the giant hedge fund
that Wall Street firms saved from collapse during the turmoil in
stock and bond markets last September, has recovered robustly and
plans to start paying back its rescuers as early as June.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium of 14 banks and brokerages firms that control
Long-Term Capital said on Tuesday that the fund was much less risky
now than it was six months ago, having reduced market risk by 50
percent, although they did not define how they measured risk.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the consortium said, Long-Term Capital's investments
have gained more than 20 percent after paying management fees, a
recovery the consortium said was faster than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a downturn in the bond markets in which Long-Term
Capital has large investment positions, the hedge fund will return
at least part of the capital invested by the consortium in the
second half of this year, the consortium said in a statement.
People close to the fund said that it was possible that consortium
members, which invested between $100 million and $300 million
apiece, could receive all of their money within a year or so,
sooner than the three years initially anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement confirms earlier reports of a turnaround in the
hedge fund's fortunes. Bond markets generally have rebounded from
their lows last fall after Russia's debt default sent global bond
markets, and Long-Term Capital's portfolio, tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street firms and other investors who specialize in
bond investments have posted big profits in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But Long-Term's recovery is noteworthy because it made sizable
gains even while reducing risk, two goals that are not always
complementary. Reducing risk generally means borrowing less money
and buying securities judged less likely to swing sharply in price.
That helps protect the fund in down markets but reduces potential
gains when things go well.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Long-Term said its total assets and liabilities,
known as the balance sheet, had been reduced, but they declined to
provide specific figures. When the hedge fund foundered last fall,
it held securities valued at $120 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The news about Long-Term Capital seems likely to bolster the
efforts of its founding partners, led by the former Salomon
Brothers bond trader John W. Meriwether, to prepare the hedge fund
for a future without Wall Street patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Meriwether has plans to raise fresh capital from private
investors as soon as possible, people close to the fund said. He is
eager to wind down his affiliation with the Wall Street consortium
that has stationed a six-man team at the hedge fund's office in
Greenwich, Conn., to oversee its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium consists of large banks and brokerages houses,
including the Chase Manhattan Corp., Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. People close to the consortium said that by
June the members will decide how much money to withdraw from
Long-Term Capital and whether to give Meriwether permission to
raise money from other sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
