A0183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-AD-COLUMN-NY     03-30 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BASEBALL'S BIG CAMPAIGN  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif., Mass., N.Y., Md., Ga., Texas)  (mk) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to capitalize on last year's phenomenal success on the
playing field and at the ticket office, Major League Baseball is
kicking off a record $25 million television advertising campaign
this Sunday on ESPN during its season opener, a game between the
Colorado Rockies and the San Diego Padres to be played in
Monterrey, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is divided into three distinct groups of
commercials, two of which will be given a local twist by 22 of the
league's 30 teams _ the first time MLB, which represents the
business interests of the 30 clubs in the American and National
leagues, has created such local advertising. The budget is double
its 1998 advertising expenditures; MLB will be responsible for $15
million and the individual teams for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to 1998's home-run exploits by Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa, and the record-breaking attendance of 70.3 million _ a 10.4
percent increase from 1997 _Kathleen Francis, MLB's vice president
for marketing, said: ``We had a great season last year, the game
played on the field, the great story with Sammy and Mark. With the
advertising, we're trying to maintain the momentum gained from last
year. And by working with the clubs locally, it reinforces the
brand.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's centerpiece is a clever series of ads involving a
role reversal: baseball players as fans of baseball fans
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Vigilante, a New York-based unit of Leo Burnett Co.,
these ads show fans receiving fan mail from various players,
thanking them for their support.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, to be broadcast nationally, a heavyset young man
receives a package from Tony Gwynn, the right fielder for the San
Diego Padres, containing the lyrics of the national anthem and a
note from Gwynn _ who reads it in the voiceover _ saying that he
and his teammates had noticed the fan had problems remembering the
song. The fan then practices singing the anthem, off-key of course,
and ends the commercial by rasping, ``Play ball.''
</P>
<P>
   A second spot, also for national broadcast, shows another fan
listening to messages on his answering machine. One is from Nomar
Garciaparra, the shortstop for the Boston Red Sox, who thanks the
fan for putting on his rally cap in the eighth inning of that day's
game. At the end of his message, Garciaparra asks the stunned fan
if he can attend any road games.
</P>
<P>
   In one commercial intended for local broadcast, a fan nursing an
injured elbow receives a fax from a player congratulating him on
his ``sweet catch at the game today'' and telling him to take care
of his elbow. Local teams will use their own players in this
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Another local ad depicts a small boy, seated at a computer, who
gets an e-mail from a player _ again differing by team _ thanking
him for sticking up for the player against an older bully at a
game.
</P>
<P>
   All commercials end with rousing music from Bizet's opera,
``Carmen.'' Nationally broadcast ads close with the MLB logo, while
local ads conclude with promotional information from each team.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Strachan, a principal of Vigilante, said the ads were
intended to ``capture the unique ballpark experience.'' He added,
``We tried to put baseball inherently where it could only be, a
game that is Americana, that can be touched, where you can win a
souvenir.''
</P>
<P>
   The humorous, somewhat edgy tone of the advertising should also
help reach baseball's hard-core supporters as well as its less
ardent fans, Jacqueline Parkes, MLB's director of advertising,
said. ``Humor transcends age and sex barriers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The second set of commercials, public service ads by Waylon
Advertising of St. Louis, shows well-known players with children at
the Boys and Girls Clubs of America, which MLB has designated as
its official charity.
</P>
<P>
   A national version of the ad shows Cal Ripken Jr., the Baltimore
Orioles' third baseman; Mo Vaughn, the Anaheim Angels' first
baseman, and Roger Clemens, the New York Yankees pitcher. MLB
officials said that all three were personally involved with the
children's organization. Ripken and Vaughn will also appear in
local ads, along with a player, chosen by each team, who is active
in the charity.
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial focuses on a special ceremony in Atlanta on
April 8, when Hank Aaron, the major leagues' career home-run
leader, will be honored on the 25th anniversary of his breaking
Babe Ruth's record of 714. The ad, also by Vigilante, shows a young
man, wearing a batting helmet but dressed in business attire,
fruitlessly trying to belt a home run in a ballpark. With each
swing, he shouts the name of a celebrated slugger, like McGwire and
Ken Griffey, Jr. The end of the spot invites viewers to celebrate
the ``home run hitter of home run hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The fan mail and Boys and Girls Clubs ads will be broadcast
throughout the season on ESPN, Fox, FX, Fox Sport Net, TBS and NBC,
and on stations in teams' local markets. The Aaron ad will be shown
through April 8 on TBS, which will broadcast the ceremony that
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Cancro, vice president of sales and marketing for the
Boston Red Sox and a member of MLB's advertising committee,
applauded the campaign's messages and execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports advertising typically shows a lot of action, but we
wanted more than footage,'' he said. ``We wanted a campaign that
was consistent with the feel of the game, that shows that players
are cognizant of the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell, the first baseman for the Houston Astros who
appeared in the fax machine fan-mail commercial for the local
market, said baseball players actually did notice ``the kind of
stuff shown in the ad all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a foul play, we watch where it goes,'' he added.
``We see some incredible things.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Bagwell said, it was necessary for Major
League Baseball to improve its public image, which until last
season seemed in particular trouble in the years following the 1994
baseball strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so bad at promoting itself for so long,'' he said.
``I think the ads are a neat thing. They're going in the right
direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
