<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMENSION-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENCOUNTER IN THE THIRD DIMENSION': PROFESSOR'S DREAMS AND 3-D
CLEAVAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The latest Imax tourist attraction is a giddy foray
into three-dimensional imagery, one that traces the history of this
technique and makes a case for its promising future. Of course that
possible renaissance is closely linked to the prospects for 3-D
Imax, the huge-screen format that puts viewers in special headgear
and sends them grasping at the illusory visions that seem just out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   While Imax still remains more of an amusement park treat than a
viable storytelling form, ``Encounter in the Third Dimension''
offers a nifty demonstration of what 3-D technology can do now.
</P>
<P>
   The pretext for the film involves a hammy professor (played
eagerly by Stuart Pankin), his pet flying saucer (with Pankin's
voice), and the professor's plan to create his own 3-D marvels. His
laboratory alone offers a screen-filling array of 3-D props and
gimmicks, not least of them the vampy Elvira, who plays herself.
The film's shifting between plain old Elvira and Elvira with 3-D
cleavage is only one of the ways it has fun with its medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encounter in the Third Dimension'' reviews the history of 3-D,
from the Lumiere brothers' oncoming train to a bit by Dean Martin
and Jerry Lewis, with a set of clips that have been enterprisingly
arranged.
</P>
<P>
   The real standout here is the elaborate roller coaster fantasy
that hurls the audience into gravity-defying races through
seemingly huge settings. What begins in an Indiana Jones-type
underground cavern takes the viewer under the sea and up toward the
stars, in sequences that are as imaginatively staged as they are
vertiginous. The excitement is offset by the deliberate cheesiness
of the professor's merry shtick.
</P>
<P>
   Young children overheard at one preview of ``Encounter in the
Third Dimension'' said it was fun, and it is.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ENCOUNTER IN THE THIRD DIMENSION'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ben Stassen; written by Kurt Frey and Stassen;
director of photography (live action), Sean MacLeod Phillips; lead
animators, Jeremie Degruson and Sylvain Delaine; edited by
Phillips; music by Louis Vyncke; production designer, Anthony
Huerta; produced by Charlotte Clay Huggins; CGI producer, Caroline
Van Iseghem; released by N Wave Pictures. At the Sony Imax Theater,
Lincoln Square, 1998 Broadway at 68th Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Stuart Pankin (The Professor/Voice of MAX), Elvira
(herself), Harry Shearer (Narrator) and Andrea Thompson (Ruth in
the Booth).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
