<SLUG> BC-EQUANT-NETWORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EQUANT PLANS TO EXPAND ITS GLOBAL DATA SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Helping to expand the digital world to some of the
globe's least-wired corners, Equant NV of the Netherlands plans to
announce on Wednesday that it will offer advanced data services in
25 additional territories and countries including Albania, Georgia,
and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement will bring to more than 100 the number
of countries and territories in which Equant offers the data
service known as frame relay, giving Equant perhaps the world's
most geographically extensive communications network.
</P>
<P>
   Equant, which first offered shares to the public just last
summer, emerged from a global communications consortium that was
formed in 1949 by many of the world's airlines to help coordinate
schedules and reservations. Equant is expanding on the network
built by the airlines in a bid to serve the communications needs of
multinational corporations outside the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Frame relay is a technology that is well suited to connecting
corporate networks in far-flung sites and to transmitting
information like credit-card data or requests from automated teller
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Corp. offers frame-relay service in about 40 countries,
a figure that an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman said would not change
significantly after AT&AMP;T completes its joint venture with British
Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom Inc. offered the service in only about 20 countries
at the end of last year, while the Global One partnership of
Sprint, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom, which appears to be in
danger of collapse, offers frame-relay service in 51 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Equant's competitors are not standing still, however. On
Tuesday, MCI Worldcom said it had extended its frame-relay network
to Argentina, Brazil, Chile, and Venezuela and that it planned to
offer the service in a total of 44 countries by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   And all of the international communications giants reach
additional countries through technologies other than frame relay.
Tuesday, for instance, AT&AMP;T announced that it would use IBM's
network to expand the number of countries in which it provides
standard telephone Internet access to 59 from 40.
</P>
<P>
   The other countries and territories to which Equant has expanded
its frame-relay service are Algeria, Armenia, Aruba, Azerbaijan,
Bosnia Herzegovina, Botswana, Cambodia, Congo Republic, Gibraltar,
Guinea, Malawi, Malta, Moldova, Monaco, Mozambique, Namibia,
Poland, Sierre Leone, Swaziland, Turkmenistan, the U.S. Virgin
Islands, and Western Samoa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
