<HEADER>
A0312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBRYO-MIXUP-625&AMP;ADD-     03-30 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-MIXUP-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 HEALTH OFFICIALS INVESTIGATE EMBRYO MIX-UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a case reverberating through the rapidly growing
world of reproductive technology, the New York state Health
Department has started an investigation into an embryo mix-up that
caused a Staten Island woman who underwent in vitro fertilization
to recently give birth to two boys, one black and one white.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeanne Linden, director of the state Health Department
division that regulates fertility clinics, said officials would try
to determine how the woman, Donna Fasano, received implants not
only of her eggs fertilized by her husband, Richard, but also of
other fertilized eggs, apparently from a Teaneck, N.J., couple,
Robert Rogers and Deborah Perry-Rogers. Both Mrs. Fasano, who is
white, and Mrs. Rogers, who is black, were patients of a Manhattan
physician, Dr. Lillian Nash, and both women apparently had
fertilized eggs implanted on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be sending somebody to the site to see exactly what
the records say and to interview Dr. Nash to see what happened,''
Dr. Linden said Tuesday. She said investigators also would speak to
employees at a Manhattan fertility clinic owned by Dr. Dov
Goldstein, where the Rogerses had paid $1,500 to store their
embryos in a freezer.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated case took a dramatic turn on Monday when lawyers
for the Fasanos announced that the couple would raise their
biological child, and that the Rogerses would raise theirs, if DNA
tests confirm they are his biological parents. The Rogerses were
expected to take a DNA test within the week, and lawyers for both
couples will negotiate a visitation agreement. Two weeks ago, the
Rogerses filed a lawsuit seeking custody of one baby and claiming
negligence, malpractice and breach of contract against Dr. Nash,
Goldstein and an embryologist, Dr. Michael Obasaju.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Tarlton, a state Health Department spokeswoman, said the
state investigation would probably be concluded this week. She said
Dr. Nash is licensed to practice reproductive technology and that
her West 57th Street clinic was recently inspected by state health
officials. Ms. Tarlton said she did not know the results of that
inspection. A secretary reached by telephone at the clinic said Dr.
Nash would not comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   If the state investigation concludes that any regulations or
standards of care were violated, Ms. Tarlton said the department
``would take appropriate action,'' possibly a statement of
deficiency. If evidence of gross negligence or incompetence by
doctors is discovered, the Office of Professional Medical Conduct
could investigate later. But Ms. Tarlton emphasized that the
investigation began only Monday and that few facts had been firmly
established.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are such things as errors made in medicine,'' Ms.
Tarlton said. ``The standard for professional medical conduct is
gross negligence or incompetence. We have no information at this
time that this is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has quickly attracted national and international
interest even as lawyers for both couples have pleaded for privacy.
David Cohen, a lawyer for the Fasanos, said the two families will
meet within days with the 3-month-old babies. Cohen described the
Fasanos as ``prisoners in their house with the blinds closed
because there are camera crews sitting outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Silas, the lawyer for the Rogerses, said his clients
also were struggling to live normal lives. Silas said both couples
were angry with Dr. Nash but not with one another. ``The Fasanos
are a little saddened that they are parting with a child, and the
Rogerses are delighted that they are receiving a child,'' he said.
Unlike Mrs. Fasano, Mrs. Rogers did not become pregnant after the
in vitro procedures. Both women have tried for years to conceive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A study conducted by the Federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention and the American Society for Reproductive Medicine found
that in 1996, 64,000 attempts at assisted reproduction were made
nationally, mostly through in vitro fertilization, resulting in
20,659 births. A study by the state Health Department documented
that 5,741 attempts at in vitro fertilization had been made in New
York state in 1995, though the success rate could not be
determined. The figures do not include cases of artificial
insemination.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Katz Rothman, a City University sociologist whose most
recent book, ``Genetic Maps and Human Imagination,'' addresses
issues involving reproductive technology, said a similar case
occurred recently in Holland. In that case, a white woman receiving
in vitro treatment received implants of her eggs, fertilized by a
white man, but the clinic mixed in eggs from another woman,
fertilized by a black man. The woman gave birth to two boys, one
black, one white, and is now raising both children, Ms. Rothman
said. Such cases, she said, raise murky philosophical questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're raising all kinds of questions about what is the meaning
of the ties between a parent and a child and between any people and
how we are related to each other,'' she said. ``What concerns me is
with all the push toward genetic determination is that we're coming
to think of `real ties' as genetic relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fasano and Rogers case almost certainly will provide
ammunition to groups calling for greater federal and state
regulation of fertility treatments. But Dr. Linden said mistakes
were very rare. New York, she said, requires that labs file records
of procedures with the state. Officials also conduct routine
inspections at the 24 licensed in vitro programs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Linden said officials did not yet know whether the mix-up in
the Fasano case happened at Dr. Nash's office, where the
implantation occurred, or at Goldstein's clinic. She said Dr. Nash,
who is 71, did not have a freezer at her clinic _ unusual for a
fertility practice _ and that someone at her office had arranged
for 10 additional fertilized eggs from the Rogerses to be stored at
Goldstein's clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Pittoni, a lawyer for Goldstein, said an embryologist from
Goldstein's office agreed to store the Rogerses' unused fertilized
eggs after someone from Dr. Nash's office called and appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Pittoni said that Obasaju, the embryologist named in the
Rogerses' lawsuit, is not the same embryologist who works for
Goldstein. Pittoni also said that the Rogerses' unused eggs did not
arrive at Goldstein's clinic until April 24, the same day that Dr.
Nash did the implants. Obasaju could not be reached by telephone
for comment Tuesday, but Silas said he worked with Dr. Nash during
the implantation.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department lists no disciplinary actions
against Dr. Nash or Obasaju, but Goldstein was censured,
reprimanded and fined $35,000 last June 22 after a hearing
committee found that he allowed unlicensed employees to perform
artificial insemination. Pittoni said his client's history was
irrelevant to the Fasano case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a doctor who was standing on the sidewalk
and witnessed an accident and he's not involved in it all, but it
brings up things that would not be related to this case,'' Pittoni
said. ``It's unfair. In no way would that be reported, except for
the fact that he was improperly served and involved in this case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
