r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-LUDWIG-TEX     03-30 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LUDWIG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUDWIG LIKES HIS HOCKEY AND HARLEYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The conversation turns to goalie masks. And, as always,
Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig has a unique perspective.
</P>
<P>
   As he studies ``The Eagle'' mask of Ed Belfour and the ``Iron
Maiden'' monster mask of Roman Turek that give insight into the
character of each player, Ludwig is asked what he would paint on a
mask if he was a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see,'' Ludwig says as his brain churns forward trying to
crystallize his personality in one poignant scene. ``How about a
can of Bud Light riding on a Harley?''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig is all about motorcycles and fast cars and slow-pitch
softball and beer. He is equal parts Evel Knievel and Homer
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   And, the funny thing is, somewhere beneath all of that rests a
pretty good hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an interesting guy,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``He has this big \Rwild man\S image, and that's there because of
the type of person he is. But I don't think he gets near enough
credit for being a true natural athlete. This is a guy who's had
success in more than a couple of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig plays softball at the elite level during the summer back
home in Wisconsin and is about to wrap up his 17th NHL season. He
turned 38 on March 15 but shows no signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has been his best season since I've been here,''
Hitchcock said. ``He's moving the puck well, he's making smart
decisions, he's got a lot of confidence out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Those attributes have come in handy the past two weeks as Ludwig
has helped fill the void created by injuries to defensemen Richard
Matvichuk and Shawn Chambers. Ludwig has pushed his average minutes
played from about 13 to 18 a game and has shown no signs of wear.
He had 11 hits _ a Stars season high _ in one game. He had four
blocked shots in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy works just as hard off the ice as he does on, but he
doesn't ever let the fun get in the way of the work,'' said
Matvichuk, who has fashioned his career after Ludwig's. ``He's
amazing. He shows up to play every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig's dedication is, in many ways, confusing. He often gripes
about the length of the regular season, has said he would rather
play softball for a living and has said countless times that he
should have retired by now. But fill an arena with people, put a
team out there in opposite colors, and Ludwig is flinging his body
in front of flying pucks and dipping low with his trademark hip
check to smash an unsuspecting forward into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the old system \Rwith the Montreal Canadiens\S
where you were expected to work hard on the ice and play hard
off,'' he said. ``But no matter what you did on your off day, the
thing that was certain was you were going to give 100 percent every
game. I'm still that way. I come to the rink every game believing
that if I don't play my best, I shouldn't be on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig recently received the nomination of the Dallas chapter of
the Professional Hockey Writers Association for this year's
Masterton Trophy. He is one of 27 nominees across the NHL that have
displayed ``perseverance, sportsmanship and dedication to hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at least the perseverance part might be right,'' Ludwig
joked.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is Ludwig qualifies on all three counts. As for
sportsmanship, he plays the rules old style: He only gives out what
he expects to get back. And as for dedication to hockey, there's
nobody on the Stars who wants a Stanley Cup more than Ludwig. It's
just that he doesn't think he has to always wear a serious face in
pursuit of the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I like to have fun; that doesn't mean I'm not serious,''
said the man who generally organizes all the NCAA Tournament and
golf pools and holiday parties for the team. ``I mean, we're
playing hockey for a living. I still realize it's a game. If we
can't laugh at ourselves every once in a while, we're in trouble.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
