<SLUG> BC-BBO-UNIFORM-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR LEAGUES MIGHT SELL ADS ON THE UNIFORMS OF THE PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major League Baseball is considering selling small
patches of advertising on the uniform sleeves of its players as a
new way to increase team revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's tentative plan, one company official said, would
probably have teams sell the advertising patches to local
corporations. When revenue reached a certain level, it might be
shared with other clubs. Only companies in the tobacco, alcohol and
broadcast businesses would be barred from the program.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, baseball has allowed uniforms to bear only the
manufacturer's logo. Currently, an `R' is visible on the sleeves,
for Russell Athletic. In the NFL, uniforms carry the logo of one of
four apparel makers _ Nike, Puma, Adidas or Starter _ on both
jersey sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum are athletes in sports like
auto racing; the jumpsuits of NASCAR drivers are plastered with the
logos of their sponsors. Golfers and tennis players also wear caps
and shirts with logos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue being considered here goes beyond the scope of a
uniform manufacturer's logo,'' said a team official who asked not
to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Smith, the vice president of licensing for Major League
Baseball Properties, would not discuss the details of a possible
uniform advertising plan. But he said: ``We're talking from A to Z
about our on-field programs, and bringing in additional sponsors in
other formats than we have now. We've talked about everything. But
we're not close to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball uniforms are considered the most traditional
in sports, they have undergone marketing-induced changes over the
years. Teams have changed uniform and cap designs, or added new
jerseys for special occasions, to enhance the sale of licensed
replica jerseys in retail outlets. (Baseball is also considering
whether its licensed apparel makers should make replica uniforms
bearing the logos of the advertisers who buy the patches.)
</P>
<P>
   To increase revenue more dramatically, teams have also covered
stadium fences and dugout walls with commercial signs and added
rotating advertising behind home plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
