<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARYNO.COM IS NOT MUD.COM, GIULIANI SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the undeclared Republican
candidate for U.S. Senate, said on Tuesday that a Web site set up
by his supporters was not intended as an attack on Hillary Rodham
Clinton but rather as an effort to capitalize on the fund-raising
opportunity presented by her potential Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference, Giuliani said he would be
politically remiss not to take advantage of the attention raised by
Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality,'' he said, ``is that we want to take advantage of
those people who think that she shouldn't run for the Senate, of
which there are many and who feel very fervently about it. I would
be foolish if I didn't take advantage of that. It's an opportunity
that she's presented us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has said she is considering running for the New
York seat being vacated next year by Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. The Web site set up by Giuliani's fund-raising committee
asserts that Mrs. Clinton has no experience in elective office and
no ties to New York.
</P>
<P>
   New York Democrats said the Web site, called Hillaryno.com, was
a sign of early mudslinging by the mayor and an indication of the
type of campaign he would wage. Mrs. Clinton, who was traveling in
Morocco, has not commented on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the new site merely reflected the sentiments
expressed by New York voters that he has met in his recent travels
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it fair?'' the mayor asked, repeating a reporter's question
Tuesday. ``Come on, it's politics. She presents us with an
opportunity and we take advantage of it and then that's not fair? I
mean is it fair that she comes to New York and raises lots of
money?''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Mrs. Clinton's expression of interest in running
had energized both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her consideration of candidacy has gotten her a great deal of
attention,'' he said. ``We're taking advantage of her consideration
to raise money and to develop volunteers should I decide to run for
the Senate. It's smart politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site was paid for by one of the mayor's campaign
committees and invites visitors to make online contributions and to
volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who was in Troy, N.Y., on Tuesday night to deliver a
speech, said the Web site received 200,000 hits Tuesday from about
25,000 dedicated users. He said that more than 1,100 people had
volunteered to help his campaign should he run, and that 2,000 had
signed a petition voicing opposition to Mrs. Clinton's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani expressed amazement at the response. ``Man, if I can
continue to do that good, who knows,'' he said. ``The sky's the
limit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2326EST &QL; 
