<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-LOAIZA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA OUT OF RANGERS' ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Right-hander Esteban Loaiza, anointed as
the fifth starter by manager Johnny Oates in February, pitched
himself out of the Rangers' rotation this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a fifth starter,'' Oates said yesterday after the
Rangers' 7-1 exhibition loss to the Boston Red Sox at Charlotte
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not need a fifth starter until April 13, and
Oates remains noncommittal as to whom it will be.
</P>
<P>
   Semantics?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but another issue surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Can Loaiza pitch himself off the Rangers' Opening Day roster and
onto the one at Triple-A Oklahoma?
</P>
<P>
   ``That decision has not been made,'' general manager Doug Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who could be optioned to the minor leagues without being
exposed to waivers, views that as unacceptable and would request a
trade should that occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes to that, all I have to do is pick up the phone and
call my agent on his 1-800 number,'' Loaiza said. ``I've been down
there before. That would be like going from sixth grade to fifth
grade. There are other teams out there who would want me.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza drew considerable interest during Major League Baseball's
winter meetings in December, and as many as seven organizations _
including the Toronto Blue Jays and San Diego Padres _ expressed
interest then, major-league officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would likely find it difficult to receive sufficient
value for Loaiza in a trade this month.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who described this as ``the worst spring training I've
ever had,'' could not stop the bleeding yesterday. The right-hander
surrendered five runs on six hits and three walks during his
five-inning appearance against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   That included a 36-pitch second inning in which Oates sent
right-hander Jonathan Johnson to warm up in the bullpen. This
latest performance gave Loaiza an 8.04 earned-run average through
15 2/3 innings, and opponents are hitting .339 (20-for-59) against
the inconsistent 27-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza's salary will not dictate whether he remains in the major
leagues. Loaiza will earn $1.4 million this season whether he
pitches for the Rangers or the Triple-A RedHawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make any difference,'' Rangers president Tom
Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, appear willing to attempt to develop what
Loaiza can offer. Loaiza allowed only a single and one walk during
his final three innings yesterday, and he has the best arm on the
staff, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to do everything we can to make them better
players,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin offered this point: ``What are the alternatives?''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza offers another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about them sending me to the minor leagues,''
he said. ``I'm capable of pitching here. I know I'm capable of
performing. I'm still confident.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
