<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ICE-SURFACE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TO GET BETTER SURFACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Reunion Arena staff has taken the first steps
toward improving the ice surface for Stars games, and hopes to have
the ice in good shape at least two weeks before the playoffs start
April 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working on a whole list of items that
collectively should make a big difference,'' arena group president
Brad Mayne said yesterday. ``We realize how important this is, and
we're going to put a lot of time and money into fixing it before we
even get to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Stars players complained that the ice
surface was ``soft'' and rutted, and that those problems led to
poor puck handling and the chance for injuries. Because of that,
Reunion Arena management has worked to keep the building cooler for
Stars games and last week shaved the surface of the ice (which is
about three-quarters of an inch thick). By shaving the ice, the top
layer, which had accumulated some microscopic dirt, was taken off
and replaced with a new layer of ice.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer impurities, the ice will freeze harder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Reunion Arena staff will bring in dehumidifiers
within the next two weeks. That will help make the air in the arena
more conducive to good ice making, especially as the temperatures
warm. The Stars used the dehumidifiers in the playoffs last season,
and Stars players said that improved the surface of the ice
dramatically.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-30-99 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
