<HEADLINE>
UCONN SAYS ITS WILL TOO STRONG FOR DUKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Champions are created in many ways, but
one constant is mental toughness. The players for Connecticut, the
1999 men's NCAA Tournament champion, showed that their minds are
sharp and highly developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' 77-74 victory over Duke probably should be regarded
as a surprise, but not a shocking upset. The Blue Devils were
``expected'' to win the title because of their seasonlong
dominance, but Connecticut was the only other team ranked No. 1
this season and both were No. 1 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   With five starters returning from a team that came within a
victory of reaching last year's Final Four, Connecticut had its own
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Huskies added their emotional leader in point
guard Khalid El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Khalid came to our program, he motivated all of us,''
said junior Richard Hamilton, who combined with El-Amin to score 26
of UConn's 40 second-half points. ``He let everybody know we had an
opportunity to win the national championship. Everybody said we
weren't going to fall short this year.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Huskies' 1997-98 season ended with a loss to North
Carolina in the East Regional final, Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun
started focusing on this season. The journey began in mid-August
with a trip to Israel. Hamilton was out with a broken foot, so the
Huskies had to play their eight exhibition games without him. They
went 3-3 against Israeli professional teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a relaxed trip, but without Richard
everybody had to step up their play and improve,'' Connecticut
junior forward Kevin Freeman said. ``Last year made us realize we
were close. Israel helped bring us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut started this season 19-0. ``People kept asking me if
they were affected by it, and I'd say no,'' Calhoun said. ``Nobody
would believe me. But the kids never concerned themselves with
records or rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the NCAA Tournament, the Huskies defeated Iowa, a team
playing for its lame-duck coach, in the regional semifinals. They
survived against a nothing-to-lose Gonzaga team in the West Region
final.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching the Final Four for the first time in school
history, Connecticut maintained its focus. The Huskies were the
first team since Texas Western (now UT-El Paso) to win the national
title on their first trip to the Final Four. Texas Western won in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough not to just settle for getting here,'' said
Freeman, whose defensive help contributed to limiting Duke's Elton
Brand to 15 points. ``We got back to campus, and it was like we had
won a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke entered the tournament ranked No. 1 and the prohibitive
championship favorite, but the Huskies say they knew they were
capable of winning the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the semifinals, all the questions people asked us were
about Duke this and Duke that,'' said center Jake Voskuhl, a junior
from Katy. ``We used that, and it hurt Duke because it put so much
pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it pressure, fate or the breaks of the game. Duke was
8-of-15 on layups or dunks. Junior Chris Carrawell missed a layup
after a steal. Connecticut twice converted first-half baskets after
the Blue Devils failed to secure a near turnover and a defensive
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outhustled us and beat us on loose balls,'' Carrawell
said.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final minutes, Connecticut made the key plays:
El-Amin's scoring the Huskies' last field goal and points (two free
throws at 5.2 seconds) and Ricky Moore's denial defense on Duke's
Trajan Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just out-willed Duke in those last few minutes,''
El-Amin, a sophomore, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the will to win,'' Calhoun said. ``We showed people the
heart and character this team has. That's what it always takes to
win a national championship.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
