<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-2ND-WRITETHRU-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THWARTED, NATO AGREES TO BOMB BELGRADE SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to expand on US-NATO decision, add
details, backfground; Pickup 8th graf pvs, Serb forces...; SUBS
last 4 grafs of 1st take, The alliance ..., to UPDATE bombing
phases; ADDS Schmitt byline; now in 2 takes.) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN,
KOSOVO-YELTSIN, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The United States and NATO agreed Tuesday
night to an escalated bombing campaign targeting government
buildings in downtown Belgrade, in an acknowledgement that air
strikes have failed to halt the assault in Kosovo or sufficiently
damage the Serbian military, two senior American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such attacks, which would probably include government centers
like the Interior and Defense Ministry buildings in the Serbian
capital as well military targets elsewhere in the country,
represent a major change in tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, NATO has largely limited its bombing to air defense
systems, factories and military installations on the outskirts of
Belgrade and forces directly involved in the Kosovo campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deepening and broadening of the target set,'' said
one of the senior American officials. The list of targets was
increased by about 20 percent, one official said. The change in
bombing plans was first reported in the early Wednesday issue of
The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   American officials made the request for authority to bomb a much
broader range of targets throughout Yugoslavia at a closed-door
meeting of delegates to NATO, but said they did not get as broad an
authority as they proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's Secretary General, Javier Solana, expressed
misgivings earlier in the day, saying he was not convinced that the
time had come to broaden the strikes dramatically, reflecting
strains within the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded bombing campaign would be considerably less
extensive than the air strikes aimed at the political leadership of
Iraq during the Gulf War in 1991, when American bombers targeted
President Saddam Hussein's palaces and the headquarters of his
political party, other officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said, however, that any attacks on the densely
populated center of Belgrade would require pinpoint accuracy to
avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to escalate the attacks came on a downbeat day for
NATO, as its commanders received bad news from every direction.
 &UR;  &LR;  Serb forces continued to advance virtually unopposed on the
battlefield and the refugee crisis threatened to spiral out of
control, with NATO officials estimating that one-third of the 1.8
million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo had been forced from their
homes. The alliance was forced to beat back an attempt by Russian
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to open negotiations on terms
dictated by President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO official said Tuesday night that the alliance
raids had been stymied by a Yugoslavian air defense that has proved
more resilient than anticipated, new tactics that involved
dispersing Milosevic's forces in the field and extremely bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the alliance was eagerly waiting to deploy
A-10 ground attack planes that they hoped would strike directly at
Serbian troops in Kosovo and knock out tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The A-10s took off Tuesday but returned without attacking their
targets because of thick clouds and rain, a NATO official said. The
A-10s could not fly below the clouds because of the risk of
exposure to anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had an impact on the infrastructure, but the impact on
their operations is a different matter,'' the NATO official said.
``Whether we can stop it or not we'll find out. A lot of people
have real doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   With the alliance excluding the use of ground forces, airpower
appeared to be the only tool NATO has to influence the Yugoslav
leadership. But the air attacks have been constrained by political
considerations, despite the West's increasingly vociferous charges
that Milosevic is engaged in a brutal campaign of ``ethnic
cleansing'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the bombing plan was developed months ago
when alliance officials anticipated that a modest air raid or two
would be enough to nudge a recalcitrant Milosevic back to the
negotiating table. But the scale and intensity of the Serb attacks
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have caught the alliance by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even we have been shocked by the sheer enormity of what is
going on in Kosovo at the moment,'' said Jamie Shea, the NATO
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with hundreds of thousands of refugees and reports of
murders, NATO's planners began to talk about the need to ``adapt''
their bombing plan.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, officials say, has a three-part bombing plan. The
first stage was to attack Yugoslav's anti-aircraft systems, an
effort that is still under way.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase, which had recently been launched, involves
strikes on the Serb forces south of Yugoslavia's 44th parallel;
those forces have been pressing the attack against the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The third phase of the NATO bombing plan had not been approved
until Tuesday night, and officials here had been reluctant to
discuss it in detail.
</P>
<P>
   It would give NATO commanders the authority to launch a broader
range of attacks against Yugoslavia's military leaders, command and
control centers, weapons depots, heavy weapons and fuel supplies.
And allied planners would get more leeway to bomb targets in
Belgrade and to put buildings like the Defense and Interior
Ministries on the target list.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States led the effort to get NATO to approve this
third phase of strikes. Gen. Wesley K. Clark, the alliance's top
military commander, had independently asked for the authority to
hit a broader array of targets, according to NATO officials. Clark
declined to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The American proposal to broaden air attacks came as Serbian
forces continue to press their attacks against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, NATO officials estimated that 118,000 ethnic Albanians
had been forced out of Kosovo since March 24. Serbian tanks have
been surrounding villages and towns. Women and children have been
separated from the men and then forcibly bused to the frontier.
Afterward, their homes are burned to the ground so that they cannot
return.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Pec, which used to have a population of some
100,000, has now been almost totally destroyed. Along with the
daily handouts touting its air strikes, the NATO press office now
distributes a daily report on ``City Torching'' by Serbian forces
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that we have not seen since the forced
evacuation of Phnom Penh in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge in the
mid-1970s,'' said Shea, the NATO spokesman, referring to the forced
migration.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance spokesmen said the alliance had received sketchy
reports that fleeing refugees were even being shelled by Serbian
artillery and tanks.
</P>
<P>
   To put pressure on Serbian commanders to curtail their attacks,
NATO spokesman have repeatedly warned that their assaults against
ethnic Albanians might be prosecuted as war crimes. But the NATO
official said there was no indication that those threats were
influencing the Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   To try to keep up the pressure, allied warplanes have also begun
flying during daytime, instead of confining their attacks to the
night. New American B-1B bombers and British Tornadoes are being
added to NATO's attack force.
</P>
<P>
   But to deter the Serbs, the alliance needs to expand the scope
of its attacks, military planners say. Whether Milosevic is worried
by the threat of escalation is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much force this is going to take is something we simply
can't predict,'' Shea said. ``We always hope for the minimum
because an alliance of democracies is never very enthusiastic about
having to use force unless pushed into a corner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
