<HEADLINE>
BAD WEATHER HAMPERS BOMBERS' EFFECTIVENESS, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to ADD comment from Pentagon spokesman on
failure to stop killing; Pickup 11th graf pvs, Made by Boeing
.... ) 
(See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PRIMAKOV, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-BRITAIN, KOSOVO-YELTSIN,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-GORE, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE,
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hampered by overcast skies Tuesday, NATO warplanes
bombarded Serb army forces, airfields and supply depots around the
clock but failed again to knock out air defenses or blunt Serbia's
offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and poor visibility have forced scores of allied
fighter-bombers to abort their missions in the weeklong air
campaign and return to base, their laser-guided bombs still in
their racks, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On only one day in seven have pilots had optimal conditions for
bombing _ a cloud ceiling of at least 25,000 feet and visibility of
more than five miles. Tank-killing A-10 Warthogs have flown air
patrol, but have yet to dare to dip down into the range of
surface-to-air missiles to attack tanks directly.
</P>
<P>
   Under strict rules to attack only when targets are visible, to
avoid civilian damage, pilots have had to dart in and out of clear
patches of sky to drop their payloads. They have been flying mostly
at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather has not been in our favor,'' said Vice Adm. Scott
A. Fry, director of operations for the military's Joint Staff, who
refused to say how many missions had been canceled because of the
weather. ``It has gotten more difficult with each succeeding
night.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Balkans are notorious for fog and rain, the week has
been unusually difficult, officials said, putting the air campaign
behind schedule, even as Yugoslav troops have stepped up their
campaign against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Military officials conceded the air war has failed to curb
the killings. ``I think right now, it is difficult to say that we
have prevented one act of brutality at this stage,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The climate has compelled NATO to rely more heavily on missiles
launched from sea and air, as well as bombs dropped from B-2's, all
of which satellites can guide to fixed targets.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem has cropped up. The Air Force is running out of
its most highly prized cruise missiles, launched from B-52's with
2,000-pound warheads. The shortage occurs as NATO gears up for a
possible assault on downtown Belgrade. Those missiles are the
weapon of choice for such missions.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of the air campaign, United States B-52's
dropped roughly 50 cruise missiles, reducing by one-third the Air
Force worldwide stock of 150. ``That's something that we do worry
about,'' Bacon said Tuesday. ``We have a supply now. But it won't
last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Made by Boeing, the air-launched missiles cost $1 million each
and are prized for their accuracy and powerful punch.
</P>
<P>
   Although equally accurate, the sea-launched Tomahawk cruise
missile has a smaller warhead, 500 pounds, and is in ample supply.
They are made by Raytheon and cost $600,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the air war began, the Pentagon ordered a
review of its guided-missiles stocks and decided to proceed without
increasing the supplies. ``We are fully satisfied that we have
sufficient ammunition,'' a senior Pentagon official said Tuesday,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The secretary of defense and
the chairman of the Joint Chiefs were involved in that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather isn't NATO's only problem. Yugoslav troops and
artillery have dispersed into the region's forests and hilly
terrain. Serbian tanks are parked next to residential buildings,
daring NATO pilots to strike.
</P>
<P>
   To work around this obstacle, NATO wants to use unmanned
reconnaissance drones to reconnoiter the battlefield and transmit
the coordinates of allied warplanes. But the weather has grounded
the drones.
</P>
<P>
   There are also political constraints. Over the past eight days,
Gen. Wesley K. Clark, the NATO military commander, has requested
Apache helicopters, only to be turned down by political leaders, a
NATO official said. The helicopters, for use against tanks, suggest
a ground war more than an air war.
</P>
<P>
   Even as commanders poured out their frustration here and at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, the Pentagon tried to put the best face
on the situation, delivering an upbeat assessment in classified
briefings to lawmakers on Capitol Hill, and then a sanitized
version to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has flown about 425 combat flights against 100 targets, a
Pentagon official told reporters, ranging from air defense radars
that require only one bomb to weapons factories that require
dozens.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with detailed charts, military briefers said Tuesday that
NATO had damaged or severely damaged the systems that integrate
Yugoslavia's vaunted air defenses, its intelligence-gathering
capability, army and police garrisons, and aircraft repair depots.
</P>
<P>
   But Fry and Rear Adm. Thomas R. Wilson, the director of
intelligence for the Joint Staff, repeatedly refused to define
exactly what those terms mean, or just how degraded they believe
Belgrade's capability really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to assign percentages to it,'' said Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday marked the first time since the air campaign started
that senior officials from the Joint Staff, which has influence
over the targets bombed 5,000 miles away, had met with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon has given regular briefings but has pointedly disclosed
few operational details.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, have clamped down on details
of military operations since last summer's cruise missile strike
against suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan. Cohen
and Shelton have justified this approach to avoid leaks of
classified information and to let Clark take the lead in releasing
most information.
</P>
<P>
   The American reticence contrasts with that of Britain, whose
Defense Ministry offers detailed news conferences. And during the
1991 Persian Gulf war, the predecessors of the two admirals who
briefed Tuesday gave daily briefings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
