<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMY-FISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPED BY WOMAN SHE SHOT, AMY FISHER MAY BE PAROLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Amy Fisher, who has served nearly seven years in
prison for the 1992 shooting of Mary Jo Buttafuoco, may soon be out
on parole, thanks to the help of her victim, who now says she
forgives Ms. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years is long enough,'' said Nassau County District
Attorney Denis Dillon, who announced Tuesday that he had filed
court papers seeking a five-year reduction in Ms. Fisher's
sentence. If a judge approves the request, and if the Parole Board
follows suit, Ms. Fisher could be free by the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Ms. Fisher and Mrs. Buttafuoco have exchanged letters and
have begun a healing relationship that has benefited everyone,''
Dillon said. ``Mary Jo felt that because Amy had been abused in her
past life and done seven years in prison, that she had been
punished enough and that the healing should begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Buttafuoco, whose husband, Joey, had carried on a yearlong
affair with Ms. Fisher, told Dillon in a letter that she had spent
much time thinking about Ms. Fisher and what she had done to her
and her family. ``From my perspective, there is no reason to keep
her in jail any longer,'' Mrs. Buttafuoco said in the letter. ``In
fact, I believe that she should be released as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Through an exchange of letters with Ms. Fisher and Rose Fisher,
Amy's mother, Mrs. Buttafuoco said that she now believed that Ms.
Fisher recognized the harm she had caused and that she wanted to
change her life. ``She wants to get the psychiatric care necessary
to be certain she will adjust well upon her release.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher was 16 when she began her affair with Buttafuoco. She
was 17 when she shot Mrs. Buttafuoco, saying later that he had
urged her to kill his wife. Part of Mrs. Buttafuoco's face remains
paralyzed from the gunshot, and a bullet remains lodged in her
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Although Buttafuoco, an auto body repairman, denied engaging in
a sexual relationship with Ms. Fisher when she was 16, he pleaded
guilty to statutory rape in October 1993 and served six months in
jail. The Buttafuocos now live in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Tuesday, Dillon announced that his office
would support Ms. Fisher's request to withdraw her original plea of
guilty to assault in the first degree, for which she was sentenced
on Sept. 23, 1992, to up to 15 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon said that when Ms. Fisher pleaded guilty, she apparently
believed, based on information from her lawyer, Eric Naiburg, that
she would be set free and placed in a work release program after
serving at least three years in jail. Dillon said that his office
had never made such a promise and that an investigation of Ms.
Fisher's claim indicated that she had been misled and denied her
constitutional right of effective counsel by Naiburg.
</P>
<P>
   In her request to withdraw her plea, Ms. Fisher accused Naiburg
of lying to her about the consequences of her guilty plea, and said
she had had a sexual relationship with him when he represented her.
Naiburg has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
   After concluding that she had been misled by Naiburg, Dillon
said he had recommended to the court that Ms. Fisher be permitted
to enter a new guilty plea to the same charge of assault, and then
be sentenced to up to 10 years in prison. The lighter sentence
would make her eligible for parole next month.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon declined to comment further on Naiburg's role in
representing Ms. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg, reached by telephone at his office in Hauppauge,
declined to comment, saying he would discuss the issue after the
court rules on Ms. Fisher's request. The judge is expected to rule
on April 22.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Ms. Fisher's mother, Rose, said she was
thankful for Mrs. Buttafuoco's ``pure act of forgiveness.'' She
said that she met with Mrs. Buttafuoco several months ago and found
that she was ``very compassionate and understanding about Amy and
her problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fisher, who met Tuesday afternoon with her daughter's new
lawyers, said she was hopeful that the judge would act in favor of
her daughter's release. But even with the court's consent, she said
she was concerned that the state Parole Board might vote against
her daughter's release.
</P>
</TEXT>
